<HEAD>
<TITLE>Flow through Textile Materials
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Flow through Textile Materials</H2>
ir. H. Gooijer (053-4892884, <A HREF="mailto:h.gooijer@ct.utwente.nl">h.gooijer@ct.utwente.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsor: Stichting Technologie van Gestructureerde Materialen<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER><B>Introduction</B></CENTER><BR>

Flow through textile materials is an important
phenomenon in the processing of textile
materials. For example, in textile wet finishing
the efficiency of the diverse processes is mainly
determined by the degree of flow through the
processed textile materials.<BR>
For the flow through porous materials several
models are available, for example the Carman-
Kozény-model or the Brinkman-model.
However problems arise when applying these
models in flow through textile materials
without adapting them to the special
geometrical structure of textile materials. For
example, woven fabrics show a biporous struc-
ture and nonwovens show a distribution in pore
size. The goal of this project is to adapt the well
known models for flow through porous
materials to the special structure of textile
materials.<P>

<CENTER><B>Theory</B></CENTER><BR>

Darcy introduced the permeability k to describe
the flow resistance of porous materials. This
permeability k is a specific property of the
porous material. For a textile nonwoven with a
monodisperse pore size distribution, k can be
determined with
the following relation
(Carman-Kozény)<P>

<IMG SRC="gooijer1.gif"><P>

In this relation is d<SUB>v</SUB> the fiber diameter, epsilon the
porosity of the material, and k<SUB>0</SUB> the empirical
Kozény constant. For k<SUB>0</SUB> often a value of 5.5-6
is assumed.<BR>
However, because nonwovens in practice
always show a multidiperse pore size
distribution equation (1) has to be adapted.
Therefore we assumed the nonwovens to be a
solid plate with a system of parallel cylindrical
pores. This pore system is considered as a

system of parallel flow resistances. Therefore
the reciproke of the total flow resistance is the
sum of the reciprokes of the individual
resistances. The permeability being the
reciproke of the flow resistance, equation (2)
has been deducted.<P>

<IMG SRC="gooijer2.gif"><P>

The porosity epsilon<SUB>m</SUB> is the volume of the pores
with a diameter dm divided by the total volume.<P>

<CENTER><B>Experiments</B></CENTER><BR>

The pore size distribution is measured by water
porosimetry according to Miller and Tyom-
kin[l] and Coulter-porometry. A typical
example of a measured pore size distribution is
given below.<P>

<IMG SRC="gooijer3.gif"><P>

<CENTER><B>Results</B></CENTER><BR>
For a few thermically bonded nonwovens k has
already been determined with equation (2). The
permeability appeared to be 2-3 times smaller
than k determined with equation (1).<BR>
The model still has to be validated
experimentally by pressure drop measurements.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>1) B. Miller, I. Tyomkin, Liquid porosimetry:New
Methodology and Applications, J. Colloid Interface Sci,
<B>162</B>, 163-170(1994)</FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
