<HEAD>
<TITLE>Foaming of Suspensions
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Foaming of Suspensions</H2>
Dr. C.W. den Engelsen<BR>
Sponsor: Stichting Technologie van Gestruetureerde Materialen<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Foam application process in the textile industry</B><P>

<B>Objective</B><BR>
<UL><LI>Saving of energy during the process of drying.
<LI>Saving of chemicals.
<LI>Better quality.
<LI>Increased production speed.
</UL><P>

<B>The Process</B><BR>
Subdivided in three paris<BR>
<B>Foam generation</B>. (foamability)<BR>
<B>Foam transport</B>. (theology, flow behaviour)<BR>
<B>Foam application</B>. (stability)<P>

<B>Foamability</B><BR>
Foamability: the maximum amount of gas, that
can be dispersed in an amount of liquid, to make
a homogeneous foam. Foamability in a mixer can
be determined by a mixing characteristic. The
influence of a solid phase and the rotational speed
of the mixer have been studied.<P>

<IMG SRC="engelsen1.gif"><P>
<B>Figure 1</B> Mixing characteristics at 1000 RPM<P>

<IMG SRC="engelsen2.gif"><P>
<B>Figure 2</B> Mixing characteristics at 2000 RPM<P>

<B>Foam rheology</B><BR>
The rheological behaviour of foam is studied by
means of flow curves. Shear stresses are measured
as a function of the shear rate. The model of Her-
schel-Bulkly is used to fit the results.<P>

<IMG SRC="engelsen3.gif"><P>

with tau the shear stress, k and n rheological con-
stants, gamma the shear rate, and x<SUB>0</SUB> the yield stress.<P>

<IMG SRC="engelsen4.gif"><P>
<B>Figure 3</B> Influence of silica<P>

<IMG SRC="engelsen5.gif"><P>
<B>Figure 4</B> Influence of blow ratio<P>

<B>Conclusions</B><BR>
Silica and rotational speed of the mixer both affect
the foamability of silica suspensions in a mixer.
Increase of the silica content or the blow ratio
increase the apparent viscosity of the foam.
The model of Herschel-Bulkly gives an excellent
description of the theological behaviour of foam.<P>

<B>Literature</B><BR>
C.W. den Engelsen, H. Gooijer,
<I>Textile Res. J</I>. <B>64</B>, 626-632 (1994).
J. Groot Wassink,


