<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Cyclone dipleg flow effects
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<B><FONT SIZE=5>Cyclone dipleg flow effects<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
PhD student: Ir. J.H. Bouma (053 - 489 40 98, <A HREF="mailto:J.H.Bouma@wb.utwente.nl">J.H.Bouma@wb.utwente.nl</A>)
<P>
Supervisor: Prof.dr.ir. G.G. Hirs (053 - 489 25 30)
<P>
Project term: September 1993 - September 1997
<P>
Sponsor: Shell International Oil Products
<P>
<HR SIZE=0>
<P>
<B>Introduction</B> 
<P>
Diplegs of gas/solids separators in FCC reactors and regenerators
serve the purpose of conveying the collected catalyst downward
towards or into a fluidised bed, whilst simultaneously ensuring
the pressure levels in- and outside the dipleg bottom end be equal.
The nature of the downflow is largely determined by the mass flow
rate, the particle size distribution, the pressure difference
top-to-bottom, the length and diameter of the dipleg, and the
inlet and outlet conditions and configurations of the dipleg.
<P>
The importance of understanding the phenomena inside the dipleg
relate to capital costs (size of reactor vessels), operational
costs (stable flow reduces possibilities of catalyst carry-over,
thus minimising wear on downstream components) and product quality
(a diminished carry-under of gas with catalyst reduces on after-cracking,
improving product quality). Faulty dipleg design made as a result
of poor understanding and prediction of the flow phenomena can
lead to very costly oversize of catcracker vessels or to poor
performance and reliability of the unit, which is also highly
detrimental to refinery economics.<BR>
<P>
<B>Objectives</B>
<P>
The main objective of the study is to improve substantially by
literature search, theoretical and experimental investigation
the knowledge on the solids flow behaviour in diplegs as required
for correct designing and operation of diplegs in various applications.
The study will address the flow nature, flow stability, pressure
build-up, gas carry under, effects of bottom termination devices,
and the effects of solids and gas properties, operating conditions
and system dimensions.
<P>
<B>Experimental facility</B>
<P>
In the course of three graduation projects running up to the current
project, a test facility has been built, in which cracking catalyst
is circulated in a closed loop, consisting of a buffer vessel,
riser, cyclone, dipleg and receptor vessel. Input parameters are
mass flux, pressure difference top-to-bottom, dipleg diameter,
dipleg termination and powder properties. Measured quantities
include pressure profile, apparent densities, gas carry-under,
cyclone efficiency, as well as determination of flow regimes and
flow instabilities.<BR>
<P>
<B>Results</B>
<P>
The graduation project preceding this project had already yielded
extensive information on the occurrence of flow regimes and flow
instabilities. During the first year of the current project, the
emphasis has been on determining the gas carry-under under varying
conditions. In the second year, measurement of radial concentration
and velocity profiles has been added, using a dual reflective
optical probe with cross-correlation. A one-dimensional model
of dipleg flow has also been developed, which shows satisfactory
agreement with the experimental results. The past year has seen
work on the influence of changes in boundary conditions.<BR>
<P>
<B>Future work</B>
<P>
During the final year of the project, the effect of changing the
powder properties will be studied. In addition, the flow behaviour
of a dipleg in combination with a Rotary Particle Separator will
be investigated.

