<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Cyclonic smal particle reactor with integrated filter
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<P>
<CENTER><H1>Cyclonic smal particle reactor with integrated filter</H1></CENTER>
<B>Ir. E.A. Bramer</B><BR>
phone 053-4892530<BR>
fax. 053-4893663<BR>
email <A HREF="mailto:e.a.bramer@wb.utwente.nl">e.a.bramer@wb.utwente.nl</A><BR>
Sponsor: IOP-MT/Recycling<BR>
<BR>
<HR SIZE=0>
<P>
<B>Introduction of research project:</B>
<P>
The rotational particle separator (RPS)
is a new device capable to separate small particles in a very
efficient way, even at high temperatures. The RPS is composed
of a cyclonic part and an integrated rotating filter element collecting
the smallest particles. Considerable collection efficiencies can
be achieved for particles down to 0.1 micron. Because of the high
collection efficiency for micron particles the cyclonic part of
the RPS can be used as a reactor for small particles. Using small
particles short reaction/capture times are achieved resulting
a compact reactor type. The working principle (three stages) can
be explained as follows.<BR>
<P>

<UL>
<LI>Injection of reactive particles into the polluted gas stream at the inlet of the RPS.
<LI>Reaction/adsorption of the gaseous pollutants with/on the small particles in the cyclone of the RPS.
<LI>Separation of the reacted particles by the cyclone and filter element of the RPS.
</UL>
<P>
<IMG SRC="bramer1.gif">
<P>
The research project consists of thefollowing parts
<UL>
<LI>High temperature dust cleaning of pyrolysis gases
<LI>Dehalogenation of pyrolysis gases at higher temperature
<LI>Cleaning of process flows using powdered activated carbon
<LI>The development of a mathematical reactor model of the RPS (fluid dynamics, mass transfer and reaction in a single particle)<BR>
</UL>

<P>
<B>Results:</B>
<P>
Results of the removal of HCl using Sodium
bicarbonate are shown below. Depicted is the conversion of HCl
as a function of the molar ratio Na/Cl. High conversions of HCl
are possible at short residence times and small molar ratios.
Calculated separation efficiencies as
a function of  flow for the cyclonic part and the filter element
of a RPS are given in the figure below.<BR>

<P>
<IMG SRC="bramer2.gif">
<P>

