<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Thermodynamic optimisation for a sustainable development
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<CENTER><H1>Thermodynamic optimisation for a sustainable development</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>The combination of exergy analysis and life-cycle assessment<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
Ph.D.-student:  Ir. R.L. Cornelissen (31-53-489 4094)<BR>
Supervisor:  Prof. Dr. Ir. G.G. Hirs<BR>
Project term: Nov. 1993 - Nov. 1997<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:R.L.Cornelissen@wb.utwente.nl">R.L.Cornelissen@wb.utwente.nl</A><BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction<BR></B>
<P>
Exergy analysis is the combination of the first and second law
of thermodynamics. In an exergy analysis the losses represented
the real losses of work. Exergy is defined as the maximum amount
of work potential of a system or a form of energy in relation
to the surrounding environment. Life cycle assessment is the analysis
of the continuous chain of processes, leading from natural resources
to final products, their use and discard and the assessment of
their influence on the environment.  <BR>
<P>
<B>Objectives<BR></B>
<P>
To determine the efficiency of a system, not only processes that
occur within the system should be taken into account, but also
all kinds of interaction between energy and material flows outside
the system's boundaries. Only then the actual performance of the
system and its impact on the environment can be evaluated. The
objective nature of the exergy can serve for various application,
from pin-pointing the losses within a process to a global estimate
of the environmental impact of a certain industry. The cumulative
exergy consumption during the life-cycle allows to evaluate the
degree of thermodynamic perfection of the production processes
and to conduct the assessment of the whole process chain. A method
is develop how to perform this analysis, which is called the Exergetic
Life Cycle Assessment (ELCA). <BR>
<P>
<B>Results<BR></B>
<P>
The first study was a conventional exergy analysis of a crude
oil distillation plant [1]. In this study it is shown that the
total rational efficiency of the distillation plant is 0.0518.
The biggest exergy losses are due to the use of high quality fuel
for the production of middle quality heat and the dissipation
of low quality heat in the environment. To stop the confusion
about the definition of exergetic efficiencies a publication [2]
has been made in which the three exergetic definitions are compared.
<BR>
<P>
With the combination of exergy analysis and life cycle analysis
the optimal design of a heat exchanger is obtained [3]. It is
shown that changes in the efficiencies of utilities to the heat
exchanger will change the optimal design. From the optimisation
can be concluded that the tube length of the present heat exchanger
is too short. In the last publication [4] different district heating
systems are analysed by the ELCA. It is shown that the life cycle
exergy saving of the district heating system with a steam and
gas turbine is 25% to 50% lower when compared with the nowadays
widely used high efficiency boilers.<BR>
<P>
<B>Future work<BR></B>
<P>
The method of how perform a ELCA will soon be published. A comparison
of the assessment with an LCA and an ELCA will be shown. <BR>
<P>
<B>References</B>
<P>
[1] R.L. Cornelissen, G.G. Hirs and T.J. Kotas, <I>An exergy analysis
of an oil distillation process</I>, Second Law Analysis of Energy
Systems, pp. 417-429,  Roma, 1995.
<P>
[2] R.L. Cornelisssen, G.G. Hirs and T.J. Kotas, <I>Different
Definitions of Exergetic Efficiencies</I>, JETC IV, Nancy, 1995.
  
<P>
[3] R.L. Cornelissen, G.G. Hirs, <I>Exergetic Optimisation of
a heat exchanger</I>, ECOS'96, Stockholm, June 25-27, 1996
<P>
[4] R.L. Cornelissen, G.G. Hirs, A.B.K. Lie and P. Steenderen,
<I>Exergy-Economics</I> <I>of a District Heating System</I>, Accepted
for the ASME Winter Annual Meeting, Atlanta, 1996.
</BODY>
</HTML>
