<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Flow of Coal-Ash Slag on a Entrained Flow Gasifier Refractory
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR>
<TD>
<H1>The Flow of Coal-Ash Slag on a Entrained Flow Gasifier Refractory</H1>
Ph. D-student: ir. J.A. Lycklama &agrave; Nijeholt (+31 (0)53 4894094)<BR>
Supervisor: Prof. Dr. ir. G.G. Hirs<BR>
Project term: Jan. 1996 - Jan. 2000<BR>
Sponsor: NOVEM/Demkolec<BR>
</TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="lycklama.gif"></TD>
</TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<P>
<CENTER><B>Introduction</B></CENTER>
<P>
Demkolec B.V. has designed and constructed a 250 MW demonstration
Integrated Coal Gasification Combined Cycle (ICGCC) power plant,
based on the Shell gasification technology. The research project
deals with the gasifier and concentrates on issues involving the
flow behaviour of the molten coal-ash deposited as a continuous
layer on the refractory of the gasifier. Understanding of the
flow behaviour of the coal-ash slag is desirable for various reasons,
originating from the function of the slag-layer in the overall
gasification process. Two important functions of the slag-layer
are to reduce the heat loss and to protect the refractory from
the high temperature gases. For a properly operating gasification
process it is necessary that the slag flows freely in a continuous
way down the reactor walls leaving through the tap hole. Also
excessive slag carry-over with the product gasses should be avoided
because of possible fouling of heat transfer surfaces outside
the gasifier.<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Results</B></CENTER>
<P>
The following areas are of interest for a proper description of
the flow on the refractory walls:
<UL>
<LI>The heat-flux through the slag-layer and refractory walls
and the temperature distribution in the slag layer.
<LI>The influence of temperature on coal-ash slag viscosity
<LI>The dependence of the slag deposition rate on the axial location
in the gasifier including the deposition mechanisms
</UL>
<P>
First preliminary  results of stationary slag-layer velocity profiles
and slag-layer thickness  are obtained, based on an estimated
heat-flux and a measured viscosity-temperature relationship, as
shown in the figure below.
<P>
<IMG SRC="lycklama1.gif">
<P>
<I>Slag flow velocity-profile at different vertical positions
along the reactor wall<BR>
</I>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Future work</B></CENTER>
<P>
We will concentrate on the first and third area of interest, as
mentioned above. Particularly the subjects of deposition mechanics
and the influence of the reactor shape on deposition rate and
distribution will be investigated, both theoretical and experimental.
As far as viscosity and other physical properties of the slag
are concerned, use will be made on external data from literature.

