<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Thermodynamic Analysis of the Advanced Energy Conversion Technologies
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">


<H1>Thermodynamic Analysis of the Advanced Energy Conversion Technologies</H1>

<B>ir Mikhail Korobitsyn</B><P>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD WIDTH=90></TD><TD WIDTH=217>At University of Twente </TD>
<TD WIDTH=170>At ECN</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=90>Phone</TD><TD WIDTH=217>31-53-489.40.94</TD>
<TD WIDTH=170>31-22-456.47.48</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=90>Fax</TD><TD WIDTH=217>31-53-489.36.63</TD><TD WIDTH=170>31-22-456.34.89
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=90>Email</TD><TD WIDTH=217><A HREF="mailto:m.korobitsyn@wb.utwente.nl">m.korobitsyn@wb.utwente.nl</A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=170><A HREF="mailto:m.korobitsyn@wb.utwente.nl">korobitsyn@ecn.nl</A></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="korobi.gif"></TD></TR>
</TABLE>


<HR SIZE=0>

<H2>INTRODUCTION</H2>
<P>
In co-operation with the Netherlands Energy Research Foundation
ECN a project on advanced energy conversion technologies has been
started. The project is funded by the Netherlands Agency for Energy
and Environment Novem within the framework of the New Energy Conversion
Technologies (NECT) programme.
<P>
The objective of the project is as follows: to identify and to
develop to a market introduction the new and advanced energy conversion
technologies which can provide higher efficiency and lower emissions.
The assessment is based both on thermodynamic, and on economic
criteria.

<H2>IDENTIFICATION</H2>
<P>
To identify new and existing combinations of energy conversion
technologies a literature survey has been carried out. More than
200 sources were reviewed, and 99 are referred to in the report&nbsp;(2).
The technologies covered  include systems based on the Joule-Brayton,
Rankine, Kalina, Otto/Diesel and Stirling cycles, fuel cells,
and heat pumps. A number of advanced cycles were also included.
<P>
For further consideration several technologies were selected,
among them: 
<UL>
<LI>Joule/Joule combined cycle, a gas turbine with air bottoming
(1)
<LI>Rankine/Joule combined cycle, a steam boiler with an air turbine
<LI>Double-pressure boiler designs with steam recompression and
water flashing
<LI>Integration of a gas turbine and a municipal solid waste incinerator
(3)
<LI>Gas turbine cycle with partial oxidation
</UL>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="korobi1.gif"><BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=2>Exergy flow diagram of an
integrated waste incineration plant.</FONT></B></CENTER>

<H2>ASSESSMENT</H2>
The cycles selected are subject to a detailed simulation and thermodynamic
analysis. An assessment of technological and market opportunities
forms the second phase of the project.

<H2>REFERENCES</H2>
<OL>
<LI>Hirs, G.G., Wagener, M.T.P.A., and Korobitsyn, M.A., &quot;Performance
Analysis of the Dual Gas Turbine Combined Cycle&quot;, in <I>Thermodynamics
and the Design, Analysis, and Improvement of Energy Systems </I>(R.Krane,
ed.), AES-Vol. 35, pp. 255-259, ASME Publications, N.Y., 1995.
<LI>Korobitsyn, M.A., &quot;Review on New and Improved Combinations
of Existing Energy Conversion Technologies&quot;, Novem Project
248.101-013.1, Final Report, Utrecht, the Netherlands, June 1996.
<LI>Korobitsyn, M.A., Hirs, G.G., and Jellema, P., &quot;Integration
of a Gas Turbine and a Municipal Waste Incinerator&quot;, Power-Gen
International 96 Conference, Orlando, Florida, December 4-6, 1996.
</OL>

