<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Improvement of the Rotating Air Inlet Filter (RIF) for Gas Turbines
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Improvement of the Rotating Air Inlet Filter (RIF) for Gas Turbines</H1>

Twaio: Ir. J. van Es<BR>
Supervisors: Ir. E.A. Bramer / Prof. Dr. Ir. J.J.H. Brouwers<BR>
Email: <A HREF="mailto:J.vanes@ct.utwente.nl">J.vanes@ct.utwente.nl</A><BR>
phone: 053-4892582<BR>
fax: 053-4893663<BR>
Sponsor: EPON<P>

<HR SIZE=0>
<P>
<IMG SRC="vanes1.gif"><P>

<B><FONT SIZE=4>Introduction<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
A severe problem in gas turbine operation is fouling.
Fouling lowers the compressor efficiency and  causes corrosion.
To prevent these effects the inlet air of a gas turbine is filtered.
A new concept in this field is the Rotating Air Inlet filter (RIF).
The RIF-device is shown in Figure 1. The RIF consists of a rotating
filter element which contains a large number of axial channels.
Solid and liquid particles down to 0.3 &#181;m in the air stream are
centrifuged towards the walls of these channels and collected.
In comparison with the conventional static filters, the RIF has
better collection efficiencies<SUP>1</SUP> in the whole range (0.3 - 10 &#181;m)
of particle diameters. It has the additional advantage of good
per-formance in high-humidity conditions, because it also collects
water droplets. The collection efficiency of the conventional
static filters decreases in these conditions.<BR>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Objectives<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
The main objectives of the project are:
<UL>
<LI>Increasing the pressure recovery of the RIF-device
by testing a different (better) outlet impeller.
<LI>Designing and testing a new inlet impeller to
decrease the pressure loss at the inlet of the filter element.
</UL>
<P>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Experimental research<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
A 15,000 m<SUP>3</SUP>/hr RIF-device is present to
test the improvements of the inlet and outlet impeller. The performance
is tested by measuring  the pump characteristics of the RIF-device.
Therefore the shaft power and the intake pressure are recorded.
<P>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Future Work<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
To increase the economic performance of the RIF-device
a simple air cooler based on water droplet evaporation will be
designed and tested in front of the RIF-device. This air-cooler
will increase the power output of a gas turbine.<BR>
<P>

<H5><SUP>1</SUP> G.H.M. Laagland (NV KEMA), J.J.H. Brouwers (UT) , J.Poorting (EPON), "The Rotating Air Inlet Filter for GasTurbines"<P></H5>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
