<HEAD>
<TITLE>Recovery of Acids and Bases from Brine Waste Water using Electrodialysis	
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Recovery of Acids and Bases from Brine Waste Water using Electrodialysis</H2>
PhD: Ir. C.R. Visser<BR>
Project term: November 1993 - November 1997<BR>
Co-operation: TNO (MEP) - Delft<BR>
Sponsor: IOP<BR>
tel. + e-mail : 050 - 3634885 / <A HREF="mailto:c.r.visser@chem.rug.nl">c.r.visser@chem.rug.nl</A><BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

The aim of this project is the development of
a technique which can reduce salt emissions
in industrial waste waters. Electrodialysis is
applied to produce acids and bases from salts
present in waste water. In some cases, this
technique can be economically feasible. An
expected tightening of (Dutch) environmental
legislation will increase the necessity of a
reduction of salt emissions. The aim of our
department is to perform model experiments
from which a mass transfer model is
developed, with which optimal process
conditions can be calculated. TNO will do
research into practical aspects of this
process, such as the pre-treatment of waste
water and membrane pollution. In contacts
with industry, pilot plants are developed for
particular applications.<P>

<B>Modelting the experiments</B><P>

A model description of the process uses the
Maxwell-Stefan differential mass transfer
equations to calculate the diffusion inside the
membranes and in both stagnant fluid films
on either side of the membranes. The multi-
component diffusion coefficients (for the
most simple system containing at least seven
components) will be calculated from
experiments with only one of the salts (in
solution) and one type of membrane present.
Four partial experiments have been carded
out: diffusion dialysis, electro-osmosis,
pressure driven salt fluxes and electric
resistance measurements. With the results the
six diffusion coefficients present in one salt-
membrane system can be calculated. At the
same time a number of additional
measurements are needed to obtain the
membrane equilibrium properties. To test the
computer model, a four-compartment
electrodialysis membrane stack was used to
produce hydrochloric acid and sodium
hydroxide from a sodium chloride solution.
Sodium sulphate was also tested.<P>

<IMG SRC="visser1.gif" WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=286><P>

<B>Stack configuration using mono-polar
membranes.</B><P>

The membranes used in the stack were the
Nation 450 cation exchange membrane by
Dupont and two types of anion exchange
membrane by Solvay. Concentrations and
volumes were monitored in time for
comparison with theory. At the moment
experiments using bipolar membranes are
being performed. The lower electrical energy
consumption of the process using bipolar
membranes is investigated.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B29-13</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000115-B022-28</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost96/rug/bosma.html 130.89.50.60 19970216182348 text/html 3793
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 18:17:10 GMT
