</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>More Efficient Process Chromatography
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>More Efficient Process Chromatography</H2>
Ph.D-student: ir. J.C. Bosma<BR>
Project term: august 1995 - juli 1999<BR>
Cooperation: TU Delft, Unilever, Gist Brocades, Diosynth, Pharmacia Biotech and DMV Campina<BR>
Sponsor: Ministry of economic affairs (IOP Preventie)<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER>INTRODUCTION</CENTER><P>

As a separation process chromatography is
expensive but it is also powerful and friendly to
the species it separates. This project focusses on
protein chromatography. The research can be split
into three levels:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>the overall separation process,
<LI>one chromatographic unit and
<LI>independent measurement of parameters.
</UL>

<CENTER>OVERALL SEPARATION PROCESS</CENTER><P>

Biotechnological separations usually exist of
several steps. To simulate the whole process a
computer program is being developed. The first
version of this program, PROSEP 1.0, can be used
as a leaming tool. Later versions should be helpful
in designing process cascades.<P>

<CENTER>CHROMATOGRAPHIC UNIT</CENTER><P>

The experimental part of the research will focus on
ion exchange chromatography and hydrofobic
interaction chromatography. To describe the
experiments we will develop models consisting of
two parts:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>
An equilibrium model which describes the
equilibrium in terms of chemical potentials. The
currently used Langmuir model has to be
changed, possibly with parts of the model
suggested by Myers and Beyington~ which
assumes different adsorption sites.
<LI>
The Maxwell-Stefan model2 which describes
the mass transfer in terms of the driving force
on a species being equal to its friction with the
other species:<P>

<IMG SRC="bosma1.gif" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=72><P>

In which i and j are components, mu is the chemical
potential, x is the molfraction, nu is the velocity and D is
the Maxwell-Stefan diffusion coefficient.
</UL>

<CENTER>INDEPENDANT MEASUREMENT OF MODEL PARAMETERS</CENTER><P>

System properties like adsorption equilibria, diffusion coefficients in the film and in the particles and
axial dispersion will be independently measured.
Some batch adsorption experiments have already been conducted. We measured adsorption
equilibria of fraction V Bovine Serum Albumin
(BSA) on Q-sepharose FF, a strong anion exchanger, in acetic acid. The measurements
could be described by a mass action model:<P>

<IMG SRC="bosma2.gif" WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=69><P>

In which subscript 1 denotes BSA and 2 acetic anions; c
denotes concentrations in the liquid and q in the resin,
both in mole/l; q<SUB>max</SUB> is the BSA binding capacity; K<SUB>1</SUB> is
an equilibrium constants and z<SUB>1</SUB> is the apparent charge
of a BSA-molecule.<P>

The fitted values are K<SUB>1</SUB> = 2657, z<SUB>1</SUB> = -1.7 e and
q<SUB>max</SUB> = 1.5 mM. The results are shown below.<P>

<IMG SRC="bosma3.gif" WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=301><P>

LITERATURE:<BR>
1. A.L. Myers and S. Byington, Thermodynamics of
ion exchange: prediction of multicomponent equilibria
from binary dam, in A.E. Rodrigues (ed.), Ion exchange:
science and technology, Martinus Nijhoff Publishers,
Dordrecht, 1986.<BR>
2. J.A. Wesselingh and R. Krishna, Mass transfer, Ellis Horwood Publishers, Chichester, 1990.<P>

