<HEAD>
<TITLE>Radical polymerisation in a Buss kneader
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Radical polymerisation in a Buss kneader</H2>
PhD student:	Ir. Erik Jan Troelstra (050-3637109)<BR>
Supervisors: 	Prof. Dr. ir. L. L. van Dierendonck, Prof. Dr. ir. L. P. B. M. Janssen<BR>
Project term: June 1993 - June 1997<BR>
Sponsor: AIO-network <BR>
Co-Sponsors: Buss AG (Basel), DSM (Geleen), CERS (Bern) <BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B> Introduction</B><BR>
The radical addition co-polymerisation of Butylacrylate (BA) and Hydroxyethyl-methacrylate (HEMA) is carried out in a Buss-Kneader PR46. To be able to model the polymerisation process the polymerisation kinetics has to be known as well as reactor characteristics like heat transfer and residence time distribution. The polymerisation kinetics are studied at the École Polytechnique Féderale Lausanne (Switzerland). With an axial dispersion model the polymerisation was modeled.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
The polymerisation was carried out at a screw and barrel set temperature of 125°C. A premix of 50/50 % (mass) of  BA and HEMA was mixed in a static mixer with the peroxide just before they entered the kneader. The axial temperature profile in the kneader is determined with six Fe/Co-thermocouples. The screw speed is varied between 60 and 285 rpm and the throughput is varied between 1 and 8 l/h. The samples were analysed on molecular weight by means of GPC and on conversion by means of gas chromatography.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
The conversion of HEMA was always higher than 95%, wheareas BA is converted typically to 70-90% depending on reaction conditions.
The used axial dispersion model contains parameters determined by the polymerisation kinetics, residence time distribution and heat transfer. The polymerisation kinetics were obtained from DSC experiments at the EPF Lausanne. Residence time distribution measurements as well as heat transfer measurements were carried out in our lab with model liquids. An example of the calculations is given in figure 1.<P>

<IMG SRC="troelstra1.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 1. Temperature profile at a screw speed of 285 rpm and a throughput of 3.3 l/h. The measured conversion was 83.2%. The curve was calculated with a Péclet number of 41, a residence time of 4 minutes and a heat transfer coefficient of 300 W/m<SUP>2</SUP>K. The calculated conversion was 90%.</I><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
