<HEAD>
<TITLE>Recycling of plastic waste by reactive extrusion
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Recycling of plastic waste by reactive extrusion</H2>
Ph. D student	: ir. Rienk Hettema (0503637109)<BR>
Supervisor	: Prof. Dr. Ir. L.P.B.M. Janssen<BR>
Project term	: august 1994 - august 1998<BR>
Sponsor	: IOP-MT/Recycling<BR>
</TD><TD> </TD></TR></TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The steady growth in the use of plastic materials in packaging applications has caused problems with solid waste disposal. Post-consumer recycling of plastics has therefore become necessary. The composition of this plastic waste stream is approximately as follows:<P>

<IMG SRC="hettema1.gif"><P>
 
The separation of these plastics into an individual polymeric type is costly and sometimes even impossible. Due to the incompatible nature of most polymers these commingled polymeric mixtures have poor mechanical properties.<P>

<B>Research topics</B><BR>
The objective of this study is to improve the compatibility of commingled plastic waste. The principle is to induce graft copolymerisation of the base blend components in the melt of an extruder. Graft copolymers are quite often prepared by adding a peroxide to generate radicals on the backbone of the blend components, followed by the addition of a selected monomer or other polymer, which grafts to the polymer.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
A major stream of post-consumer plastics is a commingled blend of polyethylenes and polypropylenes, for example HDPE from milk, water or detergent bottles with contamination of PP from sprouts or closures.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
In general the blended materials showed few signs of compatibility. Some mechanical properties such as modulus, strain at break, and impact strength are affected strongly by the addition of peroxide and monomer. The stress-strain behaviour of HDPE and three blends is shown in figure 2.<P>

<IMG SRC="hettema2.gif"><P>
 
The addition of a peroxide and a monomer results in a stronger and tougher blend. The IZOD impact strenght of the reactive extruded blend is 13.6 kJ/m<SUP>2</SUP>, equal to virgin HDPE.<BR>
The explanation for the improved properties is not quite clear yet, but DMTA results indicate an improved phase microheterogenity compared to the unmodified blend.<P>

<B>Conclusions</B><BR>
The mechanical properties of a mixture of HDPE and PP were improved through addition of a peroxide and a monomer in a counterrotating twin screw extruder. Reactive extrusion can be a relatively cheap method for improving the properties of a polymer blend with strong potential applications in recycling.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/12/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
