<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Production of plant cell secondary metabolites
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Production of plant cell secondary metabolites</H1>

Dr. Lucilla Bassetti<BR>
email: <A HREF="mailto:Lucilla.Bassetti@Algemeen.PK.WAU.NL">Lucilla.Bassetti@Algemeen.PK.WAU.NL</A>; tel: 0317-483770<BR>
sponsor: LUW<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

Typical plant cell secondary metabolites are valuable, intracellularly
stored products. Since almost no spontaneous release occurs under
physiological conditions, these compounds need to be recovered
by means of permeabilization procedures. Among them, destructive
techniques should be avoided if a continuous use or a re-use of
the biomass is requested. It is therefore essential to aim at
non-lethal methods for the release of such secondary products.
<P>
The use of non-conventional media to obtain increased production
and/or release of plant cell secondary metabolites is currently
under investigation in our department. We have been studying non-conventional
media in which an organic phase (liquid-liquid two-phase system)
or a surfactant (Pluronic F-68) were added. In both cases, addition
of these components triggered significantly the non-lethal efflux
plus the production of the selected secondary metabolites (anthraquinones,
produced by cell suspension cultures of <I>Morinda citrifolia</I>
-fam. <I>Rubiaceae</I>- and stored inside the cell vacuoles).
<P>
The release of anthraquinones from plant cells of <I>Morinda citrifolia</I>
involves the interaction of the non-conventional component (i.e.,
Pluronic F-68) with cell membranes, namely the tonoplast (vacuole
membrane) and the plasmamembrane. The next phases of our research
will be focused on this subject. In particular, the following
items will be studied:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>membrane structure (visualization and composition);
<LI>membrane functions (permeability and fluidity; transport of
selected fluorescent probes);
<LI>membrane mechanical properties (bursting tension, elastic
area compressibility modulus, cell size and viability). 
</UL>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
