<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Enzymatic synthesis of antibiotics</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Enzymatic synthesis of antibiotics</H1>

<B>Post-doctoral fellows: </B>Dr.ir. Karin Schro&euml;n, Dr. ir. Vincent Nierstrasz (tel. 0317-484708)<BR>
<B>Technical assistants: </B>Ing. Pieter Kroon, Ing. Rouke Bosma<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> May 1996 - May 1999<BR>
<B>E-mail:</B> <A HREF="mailto:Karin.Schroen@algemeen.pk.wau.nl">Karin.Schroen@algemeen.pk.wau.nl</A>; <A HREF="mailto:Vincent.Nierstrasz@algemeen.pk.wau.nl">Vincent.Nierstrasz@algemeen.pk.wau.nl</A><BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Chemferm, DSM, Gist Brocades and EZ<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
For the synthesis of semi-synthetic antibiotics the side-chains of penicillin G and V are replaced
by e.g. phenylglycine. In the past these reactions were performed
chemically. But nowadays enzymatic synthesis is gaining interest
because of a reduction in reaction steps (fig. 1) and a decrease
in the amount of waste product per kilogram of antibiotic.
<P>
<B>Enzymatic conversion</B><BR>
In many industrial processes the chemical removal of side-chains
is replaced by an enzymatic reaction step (hydrolysis) for which
immobilised penicillin acylase is used. The same enzyme also catalyses
the reverse reaction, which makes the coupling of  different side
chains possible. However the enzymatic coupling is not yet economic
and improvement of the enzymatic process is required. In order
to achieve this, an interdisciplinary project, in which 5 universitairy
research groups and Chemferm (a joint-venture of Gist Brocades
and DSM) participate, is initiated.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="chemferm1.gif">
<P>
<B>Figure 1.</B><FONT SIZE=2> Cefalexin synthesis.</FONT>
<P>
At the Food and Bioprocess Engineering group of the Wageningen
Agricultural University the following subjects are studied:
<P>
<B>Thermodynamic aspects and reaction kinetics</B><BR>
Our aim is to achieve a direct (solid-to-solid)
conversion of substrates without modification. Data about equilibrium
values of the reaction, solubilities of substrates and products
as a function of pH and temperature are necessary for the evaluation
of the conversion. Further the enzyme specificity and kinetics
and also the effects of organic solvents will be considered. An
overview of all the facets that are important for the enzymatic
synthesis of antibiotics will be obtained.
<P>
<B>Reactor development and downstream processing</B><BR>
The reaction conditions need to be
optimized. Reuse of the enzyme and methods for product removal
have to be considered in order to achieve an integrated design.
Also for this project addition of organic solvents is one of the
options that will be considered for solid-to-solid conversion.

