<HEAD>
<TITLE>Cultivation of immobilized micro-algae under intermittent exposure to photosynthesis inducing radiation
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Cultivation of immobilized micro-algae under intermittent exposure to photosynthesis inducing radiation</H1>

OIO:   Marcel Janssen<BR>
Sponsors:  SON, WAU<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Micro-algae can be used for the production of a wide variety of
compounds. These compounds range from energy sources to health
food products. Furthermore they can be used for wastewater treatment
sytems for the bioremoval of nitrogen compounds, phosphate and
heavy metals. Micro-algae have a simple nutrient demand and can
use sunlight as an energy source. The carbon source used is carbon
dioxide (CO<SUB>2</SUB>), a greenhouse gas. A problem is efficient
use of sunlight. Micro-algae exposed to full sunlight show a lower
yield of biomass on light energy as compared to algae exposed
to low light intensities.<BR>
<P>
<B>Aim</B><BR>
The purpose of this project is to study the possibility of increasing
the yield of biomass on light energy at high irradiances by intermittent
illumination, i.e. dark-light cycle times of 10-100 sec. with
dark fractions of 0-80%. <BR>
<P>
<B>Research</B><BR>
The effects of intermittent illumination are studied with <I>Chlamydomonas
reinhardtii</I> and <I>Chlorella vulgaris fo. tertia </I>(both
green algae). The algae are cultivated in continuously operated
turbidostats. The light regime is constant during the cultivation.
<I>Chlamydomonas</I> has been shown to increase its capacity to
produce oxygen (O<SUB>2</SUB>) when cultivated under intermittent
illumination. At irradiances above 300 mol photons.m<SUP>-2</SUP>.sec<SUP>-1</SUP>
this production is maximal. Altough the algae don't receive light
during one third of the cutivation time this maximum doesn't decrease
with one third, see figure.
<P>
<IMG SRC="janssen1.gif"><BR>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Figure:</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=1> O<SUB>2</SUB>
production of <I>Chlamydomonas reinhardtii</I> adapted to continuous
or intermittent illumination of 200 mol photons (PAR).m<SUP>-2</SUP>.sec<SUP>-1</SUP>.
This is determined in a separate vessel at a range of light intensities.
The culture adapted to intermittent illumination also is illuminated
intermittently in this vessel. The light intensities given are
the light intensities during the light period for the experiments
under intermittent illumination.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
By using a statistical experimental setup the influence of the
following parameters on algal growth and light absorption will
be determined and modelled:
<P>
- dark-light cycle length<BR>
- dark fraction<BR>
- light intensity<BR>
<P>
<B>Future Research</B><BR>
After this the characteristics of growth of micro-algae immobilized
in -carrageenan gel beads will be studied. This is of interest
because immobilization offers a number of advantages above cultivation
of free cells. A model describing the penetration of light in
the gel beads will be developed. Other points of interest are
the supply of CO<SUB>2</SUB> and the removal of produced O<SUB>2</SUB>.
This is done to be sure that the supply of &quot;valuable&quot;
light is growth limiting for the immobilized cells.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
