<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Effect of Structral Changes During Processing on Textural Quality of Dried Food Products
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Effect of Structral Changes During Processing on Textural Quality of Dried Food Products</H1>

<U>Post-doc fellow</U> Juan Mat&eacute;<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:Juan.Mate@Algemeen@PK.WAU.NL">Juan.Mate@Algemeen@PK.WAU.NL</A><BR>
<U>Sponsor</U>  Wageningen Agricultural University<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

One of the most important and less studied topics of quality of
dried food is texture. Texture quality changes occurred not only
during drying but also during the rest of the processing chain
(from raw material to rehydrated food product). This changes in
texture are strongly related to changes in the internal structure
of the food. By controlling the changes in structure during processing,
it is possible to control the texture of the final product. The
objective of this research is to study how changes in structure
during processing affect the textural quality of the final dried
product.
<P>
Blanching is a pretreatment of the drying processing chain of
fruits and vegetables aim to denature enzymes that can cause darkening
of the product during drying and after rehydration. Blanching
is usually a heat treatment (with hot water or steam). Blanching
affects the internal structure and texture of the food product
and thus it could be used as a tool to provide controlled change
s in the structure of the food product.
<P>
<IMG SRC="mate1.gif">
<P>
During this research two tasks are being accomplished: 1) Characterisation
of blanching, that is how blanching affects the structural quality
of the product. 2) Effect of the changes in structure over the
textural quality of the dried product.
<P>
Potatoes were chosen as the food product to perform this study.
Potatoes are structurally quite homogeneous and are readily available.
Furthermore, dried potato slices and cubes are commercial products
of economical importance (for soups and salads). Results can be
generalised to other starch-rich natural foods. For the characterisation
of blanching, degree of starch gelatinization, water uptake and
loss of soluble solids as well as compression tests are being
performed for different blanching conditions. Mechanical properties
such as hardness, brittleness, elasticity as well as macroscopic
structural parameters such as porosity or shrinkage are being
measured to study the effect of blanching on the textural quality.
In addition rehydration tests are also part of this study.<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
