<HEAD>
<TITLE>Validation of a model for Solid-State Fermentation in a scraped drum fermentor
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Validation of a model for Solid-State Fermentation in a scraped drum fermentor</H1>
<TABLE>
<TD>
<B>AIO</B> : Ir. F.J.I. Nagel<BR>
<B>Phone</B> : 0317-483770<BR>
<B>Project term  </B>: 1995 - 1999<BR>
<B>Sponsor</B>  : OSPT<BR>
</TD>
<TD>
<IMG SRC="nagel.gif">
</TD>
</TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>
<P>
<IMG SRC="nagel1.gif">
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2>Fig 1 : The fate of water in Solid-state Fermentation</FONT></I>
<P>
<B>Solid-State Fermentation</B><BR>
Solid-State Fermentation (SSF) is the cultivation of micro-organisms
on moist solid substrates in the absence of free flowing water.
The physical and biological behaviour of SSF are poorly understood;
scale-up is accomplished by trial and error.
<P>
<B>Aim of the project</B><BR>
Our aim is to solve one of the major scale-up problems: simultaneous
control of temperature and water activity.
<P>
<IMG SRC="nagel2.jpg">
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2>Fig 2 : Scraped Drum Fermentor</FONT></I>
<P>
<B>Current research</B><BR>
Full-scale SSF systems are cooled by evaporation. Furthermore,
water is taken up in the cytoplasm of new biomass. Metabolic water
production cannot keep up with these two processes (Fig 1). Water
addition is required to prevent dessication of the solid matrix.
<P>
A dynamic mathematical model is developed to predict the amount
of extracellular water in SSF. The model incorporates biokinetics,
stiochiometry and physical equilibria.
<P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="nagel3.gif">
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=2>Fig 3 : Experimental setup</FONT></I>
<P>
<B>Experimental set-up for model validation</B><BR>
A Scraped-Drum Fermentor (1.5 dm<SUP>3</SUP>, Fig 2) is used to
cultivate <I>Rhizopus oligosporus</I> on agar beads with a defined
glucose medium.
<P>
The experimental set-up (Fig 3) can simulate the nearly adiabatic
behaviour of large-scale SSF systems. Various temperatures, inlet
and outlet air humidity, CO<SUB>2</SUB> and O<SUB>2</SUB> are
measured on-line; Biomass dry weight, residual substrate and moisture
content of the agar beads are measured off-line.
<P>
<B>E-mail</B> : <A HREF="mailto:frank-jan.nagel@algemeen.pk.wau">frank-jan.nagel@algemeen.pk.wau</A><BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
