<HEAD>
<TITLE>Scale up of insect cell cultures for the production of viral biopesticides
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Scale up of insect cell cultures for the production of viral biopesticides</H1>

Aio:  Ir. A. van Oorschot<BR>
Sponsor: Commission of the European Communities.<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Baculoviruses are used for the control of insect pests. They are
specific for only a few, related insect species. From the environmental
point of view, they form a good alternative to chemical pesticides.
For the production of baculoviruses using insect cells, large-scale
production is pivotal for economic reasons. Such large-scale animal-
cell cultures require aeration by means of direct sparging with
air or pure oxygen. Much research has been done on the effects
of gas bubbles in relation to cell damage, mainly in lab-scale
bioreactors. In contrast, hardly any information is available
with cells in bioreactors at a large scale. <BR>
<P>
<B>Aim</B><BR>
The research aims at the development of a low-cost system on a
larger scale for the production of insect viruses in bioreactors.
<BR>
<P>
<B>Set-up</B><BR>
The killing of insect cells at lab-scale and pilot-scale was tested
in airlifts using:<BR>
- A constant reactor height of 1 m (7.2 Liter volume) and a variable
gas flow rate in the range 100-1000 Liter per hour<BR>
- A constant gas flow rate of 450 Liter per hour and a variable
column height in the range 0.5-3 m, which corresponded with 3.5
to 21 liter volume, respectively.
<P>
<IMG SRC="oorschot1.gif"><BR>
<P>
<B>Results and discussion</B><BR>
According to the specific hypothetical killing volume theory,
the death rate of cells is determined by the size of the specific
hypothetical killing volume (X'), the gas flow rate (Fg) and the
volume (V) used. In equation form: <IMG SRC="oorschot2.gif">.
<P>
The calculated death-rates of insect cells for the large-scale
experiments are shown in figure 1. Linear regression indicate
a constant X' of 0.004 which is the same as found at lab-scale.
Since both X' and the oxygen consumption per cell are easy to
determine, bioreactor design is facilitated. <BR>
<P>
<B>Reference</B><BR>
Tramper, J., Smit, D., Straatman, J., and Vlak, J.M. Bubble-column
design for growth of fragile insect cells.<I> Bioprocess Engineering
</I>3:37-41, 1988. 

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
