<HEAD>
<TITLE>Modelling fungal growth on solid substrates
for design and control of Solid State Fermentations</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Modelling fungal growth on solid substrates
for design and control of Solid State Fermentations</H1>

<TABLE>
<TD>
<A HREF="mailto:jaap.oostra@algemeen.pk.wau.nl">jaap.oostra@algemeen.pk.wau.nl</A><BR>
0317-483770<BR>
PhD-fellow: Ir. Jaap Oostra<BR>
Supervisors: Prof. J. Tramper, dr. A. Rinzema<BR>
Project term: July 1995 - July 1999<BR>
Sponsors: NWO-STW<BR>
</TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="oostra.gif"></TD>
</TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Solid State Fermentation (SSF) is the cultivation of micro-organisms
- mostly fungi - on moist solid particles in the absence of free
flowing water. The physical and biological behaviour of SSF are
poorly understood; scale up is accomplished by trial and error.
<P>
<B>Aim</B><BR>
Development of a mathematical model for the description of fungal
growth at particle level to provide insight into biokinetics and
physical (transport) phenomena.
<P>
<B>Systems used for modelling</B><BR>
For modelling fungal growth, three systems with increasing complexity
are used (Figure 1).<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="oostra1.gif">
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=1>Fig. 1: Different systems for modelling SSF</FONT></I><BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=1>  1. Liquid covered with membrane</FONT></I><BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=1>  2. Gel matrix covered with membrane</FONT></I><BR>
<I><FONT SIZE=1>  3. Gel matrix without membrane</I></FONT><BR>
<P>
<B>Model</B><BR>
The model is developed for an overculture: homogeneous growth
over the surface. Some model assumptions are:
<UL>
<LI>Only hyphae in contact with surface (X<SUB>surf</SUB>) can
take up substrate (Figure 2)
<LI>Aerial hyphae (X<SUB>air</SUB>) develop when X<SUB>surf </SUB>reaches
maximum
<LI>Monod kinetics
<LI>Substrate is used for growth and maintenance
</UL>
<P>
Models based on similar assumptions have been published [1, 2,
3], but have not been properly validated.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="oostra2.gif">
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=1>Fig. 2: Concept of X<I><SUB>air</SUB> and X<SUB>surf
<BR>
</SUB></I></FONT></I>
<P>
Model predictions for <I>Rhizopus oligosporus</I>, based on literature
values are shown in figure 3.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="oostra3.gif"><BR>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=1>Fig. 3: Model predictions for biomass and glucose
in system 2</FONT></I>
<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=1>D=3.6*10<I><SUP>-7</SUP>  m<SUP>2</SUP> h<SUP>-1</SUP>,
h=0.005 m, K<SUB>s</SUB>=0.2 kg m<SUP>-3</SUP>, q<SUB>s</SUB>=0.27
kg glucose kg<SUP>-1</SUP> biomass  h<SUP>-1</SUP>, m<SUB>s</SUB>=0.018
kg glucose kg<SUP>-1</SUP> biomass   h<SUP>-1</SUP>, Y<SUB>xs</SUB>=0.4
kg biomass  kg<SUP>-1</SUP> glucose<BR>
</I></FONT></I>
<P>
In the future, parameters will be experimentally determined for
systems 1 and 2 and the model will be extended for system 3.<BR>
<P>
<B>References</B><BR>
<FONT SIZE=1>Georgiou, G., <I>et al</I>. (1986) <I>Biotechnol.
Bioeng.</I> 28, 405-416.</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=1>Mitchell, D.A. <I>et al</I>. (1991) <I>Biotechnol.
Bioeng</I>. 38, 353-362.</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=1>Molin, P., <I>et al</I>. (1993) <I>Biotechnol. Prog</I>.
9, 385-393.</FONT><BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

