<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Cultivation of sponges</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Cultivation of sponges</H1>
Dr Ronald Osinga<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:ronald.osinga@algemeen.pk.wau.nl">ronald.osinga@algemeen.pk.wau.nl</A><BR>
Sponsor: Wageningen Agricultural University<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

Sponges (phylum Porifera) are the most primitive multicellular
organisms within the kingdom of the animals. Around 10.000 species
of sponges have been described, of which the majority is found
in marine environments. In the last decades, marine sponges have
been discovered as an important source of useful chemical compounds,
such as, for instance, medicines. However, the concentrations
of these compounds inside the sponge tissue are often very low,
so that a large amount of sponge biomass is needed to produce
the compounds of interest in significant amounts. Hence, when
we want to produce natural products from sponges on a commercial
scale, harvesting sponge biomass from the sea will not be a durable
solution. This realization indicates the need for methods to cultivate
sponges. 
<P>
At present, only maricultures of sponges have been used succesfully:
sponges are cut into pieces, which are placed on ropes in the
sea. The sponge pieces then regenerate into fullgrown sponges.
This method has the disadvantage that it depends on the outdoor
circumstances, which are not always optimal for growth. Cultivation
of sponges under conditions that are permanently optimal may be
possible in bioreactors, but up till now, information on cultivation
of sponges in bioreactors is scarce and often anecdotal. The first
aim of this research project, which was started recently, is therefore
to determine which factors are important for the growth and maintenance
of sponges under laboratory conditions. If we succeed in developing
a basal, general cultivation method for marine sponges, the next
aim is to find the optimal growth conditions for different species
of sponges, and to construct bioreactors that are suitable for
cultivation under these conditions. 
<P>
It is known that sponges can consume large amounts of food, and
that they need relatively clean water to live in. To meet these
requirements, a system as shown in Figure 1 is the first approach
of  a bioreactor that will be tested: a continuous culture of
microalgae will supply the reactor with food particles, which
are filtered out of the water by the sponges. Meanwhile, the outflow
of seawater out of the sponge reactor will remove the waste products
of the sponges, thus keeping the water quality on an acceptable
level.<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="osinga1.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>Figure 1: A sponge reactor fed by a continuous cultureof microalgae.</CENTER>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
