<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Enantioselective membrane separations
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Enantioselective membrane separations</H1>

<B>PhD-fellow:</B> Pieter Overdevest (project term, June 1995 - June 1999)<BR>
Supported by  Technology Foundation (STW), AKZO-Nobel and DSM<BR>
<B>PhD-fellow:</B> Ed van der Ent (project term, June 1996 - June 2000)<BR>
<P>
Supported by Wageningen Agricultural University

<HR SIZE=0>

<H2><I>INTRODUCTION</I></H2>

Chiral compounds are often applied in agrochemical, food and pharmaceutical
industries. Both the production of chiral compounds which can
be labour intensive and the separation of a racemic mixture are
possible options to obtain pure chiral products. Therefore, resolution
of enantiomers is an important field in separation science. As
a result of equal physical properties of these optical isomers,
the separation needs to be fulfilled in a chiral environment to
introduce diastereomeric interactions.

<H2><I>MEMBRANE SEPARATION PROCESSES</I></H2>

Two enantioseparation processes based on membranes are studied
at the department:

<OL>
<LI>The first project aims to anchor chiral selector molecules
in a microheterogeneous phase. These chiral selectors have different
affinities for enantiomers. Selective adsorption of enantiomers
by chiral selectors and application of ultrafiltration make enantiomer
separation possible; unassociated enantiomers pass the membrane
and complexed enantiomers do not pass (figure 1).
<LI>The system in the second project consists of a chiral selector
coated ultrafiltration or nanofiltration membrane. One of the
enantiomers will adsorb preferentially onto the chiral selector
coating. Since at the permeate side, a very low enantiomer activity
is present, the enantiomers start hopping over the free chiral
selectors and finally will desorb on the permeate side (figure
2).
</OL>
We aim at the description, application and optimisation of these
separation processes.

<P>
<IMG SRC="overdeve1.gif"><BR>
<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>Figure 1.</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> Resolution by
membrane separation with the use of chiral selectors fixed in
micelles. Micelles are unable to pass the membrane.</FONT>

<P>
<IMG SRC="overdeve2.gif"><BR>
<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=2>Figure 2.</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> Surface diffusion
in membrane pore.</FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
