<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Mass production of fungal antagonists by solid-state fermentation
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Fungal antagonists production by solid-substrate fermentation</H1>

<B>Post-doc: </B>Dr. Ing. Frans J. Weber<BR>
<B>E-Mail: </B><A HREF="mailto:Frans.weber@algemeen.pk.wau">Frans.weber@algemeen.pk.wau</A><BR>
<B>Sponsor: </B>Commission of the European Communities<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
For many years chemical pesticides have been used intensively
to control pests. The growing awareness of the adverse effects
of pesticides on man and his environment has resulted in more
attention for biological control. An example of an effective biocontrol
agent is <I>Coniothyrium minitans</I>, a fungus that can be used
to control <I>Sclerotinia sclerotiorum</I>, a widespread plant
pathogen affecting more than 360 plant species.
<P>
Generally, fungal spores retain an high viability during drying
and storage. Therefore, the use of fungal spores as biocontrol
agent is very promising. However, most fungi do not form spores
in submerged fermentations. On laboratory scale spore production
has been achieved in solid-substrate fermentations (growth on
moist solid particles in the absence of free flowing water) for
a wide range of fungi.<BR>
<P>
<B>Bottle-necks for mass-production of spores by solid-substrate
fermentation</B>
<P>
Although the use of solid-substrate fermentations for the production
of fermented food in Asia goes back as far as 1000 years BC, solid-substrate
fermentations are only scarcely used in the modern Western world.
<P>
The use of solid-substrate fermentations for the mass production
of antagonistic spores is hampered by lack of knowledge about:
(1) the intrinsic kinetics of fungal growth and spores formation.
(2) difficulties in controlling the physical conditions in solid-substrate
bioreactors. For instance, simultaneous maintenance of optimal
temperature and moisture levels is almost impossible. The metabolic
heat of the fungus is largely removed from the fermentor by evaporation
of water. Together with the incorporation of water into cytoplasm
of the fungus, this causes desiccation of the substrate, which
will have an adverse effect on the fungus.<BR>
<P>
<B>Aim</B>
<P>
The aim of the project is (1) to identify the physiological and
technical parameters influencing the inactivation of spores during
drying, and (2) to establish rules for the design of a solid-substrate
fermentor for the mass-production of high-quality spores of <I>C.
minitans</I>, based on knowledge of growth and sporulation kinetics
and transport phenomena.<BR>
<P>
<B>Results</B>
<P>
The first results have shown that a small reduction in water-activity
severely inhibited growth of <I>C. minitans</I>. (Fig. 1). These
results clearly show that maintenance of a high water-activity
in a solid-state fermentor is of utmost importance. Further research
will focus on methods to minimise the reduction in water-activity
in the reactor combined with an effective removal of metabolic
heat.
<P>
<IMG SRC="weber1.gif">
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Fig 1:</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> Effect of a reduced
water-activity on the growth rate of <I>C. minitans</I>.</FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
