<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Development of a Liquid-Liquid-Solid Fluid Bed Bioreactor
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Development of a Liquid-Liquid-Solid Fluid Bed Bioreactor</H2></FONT></B>

Erik van Zessen<BR>
0317-482240<BR>
<A HREF="mailto:Erik.vanZessen@algemeen.pk.wau.nl">Erik.vanZessen@algemeen.pk.wau.nl</A><BR>
Sponsored by ABON<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B>
<P>
A fluidised bed reactor has attractive characteristics for application
in the bioprocesindustry. Such a fluidised bed is a feasible reactorconcept
as the solid phase is easily contained in the reactor. Compared
with a stirred tank for example, particle abrasion will be less
in a fluidised bed due to the harsher conditions in a stirred
tank. This particle breakage can be a large problem as we use
gel particles, like kappa-carrageenan or alginate, as a solid matrix
for the immobilization of the biocatalyst. Removal of product
to enlarge the performance of the reactor can be done by the <I>in
situ</I> extraction with an organic solvent.  The reactor system
is schematically shown in figure 1. The model system consist of
water, dodecane and kappa-carrageenan beads. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="zessen1.gif">
<P>
<I>figure 1 Reactor system</I>
<P>
<B>Objectives</B>
<P>
Development of a general design strategy for a three-phase fluid
bed reactor in such a way that the production rate is as high
as possible by understanding the different processes acting in
this type of reactor.<BR>
<P>
<B>Theory</B>
<P>
Firstly I studied the hold-up of the different phases. These hold-ups
are described with the drift flux model. This model is shown schematically
in figure 2.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="zessen2.gif">
<P>
<B>Results</B>
<P>
The results and the predictions are shown in figure 3. This figure
shows that the experimental data are rather well predicted.
<P>
<IMG SRC="zessen3.gif">
<P>
<I>Figure 3. Experimental and predicted solid hold-ups (see fig 2).</I>
<P>
<B>Future Research</B>
<P>
A more complete understanding of the different hold-ups. Furthermore
investigation of the flow patterns through residence time distribution
and evaluation of mass transfer between the three different phases.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
