<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Optimal enzymatic conversion of starch
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H1>Optimal enzymatic conversion of starch</H1>
PhD-student:Leon Marchal<BR>
Sponsors: Avebe, PBTS Biotechnology<P>

<HR SIZE=0><P>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The hydrolysis of starch to low-molecular weight
products using an alpha-amylase is one of the biggest
commercial enzyme processes. The hydrolysed
products are widely applied in the food, paper
and textile industry. Although the alpha-amylolytic
conversion of starch is a classical process,
detailed knowledge on industrial scale (high dry
weight concentrations) is scarce.<P>

<B>Aim</B><BR>
The aim of this research is to obtain a better
insight in the way the process conditions
influence the enzymatic conversion of starch.
This can be used for better process controllability
(narrow product specification) and / or cheaper
production process.<P>

<B>Research</B><BR>
This research started by looking both at a
measuring method used in the starch industry
(D.E.) as on the process conditions that influence
the hydrolysation of starch with an alpha-amylase.
The parameter for the degree of hydrolysis of
starch is the dextrose equivalent (D.E.):<P>

<IMG SRC="marchal1.gif">
<P>

The commonly used titration methods such as
Luff-Schoorl and Lane-Eynon overestimate D.E.
The overestimation varies for different saccharides. As an alternative, D.E. can be obtained
from:<P>

<IMG SRC="marchal2.gif">
<P>

in which osm is the osmolality (= molality in this
case) directly obtained from the freezing-point
depression.<P>

<IMG SRC="marchal3.gif">
<P>
Fig 1: D.E. of several oligosaccharides (dextrose-
maltoheptaose).<P>

To study the influence of pH, temperature, added
calcium, enzyme dosage, dry weight and stirring
speed on the alpha-amylolytic hydrolysis a central
composite design experimental design was used.
New amylopectin potato starch, lacking amylose,
was used because of its low tendency for
retrogradation.<P>

<IMG SRC="marchal4.gif">
<P>

Fig 2: The hydrolysis speed (at D.E. 20) influenced by
Calcium addition and Temperature.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/11/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
