<H3>Verslag cursus "Adsorptive Processes"</H3>

Report on the Advanced Course on "Adsorptive Processes: Fundamentals, Design and Operation", organized by OSPT and PTE, October 30 - November 3, 1995, At Eindhoven University of Technology.<BR>
The teachers were: Professors Piet J.A.M. Kerkhof (Eindhoven), Alírio E. Rodrigues (Porto) and Tom Reith (Twente). Course director was professor Piet Kerkhof, and as a special guest dr. Freek Kapteijn of Delft reported on zeolite membrane diffusion. Organizing assistance was provided by Ms. Anniek van Bemmelen, Ir. Bas Kroes and dr.ir. W.J. Coumans. The course was attended by 20 very active participants, two of whom came from industry and the others from university. The academic participants were a mix from staff, undergraduate, twaio's and Ph.D. students. As expected most came from the process groups at the universities represented in the OSPT; it should be noted that 3 participants work in the Eindhoven catalysis group. As reference material the book of Yang, chapters from other books, paper reprints, specially written compilations and topical chapters, written exercises, and last but not least copies of the slides, were provided to the participants, in total about 1000 pages. Especially prepared computer programs were provided; most of them with explanatory notes and manuals and source code, so the participants can also adapt them for other problems. The package PDESOLTM of NUMERICA® was provided on a license basis to the participants, and a number of exercises on column phenomena was specially preprogrammed for the course within this package. Other exercises made use of spreadsheets. Although warm sometimes, the classroom at the Eindhoven Rekencentrum provided ample opportunity for both lectures and computer exercises in groups. All programs and exercises were provided to the participants on floppy disks also. The area covered was broad and ranged from gas adsorption (PSA) to liquid chromatography; in a systematically built up sequence of lectures and exercises the matter was presented in such a way that participants showed great appreciation for the course. In the sections on fundamentals from a small number of basics specials cases were derived. In equilibria the site-oriented theories (Langmuir, BET, etc.), potential theory (Dubinin), porefilling, and Gibbs surface energy based theories (Henry, co-volume, Harkins-Jura, IAS, VSM) as well as correlations were treated for single and multi-component systems. Exercises were provided on the analysis of experimental data and the predictionof multicomponent equilibria, as well as the determination of the final situation in multicomponent batch adsorption. Column processes were based on a fundamental treatment of mass transfer kinetics, hydrodynamics, axial dispersion, dispersive and compressive wave formation and heat transfer, and extended with the effects of intraparticle convection. Numerical exercises showed the effects of equilibrium breakthrough as well as kinetic separations, both for the liquid phase and for gas adsorption. Multicomponent equilibrium breakthrough exercises showed the complicated patterns of roll-up and plateaus. Intraparticle kinetics were based on the Maxwell-Stefan equations and special cases were derived (Fickian diffusion, Nernst-Planck, gaseous diffusion, diffusion in porous media, Krishna surface and zeolite diffusion, Kouyoumdjiev & Vorstman parallel pore and surface diffusion, Srinivasan bottleneck theory) and later extended by recent results on the zeolite membrane work at Delft. Attention was paid to the basis and limitations of the Linear Driving Force approximation. Process systems for PSA were treated starting from the Skarstrom 2-step cycle through the Guerin-Domine 3-step process towards pressure equalization and Rapid PSA, and self-purging systems, with all the basic characteristics. To this temperature effects were added as well as intraparticle convection effects. In liquid phase adsorption attention was paid to parametric pumping by temperature swing adsorption, Simulated Moving Bed processes, chemical and physical regeneration as well as washing steps. Interesting exercises on these topics were carried out. Also the subject of adsorptive reactors was treated. In the evaluation the participants showed their appreciation for the course program, the reference material, the lectures and the exercises, and made some useful comments for future treatment of exercise material. They appreciated the international character of the course as a factor adding value to it. The commercial PDESOL package, based on Schiesser's methof of lines was a very valuable tool in the exercises, which was strongly enhanced by the preprogramming of examples by prof. Reith and the distribution of working demos to the participants 2 weeks before the course. The participants expect fruitful use of the course material and programs in their future activities. The preparation and realization of the course has brought with it extra costs in traveling, development of special programs and attainment of licenses for PDESOL, copyright payments for the material and use of computer facilities. The financial support from the OSPT has made this possible. This, and the considerable efforts of the teachers and organizers, have made this course in a single step well-balanced and succesful. We expect that there will be sufficient interest in future for organizing such a course typically every two years. In order to balance the course budget, we will further increase our efforts to have participants from industry, but also a somewhat higher contribution from academic participants will be required.<P>

Piet J.A.M. Kerkhof, course editor<P>

