<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>OSPT Nieuws juni 1996</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H3>OSPT-Cursussen</H3>

<A HREF="#distillation"><B>Distillation, Absorption and Extraction</B></A><P>

<A NAME="distillation"></A><I>11 - 15 november 1996</I><BR>
<B>Distillation, Absorption and Extraction</B><BR>
An advanced Course at the University of Twente.<BR>
<I>Objectives</I><BR>
The course deals with design and operation of the important industrial multicomponent separations: distillation, absorption and extraction. It will provide you with state-of-the-art procedures on:
<UL>
<LI>multicomponent phase equilibria, ideal and non-ideal,
<LI>rigorous equilibrium stage calculations,
<LI>hydrodynamics and mixing in trays, packings and stirred columns and 
<LI>most importantly: non-equilibrium multicomponent stage calculations (based on thermodynamics of irreversible processes).
</UL>

The emphasis will be on fundamentals, although empiricalcorrelations will be used where necessary.<BR>
<I>The course</I><BR>
This is a five days course organized by the 'Onderzoekschool Procestechnologie' (Graduate School Process Engineering of the Dutch Universities). It is to be held at the 'Rekencentrum' of the University of Twente. The course is given by Professors J.A. Wesselingh (Groningen), T. Reith (Twente) and R. Krishna (Amsterdam).<BR>
<I>Who should participate</I><BR>
The course has been set up for Ph.D. students in Chemical Engineering, but industrial designers and specialists are also welcome. It is not an introductory course. We expect you to have a background in thermodynamics, transport phenomena and elements of separation processes. We will be pushing you as far as our knowledge and the time of one week permit. You will spend half of the time on intensive computer exercises together with the other participants. Many of the exercises will make use of 'ChemSep 3', a multi-component non-equilibrium program written by R. Taylor and H. Kooiman of Clarkson University. The course represents a new development in Separation Engineering. Our documentation is good and is still being improved.<BR>
<I>Course outline</I><BR>
Monday:<BR>
introduction and course strategy, equilibrium stage calculations on the computer, hydrodynamics and design of trays, determining the operating limits of an existing column<BR>
Tuesday:<BR>
introduction to multicomponent mass tranfer, mass transfer in multiphase mixtures, the non-equilibrium multicomponent model, non-equilibrium effects (efficiencies) in multi-component distillation<BR>
Wednesday:<BR>
high pressure distillation, non-ideal equilibria using NRTL, UNIFAC and UNIQUAC, extractive and azeotropic distillation<BR>
Thursday:<BR>
hydrodynamics and mass transfer in packed columns, vacuum distillation, non-isothermal absorption, equilibria in liquid-liquid extraction<BR>
Friday:<BR>
choice of equipment, hydrodynamics of tray columns and rotating disk contactors for extraction, non-equilibrium modelling of extraction, course evaluation.<BR>
<I>Fees and registration</I><BR>
The fee for the course is fl. 3.000,--. University participants obtain a reduction, so that their payment is limited to fl. 500,--. This includes: the latest version of the non-equilibrium program ChemSep for personal use (including documentation), the book of R. Krishna and R. Taylor "Multi-component Mass Transfer", Wiley 1993, lecture notes, documentation of the many examples you will work through during the course and lunch & coffee. To register for the course, please write a short letter with your name, address, telephone number and a short indication of your current job to: professor T. Reith, Department of Chemical Engineering, University of Twente, PO Box 217, 7500 AE Enschede, The Netherlands. For further information you can phone 053 - 489 2921/489 3017 or fax 053 - 489 4821.<P>

