<H3>Overige cursussen</H3>

<A HREF="#fundamental"><B>Fundamental Characteristics of Bubble Columns and Gas-LiquidSolid Fluidization Systems</B></A><BR>
<A HREF="#scale-up"><B>Scale-up</B></A><P>

<A NAME="fundamental"><I>22 en 23 augustus 1996</I><BR>
<B>Fundamental Characteristics of Bubble Columns and Gas-LiquidSolid Fluidization Systems</B><BR>
Two-day seminar held during 22 and 23 August 1996 at the University of Amsterdam, Department of Chemical Engineering. All lectures will be held in Room C206, Van 't Hoff Instituut, Nieuwe Achtergracht 166, 1018 WV Amsterdam<P>

A series of four advanced lectures will be presented by Professors Fan and Hyndman on 22 and 23 August 1996. The lectures are open to all interested university and industrial researchers.  There are no fees for attendance and registration is not required. Just turn up at the mentioned time and place. Please note that no assistance can be offered for parking etc; participants will need to make their own arrangements. No lunches etc can be provided to participants.<BR>
<I>Thursday 22 August 1996, 1030-1200 h</I><BR>
Gas phase flow and hold-up structure in bubble columns by Prof. Caroline Hyndman, University of Calgary, Canada Gas phase flow in bubble columns has commonly been described by an axial dispersion model. Thus, the complex flow behaviour is modelled by a single average velocity with a dispersion coefficient. This type of model has proven to be inappropriate in the industrially important churn turbulent regime. At higher superficial gas velocities a distribution of bubble sizes and velocities exist in bubble columns. A convective model based on a bubble velocity distribution and many plug flow models superimposed has been verified with non-intrusive radioactive tracer data. The model may be used to calculate an average bubble velocity distribution over the column. Researchers have shown that while a population of uniformlysized bubbles exists in the bubbly flow regime, gas hold-up structure for the churn turbulent regime consists of large and small bubble populations. Dynamic gas disengagement experiments are normally performed to determine the gas hold-up for each population of bubbles. A kinetic model based on rules of bubble interaction has been proposed to predict overall gas hold-up in the bubbly and churn turbulent flow regimes as well as the fraction of gas hold-up in the form of large bubbles for the churn turbulent regime. The kinetic model has been verified with dynamic gas disengagement data. Results from the above mentioned modelling approaches to gas phase flow and gas hold-up structure in bubble columns will be presented.<BR>
<I>Thursday 22 August 1996, 1400 - 1700 h</I><BR>
Fundamental Characteristics of Bubble Columns and Gas- Liquid-Solid. Fluidization Systems<BR>
Lecture I. Semi-Empiral Approaches by Prof. Liang-Shih Fan, Professor and Chair, The Ohio State University;
Bubble columns and three-phase fluidization systems have found increased industrial application over the past three decades. Successful application of gas-liquid-solid fluidization systems lies in comprehensive understanding of the transport phenomena, including hydrodynamics, heat and mass transfer, and mixing. The transport behavior in these systems is, however, very complex. In Lecture I, mechanistic interpretations based on theoretical and semi- theoretical approaches to transport phenomena systems will be described. An account of the the empirical aproaches in terms of correlations will also be given.<BR>
<I>Friday 23 August 1996, 0900 - 1200 h</I><BR>
Fundamental Characteristics of Bubble Columns and Gas- Liquid-Solid. Fluidization Systems<BR>
Lecture II: Flow Structures by Prof. Liang-Shih Fan, Professor and Chair, The Ohio State University;
The time-averaged results, in these studies, have demonstrated a circulatory flow pattern of the liquid phase, wherein the liquid phase rises in the center of the column and descends near the column walls. Researchers, in measuring the liquid circulation, have modeled these systems based on a one-dimensional, time-invariant approach. The flow in these systems, however, is truly multi-dimensional and transient. In order to better model the hydrodynamics of these multi-phase systems, the transient nature of these systems need to be understood and quantified. Lecture II will discuss a state- of-the-art digital image analysis technique known as Particle Image Velocimetry (PIV) to study the transient hydrodynamic behavior of bubble columns and three-phase fluidized beds. The PIV technique is capable of yielding qualitative and quantitative flow information of all phases present for an entire plane of view. The technique is, therefore, able to provide insight to the coupling effects between phases and of the flow field. Through the use of this technique the intrinsic flow phenomena, namely the instantaneous coherent structures, of these multiphase systems have been characterized and quantified for later model verification. Lecture II will address these coherent structures and their relationship to the instantaneous and time-averaged flow structure.<BR>
<I>Friday 23 August 1996, 1400 - 1700 h</I><BR>
Fundamental Characteristics of Bubble Columns and Gas- Liquid-Solid Fluidization Systems<BR>
Lecture III: Pressure and Temperature Effects by Prof. Liang- Shih Fan, Professor and Chair, The Ohio State University;<BR>
Many industrial applications of bubble columns and three- phase fluidization systems involve operation under high pressure and high temperature conditions. Proper understanding of the pressure and temperature effects on the transport phenomena in three-phase fluidization systems is essential to the theoretical account of the flow behavior and the ultimate development of optimum operation criteria for these ]systems. The fundamental importance lies in the understanding of the underlying principles or mechanisms governing the pressure and temperature effects on the hydrodynamic behavior which dictates the performance of the system. Lecture III will discuss the hydrodynamic behavior of these systems operated under high pressure, up to 22 MPa, and high temperature, up to 200oC, conditions. The results of the measurement of the insitu physical properties and quantification of three-phase fluidized bed hydrodynamics including phase holdups, bubble behavior, regime transition, and flow structure through direct visualization will be presented in Lecture III.<P>

<A NAME="scale-up"><I>25 - 27 september 1996</I><BR>
<B>Scale-up</B><BR>
A three-day course in the Chemical and Petroleum Industry.<BR>
<I>Course Objective</I><BR>
The development of a new chemical or petroleum refining process, the basic idea of which is usually conceived in the laboratory, demands a lengthy and costly development plan before the first industrial unit can be built. Scale-up is one of the important steps in the development plan.<BR>
The course deals with the theory and the practical aspects of scale up. Important topics are the different types of similarity and their hierarchy, macroscopic versus microscopic effects, pilot plant philosophy and research strategies with respect to the scalability of the results. Case studies derived from practical experience in industry will be used to illustrate the various aspects.<BR>
At the end of the course we expect that the attendants will be able to:
<UL>
<LI>establish a scale up strategy based on the analysis of the process
<LI>recognize the critical aspects of a scaling process, quantify the problems and define the methods to obtain a solution
<LI>define a research program in such a way that scale up problems will be minimized
<LI>scale down part of a process for optimization purpose
<LI>recognize the economical aspects that might lead to a scale up-risk and judge the economical feasibility of the scale up.
</UL>

<I>For more information:</I><BR>
Technologisch Instituut vzw, Attn. Rita Peys, coordinator, Desguinlei 214, B-2018-Antwerpen, België, telefoon: +32 3 219 09 96 fax: +32 3 216 06 89.<P>

