<HEAD><TITLE>A unified approach to ...</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>        

<TR>        

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>A unified approach to ...</Font></b> </TD>

	 

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=top >

<Font Size = +2>Scientists:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=top>

<Font Size = +2>R KRISHNA,  J ELLENBERGER, POST-DOC VACANCY, R JACOBS, M LETZEL, J W A de SWART and AIO VACANCY</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Collaborators: </Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>C M van den Bleek (Delft), M P Dudukovic (USA), S T Sie (Delft), W P M van Swaaij (Twente) and J A Wesselingh (Groningen)

</Font></TD>

        </TR>



   	</Font>

</TABLE>

<HR SIZE = 0>

<b>Abstract</b> - Our research efforts have the general aim of developing unifying concepts in chemical engineering.  

We are pursuing three different areas of research. <ul>

<li>We aim to develop a unified theory of mass transfer processes using the Maxwell-Stefan formulation.  We are attempting to extend this theory to describe intraparticle diffusion in membrane separations and microporous materials e.g. zeolites and carbon molecular sieves.

<li>We are attempting to develop a unified approach to the scale up of "fluidized" multiphase reactors, e.g. gas-liquid bubble columns, gas-solid fluidized beds, gas-liquid-solid slurry reactors.  The unified approach has its basis in hydrodynamic analogies, which are being investigated in a comprehensive program of experimentation.

<li>We are developing a fundamental approach to the "synthesis" of reactors and separation processes.  The "ideal" reactor is synthesised on the basis of a three-strategy level decision process.

</ul>



<b>PREAMBLE</b><br>

	Our research efforts are concentrated in three areas.  In each area we are seeking unification of ideas and 

concepts.  We look to unifying the theories of mass transfer.  We are attempting to develop a unified approach to 

the scale up of multiphase reactors.  We are conceptualising the problem of reactor synthesis.  

Since we work thematically, we prefer to present our research too in a unified manner.<p>



<b>UNIFIED APPROACH TO MASS TRANSFER</b><br>

	Our research efforts are concentrated on developing the Maxwell-Stefan theory (Wesselingh and Krishna; 

1990; Taylor and Krishna; 1993) for describing diffusion inside porous structures.  Currently we are examining 

the relative merits of the Mason-del Castillo formulation:<br>

<center>

<img src="cr1.gif">

</center><br clear=all>

and the Lightfoot formulation, which does not explicitly consider the influence of viscous transport:<br>

<center>

<img src="cr2.gif">

</center><br clear=all>

The question which puzzles Wesselingh and myself is the proper interpretation to the viscous selectivity factors 

alpha_i in the Mason formulation.  Also, can we inter-relate the Mason and Lightfoot transport coefficients ?<br>

<img align=left src="cr3.gif">	

We had earlier extended the Maxwell-Stefan theory to describe diffusion inside microporous materials such 

as zeolites and carbon molecular sieves (Krishna, 1990; Krishna, 1993a; Krishna, 1993b).  This theory, assuming 

single file diffusion, has been verified to be more accurate than the usual LDF models (Van den Broeke and Krishna, 1995).

The single file diffusion variant of the theory when applied to describe permeation across zeolite membranes is able 

to anticipate the experimentally observed "curious" maximum for hydrogen in a mixture with butane (Krishna and van 

den Broeke, 1995); cf. Fig. 1.   Since the  PhD thesis of Van den Broeke was completed in 1994 we are examining the 

important assumption of single file diffusion as a mechanism of zeolite diffusion.  	

In collaboration with Prof van Swaaij we are examining the application of Maxwell-Stefan theory for describing 

heat and mass transfer with chemical reaction (Frank et al., 1995).

<br clear=all><p>


<hr size = 0>

<a href="cr2.html">Read on: Unified approach to scale up of "fluidized" multophase reactors</a><br>

