<HEAD><TITLE>Unified approach to scale up of "fluidized" multiphase reactors</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0>

        <TR>

        <TD>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif">        </TD>

        <TD width = 400 align=middle>

<Font Size = +2><b>Unified approach to scale up of "fluidized" multiphase reactors</b></Font></b> </TD>

        </TR>

</TABLE>

<HR size = 0>


	Fluidized bed and bubble column slurry reactors are finding increasing use in industrial practice; 

these two reactor technologies figure prominently in processes for converting natural gas to liquid fuels

 and light olefins. There are considerable reactor design and scale-up problems associated with these natural 

gas conversion technologies; these problems arise because of several special features of these processes: 



<img ALIGN=RIGHT src="cr4.gif">



(i) large gas throughputs necessitating the use of large diameter, typically 5-8 m,  reactors, (ii) high pressure operation, 

typically 10-80 bar, (iii) large reactor heights, typically 20-30 m tall, and (iv) high exothermicity of reactions, 

requiring heat removal by means of cooling tubes inserted in the reactor.  Successful commercialisation of natural 

gas conversion technologies are crucially dependent on the proper understanding of the scaling up principles of 

fluid beds and bubble columns for these conditions which fall outside the purview of most published theory and 

correlations. Our approach to scale of these "fluidized" multiphase reactors is to cut  development time and 

costs by appreciation of the analogies in the hydrodynamics, mass transfer and mixing characteristics of fluid 

beds and bubble columns; cf. Fig. 2.  In order to demonstrate these analogies we have undertaken a comprehensive 

experimental program of investigation of these systems.   G-S, G-L and G-L-S experiments have been carried out in 

columns of diameters 0.05, 0.1, 0.174, 0.19, 0.38 and 0.63 m, fitted with either sintered plate, sieve plate or 

sparger type gas distributors.  The superficial gas velocity U was varied in the range 0 - 0.8 m/s and the 

dispersion heights H ranged up to 3.5 m.  Gases with varying gas densities have been studied:  air, helium, 

argon and SF6 .  As solid phase in fluid bed experiments we used: fluidized cracking catalyst (FCC) (49 mm) and 

polystyrene (570 mm).  The liquid phase in G-L bubble column experiments were water, paraffin, tetradecane and 

aqueous polyacrylamide solutions of varying.  Bubble column slurry operation was studied with paraffin oil 

containing upto 29 % wt per cent of silica particles (50 mm) and 48% wt per cent of glass beads (50 mm).  

The hydrodynamics were studied with the aid of bed collapse experiments; see Fig. 3.  The collapse experiments 

help to identify the "dilute" and "dense" phases, which are essential ingredients of our unified approach, as 

discussed below.  Further, we have used video imaging techniques in a 2D column to obtain a clearer picture of 

bubble interaction phenomena in G-S, G-L and G-L-S systems.  Some hitherto unrealized analogies are being unearthed 

with respect to interphase mass transfer; these will be indicated later.<BR CLEAR=ALL><p>


<img src="cr5.gif">

<BR CLEAR=ALL><P>

<hr size=0>

<a href="cr3.html">Read on: Gas holdup</a><br>

<a href="cr1.html">Back to: Unified approach to mass transfer</a>

