<HEAD><TITLE>Gas holdup</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0>

        <TR>

        <TD>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif">        </TD>

        <TD width = 400 align=middle>

<Font Size = +2><b>Gas Holdup</b></Font></b> </TD>

        </TR>

</TABLE>

<HR size = 0>

<img ALIGN=LEFT src="cr6.gif"> 

For G-S fluid beds, the bed expands only when the minimum fluidization velocity Umf is exceeded.  

For G-L systems we have Umf = 0; emf = 0.  In Fig. 4 we compare (e   - emf) for fluid beds with e for G-L systems. 

 The initial, linear, portion of the Voidage - U curve represents the homogeneous regime. Both curves exhibit a 

maximum at the regime transition point, Utrans; this maximum is prominent for columns with sintered plate distributor. 

For G-S fluid beds Utrans corresponds to the minimum bubbling point Umb.  For sieve plates and spargers the maximum at

 Utrans is not observed.  Beyond the transition point (region), we have the heterogeneous regime. The regime transition 

point Utrans is shifted to higher values with increasing gas density for both G-S and G-L systems; in other words

 increasing pressure has a stabilising effect on the homogeneous flow regime.  

<BR CLEAR = ALL>

<img ALIGN=LEFT src="cr7.gif">

Increasing particle size in fluid beds 

leads to earlier transition; for fluid bed experiments with polystyrene no homogeneous expansion was observed. This

 destabilising effect is also observed for G-L systems with increasing liquid viscosity and the behaviour corresponds 

to fluid beds with Geldart B type powders.  The determination of the regime transition point is an important item of

 research.  We collaborate with Prof C M van den Bleek (Delft) in developing the use of chaos theories to obtain a 

proper fingerprint of the homogeneous and heterogeneous regimes, and of the transition point.  Figure 5 compares the 

gas holdup and the Kolmogorov entropy for operation of an air-water bubble column of 0.1 m diameter.  The peak of the

 voidage curve corresponds to a deep valley in the value of the Kolmogorov entropy.  It appears that chaos theory could

 be a useful tool for regime characterization. 

<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<img ALIGN=LEFT src="cr8.gif"> 

	 The dense phase gas voidage <i>E</i>df was found to be practically constant in the heterogeneous regime; a 

common picture for the gas voidages in G-S and G-L systems which emerged from the experiments is shown in Fig. 6.  

For estimation purposes we may take <i>E</i>df = <i>E</i>trans and Udf = Utrans. The dense phase gas voidage edf is significantly 

affected by system physical properties but is relatively insensitive to the scale of operation; this parameter 

can therefore be determined in a column of relatively small scale under realistic conditions of temperature and pressure. <P>

	A unified model for the dilute phase holdup has been developed taken into account the phenomena of bubble growth 

in the zone above the distributor. The growth zone is limited to an equilibration value; this value is of the order of 

1 - 1.5 m for G-S systems and is only about 0.1 - 0.3 m for G-L systems. Further, on the basis of our experimental work 

in G-S and G-L systems, the rise velocity of the dilute phase Vb in fluid beds is found to be a strong function of column 

diameter DT .  This scale dependence is somewhat weaker for G-L systems than for G-S systems. The quantitative analogies 

between G-S and G-L systems are evident from Fig. 7; note the strong influence of the column diameter on the dilute phase 

gas holdup.  For G-L systems the dilute phase gas holdup is practically independent of the liquid and gas phase properties.<P>

<BR CLEAR=ALL><p>

<hr size=0>

<a href="cr4.html">Read on: Holdups in slurry bubble columns</a><br>

<a href="cr2.html">Back to: Unified approach to scale up of "fluidized" multiphase reactors</b><p></a>

