</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Generalized model</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<HR size = 0>

<TABLE BORDER=0>

        <TR>

        <TD>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif">        </TD>

        <TD width = 400 align=middle>

<Font Size = +2><b>Generalized Model</b></Font></b> </TD>

        </TR>

</TABLE>



<HR size = 0>





<img align=right src="cr11.gif"> 



Based on the common hydrodynamic picture which has emerged from our experimental studies we suggest a generalisation 

of the "two-phase" model of May (1959) and Van Deemter (1961), developed for G-S fluid beds, to G-L and G-L-S bubble

 columns; this extension is pictured in Fig. 9. For bubble columns the dense phase is to be identified with the liquid 

phase together with the small bubbles which are entrained in the liquid. In the heterogeneous flow regime, the small 

bubbles have the backmixing characteristics of the liquid, or slurry,  phase.  

<img align=left src="cr12.gif"> 



The fast-rising "dilute" phase tend to 

churn up the "dense" phase as pictured in Fig. 10. It may be expected that the backmixing coefficient must be relatable 

to the rise velocity of the fast rising large bubbles, Vb and to the size of the eddies in the liquid phase generated 

by these fast-rising bubbles.<br>

We plan to use CFD techniques to develop a unified description of the liquid circulation patterns in multiphase reactors.  

Collaborative links have been set up with Prof M P Dudukovic of Washington University in St Louis.

Video imaging techniques in a 2D column have is being used to shed some new light on the mass transfer mechanism from 

"large" bubbles in G-S, G-L and G-L-S systems.  The large bubble population is constantly coalescing and splitting up; 

see the grabbed images for air-FCC in Fig.11. The bubble-bubble interchange coefficients can be determined from 

frame-by-frame analysis of the video images.  This constant coalescence-breakup phenomenon leads to an enhancement in 

mass transfer from the  dilute phase as has been shown by Sit and Grace (1981).  We may wonder if an analogous phenomenon 

exists for G-L systems.  De Swart (1996) will be attempting to provide some answers.

<br clear=all> 

<img align=left src="cr13.gif"> 

<br clear=all> <p>



<hr size=0>

