<HEAD><TITLE>Synthesis of "ideal" reactor and separator configurations</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<HR size = 0>

<TABLE BORDER=0>

        <TR>

        <TD>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif">        </TD>

        <TD width = 400 align=middle>

<Font Size = +2><b>Synthesis of "ideal" reactor and separator configurations</Font></b> </TD>

        </TR>

</TABLE>


<HR size = 0>

The "ideal" reactor for a given reaction is synthesised on the basis of a three- strategy level decision making process.  

The decisions are made on the basis of a basis of "wish" list consisting of "wants" and "musts".  This philosophy was 

expounded in a plenary presentation at ISCRE-13 in Baltimore (Krishna and Sie, 1995).  It is important to emphasise 

that our approach does not involve brute force evaluation of known alternatives.  Rather, we first decide what we want 

and then engineer to get what we want.  Naturally, compromises need to be made if decisions at different levels conflict

 with one another; see Figure 12.<p>

In future we will develop a strategy for synthesising the "ideal" separation technology for a given problem.  

Our approach will use the theory of irreversible thermodyamics and the Maxwell-Stefan formulation of transport.  

The synthesis approach may unearth some novel separation routes.

<br clear=all>

<img align=left src="cr14.gif"> 

<p>

