<HEAD><TITLE>Microwave heating of solid catalysts</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>

        <TR>

        <TD ALIGN=right>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

    </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=middle width=500>



<Font Size = +2><b>Microwave heating of solid catalysts</Font></b> </TD>

	
	<TD align=right>

	<img src="bron.gif">

	</TD>

        </TR>

        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Bron Vos</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Supervisors:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Alfred Bliek, Eduard K. Poels</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

        </TD>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>OSPT</Font></TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Project term:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>November 1995 - November 1999</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</TABLE>









<HR SIZE = 0>

<b>Introduction</b><p>

It is well known that some solids can be heated efficiently in a microwave field as a 

result of the dielectric relaxation, causing the microwaves to act as a transfer agent 

of the electric power. As a result rapid heating of solids is possible. Interesting 

aspects of the use of microwave energy are:<p>



<b>1.</b> It is possible to create inverse temperature fields due to bulk heating by radiation instead of by conduction<br>

<b>2.</b> Rapid heating and cooling is feasible, in contrast to the (slow) heat transfer in case of conduction. Pulsing of the waves is possible.<br>

<b>3.</b> Heating of solids is selective as gases are transparent to microwaves.<p>



<b>The Objective</b><p>

In the present project the objective is to investigate the characteristics of the solid 

matter that can be heated in a dielectric field. In particular the impact of seeding is 

interesting, as the bulk material itself may have a low dielectric loss factor and still 

be made microwave sensitive by the addition of seed material. The field of application 

aimed at is the heating of conventional and less conventional catalyst support materials, 

like alumina, zeolites and silicas. A second, related objective is to develop models that 

are able to satisfactorily model the process of heating of a solid in a microwave field.<p>



<b>Problems and Pitfalls</b><p>

The analysis of microwave heating is complicated by the difficulty of temperature 

measurements and the sample-size effect. In view of the radiation wavelength of microwaves 

(normally 2.45 GHz is used, corresponding to a wave length of 0.12 m) the size of the sample 

to be heated influences the distribution (homogeneity) of the dielectric field experienced by 

the particle.<p>

 

<b>Equipment</b><p>

A 1 KW monomode microwave cavity was constructed (Fig.1) with an accurately controlled field 

distribution and power consumption measuring devices. Both standing and travelling waves can

be applied. In the microwave field a tubular, glass reactor is placed, containing the solid 

catalyst or catalyst support material. A noninvasive, non-contact temperature measurement is 

applied on the basis of fiberoptics.<p>



<img src="ospt2.gif"><br>



<b>Program</b><p>

The program consists of a theoretical part in which heating of solids / microwave field 

strength distribution are modeled for the cavity and reactor configuration at hand. 

Experimental work is for a number of supports, starting with alumina supports. Initially 

in particular Ni on alumina will be investigated. Calcination as well as reduction behaviour 

of this catalyst type in a microwave field will be tested in order to assess the impact of 

this heating technique on the catalyst strucure and activity.<p>

<i>

<HR SIZE=0>

Bron Vos<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:vos@chemeng.chem.uva.nl">vos@chemeng.chem.uva.nl</A><br>

Department of Chemical Engineering<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 02/02/96</CENTER></H6>

