<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Selective catalytic reduction (SCR) of NO with NH3 over MnOx/Al2O3 catalysts at low temperatures</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>



        <TR>

                <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>



        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>Selective catalytic reduction (SCR) of NO with NH<sub>3</sub> over MnO<sub>x</sub>/Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> catalysts at low temperatures</Font></b> </TD>

        <TD>

	<img src="sjoerd.gif">

	</TD>

	</TR>

        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Drs. W. Sjoerd Kijlstra</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Supervisors:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Eduard K. Poels, Alfred Bliek</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

        </TD>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>SON</Font></TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Project term:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>1992-1996</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</TABLE>





<HR SIZE = 0>

<i>Alumina supported manganese oxides are studied as catalysts for the selective 

catalytic reduction (SCR) of NO with NH<sub>3</sub>. Transient experiments (with labelled

 reactants), TPD and FTIR are used to elucidate the complex reaction mechanism. 

Besides, the mechanism of inhibition/deactivation by SO<sub>2</sub> and H<sub>2</sub>O is evaluated.</i><p>





<b><u>Introduction:</u></b>

Selective catalytic reduction of NO with NH<sub>3</sub> is one of the most effective ways 

to remove NO<sub>x</sub> from flue gases emitted by stationary sources:<p>

<pre>

4 NO  +  4  NH<sub>3</sub>  +  O<sub>2</sub>  ===>   4 N<sub>2</sub>  +  6 H<sub>2</sub>O

</pre><p>





To apply SCR in add-on units, catalysts active and selective at low temperatures (383-573 K) 

are required. Alumina supported with 2 wt% MnO<sub>x</sub> has appeared to meet these criteria.   



Results and discussion:



<ul>

<li><b>Transient experiments</b>, combined with <b>TPD</b> revealed that under reaction conditions the catalyst surface is almost completely covered by NH<sub>3</sub>. However, NO appeared to react both directly from the gas phase as from an adsorbed state. Moreover, NO can adsorb in a very stable form, partly deactivating the catalyst. Removal of O<sub>2</sub> from the gas stream stops the reaction instantaneously. At the moment, special attention is paid to the role of surface oxygen and gas phase oxygen in the NO-adsorption.

<li>

<li><b>FTIR</b> studies turned out that the stable form of adsorbed NO, as established by TPD, has to be a bidentate nitrate. Moreover, nitrosyls are only detected in the absence of O<sub>2</sub>, and disappear in its presence. As O<sub>2</sub> is essential for reaction, nitrosyls are not likely SCR-intermediates (as argued by other authors on comparable systems) on this catalyst. NH<sub>3</sub> coordinates on both Lewis and Brønsted acid sites. Attention is focused on the type of nitrite that can function as active intermediate in the catalytic cycle.

<li>

<li><b>Water</b> appeared to exhibit a reversible inhibition on the reaction as well as an irreversible deactivation on the catalyst. Inhibition is caused by molecularly adsorbed H<sub>2</sub>O. Deactivation is probably due to dissociative adsorption of H<sub>2</sub>O to surface hydroxyls, which remain on the surface upon removal of H<sub>2</sub>O from the gas stream (at 383-523 K). This effect reaches a plateau value, so can be dealt with easily in practical applications.

<li>

<li><b>SO<sub>2</sub></b> can deactivate the catalyst completely in a very short period due to the formation of MnSO<sub>4</sub>. This formation is almost inevitable, so the application potential of the catalyst is reduced to sulphur free conditions.

<li>

<li>A large amount of adsorbed NH<sub>3</sub> is present on the catalyst surface during reaction conditions. The possibilities of application of a <b>periodically reversed flow reactor</b> to use this buffer in periods of excess NO<sub>x</sub> in the stack gases (and avoid NH<sub>3</sub>-slip in periods of excess NH<sub>3</sub> !) is under investigation.

</ul>

<HR SIZE=0>

<i>

Sjoerd Kijlstra<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:sjoerdk@chemeng.chem.uva.nl">sjoerdk@chemeng.chem.uva.nl</A><br>

Department of Chemical Engineering<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

