<HEAD><TITLE>Forced oscillations on catalytic systems</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>        

<TR>        

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>Forced oscillations on catalytic systems</Font></b> </TD>

        </TR>


        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Frank van Neer</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>

        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Supervisor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Alfred Bliek</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

        </TD>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>University of Amsterdam</Font></TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Project term:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>june 1993 - june 1997</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</TABLE>





<HR SIZE = 0>

<i>Forced concentration and temperature oscillations are used to serve various purposes 

such as kinetic model discrimination, selectivity improvements and vibrational control. 

The present study is focused on the response of a catalytic system under forced oscillations 

to obtain a generic basis for predicting the occurrence of the phenomena mentioned above.</i><p>

The research topic is considered on theoretical as well as experimental basis. As model 

system we use among others CO oxidation on a Cu-based catalyst. Oscillations of O2 and CO 

are imposed on the catalyst and products are determined in time. The kinetic mechanism for 

this reaction has been partly elucidated by step-response experiments and further mechanistic 

information is gathered by periodic oscillations. Model discrimination and practical 

applications of f.o. are the main issues in the former experimental study whereas CO oxidation 

on Pt has been chosen as model reaction to investigate the effects of concentration transients 

on a non-linear system. <p>



The latter aspect is also analysed on a pure theoretical basis. Starting with a comparatively 

simple Langmuir-Hinshelwood type reaction mechanism, the study will be expanded to more complex 

reaction kinetic networks. Resonance of a system towards oscillations of a weakly 

(concentration) and a strongly non-linear forcing variable (temperature) is now well 

understood for the simple models and generalised rules are formulated.<p> 

<img align=left src="frank.gif">

<i>Reaction rate vs. cycling frequency of the inlet concentration<br>

(____): CA=0.1 - 0.7 mol m-3; CB=0.3 mol m-3<br>

(----): CA=0.1 - 0.9 mol m-3; CB=0.3 mol m-3<br></i>

<br clear=left><p>



Besides using numerical techniques to investigate the dynamics of the catalytic system, 

also the linearised system is analysed by means of focusing on the eigenvalue structure 

of the concerning matrices which gives information on the relaxation time of a system to 

steady state.<p>



The figure shows the time averaged rate vs. the frequency of oscillation in case of a 

three-step LH model obtained by numerical integration of the governing equations 

(solid line) and calculations with the linearised system (markers). It can be concluded 

that linearisation is not always appropriate in predicting responses on forced oscillations. 

Therefore this technique can only be applied in combination with numerical analysis, however 

it is very useful in case of multiparameter optimisation problems. Furthermore the figure 

illustrates how complicated and sensitive responses of just a simple catalytic system can be.


<HR SIZE=0>

<i>

Frank van Neer<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:FVN@SARA.NL">fvn@sara.nl</A><br>

Department of Chemical Engineering<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

