<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>The copper catalysed hydrogenolysis of fatty methyl esters</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>

        <TR>

                <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>



        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>The copper catalysed hydrogenolysis of fatty methyl esters</Font></b> </TD>

        <TD>

	<img src="danny.gif">

	</TD>

	</TR>

        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Danny S. Brands</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Supervisors:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Eduard K. Poels, Alfred Bliek</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

        </TD>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>University of Amsterdam</Font></TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Project term:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>September 1993 - September 1997</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</TABLE>





<HR SIZE = 0>

The hydrogenolysis of fatty methyl esters towards fatty alcohols is an important step 

in the production of detergents from natural fats and oils.<p>



Copper containing catalysts show activity in the hydrogenolysis of esters towards 

alcohols:<p> 



<pre>R-CO-O-CH3 + 2 H2  ->  R-CH2-OH + CH3-OH</pre><br>

with: <pre>R = C11-C17</pre><p>



The currently applied copper-chromite catalysts are under pressure for environmental 

reasons. In our laboratory, Cu/SiO2 and Cu/ZnO/SiO2 catalysts have been developed that

show activity in ester hydrogenolysis comparable to industrial chromium containing 

catalysts. Pre-treatment under a hydrogen atmosphere at (for Cu/ZnO catalysts) unusually 

high temperatures considerably increases activity of zinc promoted catalysts. Research 

is now focused on determining the nature of the active phase of the Cu/SiO2 and 

Cu/ZnO/SiO2 catalysts, especially after high temperature reductive treatments. 	<p>



The models, developed for the active phase of the Cu/ZnO/SiO2 catalyst, might also be

applied to copper containing catalysts used for the very important methanol synthesis 

and could elucidate some of the aspects of the Cu+/Cu0 debate for this reaction.<p>





<img align=left src="danny1.gif"><br>



<br clear=left>

<i>Fig. 1: Model for dynamic behaviour of copper in Cu/ZnO catalysts.</i>



<HR SIZE=0>

<i>

Danny Brands<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:brands@chemeng.chem.uva.nl">brands@chemeng.chem.uva.nl</A><br>

Department of Chemical Engineering<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

