<HEAD><TITLE>Selection criteria for carbon supported noble metal catalysts in three-phase reaction systems</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>        

<TR>        

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>Selection criteria for carbon supported noble metal catalysts in three-phase reaction systems</Font></b> </TD>

	<TD>

	<img align=middle src="monique.jpg">

	</TD>

        

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Monique van der Zon</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Supervisors:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>E.K. Poels, P.J. Hamersma, and A. Bliek</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

        </TD>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>IOP- Katalyse</Font></TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Project term:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>4 years</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

</TABLE>





<HR SIZE = 0>



<b>Introduction:</b><p>



In a number of industrial hydrogenation and oxidation reactions transport limitations 

occur. Many  authors observe under these conditions a clear effect of the choice of t

he catalyst support on conversion. Vinke (Ph.D. thesis Amsterdam, 1992) showed that 

during hydrogenation in a three-phase agitated slurry reactor the gas-absorption is 

enhanced if the support of small catalysts particles is chemically modified resulting 

in a better particle-to-bubble adhesion. Other experiments showed that this adhesion 

behaviour can also be affected by changing the gas phase. The question now arises 

whether we can optimise the chemical environment and catalyst for such reactions in 

industrial reactors? To answer this question adhesion and gas-absorption experiments 

are performed with gas-liquid systems and a palladium catalyst on different supports.<p>





<TABLE BORDER = 0 CELLPADDING = 5 CELLSPACING= 1>

<TR>

<TD VALIGN = top align=center width= 442>

<img align=LEFT src="monique.gif">

</TD>

<TD width = 300>

<table border = 1 CELLSPACING = 0 width = 300>

<TR><TD><b>Gas</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER><b>Liquid</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER><b>Catalyst</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER><b>Alpha(degr.)</b></TD></TR>

<TR><TD>air</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>octane</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>Pd/Al2O3</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>hydrogen</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>octane</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>Pd/Al2O3</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>air</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>water</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>Pd/Al2O3</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>112</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>hydrogen</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>water</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>Pd/Al2O3</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>air</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>octane</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>Pd/C</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>hydrogen</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>octane</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>Pd/C</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>air</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>water</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>Pd/C</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>88</TD></TR>

<TR><TD>hydrogen</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>water</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>Pd/C</TD><TD ALIGN=CENTER>180</TD></TR>

</TD></TABLE></TD></TR>

<TR><TD><i><b>Figure 1:</b>Pick-up needle with gas bubble and adhering catalyst particles.</i></TD>

<TD><i><b>Table 1:</b> Effect of different three-phase systems on the bubble-surface coverage angle alpha.</i></TD></TR>

</TABLE><p>



<b>Results and Discussion:</b><p>

Experiments were performed to establish the effect of the liquid phase on the adhesion of

  Pd/C and Pd/Al-2O3 to air and hydrogen bubbles under static conditions (fig.1). 

A comparison of the obtained values of the bubble-surface coverage angle a for different 

three-phase systems is represented in Table 1. It can be seen that adhesion is influenced 

by all of the phases involved.</p>



<b>Future work:</b><p> 

In a joint project with the Universities of Delft and Utrecht sponsored by the 

"IOP-Katalyse", future research will focus on carbon supported noble metal catalysts. 

The relation between catalyst parameters and their performance in hydrogenation and 

oxidation reactions will be investigated.<p>


<HR SIZE=0>

