<HEAD><TITLE>New methods for the preparation of oleochemicals using solid acid catalysts</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>        

<TR>        

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>New methods for the preparation of oleochemicals using solid acid catalysts</Font></b> </TD>

	 

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Drs. R.M Koster</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Supervisors:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Dr. E.K. Poels, Prof.dr.ir. A. Bliek</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

        </TD>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>IOP- Katalyse</Font></TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Project term:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>4 years</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

</TABLE>



<HR SIZE = 0>



<b>Objective:</b><ul>Development of new catalytic methods to obtain a higher selectivity in the conversion 

and synthesis of oleochemicals. The research should lead to reduction of waste streams and by-products.</ul>

<b>Catalyst:</b><ul>Solid acid catalysts with controlled shape selectivity and acid properties.</ul>

<b>Reactions:</b><ul>Three important types of conversions in oleochemicals production will be studied: dimerisation, 

esterification and (in future) amidation of fatty acids.</ul>



<b>A:	Catalysed dimerisation of unsaturated fatty acids<p>

Reaction:</b><p>



<img Align=LEFT src="remko.gif">

<br clear=all>



<b>Problems:</b>

<ol>

<li>Development of a regenerable heterogeneous catalysts required.

<li>Manipulation of selectivity to the three major products (isostearic acid, dimers, trimers) desired.

<li>Mechanism dimer formation unclear: Diels-Alder, Ene reaction, or Carbocation or?

<li>A Montmorillonite clay catalyst is commercially used. Why is this catalyst superior?

<li>Many side reactions: lactone and estolide formation, hydrogen transfer, cracking, decarboxylation, darkening.

</ol>



<b>Approach:</b>

<ol>

<li>Determination of type of active sites and structural and textural parameters of the commercial Montmorillonite clay catalyst.

<li>Tests of influence of nature of active sites using model catalysts. 

<li>Elucidation of the mechanism of the dimerisation reaction by analysis of intermediates and products and by using specific reactants, i.e. using reactivity data and IR spectroscopy. 

<li>Rational design of new highly selective dimerisation catalysts with optimal acidity and shape selectivity.

</ol>



<b>B:	Esterification of fatty acids using solid acid catalysts<p>



Reaction:</b><p>



<img Align=LEFT src="remko1.gif">

<br clear=all>



<b>Problems:</b>

<ol>

<li>Transition metals in waste streams or product.

<li>Mechanism/kinetics ambiguous.

<li>Filterable, regenerable catalyst required.

<li>Many side reactions: soap, alkene and ether formation, decarboxylation and darkening.

<li>Corrosion by conventional catalysts.

</ol>



<b>Approach:</b>

<ol>

<li>Determination of the relation of activity/, selectivity and

<ul>

<li>	type, strength and concentration of acid sites

<li>	hydrophobicity/hydrophilicity

<li>	pore diameter

</ul>	

by systematic catalyst variation.

Heteropoly acids on MCM type support seem appropriate because of the variable controlled uniform meso-pore diameter

<li>Tests of model catalysts pTsOH, H2SO4 and Sn-octoate as reference catalysts.

<li>Activity and kinetic measurements on the reaction to ethyl acetate in the gas phase.

<li>Verification of gas phase results and investigation of mass transport problems using larger reactant molecules in liquid phase.

<li>Tests of the regeneration, filtration and deactivation of developed catalysts and the application in a fixed bed process.

</ol>



<HR SIZE=0>

<i>

Remko Koster,<br>

E-Mail: <a href="mailto:remkok@chemeng.chem.uva.nl">remkok@chemeng.chem.uva.nl</a><br>

Department of Chemical Engineering<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

