<HEAD><TITLE>Porosity of heterogenous catalysts</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>

        <TR>

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

    </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>Porosity of heterogenous catalysts</Font></b> </TD>

 <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="marjo.jpg"></TD>

        </TR>


        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Research scientists:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ms. M. C. Mittelmeijer-Hazeleger (Marjo)</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



       

</TABLE>

<HR SIZE = 0>

Next to the normal work as a senior laboratory assistant on a department of chemical engineering I have 

my own research field about porous materials.<p>

During the last years I determined the porosity and pore size of very different kind of materials, like the normal catalysts, carbons, coals and soils.

I find porous materials very interesting, especial micro porous materials like zeolites and carbon molecular sieves.  Establishing the micro-pore-size-distribution and relating this distribution to adsorption phenomena in my biggest hobby.

Besides determination of the normal adsorption isotherms also measuring  the heat of adsorption is part of my present work. <P>

A complete new challenge in this field is measuring the adsorption of mixtures in microporous materials. Not only measuring, but also explaining and afterwards finding a way to predict the adsorption is my latest hobby.

At the moment mixtures of ethane, ethene and acetylene on the Takeda CMS5A and the zeolite ZSM5 are under investigation.

<P>As the problem of explaining the observed phenomenon is much bigger than expected from the results of mixture on "normal" activated carbons, I am very interested in contact with other persons working in this field. Please contact me if you are working in this or related area.



<HR SIZE=0 >

Ms. M. C. Mittelmeijer-Hazeleger (Marjo)<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:marjom@chemeng.chem.uva.nl">marjom@chemeng.chem.uva.nl</A><br>

Department of Chemical Engineering<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

