<HEAD><TITLE>Control of reactive polymer processing</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="ospt1.gif" ALIGN=left></TD><TD><H2>Control of reactive polymer processing</H2></TD></TR></TABLE>

<B>Research scientists:</B> Peter Hamerstoa, Huub Hoefsloot, Piet Iedema, 1 PhD vacancy<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> DSM<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In the chemical process industry a Farrel
Continuous Mixer (FCM) is used for the
reactive processing of blends of
homopolymers and copolymers of
polypropylene and polyethylene. At our
laboratory a project will be started with a
model polymer system to study the
interaction between flow phenomena and
polymerisation kinetics and their relation
to the chemical structure. It is expected
that three main area's of research will be
covered i.e.: hydrodynamics and kinetics,
melting and coalescence /dispersion
behaviour.<P>

<B>Effect of hydrodynamics and kinetics on polymer properties</B><BR>
A challenging part of this topic will be the
simulation of the 3D flow field around the
counter-rotating kneader discs with the
CFD package POLY3D from Rheotek
(Montreal, Canada). It involves aspects of
polymer processing including mixing,
melting and coalescence.<P>

<IMG SRC="vacan1_1.gif"><P>

<B>Aspects of melting</B><BR>
From the literature it is concluded that the
dissipative mix-melting mechanism
should be the concept to be explored as
applied on a specific geometry and
rheological conditions. The following
research elements will be considered:
identification of the mixing regime,
analysis of heat dissipation rate
distribution in the liquid melt,
experimental validation.<P>

<B>Coalescence / dispersion behaviour</B><BR>
This part contributes to the identification
and understanding / modelling of the
dominant mechanisms. A hypothetical
mechanism is the contraction of
copolymer layers (network structure) to
small droplets of 0.1 microns , which
subsequently coalesce to larger ones.
This mechanism could be verified with
SEM photographs of, in first instance,
shearless melted powder. Another
relevant theme is the rheology of a
dispersed system including the average
drop size and the drop size distribution.<P>

<IMG SRC="vacan1_2.gif"><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 09/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
