<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Reactive polymer systems in a static mixer reactor</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="ospt1.gif" ALIGN=left></TD><TD><H2>Reactive polymer systems in a static mixer reactor</H2></TD></TR></TABLE>

<B>Research scientists:</B> Peter Hamersma, Huub Hoefsloot, Piet Iedema, 2 PhD vacancies<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> SON and UvA<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Control of polymer product properties by
manipulating variables during the most
important process steps is the long term
objective of polymer process research.
End use properties are determined by
chemical and morphological structure.
The research theme will focus on the
relationship between process variables
and chemical structure i.e. molecular
weight distribution, degree of branching,
conformation, copolymer composition,
sequence length distribution etc.<BR>

Although there are several aggregation
levels the current project will be focused
on the numerical and experimental study
of reactive polymer systems in a static
mixer reactor. The numerical part
concerns the simulation of the laminar
flow field of the reacting polymer system
in a static mixer reactor by means of
computational fluid dynamics (CFD). The
experiments are focused on the
measurement of the velocity and
temperature distribution, the chemical
rate of conversion and the development
of on-line detection equipment for the
determination of the molecular mass /
molecular mass distribution. Parallel
attention will be paid to the rheological
behaviour of reactive polymer systems in
a non-isothermal shear field.<P>

<B>Static Mixer Reactor</B><BR>
Challenging aspects of polymerisation
research in a SMR are the complex
geometry of the reactor combined with
the high (non-Newtonian) viscosity of the
reacting fluid. Although this type of
reactor is interesting for chemical
industries, the methodology to be
developed in this study has a generic
character and is generally applicable.<P>

<B>Research objective</B><BR>
The main objective is the modelling,
experimental verification and CFD 3D-
simulation of the interaction between<P>

<IMG SRC="vacan2_1.gif"><P>

laminar non-Newtonian reacting flow
phenomena in a complex reactor
geometry and the molecular weight
distribution / polymer end-use properties.<P>

<IMG SRC="vacan2_2.gif"><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 09/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
