<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Plant-wide multivariate statistical process control</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>

        <TR>

                <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>Plant-wide multivariate statistical process control</Font></b> </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Research scientists:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>A.K. Smilde, P.D. Iedema, C. Georgakis, vacancy</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>University of Amsterdam</Font></TD>

        </TR>



</TABLE>

<HR SIZE = 0>

<b>Philosophy of multivariate statistical process control (MSPC)</b><p>



Detecting variation due to special causes. In a process there are two types of variation: 

common cause and special cause variation. The first one is inherent to the process and can

 only be changed by optimizing the process and control structure design. The second type of

 variation moves the process out of normal operating conditions. There are three reasons to

 perform MSPC: detecting if there is special variation, locating where this special variation

 starts in the process and assigning cause(s) of special variation.<p>



<img ALIGN=left src="ospt3.gif"><br>





<b>Multivariate Statistical Process Control </b><p>





Measurements M1, M2 and M3 are measured simultaneously. The results can be processed in a 

T2-chart which shows the behavior of the 3 measurements in time. Remark that this set up 

does not allow to answer the question where the special variation started.

<br clear=left>



<img align=right src="ospt4.gif"><br>



<b>Plant-Wide MSPC </b><p>



The idea of Plant-wide MSPC is to look at the whole plant simultaneously. Due to recycle 

streams and controller structures the measurements at different locations in a process are

not independent. It is this dependency that should be utilized. <p>

<br clear=right><p>

<HR SIZE=0>

<i>

Age Smilde,<br>

E-Mail: <a href="mailto:asmilde@anal.chem.uva.nl">asmilde@anal.chem.uva.nl</a><br>

Department of Analytical Chemstry<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

