<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Dynamic gas/liquid flow in pipes and regular T-junctions</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>

        <TR>

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>Dynamic gas/liquid flow in pipes and regular T-junctions</Font></b> </TD>

	

        </TR>

        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Marcel Ottens</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Supervisors:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Peter Hamersma, Huub Hoefsloot</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

        </TD>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>UvA</Font></TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Project term:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>1-7-'93 - 1-7-'97</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

</TABLE>





<HR SIZE = 0><p>



<b>Introduction.</b><p>

Gas-liquid flow systems are often encountered in the chemical process industry. 

In many Engineering Departments multiphase flow systems like bubble columns, 

fluidized beds and pipe flow are a topic of extensive research. Our research is 

focused on dynamic gas-liquid flow experiments in pipes with inclination angles 

varying between -5&lt;&szlig;&lt;+5 and in T junctions with different geometric configurations. 

Our aim is to develop process engineering models which can be used for design and 

scale-up of process equipment.<p>



<b>Results.</b><p>

In the last year our attention was focused on performing steady-state measurements on 

gas/liquid flow split in a T junction with an inclined branch. Under practical conditions 

a pipe or junction is never really horizontal. <p>



<TABLE border = 0>

<TR><TD WIDTH=340>

<img src="marcel1.gif" align=left>

</TD><TD WIDTH=339>

<img src="marcel.gif" align=left>

</TD></TR>

<TR><TD><i>Figure 1:"Critical gas branch mass intake fraction where liquid leaves the branch outlet as function of actual gas velocity in the inlet. Lines drawn according model"</TD>

<TD><i>Figure 2:"Calculated interfacial wave velocities vs. experimental ones, for different types of waves. 2D: regular Jeffrey waves; KH: Kelvin-Helmholtz waves; AT: idem, with atomisation.</TD>

</TD>

</TABLE><p>



The gas/liquid flow split in a T junction with a small inclination angle showed different 

results to those obtained in the horizontal case. Figure 1 shows the influence of the 

angle of inclination on the flow split together with the model results. Contrary to the 

horizontal case, a certain critical gas branch mass fraction intake is needed to transport

liquid out the branch. <p>

Further effort was concentrated on the measurement of the interface, like shape and form. 

The shape of the interface in two-phase gas/liquid pipe flow is important for predicting 

models. It is known that interfacial wave structures are linked with interfacial friction. 

An experimental set-up is developed to measure these characteristics by means of video 

images processing techniques. Figure 2 show the measured wave velocities against the 

modelled, for three different types of waves, i.e. so called 2D regular Jeffrey waves, 

Kelvin-Helmholtz waves and Kelvin-Helmholtz waves with atomisation.<p>

<HR SIZE=0>

<i>

Marcel Ottens<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:otje@sara.nl">otje@sara.nl</A><br>

Department of Chemical Engineering<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

