<HEAD><TITLE>Including external process variables in multivariate calibration of process instruments</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>        

<TR>        

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

        

<TD VALIGN=MIDDLE><Font Size = +2>

<b>Including external process variables in multivariate calibration of process instruments</Font></b> 

</TD>        

</TR>        

<TR>        

<TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

</TD>        

<TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Florian Wulfert</Font>       

</TD>        

</TR>        

<TR>        

<TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>        

<TR>        

<TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>Supervisor:</Font>        

</TD>        

<TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>Age Smilde</Font>

</TD>        

</TR></Font>        

</TD>        

<TR>        

<TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>        

</TD>        

<TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>University of Amsterdam</Font>

</TD>        

</TR>        

<TR>        

<TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Project term:</Font>        

</TD>        

<TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>December 94 - December 98</Font>

</TD>        

</TR>

</TABLE>

<HR SIZE = 0>

<b>Introduction:</b><p>



In order to control an industrial process, information about the process has to be 

obtained and the quality of this information has to be evaluated. The concentration 

measurements in process analysis can be done by near-infrared (NIR) spectroscopy. 

Multivariate calibration is performed on the measured spectra, using the absorption 

data of all wavelength. <p>



<img align=left VALLIGN=bottom src="florian.gif"><br>



<i>Fig. 1: Simulation of spectral changes due to concentration and temperature variation.</i><p>



<br clear=left>



<b>Project:</b><p>The spectra are modified by "external" variables (such as temperature, 

viscosity, pressure etc.) and show shift, band broadening and intensity changes due to 

those. In order to make the model robust against such influences, the effect of the 

external variables on the measurements has to be included explicitly in the calibration 

model.<p> 



Because of the non-linearity of the above described disturbances it might be necessary 

to transform the data to a different domain, for example by using wavelet- or 

fourier-transform. <p>The external variables hold further information that can be used 

to distinguish between errors in the process and errors in the measurement, making on-line

diagnostics and performance monitoring of the measurement device possible. To achieve this

 it is necessary to describe the measurements not as independent but to take in account the 

correlation between them in the time domain.



<p>

<i>

<HR SIZE=0>

Florian Wulfert<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:florian@anal.chem.uva.nl">florian@anal.chem.uva.nl</A><br>

Department of Analytical Chemistry<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

