<HEAD><TITLE>Bias by sample injection and detection in capillary zone electrophoresis</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>        

<TR>        

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>



        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>Bias by sample injection and detection in capillary zone electrophoresis</Font></b> </TD>

        </TR>

        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Hans van der Moolen</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Supervisor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Her Smit, Hans Poppe</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

        </TD>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Dutch Organization for Scientific Research (NWO)</Font></TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Project term:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>may 1993 - may 1997</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</TABLE>


<HR SIZE = 0>

<b>Introduction</b><p>

Capillary Zone Electrophoresis (CZE) is a modern analytical separation method based on 

differences in charge and size of molecules. The use of chemometric correlation techniques 

to modify CZE resulted in a novel technique, Correlation Capillary Zone Electrophoresis 

(CCZE). To improve the signal-to-noise ratio drastically, to improve the detection limit, 

CCZE has already been achieved. Other applications are monitoring processes and analysing 

several samples and calibration standards simultaneously. The injection in CZE was subject 

of a study, because proper sample introduction is very important in correlation techniques.<p>



<b>Considerations</b><p>

It is well known that electrokinetic sample introduction leads to a bias in CZE due to 

differences in the electrophoretic mobility of the substances. Therefore, a correction 

by multiplying the peak area with the migration time is often deemed necessary, e.g. 

in case an internal standard for quantitative analyses is used.<p>

With on-column detection, the peak width in the electropherogram depends not only on the 

width of a zone and on the length of the detection cell, but also on the velocity of the 

zone in the detection cell. Differences in velocity lead to a bias in detection. For that 

reason another correction by dividing the peak area by the migration time is used in 

quantitative analyses.<p>

It can be shown, however, that the injection and detection bias are inversely proportional 

to each other. That means that no correction of peak area is necessary for these biases in 

case electrokinetic injection is used in combination with UV-detection, in contrast with 

hydrodynamic injection.<p>

Various experiments have been performed to illustrate the injection and detection bias, 

and to prove that no correction of the peak area is necessary in case the peaks have been 

obtained by UV-detection after electrokinetic sample introduction.<p>

<HR SIZE=0>

Hans van der Moolen<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:hansm@anal.chem.uva.nl">hansm@anal.chem.uva.nl</A><br>

Department of Analytical Chemistry<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 02/02/96</CENTER></H6>

</body>
