<HEAD><TITLE>Plant wide instrumentation: combining analytical measurements made at different locations in a process</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>        

<TR>        

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>Plant wide instrumentation: combining analytical measurements made at different locations in a process</Font></b> </TD>


        </TR>

        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Michel Muller</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Supervisors:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Wim Kok and Age Smilde</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

        </TD>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>University of Amsterdam</Font></TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Project term:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>April 94 - April 98</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

</TABLE>





<HR SIZE = 0>



To be able to perform control of an industrial process, as in the figure below, 

information on the process has to be obtained by analytical instruments (symbolised 

by the Ms in the first figure)<p>

In Process Analysis, measurement data is evaluated to extract optimal process information.<p>

 

It is advantageous to use plant-wide instrumentation since with multiple-instrument data 

instead of single-instrument data a better 'view' of the total process can be created. <p>

<img align=left src="michel.gif">

Also, using multivariate data may lead to improved measurement precision. Problems such 

as the optimal location of the measuring instruments in a process plant and their 

analytical requirements can be investigated.<p>



<img Align=right src="michel1.gif"><p>

<br clear = left>

The focus of the project is on investigating the advantages of combining the data from 

different measuring instruments in one process-plant. Methods that can be used are 

a.o.: multivariate data analysis and -calibration (figure), using the time-behaviour

of the data and computer-based modelling.

To be able to improve process-control, fast measurements have to be made. These 

can be performed with near-infrared spectroscopy. Investigations are carried out 

using process simulations and real NIR-measurements, which will be used for 

calibration, model building and -evaluation of an experimental process. Also, 

introduction of dynamics (time-series behaviour) will be investigated.	

<br clear = all>


<hr size=0>

<i>

Michel Muller<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:mmuller@anal.chem.uva.nl">mmuller@anal.chem.uva.nl</A><br>

Department of Analytical Chemistry<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

