<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Maximum information from separations</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>        

<TR>        

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>


<TD VALIGN=MIDDLE><Font Size = +2><b>Maximum information from separations</Font></b>

 

</TD>	        </TR>        <TR>        

<TD VALIGN=MIDDLE ><Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>        

</TD>        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE ><Font Size = +2>Raivo Kilg</Font>       

</TD>        </TR>        <TR>        <TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>        

<TR>        <TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>Supervisors:</Font>        

</TD>        <TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>H. Smit</Font></TD>        </TR></Font>

        </TD>        <TR>        <TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>        </TD>        

<TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>University of Amsterdam</Font></TD>        

</TR>        <TR>        <TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>        <TR>   

     <TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>Project term:</Font>        

</TD>

<TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>October 1991 - October 1995</Font></TD>    

</TR></Font></TABLE><HR SIZE = 0><b>Introduction</b><p>

The main goal of chromatography, being an analytical technique, is to get 

information about the qualitative or quantitative composition of a sample.  

Therefore, a chromatographic system, a column together with detector, can 

be considered as an information channel in the sense of the information 

theory formulated by Shannon. Extension to the classical information theory 

allows to calculate the maximum information rate passing through the channel, 

assuming certain chromatographic properties like plate number, peak and 

noise models, etc. <p><b>Channel capacity and the quality of peak area 

estimation.</b><p>The channel capacity determines the maximum amount of 

information that can pass through the channel per time unit. The amount of 

information determines the uncertainty in the peak area estimation. The 

quality of the estimation depends on a priori known information about the 

compounds, properties of the column, interferences and on the selected data 

processing method. <p>



<img align=LEFT src="raivo.gif">



<b>Optimal resolution of chromatographic peaks</b><p>

Two important factors in process control are the analysis time and the 

error in the estimation. In chromatography these factors are considered 

mainly to be exclusive - a smaller analysis time results in a bigger error.  

It can be proved  that this is not always the case if all the available 

pre-information and optimal signal processing methods are used. In case 

of a known compound mixture, as is often the case in process control, it 

can be shown that a complete separation of the peaks is not optimal. Peak 

resolution is determined by the properties of the column and can be 

optimised with respect to a minimum uncertainty.<p>An important factor 

influencing the estimation error is the uncertainty in the peak models. 

This uncertainty in the models has to be also modelled and included in 

the signal processing to achieve an optimal result. <p>Defining exactly the 

properties of a system and choosing an optimal signal processing method 

results in significant reduce in analysis time and in far better 

controllability.<p>



<br clear=all>

<hr size=0>

<i>

Raivo Kilg<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:raivo@anal.chem.uva.nl">raivo@anal.chem.uva.nl</A><br>

Department of Analytical Chemistry<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 02/02/96</CENTER></H6>

</body>
</HTML>
