<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Optimal calibration of optical emission spectrometers used for process control</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>        

<TR>        

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>Optimal calibration of optical emission spectrometers used for process control</Font></b> </TD>

	

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>R.H. Jellema</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Supervisors:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>A.K. Smilde (UvA), H.F. Pronk & M.J.P Gerritsen (Hoogovens IJmuiden)</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

        </TD>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Hoogovens IJmuiden</Font></TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Project term:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>september 1995 - september 1999</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

</TABLE>





<HR SIZE = 0>



<b>Introduction</b><p>

<img align=RIGHT src="renger.gif">

At the analytical laboratory for process control of Hoogovens IJmuiden, Optical Emission

 Spectrometers (OES) are used for the analyses of C, Mn, P, S, Si, Al, Cu, Sn, Cr, Ni, 

Mo, Nb, V, B, Ti and Ca in steel samples for process control. The total variance in 

the product is caused by both variance in production and analyses. The product quality 

has to meet stringent product specifications.<p>



We are concerned with two main sources of variance. First, the process variance is 

caused by variance in the production process. Secondly, with the analysis of the product, 

variance of the analysis method is introduced. Figure 1 shows a univariate control chart 

in which the process variance 

(<img src="renger2.gif">) 

and the total variance 

(<img src="renger1.gif">), 

due to process and 

analysis, is plotted for element E. The process will be in control as long as the 

concentration of element E remains within the specification limits (·······). 

Two problems can arise due to analysis error. First, (A) a product can be rejected 

unjustly. Secondly, (B) a product can be approved although the concentration of element 

E exceeded the specification limits.<p>



<br clear=right>



<b>Research project</b><p>



The total calibration procedure involves primary and secondary calibration, verification, 

adjusting, ratio measurements, and analyses. As a first step, the total calibration 

procedure of the OES has been described and some parts have been analysed in depth.<p>



The influence of the different parts of the total calibration on meeting the 

specification limits will be assessed given the interplay between process variance 

and analysis variance. This assessment allows for the optimization of the total 

calibration procedure. Among many, possible techniques which can be used for the 

optimization are, multivariate calibration, Kalman filter, and dynamic calibration[1] . <p>



[1] A. Müller et al., Dynamic calibration and automated instrumental analysis, Fres. J. Anal. Chem, 348(1994)615-625.


<br clear = all>

<hr size=0>

<i>

R.H. Jellema<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:renger@anal.chem.uva.nl	">renger@anal.chem.uva.nl</A><br>

Department of Analytical Chemistry<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

