<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>A knowledge based system for reactor selection</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="ospt1.gif" ALIGN=left></TD><TD><H2>A knowledge based system for reactor selection</H2></TD></TR></TABLE>

<B>Ph.D. student::</B> Drs. R. Jacobs<BR>
<B>Supervisors:</B> Prof. P. Iedema<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> October 92 - October 96<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> NWO/SON<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

The most important step in developing a knowledge based system (KBS) is to decide which tasks
are needed to solve the problem. In this case, which tasks are needed to select a reactor. The
main-task reactor selection is decomposed into six sub-tasks. This results in a program that
closely mimics the behaviour of an experienced reactor engineer. The tasks and a short
description of each task is given below.<P>

<UL>
<LI><I>Collect-fixed-input</I>: This task collects input that is not likely to change during the selection
process. An example of such input is the kinetics.

<LI><I>Analysis-reaction-network</I>: The reaction network that has been specified in the previous task
'collect fixed input' is analysed.

<LI><I>Collect-variable-input</I>: This task collects input that is likely to change during the selection
process.

<LI><I>Derive-hard-features</I>: This task derives the hard features. A hard feature is a feature of the
reactor selection problem that must always be satisfied and cannot be compromised.

<LI><I>Apply-hard-features</I>: This task makes a selection using the hard features derived in the
previous step. Reactors that satisfy the hard features are selected from the set of reactors. The
set of reactors that satisfy the hard features will be called the hard selection.

<LI><I>Apply-specific-and-soft-properties</I>: This task takes a closer look at the hard selection.
Reactors that are member of the hard selection possess specific properties and soft properties.
A specific property is a property of a reactor that must always be satisfied and cannot be
compromised. Soft properties are not used individually, they are evaluated simultaneously. A
large number of small positive effects could compensate for a larger negative effect. So for
soft properties a compromise is possible.
</UL>

<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="jacobs1.gif" ALIGN=left></TD><TD>
The task decomposition serves as a model for the
KBS. This is identical to modelling with which
we are all familiar in chemical engineering. The
only difference is that the physical phenomenon
is replaced by a person, the reactor engineer. The
tasks listed above provide the framework in
which knowledge needed for reactor selection
can be organised in a structured manner. Future
research will encompass the elicitation of this
knowledge, this requires special techniques. An
example of such a technique is concept sorting.
The card shows an example of a reactor that is
used in concept sorting for the problem class
gas-catalyst.</TD></TR></TABLE><P>


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 09/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
