<HEAD><TITLE>Plant-wide controllability and flowsheet structure of complex continuous process plants</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>        

<TR>        

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>


<TD VALIGN=MIDDLE><Font Size = +2><b>Plant-wide controllability and flowsheet structure of complex continuous process plants</Font></b> 

</TD>	        </TR>        <TR>        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>        </TD>        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>A.J. Groenendijk</Font>       </TD>        </TR>        <TR>        

<TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>        <TR>        <TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>

Supervisors:</Font>        </TD>        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>A.C. Dimian, P.D. Iedema</Font></TD>        </TR></Font>        

</TD>        

<TR>        

<TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>        

</TD>        

<TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>University of Amsterdam</Font></TD>        

</TR>        

<TR>        

<TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>        

<TR>        

<TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>Project term:</Font>        

</TD>        

<TD VALIGN=TOP ><Font Size = +2>1995-1999</Font></TD> 

       

</TR></Font></TABLE><HR SIZE = 0><b>Introduction</b><p>Plant-wide controllability 

analysis in the Conceptual Design stage is an issue that has been raised by Dutch 

Process Industries and Engineering Companies for the last five years. This research 

area presently is entered by the University of Amsterdam with the main theme 

Plant-wide Controllability and Flowsheet Structure of Complex Process Plants. The 

rationale behind this theme is evident, since it reflects the notion that in the 

Conceptual Design stage opportunities exist to optimise the Flowsheet Structure with 

respect to controllability. This stands as opposite to the conventional treatment of 

the control structure as an add-on to Process Design after the flowsheet structure 

has already been determined.<p><b>Research issues</b><p>The main theme will be split 

into several research issues:<p><b>* Dynamic simulation of plants</b><br>This issue will 

study a methodology of combining steady-state and dynamic simulation in the case of a 

large plant with recycles. The software environment will be a combination between a 

sequential-solution steady-state simulator (ASPEN PLUS(TM)) and a global-solution dynamic 

simulator (SPEEDUP(TM)).<p><b>* Plant-wide stability analysis</b><br>This issue will study 

the Analysis of Stability and Controllability at the flowsheet level. Use will be made of 

techniques, known from control, and dynamic simulation. The software environment will be a 

combination between SPEEDUP(TM) and MATHLAB®.<p><b>* Treatment of impurities</b><br>This 

issue will study the interactions of recycles dynamics generated by the separation of 

impurities and trace  components in a complex plant, using information both from 

steady-state, as well as from dynamic simulation. This scope is to develop a methodology 

for evaluating flowsheet alternatives and specific design targets.<p><b>* Operability of 

Integrated Flowsheets</b><br>This issue will treat the Operability of complex flowsheet 

structures by applying Process Integration design methods, namely Pinch Point and Water 

Pinch. Waste water minimisation by recycling will receive a special attention.<p>

<b>* Self-regulatory properties of flowsheet structures</b><br>Interaction between units 

usually is expected to complicate dynamics and control. From this point of view it is 

desirable to obtain a self-regulatory flowsheet at the Conceptual Design stage. This issue

 will develop quantitative methods to identify and to characterise self-regulatory 

flowsheet structures, using the experience gained previously.<p><b>* Plant-wide Dynamic 

Multivariate Stability Process Control</b><br>This issue explicitly addresses the 

measurability aspects contained in plant controllability. The challenge here is to 

envisage optimal placement of advanced measurement equipment already in the Conceptual 

Design stage.<p><b>* Systematic Flowsheet Optimisation</b><br>A systematic approach 

directly leading to optimal controllability and operability does not exist and it seems 

to be a high challenge to develop one.

<HR SIZE=0>



<i>

Sander Groenendijk<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:sanderg@chemeng.chem.uva.nl">sanderg@chemeng.chem.uva.nl</A><br>

Department of Chemical Engineering<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 02/02/96</CENTER></H6>

