<HEAD><TITLE>A knowledge-based approach to phenomena-driven process synthesis</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>        

<TR>        

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>A knowledge-based approach to phenomena-driven process synthesis</Font></b> </TD>

	<TD>

	<img align=middle src="ioa.gif">

	</TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ioa Silva Gavrila</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Supervisor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Piet Iedema</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

        </TD>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</TABLE>





<HR SIZE = 0>

<b>Introduction</b>

A design strategy is under development that uses kinetic and thermodynamic information to 

propose process design alternatives. The design alternatives consist of abstract 

processing units that are characterized by: phases of ingoing and leaving streams, mixing 

pattern and volume.<p>

The proposed design strategy has evolved out of the view that we are interested in the 

effect of certain phenomena, such as reactions and phase changes. Therefore we must know 

under which operating conditions these desi-red phenomena proceed, which other pheno-mena 

will take place under these conditions, and how these conditions can be maintained.<p>

A knowledge-based system is currently under development that performs these tasks. The 

system needs as input information about 1) the reaction network and associated kinetic 

and equilibrium data, 2) the feed streams, and 3) the desired products and purities. It 

produ-ces feasible design alternatives in which all occurring phenomena are justified.<p>



<b>Design strategy</b><p>

The design strategy proceeds in two phases. In the first phase the phenomena that will 

take place in a unit are determined, based on their 'role' in the overall process. 

Knowing the role while designing is essential; storing it for later has also advantages: 

it is more obvious why certain decisions have been taken. Some roles of reactions are:

<pre>

needed          reaction lies on reaction path

not tolerable   to be avoided, produces toxics

do-not-care     can be disregarded

</pre>



There are many ways to group phenomena of complex systems and this gives rise to 

<i>structural</i> design alternatives.<p>



<img src="ioa1.gif"><br clear = all><p>

<img src="ioa2.gif"><br clear = all><p>

In the second phase operational alternatives are created. In contrast to optimisation 

approaches where values for the design parameters are looked for, the search here is 

for value ranges. In this way design classes are generated that have certain 

characteristics, e.g. selectivity orderings 

(<i>f</i>(R)><i>f</i>(S), <i>f</i>(R)<<i>f</i>(S)). The choice for numerical values can 

then be deferred to a later stage.<p>



<b>Future work</b><p>

Future work will focus on more complex reactions and reaction networks, and on 

gas/liquid phase changes that proceed in parallel or separate from the reactions.<p>

<br clear=all>

<HR SIZE = 0>

<i>

Ioa Gavrila<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:ioan@chemeng.chem.uva.nl">ioa@chemeng.chem.uva.nl</A><br>

Department of Chemical Engineering<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

<br clear=all>

