<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Phd-projects Amsterdam</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Bioprocess Engineering<HR></H2>

<TT><PRE>
University of Amsterdam
Department of Chemical Engineering
Nieuwe Achtergracht 166
NL 1018 WV Amsterdam

telephone: +31 (0)20 525 6517
fax:       +31 (0)20 525 5604
e-mail:    <A HREF="mailto:heuvel@chemeng.chem.uva.nl">heuvel@chemeng.chem.uva.nl</A>
internet:  <A HREF="http://chemeng.chem.uva.nl:80/bpk/">http://chemeng.chem.uva.nl:80/bpk/</A>
</PRE></TT>

<HR>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../pic/home.gif"></A> PhD-projects Amsterdam

<HR>

<H3>University of Amsterdam<BR>
Faculty of Chemistry</H3>

<H2>Bioprocess Engineering</H2>

<B>Permanent Staff:</B><BR>
S.P.P. Ottengraf<BR>
J.C. van den Heuvel<BR>
E.P. le Comte<BR>
P.G. Verschuren<P>

<B>Research Scientists:</B><BR>
E.E. Beuling<BR>
L. Hellendoorn<BR>
M.C.J. Smits<BR>
W.J.H. Okkerse (TUE)<P>

Our research is dedicated to exploit the full potential of reactor systems employing selective retention of immobilized biomass. To this end the interaction of transport phenomena and kinetics is studied on the scale of the basic unit itself, i.e. the biofilm. This objective is realized by the development and use of appropriate micro-sensors for the measurement of local concentrations and profiles of substrates and products. The insight obtained is used for design, scale-up and optimization of biological conversions, specifically waste gas treatment systems. Current research topics include:<P>

<B>Acceleration of mass transfer</B><BR>
Hydrostatic pressure changes in loop reactors will increase mass transfer in recirculating, gas-producing biofilms. Volume variations of the entrapped gas phase will be compensated by convective flows inside sufficiently rigid biofilms. The effect of these fluctuations is studied on lab-scale by variation of the pressure in a stirred tank reactor.<P>

<B>Co-immobilized mixed culture systems</B><BR>
Diffusion limited oxygen penetration in biofilms may advantageously be used for the successive conversion of substrate by co-immobilized aerobic and anaerobic micro-organisms. Compared to immobilized pure cultures in series, the intermediate product concentration in a co-immobilized culture will both be lower for the first organism at the periphery, and higher for the second organism in the centre.<P>

<B>Transport properties of biofilms</B><BR>
Literature data on effective diffusion coefficients in immobilization matrices are contradictory, and hamper interpretation of observed kinetics. Research is undertaken to extend conventional methods for the determination of diffusive transport in biofilms with micro-electrode measurements, to elucidate contributions of molecular diffusion, void fraction, cell density, tortuosity, etc.<P>

<B>Waste gas treatment</B><BR>
The application of biological trickling filters is studied for the treatment of waste gas streams containing ammonia and dichloromethane, respectively. The influence of other C-sources, heterotrophic organisms and inhibitory products is investigated on a fundamental level. Their effect on operation, design and economics is studies on a macroscopic scale.<P>

<I>Micro-electrodes with tip diameters of 1 - 10 &#181;m were developed for H<SUP>+</SUP>, O<SUB>2</SUB>, NH<SUB>4</SUB><SUP>+</SUP>, NO<SUB>3</SUB><SUP>-</SUP>, and glucose. Financial support is received from the Biotechnological Centre at the UvA, StiPt IOP Milieutechnologie, Hoogovens, and a consortium of several industries and semi-governmental bodies. Co-operation with other institutes include TUE, LUW, University of Hannover, and Technical University Munich.</I><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 26/01/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
