<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Mass transfer properties of biofilms</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>        

<TR>        

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>Mass transfer properties of biofilms</Font></b> </TD>

	</TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Evelien E. Beuling</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Biotechnological Centre UvA</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</TABLE>





<HR SIZE = 0>

<b>Introduction</b><p>



Diffusion of substrates and products through biofilms is often the rate limiting step in 

bioreactors utilizing immobilized cells. Therefore, characterization of the diffusion 

properties is considered essential for the modelling and scale-up of microbial conversion 

processes. Due to the complex and heterogeneous structure of biofilms, however, determination 

diffusion coefficients is difficult. In this project these practical difficulties were 

circumvented by the use of well defined model systems. In this way the influence of different

biofilm properties could clearly be distinguished.<p>



<b>Experimental</b><p>



The diffusion coefficients of oxygen and glucose were determined using a micro-electrode 

which was positioned in the middle of a 3 mm spherical biofilm. The transient response 

upon a step function in the well mixed bulk phase was monitored. The recorded curve was

used to calculate the diffusion coefficient in the biofilm, which under these conditions 

is determined by the tortuosity only.<p>



The obstruction effect of cells in a polymer matrix was first studied on an artificial 

biofilm, consisting of impenetrable particles with the same size as bacteria, embedded 

in an agarmatrix. Subsequently, the influence of different bacterial fractions immobilized 

in the same agar matrix was determined (see Fig. 1). The obstruction imposed by the real 

bacteria on the diffusion of glucose was equivalent to that of the artificial bacteria. 

The transient response of oxygen, however, was far more affected by the biomass fraction. <p>



This phenomenon could be caused by adsorption of oxygen at the bacteria, since this will 

effect a delay of the transient response in the middle of a gel bead. Additional experiments 

confirmed that oxygen was adsorbed by the bacteria, the partition coefficient m amounted 

to 3.5, while glucose was not adsorbed at all (see calculated curves in Fig. 1).<p>



<img src="evelien.gif"><br clear = all><p>



<b>Future work </b><p>



Steady-state experiments will be done in a classical two-compartment diffusion cell, 

in order to determine the effective diffusion coefficient and cell permeability without 

disturbances of phenomena like adsorption.<p>

As most experimental methods reported in the literature are applicable only to rather 

homogeneous systems exhibiting a well-defined geometry, the possibilities of pulsed-gradient 

spin echo NMR are currently investigated. This non-invasive technique enables determination of 

diffusion coefficients in irregularly shaped, spontaneously formed biofilms.<p>

<HR SIZE=0>

<i>

Evelien E. Beuling<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:evelienb@chemeng.chem.uva.nl">evelienb@chemeng.chem.uva.nl</A><br>

Department of Chemical Engineering<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

<br clear=all>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 02/02/96</CENTER></H6>

