<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Co-immobilized mixed culture systems</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>        

<TR>        

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>Co-immobilized mixed culture systems</Font></b> </TD>

	</TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Laura Hellendoorn</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>

        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>University of Amsterdam</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</TABLE>


<HR SIZE = 0>



<img src="laura.gif" align=left>

<br>

<b>Introduction</b><p>



Diffusion limited oxygen penetration in biofilms may advantageously be used for the successive conversion of 

a substrate by co-immobilized aerobic and anaerobic micro-organisms. The production of ethanol from starch 

via glucose by Aspergillus awamori and Zymomonas mobilis was used to investigate the possibilities of such 

systems (see Fig. 1).<p>





<br clear=all>

<img src="laura2.gif" align=right>

<br>

<b>Co-immobilized organisms</b><p>

Competition for the intermediate glucose between the fungus and the bacterium determines the ethanol yield. 

The oxygen concentration in the bulk liquid is an important control parameter for the system. In a shaking 

flask this was found to be rather high, and resulted in excessive growth of the aerobic mold and a 

corresponding low ethanol yield of only 5% (Fig. 2). Cultivation in an airlift loop reactor with a 

carefully monitored oxygen bulk concentration is intended to optimize the ethanol yield of the 

co-immobilized system.<p>



<br clear=all>



<img src="laura4.gif" align=left><p>

<br>

<b>Co-immobilized enzym and bacterium</b><p>

To eliminate the competion for glucose and to circumvent growth of the fungus, the kinetics of the system were 

simplified by replacing the fungus with the relevant amylo-glucosidase enzym. The kinetics of the suspended 

enzyme were determined seperately. Subsequently, the enzym was immobilized in 1% agar beads, coated with a layer

 of poly-ethylene imine and glutaraldehyde to prevent leakage of the enzyme. The glucose production rate of 

two different concentrations of immobilized enzym was measured (Fig. 3). Although the activity amounted to 

only 6% of the value obtained with the free enzym, it remained much more stable time. The measurement of both 

bulk kinetics and internal glucose concentration profiles is intended in the enzyme-bacterium system. Finally, 

the simplified system will be used to model the real system.<p>

<br clear=all>



<HR SIZE=0>

<i>

Laura Hellendoorn<br>

E-Mail: <A HREF="mailto:laurah@chemeng.chem.uva.nl">laurah@chemeng.chem.uva.nl</A><br>

Department of Chemical Engineering<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

<br clear=all>

