<HEAD><TITLE>Removal of ammonia from waste gases with a nitrifying bio-trickling filter</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>



        <TR>

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>Removal of ammonia from waste gases with a nitrifying bio-trickling filter</Font></b> </TD>

	

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Maarten C.J. Smits</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Supervisors:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2></Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

        </TD>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Senter IOP Milieubiotechnologie</Font></TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Project term:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2></Font></TD>

        </TR>

</Font>

</TABLE>





<HR SIZE = 0><p>



Acidification of the environment is a well known problem in Europe. Ammonia emissions 

cause about half of the acid rain. Reduction is possible by controlled microbiological

 oxidation of ammonia to nitrate. A packed bed operated as a bio-trickling filter 

(BTF) is an attractive system for nitrification: nitrifying organisms attach easily 

on a suitable packing material, and, due to their selective retention, high elimination 

capacities (EC) up to 1.6 mol NH3/m3.h can be obtained. Liquid circula-tion and draining 

prevent nitrate and acid accumulation in the biofilm, enabling stable and long-term 

operation. Nevertheless, axial and transversal concentration profiles exist along the 

reactor and the biofilm, respectively, affecting the local kinetics. For design purposes, 

the macrokinetic behaviour of the system has to be understood in terms of these local 

kinetics.<p>



<img src="smits.gif" align=left>



<b>Experimental</b><p>

The effect of the superficial liquid velocity on the performance of a lab-scale BTF was 

investigated. Mass transfer from the gas to the liquid phase was not rate limiting, as 

can be seen from the measured and calculated ammonia profiles in Fig.1. Calculations 

weredone using a simple scrubber model and common correlations for the mass transferring 

area (= wetted area aw) and the mass transfer coefficients. It is also possible, however, 

that ammonia is transferred directly from the gas phase to the non-wetted biofilm.

<br clear=left><p>



<img src="smits2.gif" align=right>



Variation of the liquid rate over a decade only influences the EC some 15% (Fig.2.). 

Comparison of the EC with aw suggests that the active biofilm is considerably larger. 

This can be explained by assuming a dynamic wetted area made up by continuously and 

intermittently wetted biofilm surface, subjected to wash out of the acid reaction 

product. It should be stressed that this is the main function of the recirculating 

liquid flow, since mass transfer was not rate limiting. Futhermore, the increased 

ammonium concentration from 0.22 to 10 mol/m3 at low liquid rates, enhances the 

biological reaction rate.<p>

<br clear=all>

<i>


<HR SIZE=0>

Maarten Smits,<br>

E-Mail: <a href="mailto:maartens@chemeng.chem.uva.nl">maartens@chemeng.chem.uva.nl</a><br>

Department of Chemical Engineering<br>

University of Amsterdam<br>

Nieuwe Achtergracht 166,<br>

1018 WV Amsterdam<br>

The Netherlands<br>

</i>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 02/02/96</CENTER></H6>

