<HEAD><TITLE>Removal of dichloromethane from industrial waste gases</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=TOP CELLPADDING=1>        

<TR>        

        <TD width = 150  VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<img align=middle src="ospt1.gif"></TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE>

<Font Size = +2><b>Removal of dichloromethane from industrial waste gases</Font></b> </TD>

	<TD>

	<img align=middle src="okker1.gif">

	</TD>

     

	</TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Ph.D. student:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=MIDDLE >

<Font Size = +2>Willem Jan H. Okkerse</Font>       </TD>

        </TR>



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >



        <TR>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Sponsor:</Font>

        </TD>

        <TD VALIGN=TOP >

<Font Size = +2>Senter IOP Milieubiotechnologie</Font></TD>

        </TR>

</TABLE>

<HR SIZE = 0>


The solvent dichloromethane is extensively used in industry and the anual emission is

 considerable, due to the relatively high vapor pressure at atmospheric conditions. 

Because of the harmful effects of this compound on the environment, emission has to 

be reduced.<p>



Previous research at the Eindhoven University of Technology has shown that 

dichloromethane can be removed from a contaminated air stream in a biotrickling 

filter if it is the only carbon source present.<p>



<img src="okker.gif" align=right >



Dichloromethane is degraded in the biotrickling filter by a microbial population 

growing on the packing in the form of a biofilm. Prolonged operation of such a 

filter showed that a steady state can be maintained for at least 3 years. This 

can be explained only by the gradual evolution towards a biological equilibrium 

where the carbon fixation rate equals the carbondioxide production rate, i.e. 

the net growth rate equals zero. However, problems arise when other, easy degradable 

compounds like acetone or methylmethacrylate are present in the waste gas: <p>



<ul>

<li>Clogging of the filter bed due to excessive biomass growth.

<li>A considerable decrease of the dichloro-methane conversion.

</ul>



A better understanding of these phenomena is needed to design reliable waste gas 

treatment processes. To that end, the following questions will be addressed for 

a model system treating a dichloromethane / methylmethacrylate mixture:<p>



<ul>

<li>Is it possible to eliminate both compounds in a single biotrickling filter?

<li>Does such a system eventually reach a biological equilibrium? 

<li>If the answers on the previous questions are positive: which factors determine the upper boundaries of the organic load that you can imposed on the system? Are there general rules that can be deduced from these experiments?

</ul>



To answer these questions information is needed on the elimination capacity and the 

structure of the biofilm under various conditions. For this purpose, a special falling 

film reactor was build in which the biofilm area, the pH and the hydrodynamic conditions 

are much better defined than in a biotrickling filter. The biofilm structure will be 

studied at the University of Amsterdam using micro-sensors. Different gradients across 

the biofilm will give information about its spatial build up.

<br clear=all>

<br clear=all>

<HR SIZE=0>

<i>

Willem Jan H. Okkerse<br>

Eindhoven University of Technology<br>

</i>

<br clear=all>

