<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>PhD-projects Delft</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Chemical Reactor Engineering<HR></H2>

<TT><PRE>
Delft University of Technology
Department of Chemical Technology and Material Science
Julianalaan 136
NL 2628 BL Delft

telephone: +31 (0)15 278 4390
fax:       +31 (0)15 278 4452
internet:  <A HREF=http://www.cpt.stm.tudelft.nl/cpt/cre/cre_home.html>http://www.cpt.stm.tudelft.nl/cpt/cre/cre_home.html</A>
</PRE></TT>

<HR>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../pic/home.gif"></A> PhD-projects Delft

<HR>

<H2>TU Delft
Research Group
<B>Chemical Reactor Engineering</B></H2>

<B>Permanent Staff</B><BR>
prof.ir. C.M. van den Bleek<BR>
dr.ir. A.W. Gerritsen<BR>
dr.ir. J.C. Schouten<BR>
dr.ir. H.P.A. Calis<BR>
A. Hexspoor (O&O assistent)<BR>
S. Sewmar (secretary, 015-2783516)<P>

<B>Research Scientists</B><BR>
<TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR><TD>Dipl.-Ing. J.P. Hannes</TD><TD>Dipl.-Ing. F-K&uuml;hn</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>ir. R. Bakker</TD><TD>ir. G.J. Zijlma</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>ir. O.L. Oudshoorn</TD><TD>ir. B.W. van Hasselt</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>ir. O.C. Snip</TD><TD>ir. S. Kaart</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>ir. R.-J. de Korte</TD><TD>Bin Liang PhD</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>E. Ito MSc</TD><TD>J. Tak&aacute;cs MSc</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>ir. R. Korbee</TD><TD>ir. R.C. Zijerveld</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>ir. H.M. Letzel</TD><TD>ir. J. van der Schaaf</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>ir. C.S. Stellema</TD><TD>ir. H.C. Ijselendoorn</TD></TR>
</TABLE><P>

The overall objective of the research group on Chemical Reactor Engineering is the <B>design, development, improvement and application</B> of chemical reactors. Within the framework of the university department, sister institutions and social relevance, the <B>low-pressure drop reactors</B> have been chosen specifically. Regarding the aspects of <I>design, development and improvement</I>, the research effort is aimed in practice at <B>(1) the "fluidized" multiphase reactors</B> (G/S fluidized bed reactor, G/L bubble column and G/L/S slurry reactor) and <B>(2) reactors with structured catalyst packing</B> (Bead String Reactor (BSR), Polylith Reactor (PLR), Zeolite-covered Screen Reactor (ZSR), Three Level of Porosity reactor (TLP), Radial Flow Reactor (RFR), Monolith Reactor (MR)).With respect to these reactor types, the following research areas are identified:<P>

<B>"Fluidized" Multiphase Reactors</B><BR>
Research is carried out on the bubbling as well as on the circulating fluidized bed reactor. The research is aimed at (1) the characterization of fluidization regimes and (2) the improvement of the existing scaling rules for fluidized bed reactors by taking into consideration the dynamic (chaotic) information that is present in time-dependent signals (such as pressure, porosity and particle velocity). Recently, in cooperation with Prof. Krishna (UvA), this work has been extended to include bubble columns, air lift reactors and three phase slurry reactors as well.<BR>
Insight in the chaotic behavior of the fluidized bed reactor is also used to 'de-chaos' the fluidized bed system in order to obtain a fluidized state without - or with only thin - bubbles to improve gas/solid contacting which will be advantageous for conversion and selectivity. Further research is carried out on the 4-bed Interconnected Fluidized Bed Reactor (IFB) which enables a continuous gas/solids acceptation/regeneration system. The objectives of the work are (1) to model the solids and gas flows between the compartments, (2) to determine the influence of the process parameters on these flows, (3) to influence these flows by the geometry of the connecting orifices and (4) the formulation design rules for this type of reactor.<P>

<B>Reactors with Structured Catalyst Packing (BSR, MLR, ZSR, TLP, RFR, MR)</B><BR>
The BSR, MLR, ZSR and TLP are new types of chemical reactors in this area. The objectives are (1) to develop these type of reactors and (2) to formulate reactor models that can be used for design purposes. Due to the structured catalyst packing, not only the pressure drop over the bed is low, but also the sensitivity for dust is small. The structured packing of the BSR, MLR and TLP enables also an improved trickle flow behavior due to the fact that the gas and liquid flows can be geometrically separated; because of this, trickle flow is possible in counter current operation without flooding.<BR>
With the ZSR and MR, the accent is laid on (1) the improvement of reactor calculations with CFD techniques in connection with chemical reactions and on (2) a controlled manufacture. Regarding the latter aspect, the work is linked to that of Van Bekkum where techniques are developed to let the zeolite structure "grow" on, amongst others, this type of structured reactor materials.<P>

The above mentioned low-pressure drop reactors, all find their <I>application</I> within the framework of the research in the section in the areas of Environmental Technology and of Coal Technology.<P>

<B>Environmental Technology</B><BR>
<I>Removal of NOx from off gases of gas engines:</I> Research is carried out on the further development of a specific process for the removal NOx from off gases from Total Energy installations by using injection of a urea solution in order to use the carbon dioxide present in the off gases for fertilization in greenhouses. Recently the first two commercial units have been built and set successfully in operation.<BR>
<I>Catalytic removal of soot and NOx from diesel exhaust gases:</I> The same process is applied in the simultaneous removal of soot and NOx from diesel exhaust gases. With these NOx removal techniques, BSR, MLR, ZSR and MR are used.<P>

<B>Coal Technology</B><BR>
<I>Fluidized Bed Combustion of Coal:</I> The research on FBC has various aims. First of all, the determination of the influence of sub-stoichiometric firing on (1) sulfur retention, in case of the classical (non-regenerable) sorbents like limestone and dolomite as well as for the developed regenerable sorbent CaO/alumina and on (2) the interaction between the emissions of NOx and SO<SUB>2</SUB>. Further, the work is aimed at the development of an engineering model for the sulfur retention/NOx emission on a (circulating) fluidized bed combustor that is based on process parameters that are easy to measure, to calculate or to set and that can be used in the analysis of existing installations and in the design of new ones. Finally, the aim is the formulation of an overall reactor model for the circulating fluidized bed combustor, in the framework of the International Energy Agency (IEA).<BR>
<I>Regenerative removal of H<SUB>2</SUB>S during coal gasification:</I> The aim is the development of a high-temperature regenerative H<SUB>2</SUB>S capture process with characteristic features such as (1) an acceptation of hydrogen sulfide and the subsequent regeneration of the loaded sorbent at the same process temperature and (2) a continuously carried out process using the Interconnected Fluidized Bed reactor.<P>

The group has many (inter)national cont(r)acts. Most PhD projects are part of larger research projects in a national or international framework; part of the work is often carried out at the partners' institute or university, while colleague researchers perform part of their research in Delft.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 21/02/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
