<HEAD><TITLE>Characterization of circulating fluidized bed dynamics with deterministic chaos analysis</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Characterization of circulating fluidized bed dynamics with deterministic chaos analysis</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> ir. John van der Schaaf (015 - 278 2133)<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Burgers Centre<BR>
<B>Cooperation:</B> prof. F. Takens (RU Groningen), prof. Jinghai Li (Institute of Chemical Metallurgy (China)), T.A. Fuller (Babcock & Wilcox, Ohio, USA)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

A circulating fluidized bed (CFB) is a
reactor wherein particles are fluidized with
high gas velocities (~3 - 15 m/s). Particles
blown out of the reactor are separated
from gas flow and reinjected in the reactor.
Major applications are FCC and coal
combustion where the particles act as
catalyst (FCC) and heat carrier (sand)
respectively.<BR>
Different hydrodynamic regimes exist in a
CFB, depending on operating parameters,
such as gas velocity and solids mass flow,
and CFB geometry. Each regime will
behave dynamically different; this can be
characterized using deterministic chaos
analysis on measured pressure fluctuations.
Ultimately, dependence of CFB dynamics
on operating parameters can be used in
scaling up CFBs.<P>

<B>Deterministic Chaos Analysis</B><P>

Pressure fluctuations in a CFB are
generated by dense clusters of particles
moving in a dilute phase, and by a dense
bed, if present, in the riser bottom. CFB
dynamics are considered as nonlinear.
Nonlinear dynamics can be characterized
with deterministic chaos analysis, yielding a
measure for the predictability (Kolmogorov
entropy <B>K</B>) and complexity (correlation
dimension <B>D</B>) of the dynamics.
From measured pressure time series <B>K</B> and
<B>D</B> are determined. How <B>K</B> and <B>D</B> are
coupled to cluster characteristics and dense
bed dynamics is unknown and is subject of
research.<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

The formation, break up and transport of
clusters throughout the circulating fluidized
bed is the main dynamics determining
process ira dense bed is absent. Once a
dense bed has been formed, the dynamic
behaviour is more or less uniform over the
whole riser: gas voids erupting at the dense
bed surface dominate the pressure signal.
Results from deterministic chaos analysis
suggest that a CFB behaves as a spatio-
temporal chaotic system. To obtain more
information on cluster dynamics,
capacitance tomography will be used to
measure voidage fluctuations.<P>

<B>Spatio-temporal Chaos</B><P>

<B>K</B> and <B>D</B> determined in a (circulating)
fluidized bed at various flow regimes are a
function of attractor length scale which is
related to measurement intensity (Pa). The
measured signal can be thought of as being
built up by all pressure waves in the riser
which will be dampened with distance: the
further away a wave is generated the less it
will contribute to the signal at probe
position. Also the coupling between two
positions will decrease with distance.
Zooming in on smaller intensity scales is
therefore equivalent to regarding dynamics
further away from the measuring position.
An important phenomenon for spatiality is
the coupling between positions, determined
by solids and gas momenturn transport.
This coupling will be investigated by
correlating pressure and voidage time
series at different measurement positions.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B29-177</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000116-B040-82</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost95/tud/robert.html 130.89.50.60 19970216191417 text/html 3841
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 19:07:41 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Wednesday, 23-Oct-96 06:56:48 GMT
Content-length: 3658
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Classification of regimes in circulating fluidized beds using deterministic chaos analysis</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Classification of regimes in circulating fluidized beds using deterministic chaos analysis</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. Robert. C. Zijerveld (015-2782133)<BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> NWO, Burgerscentrum, European Union<BR>
<B>Cooperation:</B> Universities of Naples (dr. A. Marzocchella), Hamburg (prof. J. Werther), G&ouml;teborg (dr. F. Johnsson) and Groningen (prof. F. Takens) and Cerchar ( dr. A. Koniuta)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>



<B>Project background</B><P>

Fluidized bed reactors are among the most
important reactors in chemical industry,
because they offer excellent possibilities of
dealing with solid reactants in gas/solid exo-
and endothermic reaction systems. Especially
circulating fluidized beds (CFB's) are of
increasing importance in chemical industry
as well as in the energy sector. However,
design and scale-up of CFB's is still more an
'art' than based on 'knowledge', while also
the fluid dynamic regimes that can be
distinguished in the zones of this reactor are
not very well understood yet. It is expected
that characterization and classification of
these regimes can be enhanced significantly
by application of the methods and techniques
of deterministic chaos analysis. This would
be already of great importance for the design
and further development of applications of
this type of fluidized bed reactor.<P>

<B>Project objective</B><P>

Deterministic chaos analysis is carried out on
time series of pressure that are measured in
cold pilot scale CFB's with different
diameter of the riser (30, 83, 120, 400, 700
and 1000 mm) and in a 12 MW<SUB>th</SUB> full scale
CFB boiler. The dependency of chaos
invariants dimension and entropy on the
fluidizing conditions (gas velocity, solids
size, riser solids hold-up) is determined in
relation to the fluidization regimes, the
geometry of the CFB and the riser diameter.
In this way, a classification of the fluid
dynamic regimes will be set up in terms of
degree of freedom and complexity
(dimension) and degree of information loss
(entropy).<P>

<B>Project organization</B><P>

The project is carried out in the framework
of a cooperation between Delft University of
Technology and University Federico II
(Naples, dr. A. Marzocchella), the Technical
University of Hamburg-Harburg (prof.
Werther), the Rijksuniversiteit Groningen
(prof. Takens), Chalmers University of
Technology (G&ouml;teborg, prof. B. Leckner,
dr. F. Johnsson) and Cerchar (Mazingarbe,
dr. A. Koniuta).<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

Chaos analysis has been done on pressure
fluctuations in a 30 mm ID riser at DUT. At
fixed operating conditions, Kolmogorov
entropy changed along the riser. It appeared
to be a function of the local voidage and
showed a minimum when voidage decreases
from 1.00 until about 0.90. Changes of
Kolmogorov entropy (K, bits/s) with local
voidage (see figure) were interpreted on the
basis of interactions among solids and gas
turbulence structures. Three regions were
identified in the voidage range investigated:
1) particles-controlled region, in which gas
turbulence is damped; 2) clusters-controlled
region, in which gas turbulence is enhanced;
3) bottom bed controlled region, in which
dynamics are determined by the presence of
a dense bottom bed.<P>

<IMG SRC="robert1.gif"><P>

