<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Chaotic control of fluidized beds</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Chaotic control of fluidized beds</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. Robert Jan de Korte (015-2784343)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> September 1994 - September 1998<BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> STW, Cie. Beek, Setpoint IPCOS<BR>
<B>Cooperation:</B> Setpoint IPCOS, research groups prof. Grievink, prof. De Jong, prof. Takens (RUG).<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

Research in recent years has shown that the
hydrodynamics of fluidized beds are chaotic.
Because the hydrodynamics of the bed
determine the performance of the fluidized
bed reactor (mass transfer / conversion) it can
be useful to change it. For instance, if the
average bubble size of gas bubbles in the bed
could be reduced, the bypass of the solids
reduces, resulting in a higher conversion.<P>

<B>Control of chaotic systems</B><P>

Because a fluidized bed is a chaotic system, it
should have the general characteristics of
chaotic systems. Chaotic systems are
deterministic nonlinear systems, showing
irregular - almost random - behavior. It is
impossible to make long term predictions of
the system development because these are
extremely sensitive to initial conditions or
external perturbations. However, short term
predictions are possible and the sensitivity to
control actions can be exploited by a chaos
controller. Such a controller can change the
system behavior completely at the cost of only
very small control actions. This chaos control
idea is only a few years old (1990) and has
not been applied to complex systems yet. To
obtain experience with chaos control
algorithms, a simple experimental chaotic
pendulum was studied.<P>

<B>Control of the chaotic pendulum</B><P>

A new control algorithm was developed for
controlling the pendulum shown in figure 1.
Figure 2 shows that the bevior changes from
chaotic to periodic when the control is
switched on.<P>

<IMG SRC="robertjan1.gif"><P>

<B>Figure 1</B> Schematic drawing of the pendulum
rotating chaotically around its axis because a
electromotor forces it periodically.<P>

<IMG SRC="robertjan2.gif"><P>

<B>Figure 2</B> Angle of pendulum vs time. After a
transient time the control suppresses the
chaotic behavior.<P>

<B>Future work</B><P>

The control algorithms developed for the
pendulum will tried to be applied in a small (4
cm diameter, 20 cm height) fluidized bed to
prevent slugging (this is a flow regime that is
very undesired in general). Preliminary results
show that the slugging can be reduced when a
small fraction of the gasfeed is injected above
the gas distributor. In the future it will be tried
to develop a smart control strategy that
controls this gasflow such that them is a
maximum change to the required
hydrodynamics.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
