<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Controlling chaos in gas-solids fluidized beds to improve chemical performance</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Controlling chaos in gas-solids fluidized beds to improve chemical performance</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> ir. Sander Kaart (015 2784343)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> August 1995 - July 1999<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> SON (programme "Jonge Chemici")<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER><B>INTRODUCTION</B></CENTER><P>

Recent studies show that the hydrodynamic
behavior of fluidized beds has chaotic features.
It is this chaotic behavior that causes the
difficulties in scale-up of bench-scale reactors to
full size industrial plants. However as was shown
by Van der Stappen et al. [1] it is possible to
choose operating conditions in such a way that
the chaotic behavior and so the dynamic
performance will be the same in both small and
large scale reactors.<BR>

As was also shown, there is a direct link between
the bubble behavior and the chaotic behavior of
the fluidized bed. Bubbles are also responsible
for a poor conversion if a mass transfer limited
catalytic reaction is performed in a bubbling gas-
solids fluidized bed reactor (fig. 1). Reactant gas
present in bubbles has to be transferred across
the bubble boundary before it can react at the
catalyst particles. This additional mass transfer
resistance, in combination with the high rise
velocity of the bubbles, leads to bypass of
reactant gas and thus to a lower conversion in a
fluidized bed reactor than in a tube reactor with
the same contact time. If it is possible to
influence the average bubble size, the bypass can
be influenced and preferably be reduced. It was
also shown that bubble size also influences the
selectivity of the reaction system. Since bubbling
fluidized beds are chaotic systems, it may be
possible to influence the hydrodynamics (average
bubble size) of the fluidized bed by using 'chaos
control'.<P>

Another recent study done in the group of Van
den Bleek shows that it is possible to control
chaos in an experimental driven damped
pendulum (De Korte <I>et al</I>.[2]) by stabilizing
unstable periodic orbits (UPO's) using only very
small control actions. The fact that only small
control actions are required is a useful property
of chaotic systems, since the extra energy
demand needed by the control will be small.
If the concept of stabilizing UPOs is extended to
fluidized beds, it might be possible to find a UPO
corresponding to more smaller bubbles in the bed
and thus less bypass.<P>

<IMG SRC="sander1.gif"><P>

Fig. 1: Calculated conversion as function of bubble size for a
model reaction.<P>

<CENTER><B>GOALS</B></CENTER><P>

The main goal of this research will be the
implementation (and modification) of the control
algorithm developed by De Korte, in a 'hot'
fluidized bed to investigate the expected
improvement of the conversion and selectivity.
A sub-goal of this research will be to investigate
if the chemical performance (conversion) in both
small and larger scale reactors will be the same
if both chaotic behavior and number of reaction
units are kept constant.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>[1] Van der Stappen, M. L. M., Schouten, J. C., Van den
Bleek, C. M,'Chaotic hydrodynamics and scale-up of gas-
solids fluidized beds', Fluidization VIII, May 1995<BR>
[2] De Korte, R. J., Schouten, J. C., Van den Bleek, C.
M.,'Experimental control of a chaotic pendulum with
unknown dynamics using delay coordinates', to be
published in Physical Review E October 1995.</FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
