<HEAD><TITLE>Analysis and prediction methods for nonlinear dynamic systems</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Analysis and prediction methods for nonlinear dynamic systems</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> ir R. Bakker (015 - 2784343)<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> SON/NWO<BR>
<B>Cooperation:</B> Prof. dr. R. Krishna (UvA) / Prof. dr. F. Takens (RU Groningen)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The dynamic behavior of 'fluidized'
multiphase reactors is considered to be
chaotic.<BR>
Chaotic systems are very sensitive for small
perturbations. On one hand, this is the reason
that future behavior can be predicted only for
a very short period of time. On the other hand,
this offers the possibility to
drastically change
the system
behavior <I>applying</I>
only small
perturbations. This
is known as
'chaos-control'.<BR>
To find out what kind of behavior
(e.g. hydrodynamical regime) can be
created this way, it is necessary to
identify the deterministic rules
underlying the chaotic system.<BR>
'Fluidized' multiphase reactors are too
complex to derive these rules from first
principles. Instead, a general nonlinear model
structure is chosen that has parameters that
can be fitted to measured data.<P>


<B>Objectives</B><BR>
In chronological order, the aims of the project
are:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>find model structure that is most
suited for chaotic systems
<LI>apply modeling technique to a
fluidized bed
<LI>make models available for 'chaos-
control'
</UL>

<B>Preliminary results</B><BR>
As candidate model structures, both
polynomial (NARMA) and neural network
models have been taken into consideration.
A well understood, low dimensional chaotic
system was used as a test case. The system is
an experimental, driven and damped
pendulum. The figure below shows how the
non-linearity of the functions to be
approximated grows with increasing
prediction time phi.<BR>
This causes the limited predictability of
chaotic systems.<P>

<IMG SRC="bakker1.gif"><P>

<I>surfaces that predict future values of the
angle theta of the pendulum (see text)</I><P>

Actually these functions are not known, only
a large number of measured function values
(as shown in the figure) is known. The
surfaces are generated by a neural network
model trained on this data.<BR>
It has been found that the prediction accuracy
highly improves when predicting multiple
small steps ahead instead of one larger step in
time.<P>

<B>Future work</B><BR>
The neural network modeling technique will
be extended to fluidized bed data. This
requires the development of additional
techniques, e.g. local linear predictors, that
will estimate the predictability and dimension
of the underlying chaotic system, prior to
network training.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
