<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>A fundamental approach to the scale up of bubble columns and air-lifts</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>A fundamental approach to the scale up of bubble columns and air-lifts</H2>

<B>PhD:</B> Ir. H.M. Letzel (015-2786329)<BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> SON/NWO, AKZO NOBEL, DSM<BR>
<B>Cooperation:</B> Prof. dr. R. Krishna (UvA, Copromotor), DSM<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In this project we aim to find methods for
the scale up of the hydrodynamics and mass
transfer in bubble columns and air-lift
reactors, especially under high pressure
conditions. To achieve this, two strategies
are combined: that of the group of Prof.
Krishna (Amsterdam) which uses the
concept of hydrodynamic analogies and that
of the group of Prof. van den Bleek (Delft)
where the scale up problem is approached
considering the chaotic characteristics of the
reactor.<P>

Using the method of chaos analysis we hope
(and seem) to find a powerful method for
determining regime transitions with high
precision, which is very important for
understanding the hydrodynamics at high
pressure conditions.<P>
Furthermore, correlations are sought
between flow parameters and chaotic
characteristics, which should lead to new
scale up rules.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
Experiments are performed simultaneously in
Delft in a 0.l m and a newly built 0.19 m
diameter column, and in Amsterdam in a
wide range of column sizes. Starting at the
beginning of 1996 experiments will be
performed at DSM research in a 0.15m
column which can be operated up to
pressures of 20 bar.<BR>
Hydrodynamics are studied using pressure
fluctuation signals from probes which can be
placed at different positions in the column.
In the future mass transfer will be
investigated simultaneously with the
hydrodynamics.<P>

<B>Signal (pre-)processing</B><BR>
A pressure signal from a G/L system is very
complex due to the high conductivity of the
continuous phase for pressure waves. Using
cross spectral analysis from signals of two
sensors placed above each other, a method is
developed to separate these shock effects
from the part of the signal produced by
bubbles in the direct neighbourhood of the
sensors.<P>

<B>Flow Regime</B><BR>
Several signal processing methods have been
investigated and applied. It was found that,
calculating chaotic characteristics of a time
series, a razor sharp picture of the regime
transition is obtained (figure). Therefore this
analysis method is very promising for
fingerprinting the regime of operation of a
G/L system.<P>

<IMG SRC="letzel1.gif"><P>

<I>Flow-regime transition in pre-salinated water</I><P>

<B>Future</B><BR>
Starting in the beginning of 1996,
experiments will be carried out at DSM-
research using the method of pressure
sensing that was refined for G-L systems.
Simultaneously, scale effects will be studied
in Delft and Amsterdam.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
