<HEAD><TITLE>Electrical capacitance tomography (ECT) applied to a fluidised bed</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Electrical capacitance tomography (ECT) applied to a fluidised bed</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Dipl.-Ing. Frank T. K&uuml;hn (phone: 015-786329)<BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> J.M. Burgerscentrum<BR>
<B>Cooperation:</B> Joint project of the research groups of Van den Bleek, Scarlett and Van den Akker<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>INTRODUCTION</B><P>

This project uses chaos theory to investigate
dynamic behaviour of fiuidised beds. The measuring technique <I>electrical capacitance tomography (ECT)</I> serves to determine the fluctuation of the local porosity in a gas-solids fluidised bed with time. These data are translated into invariants such as the <I>Kolmogorov entropy</I> to quantify the degree of chaos. Measurements show a strong variation of this number with bed position and operational parameters.<P>

<B>EXPERIMENTAL SET-UP</B><P>

<IMG SRC="frank1.gif"><P>

The ECT set-up depicted in the schematic
above consists of the following main parts:<P>

<B>The capacitance sensor</B>, i.e. 12 copper
electrodes glued to the outer wall of the
nonconductive fiuidised bed pipe segment.<P>

<B>The sensor electronics</B> which are consisting of 12 channels based on the <I>charge
transfer principle</I>.<P>

<B>The image reconstruction part</B> that
translates the capacitance values measured between any two of the electrodes
into cross-sectional voidage distributions.<P>

<B>RESULTS</B><P>

The figure below shows radial dependencies of
the Kolmogorov entropy obtained by an analysis of the voidage fluctuation of single image
pixels. Measurements were done using various gas velocities.<P>

<IMG SRC="frank2.gif"><P>

<B>OUTLOOK</B><P>

<UL>
<LI>
A wide variety of measurements will be
done with the goal to enhance the reliability of scale up rules for fiuidised beds.
<LI>
The system will be used to see whether
the compressor system used influences
the hydrodynamic behaviour.
<LI>
The image reconstruction part merely
gives qualitative data. A quantitative algorithm using multiple iterations is to be
developed and tested.
</UL>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
