<HEAD><TITLE>Emissions of NOx and SOx in circulating fluidized bed combustion of coal</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Emissions of NO<SUB>x</SUB> and SO<SUB>x</SUB> in circulating fluidized bed combustion of coal</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. Geuch Zijlma (015-2784753)<BR>
<B>Project period:</B> September 1995 -October 1999<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> European Communities<BR>
<B>Cooperation:</B> Cerchar (France), EdF (France), Stein Industries (France), Chalmers University (Sweden), Vattenfall (Sweden)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In future, energy generation from coal will
become more important. The generation by
means of coal combustion should be realized
with maximum possible efficiency and a
minimum emission of pollutants such as SO<SUB>x</SUB>
and NO<SUB>x</SUB>. Circulating Fluidized Bed
Combustion (CFBC) is a very promising
technology for clean coal combustion.<BR>

In a Circulating Fluidized Bed (CFB) the
emission of SO<SUB>2</SUB> can be lowered by addition of
a lime-based sorbent such as limestone. Due
to the lower temperature in a CFB (850°c)
than other combustion processes, the emission
of NO<SUB>x</SUB> from a CFB will be lower. On the
other hand limestone can have a promoting
effect on the emission of NO<SUB>x</SUB>. Air staging is
applied to decrease the emission of NO<SUB>x</SUB>,
dividing the combustion air in primary and
secondary air. The low oxygen concentration
in the lower part, however, may lead to a
decreased retention of SO<SUB>2</SUB>.<P>

<TABLE>
<TR><TD>
<IMG SRC="geuch1.gif"><P>
Figure 1: <I>quartz CFB set-up</I><P>
</TD>
<TD>
<B>Experimental set-up</B><BR>
The reactor consists of a riser (2 m high, 0.063
m ID), two cyclones, a standpipe and a L-valve to control the solid flow rate. The CFB
is made of quartz glass in order to eliminate
the otherwise relatively large catalytic wall
effect of a small-scale plant. In order to
operate the CFB at 850°C without the
combustion of coal, the set-up is equipped
with electrical heating. The pressure in the
reactor is approximately atmospheric.<BR>

The primary air is introduced through a
distributor plate in the bottom of the riser.
The secondary air can be introduced through
three inlet ports at different heights. A
synthetic gas mixture containing N<SUB>2</SUB>, 0<SUB>2</SUB>, S0<SUB>2</SUB>,
CO, CO<SUB>2</SUB>, H<SUB>2</SUB>, H<SUB>2</SUB>0, NH<SUB>3</SUB>, or NO can be
fed with the primary air.
The riser is equipped with nine sample ports at
different heights, with which gas samples can
be obtained for analyses. All relevant
components are determined by means of a
Fourier Transformed Infra Red spectrometer.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Further research on the influence of
primary/secondary air ratio and feed
location of secondary air on SO<SUB>x</SUB>/NO<SUB>x</SUB>
emission.
<LI>Testing of catalytic properties of bed
materials, especially on NO<SUB>x</SUB> formation.
<LI>Mapping the CFB's fluid dynamical
behavior by means of pressure
measurements, to support reactor modeling.
</UL>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
