<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Modelling of circulating fluidized bed combustion</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Modelling of circulating fluidized bed combustion</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Dipl.-Ing. Jens P. Hannes (tel: +49 241 80 7098)<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Prof. ir. C.M. van den Bleek (tel: 015 78 4390)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> September 1991 -October 1995<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> DUT Fellowship, STW, RWTH-Aachen, EDF<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Opposite to the increasing need for supply
with heat and electricity the emission
limitations steadily increase and the vivid
discussions about greenhouse effects claim
the necessary reduction of the carbon dioxide outputs to the atmosphere.<P>

<B>The technology</B><BR>
Figure 1 shows an abstract scheme of a
CFBC plant including all possible extentions like tube bundles or the external heat
exchanger.<P>

<IMG SRC="jens1.gif"><P>

<B>Figure 1:</B> Schematic CFBC Furnace<P>

In a CFB particles are fluidized with a high
gas velocity to carry them out of the furnace,
separate them with a cyclone and reinject
them after extraction of heat, to the furnace
again.<BR>
Advantages: Direct desulfurization by limestone injection; low NOx emissions due to
low combustion temperatures; good burn
out of fuel due to long residence times of
the particles.<P>

<B>The project</B><BR>
TU Delft and RWTH Aachen (Germany)
took over the task to develop a basic steady
state, one dimensional model, free to be used
and improved by any member of the FBC-
framework of the International Energy
Agency.<BR>
The model includes the following items:
<UL>
<LI>adaptation of the geometry and layout
<LI>hydrodynamics of solids and gas
<LI>population balances of the particles
<LI>combustion and chemical reactions in gas
<LI>heat transfer and temperatures
</UL>

<IMG SRC="jens2.gif">

<B>Figure 2:</B> Cumulative size fractions<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
First calculations show a reasonable fit of
the description of the hydrodynamic beha-
viour of the model. Exemplary, the cumula-
tive size distribution function is plotted in
Figure 2 and the temperature profile in the
riser in Figure 3.<P>

<IMG SRC="jens3.gif"><P>

<B>Figure 3:</B> Temperature profile in a riser<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
