<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Interconnected fluidized bed technology for regenerative desulfurization</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Interconnected fluidized bed technology for regenerative desulfurization</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. Onno C. Snip (015- 2784753)<BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> European Communities, Cie. Beek<BR>
<B>Cooperation:</B> Universit&eacute; de Compi&egrave;gne, IRI, Research groups Grievink and Moulijn (DUT-CPT), NOXSO corporation (USA)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

An Interconnected Fluidized Bed (IFB)
reactor system for regenerative sulfur
capture during fluidized bed combustion of
coal and coal gasification processes is
investigated. The main advantages of the
IFB system are: (1) compactness and (2)
minimal attrition due to the effective solids
transport.<BR>

The solids transport is induced and
controlled by means of differences in
fluidization velocity. This causes the solids
to flow in turn over a weir and through an
orifice. See Figure 1.<P>

<IMG SRC="onno1.gif"><P>

Figure 1. <I>Principle of solids flow.</I><P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Testing the IFB concept in a hot facility
for continuous sulfur capture and
regeneration.
<LI>Further development of a hydrodynamic
model for the transport of solids and
gas between the compartments.
<LI>Development of rules for design,
operation and control of the IFB
process.
</UL>

<B>Experimental set-up</B><P>

The hydrodynamics are studied in two cold
facilities: (1) 'twin-bed facility' to study in
detail solids and gas transport through a
system of two connected beds and (2) 'jet-
facility' in which solids flow from a
fluidized or aerated bed to a pressurized or
atmospheric (empty) compartment.
Further a small high temperature IFB pilot
plant was constructed. In this facility the
behaviour and performance of the IFB
reactor for continuous regenerative
desulfurization is studied.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>

Introductory experiments in the 4-bed IFB
pilot plant facility showed that it can be
successfully used for regenerative
desulfurization. Further, the elucidation of
the hydrodynamics is continued with the
development of a hydrodynamic model
based on a momentum analysis. In Figure 2
it is shown that the model is able to
describe the solids flow in the experimental
facilities reasonable. The model is therefore
a useful tool in predicting the solids
circulation in an IFB system.<P>

<IMG SRC="onno2.gif"><P>

Figure 2. <I>Measured versus calculated solids
flux in 'twin-bed facility'.</I><P>



<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
