<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Solids & gas transport in interconnected fluidized beds</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Solids & gas transport in interconnected fluidized beds</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir Cees S. Stellema (015-278 1485/4753)<BR>
<B>Cooperation:</B> Radioisotope Applications at IRI, DUT / Chemical Reactor Engineering at STM, DUT<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

An Interconnected Fluidized Beds (IFB)
system consists of a multitude of two vessels
(twin beds) that are connected via an orifice.
By aerating the beds differently, solids can be
transported from the dense bed (low aeration,
downflow) to the lean bed (fluidisation,
upflow). These twin beds feed each other by
weirs. A possible application of a 4-vessel IFB
is regenerative desulfurization of exhaust
gases.<P>

<B>Experimental setups</B><P>

The first setup is an open twin bed system
fed by an external hopper. Solids (glass beads)
are transported through the system and
collected in a bucket. The bucket and the twin
bed both are continuously weighed. The mass
flow can be measured under various
conditions (orifice diameter, feed rate and
aeration rates). The pressure at various
positions in the beds is also monitored.<BR>

The second setup is a closed 4-bed system
through which the glass beads circulate (see
figure 1.). One of the beads is made
radioactive through irradiation by thermal
neutrons in a nuclear reactor. This bead is
used as a tracer. It contains Sb-124 emmitting
y-rays of 660 keV. From the time series of the
siguals of two external scintillation detectors
relatively positioned at a 90&#176; angle, residence
time distribution histograms for each bed can
be made (see figure 2.).<BR>
The third setup is in preparation. A gamma-
camera (a large scintillation crystal with
several photo multipliers) will be placed
alongside the IFB-system. With an extra
scintillation detector placed on the opposite
side of the IFB-system three dimensional
single particle tracking (SPT) may become
feasible.<P>

<IMG SRC="cees1.gif"><P>

<I>fig. 1. Schematic 4-bed lFB system.</I><P>

<B>Results</B><P>

The results of the first setup are mainly
used for model and tracer representativeness
verification.<BR>
With the second setup under certain
circumstances interesting deviations from
ideally mixed solids flow are measured:<P>

<IMG SRC="cees2.gif"><P>

<I>figure 2. normalized RTD-histograms (E[theta]).</I><P>

<B>Future Developments</B><P>

- Gas tracing (He, <SUP>81m</SUP>Kr) in all three setups.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
