<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Development of the polylith reactor (PLR)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Development of the polylith reactor (PLR)</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. Henk C. IJselendoorn (015-(2)782635)<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Delfts Stimulus Committee (Committee Beek)<BR>
<B>Cooperation:</B> Joint project of the research groups of Van den Bleek and Sie<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In July 95 the project of the development of
the PolyLith Reactor (PLR) was started. The
?LR is a novel low pressure drop reactor with
a structured catalyst packing for heterogeneous
catalysis. The catalyst packing consists of
catalyst rods. These rods are formed by
pressing suitable catalyst material on (metal)
wire structures. The resulting catalyst rod
structures are arranged in the reactor.
Depending on the arrangement of the rods, a
structured catalyst packing can be created
with:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>excellent radial mixing properties (~ static
mixer)
<LI>rates of heat and mass transfer from
catalyst to fluid that are comparable with
a fixed bed reactor
<LI>low pressure drop that can be manipulated
through a.o. the voidage
<LI>low sensitivity to dust
<LI>efficient use of reactor volume (voidage
adjustable between nearly 100% and 22%)
</UL>

<B>Research topics</B><BR>
The research objective is the development of
experimental verified reactor models and
design equations for the PLR. Therefore, four
items will be investigated. These are (1) a
study of pressure drop across a PLR, (2) a
study of mass transfer from the catalyst rods
to the gas phase in a PLR, (3) a study of
mixing behaviour of a PLR and (4) a study of
the kinetics of a suitable model reaction:
selective catalytic reduction of NO with NH<SUB>3</SUB>.
The pressure drop will be studied with model
rods of glass or catalyst rods. Parameters will
be: the diameter of the rods, the porosity of
the packing (distance between rods), the angle
between the rods and the reactor wall and the
gas velocity. The mass transfer will be studied
by measuring the mass decrease of
sublimating naphthalene particles placed in
the reactor. The same parameters will be
varied as with pressure drop, but also the
place of the naphthalene particles in the
reactor will be a parameter. The mixing
behaviour of the reactor will be studied by
measuring the mixing of a hot and a cold gas
in the reactor. From the measured
temperature profiles dispersion coefficients
will be derived for a reactor model of the
PLR. The kinetics will be measured in a
'Berty' internal recycle reactor. Experimental
validation of the reactor models will take
place by performing the model reaction as a
test reaction in an PLR. Another part of the
research is the study of pressing of catalyst
material on wires. The study of the pressing
will consist of two parts: (1) how should the
rods be pressed and (2) what are the
consequences of the pressing for the strength
of the catalyst rods and the activity of the
catalyst rods (pore volume, pore size
distribution, kinetic activity)?<P>

<IMG SRC="henk1.gif"><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>Fig: Structure of PLR</FONT>


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
