<HEAD><TITLE>Development of a zeolite catalyst for NOx removal from diesel exhaust gas</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Development of a zeolite catalyst for NO<SUB>x</SUB> removal from diesel exhaust gas</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> Eri Ito, M.Sc.<P>
<B>Status:</B> PhD student<BR>
<B>Started:</B> September 1991<BR>
<B>External Support:</B> VROM<BR>
<B>Cooperation:</B> Joint project between the groups of Van Bekkum and Van den Bleek
<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>The project aims at the development of a zeolite catalyst applicable for reduction of
nitrogen oxides (NO<SUB>x</SUB>) in diesel exhaust gas by means of a urea solution.<BR>
Our catalyst system will finally be integrated with a soot removal catalyst system to
be developed by the group of Moulijn (TU Delft), in order to obtain a total exhaust
treatment system for diesel exhaust gas.</I><P>

<B>INTRODUCTION</B><P>

The NO<SUB>x</SUB> emission from vehicles is an urgent environmental problem. For gasoline
automobiles, an applicable exhaust treatment catalyst: three-way catalyst, is already developed,
however, there is still no proper catalyst for NO<SUB>x</SUB> reduction in diesel vehicle application. We
have started our project to develop a zeolite catalyst, which effectively reduces nitrogen oxides
by NH<SUB>3</SUB> or an aqueous urea solution.<P>

<B>RESULTS</B><P>

<I>The finding of cerium-exchanged zeolite catalyst</I><BR>
A variety of metal-exchanged zeolites were tested for the model reaction of NO
reduction with NH<SUB>3</SUB> in the presence of oxygen, and cerium-exchanged zeolite (ZSM-5 and
mordenite) turned out to be highly active and selective. Furthermore, cerium-zeolite catalyst
was found to be exceptional with its low catalysis in the undesired side reaction of SO<SUB>2</SUB>
oxidation, and also with a possible application of an excess NH<SUB>3</SUB> to NO without the secondary
NH<SUB>3</SUB> emission. This catalyst was patented in 1993. At this moment, the deactivation behavior
of this cerium-zeolite catalyst is under investigation.<P>

<I>The reaction mechanism study</I><BR>
The reaction mechanism has been investigated with cerium-exchanged mordenite using
different techniques. In particular, with use of in-situ infrared spectroscopy, we have suggested
that the reaction proceeds as a pair of nitrosation reactions (NO<SUP>+</SUP> - NH<SUB>3</SUB>, and NO<SUB>2</SUB><SUP>-</SUP> - NH<SUB>4</SUB><SUP>+</SUP>) at and
below 300 &#176;C.<P>

<I>Preparation of a supported zeolite catalyst</I><BR>
A direct synthesis of ZSM-5 and mordenite on a metal support was performed, and
tested for NO reduction with NH<SUB>3</SUB>. This low pressure-drop zeolite catalyst, particularly ZSM-5,
can be potentially applied as a real diesel exhaust treatment catalyst.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
