<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>The zeolite-covered screen reactor - a dust-resistant, low pressure drop-reactor</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>The zeolite-covered screen reactor - a dust-resistant, low pressure drop-reactor</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. Otto L. Oudshoorn ((015) 2782129)<BR>
<B>Project period:</B> July 1993 - August 1997<BR>
<B>External support:</B> Koninklijke/Shell-Laboratorium Amsterdam<BR>
<B>Cooperation:</B> Joint project of the research groups of Van den Bleek and Van Bekkum<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Zeolites <I>grown</I> on a Support</B><BR>
Recently, a new technique has been found at our
laboratory by which it is possible to grow
zeolite crystals <I>in situ</I> on structured packings of
various shapes and forms:<P>

<IMG SRC="otto1.gif"><P>

<I>Zeolite crystals grown on a
stainless steel wire (D=35/&#181;m)</I><P>

The zeolite crystals appear to be chemically
bonded to a surface, thus providing a reliable
catalytic system.
Application of Zeolites as catalyst finds an
increasing interest in industry. Common
practice in applying Zeolites is to bring them in
a matrix, such as silica-alumina. This form of
operation, however, is not optimal: the active
sites are shielded from the reacting fluid by the
matrix and not all zeolite crystals are utilized
equally well due to concentration gradients.
Preferably, the Zeolites should be applied in
their crystalline form; however, since zeolite
crystals are very small, this would give rise to
other problems, such as high pressure drops
and/or difficulties in recollecting the catalyst.<P>

<B>Research Objectives</B><BR>
The objective of this Research Project is to
investigate the feasibility of reactor systems
based on this new type of Zeolite Packings.
Removal of NOx is chosen as one of the model
reactions. Selective Catalytic Reduction of NO<SUB>x</SUB>
with methane as a reductant is a new technology
for reducing NOx emission from off-gases:<P>

2NO + CH<SUB>4</SUB> + 0<SUB>2</SUB> --> N<SUB>2</SUB> + CO<SUB>2</SUB> + 2H<SUB>2</SUB>O<P>

This type of de-NOx-ing provides a number
of strong advantages over common processes,
using ammonia. Besides methane, other
hydrocarbons could be used. This type of
reaction is, for example, catalysed by cobalt
exchanged MFI zeolite.<BR>
Several zeolite types have been successfully
grown on a carrier, among others ZSM-5 and
zeolite beta. Parameters affecting growth are
investigated, such as the concentrations of the
components in the synthesis mixture,
crystallization temperature, etc.<BR>
Catalytic tests will initially be conducted
using an internal recycle reactor-based set up. In
this way gradientless measurement of the
catalytic activity of produced packings can be
performed.<P>

In a later stage other types of reactions will be
investigated. Attention will be focussed on
reaction systems which benefit by the use of
structured packings, <I>i.e.</I>, a low pressure drop
and/or a strong heat effect (endothermic or
exothermic), such as oxidation reactions.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
