<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Three level porosity reactor concept</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Three level porosity reactor concept</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. Bastiaan W. van Hasselt<BR>
<B>e-mail:</B> <A HREF="mailto:B.vanHasselt@stm.tudelft.nl">B.vanHasselt@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
<B>External support:</B> Onderzoekschool Procestechnologie<BR>
<B>Cooperation:</B> Joint project of the research groups of Sie/Moulijn and Van den Bleek<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER><B>Introduction</B></CENTER>
In many multiphase catalytic processes,
an economic balance between diffusion
limitation and pressure drop determines
the size of the catalyst particles. For
hydroprocessing of heavy oils these
particles are generally 0.8 to 3 mm in
size. With these particles, operating
countercurrently below the flooding point
is only possible at unacceptably low
linear    velocities.    Countercurrent
operation, however, gives the highest
catalyst activity and hydrogen purity in
that part of the bed where it is needed to
convert the least reactive compounds.
Besides the countercurrent mode of
operation results in a more favourable
flat temperature profile.<P>

<CENTER><B>The TLP concept</B></CENTER>
Simultaneous presence of gas and liquid
and their intimate contact on particle
scale is not necessary in hydroprocessing
as the G/L mass transfer is relatively fast.
Therefore a reactor is conceived in which
a low pressure drop is obtained at the
expense of G/L mass transfer
effectiveness. In this reactor gas and
liquid flow countercurrently through
separate channels with the possibility of
periodic contact.<BR>
The reactor packing has three levels of
porosity: nanometre pores inside the
catalyst particles, millimetre pores
between the catalyst particles packed in a
bed or cluster and centimetre pores
between the various beds or clusters.
Liquid flows through the millimetre
pores driven by gravity, gas flows
preferentially through the centimetre
pores driven by a small pressure
difference. The structured catalyst
packing gives the three level porosity
(TLP) reactor the advantage of easy scale
up.<BR>
One of the actual embodiments of this
TLP reactor concept may be a reactor in
which normal catalyst particles are
contained in beds, formed by horizontal
layers of folded wire gauze.<P>

<IMG SRC="bastiaan1.gif"><P>

<I>the TLP concept in G/L countercurrent operation</I><P>

<CENTER><B>Objectives</B></CENTER>
The objective of the project is to
establish the feasibility of the TLP
concept and to develop specific
embodiments of it. The characteristics
and scope of the reactor for three phase
catalytic processes must be determined.
Investigations    will    focus    on
hydrodynamics and mass transfer.
Attention will be paid to modelling of
flow behaviour, gas and liquid
distribution and reactor filling. A lab-scale reactor module is currently under
construction.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
