<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>PhD-projects Delft</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Industrial Catalysis<HR></H2>

<TT><PRE>
Delft University of Technology
Department of Chemical Technology and Material Science
Julianalaan 136
NL 2628 BL Delft

telephone: +31 (0)15 278 5008
fax:       +31 (0)15 278 4452
e-mail:    <A HREF="mailto:klis@stm.tudelft.nl">klis@stm.tudelft.nl</A>
internet:  <A HREF="http://www.cpt.stm.tudelft.nl/cpt/ic/Research/">http://www.cpt.stm.tudelft.nl/cpt/ic/Research/</A>
</PRE></TT>

<HR>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../pic/home.gif"></A> PhD-projects Delft

<HR>

<H3 ALIGN=center>Delft University of Technology<BR>
Research group 'Industrial Catalysis'
</H3>

<B>Scientific-Staff:</B><BR>
prof.dr. J.A. Moulijn<BR>
prof.dr.ir. S.T. Sie (parttime)<BR>
dr.ir. M. Makkee<BR>
dr. F. Kapteijn<BR>
dr.ir. A. Stankiewicz<BR>
dr. A.D. van Langeveld<BR>
dr. X.D. Xu<P>

<B>Management-assistent:</B><BR>
mw. Q. Klis (015-2786725)<P>

The group, named "Industrial Catalysis" aims to cover the whole range of catalytic activities from micro to the macro level with the aim to improve existing and to develop new catalytic processes. Especially new developments in this area ate topics of investigation. More specifically, the present and future activities focus in the following topical areas:<P>

<UL>
<LI><B>application of monoliths and other structured catalysts</B> (at present: diesel exhaust cleaning, LPT, rotating monoliths; future plans in the area of multiphase hydrotreating, liquid phase catalysis and other rotating monoliths applications);
<LI><B>catalysis under transient conditions</B> (Multitrack, LPT, Temperature programmed techniques, FCC and rotating monoliths);
<LI><B>membrane applications in catalytic processes</B>, to enhance energy efficiency, reactor selectivity and yields;
<LI><B>process improvement/development</B> (benzene hydrogenation, CFC-conversion, diesel exhaust cleaning, hydrotreating, N<SUB>2</SUB>O emission reduction.
</UL>

To this purpose various standard facilities for catalytic research are available within the group and several techniques within the faculty (XRD, XPS, HREM). Especially worth mentioning are the following techniques: Quasi-in-situ HREM and XPS, a miniriser (FCC), in-situ FTIR-DRS, TG/DSC/MS, TPR/TPS, Multitrack (under construction), membrane permeation equipment and several catalytic testing facilities.<P>

The research group cooperates intensively with industry and research groups at institutes and universities. Most PhD-work is a part of a bigger national or international framework. The coaching is in principle performed by the permanent staff.<P>

