<HEAD><TITLE>Continuous regenerative H2S removal from fuel gases in a rotating monolith reactor</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Continuous regenerative H<SUB>2</SUB>S removal from fuel gases in a rotating monolith reactor</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> Ir. W.J.W. Bakker<BR>
<B>Status:</B> PhD Student<BR>
<B>Started:</B> December 1991<BR>
<B>External support:</B> Stimuleringsruimte TU-Delft, EU<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

The use of monoliths as structured
catalysts in the chemical industry is
getting growing attention. Conventional
fixed bed reactors have some obvious
disadvantages, such as high pressure drop
and realdistributions of various kinds.
The composition of a gas outflowing
from a periodically operated absorber
changes in time which is often considered
as a significant drawback. Moreover, if a
frequent regeneration of an acceptor is
required the operation of the system
becomes troublesome.<BR>
Therefore, the concept of the rotating
monolith reactor has been adopted. In
this multi-functional reactor system
adsorption and regeneration takes place
simultaneously. Pressure drop, dust and
attrition sensitivity is low and a relative
small reactor can be applied for moderate
rotation speeds.<P>

<B>Goal</B><BR>
The first aim is to develop a rotating
monolith reactor and a sotbent for
continuous, high temperature (up to 1273
K) and regenerative desulfurisation of
fuel gas from coal gasification. High
temperature removal can increase the
thermal efficiency and is thus preferred
over existing low temperature processes.<P>

<B>Approach</B><BR>
A manganese oxide on gamma-A1<SUB>2</SUB>0<SUB>3</SUB> particles
is being used as acceptor in this project.
This sorbent material has been developed
[1] for use in an isothermal process for
regenerative removal of H<SUB>2</SUB>S from fuel
gas at high temperature (>= 673 K). The
following overall reaction was envisaged
for the acceptor process:<P>

MnO/gamma-A1<SUB>2</SUB>0<SUB>3</SUB> + H<SUB>2</SUB>S <-> MnS/gamma-Al<SUB>2</SUB>0<SUB>3</SUB> + H<SUB>2</SUB>0   dH = 0<P>

For application in a rotating reactor,
manganese oxide is put on washcoated
and pure T-Al203 monoliths via different
preparation methods.<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

Pure gamma-A1<SUB>2</SUB>0<SUB>3</SUB> and washcoated cordierite
monoliths impregnated with manganese
acetate and calcined at 973 K resulted in
highly dispersed Mn<SUB>3</SUB>0<SUB>4</SUB> on gamma-Al<SUB>2</SUB>0<SUB>3</SUB>. MnS
was formed during sulfidation and bulk
MnAl<SUB>2</SUB>0<SUB>4</SUB> during subsequent regeneration
with steam. The maximum capacity of
the acceptor was 17 wt % sulfur which
was obtained with a 32 wt % manganese
loading and operation between 1123 and
1223 K. A deactivation test showed only
minor deactivation (< 20 %) during 110
subsequent sulfidation and regeneration
cycli.<BR>
A labscale rotating monolith reactor has
been built and will be used in the near
future to demonstrate and follow the
acceptor characteristics upon continuous
acceptance-regeneration operation.<P>
[1] J.P. Wakker, A.W. Gerritsen, J.A.
Moulijn, Ind. Eng. Res, <I>1993</I>, 139<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
