<HEAD><TITLE>Permeation of gases through a silicalite-1 zeolite membrane: applied to air purification</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Permeation of gases through a silicalite-1 zeolite membrane: applied to air purification</H2>

L J P van den Broeke<BR>
Delft University of Technology<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:vandenbroeke@stm.tudelft.nl">vandenbroeke@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The permeation behaviour of noble and
permant gases through a silicalite-1
zeolite composite membrane is studied.
The zeolite membrane is formed by a
silicalite-1 layer of 50 &#181;m grown on a
stainless steel support.<BR>
In the current research project zeolitic
diffusion is studied using the silicalite-1
membrane. An experimental program is
undertaken to investigate the sorption
kinetics of single-component gases and
multi-component mixtures. Both transient
and steady state profiles are considered
for this purpose. A Wicke-Kallenbach
diffusion cell is used. Also, possible
applications of zeolite membranes are
investigated. At first instance, we look at
gas separation with the silicalite-1
membrane.<P>

<B>Sorption kinetics in microporous materials</B><BR>
To study zeolitic diffusion permeation
experiments are performed with simple
gases, like nitrogen, argon, krypton, and
air. The following experiments are
conducted for both single- and
multicomponent gases:<BR>

<UL>
<LI>Flux as function of the concentration
(partial pressure), at the feed side.
<LI>Flux as function of the temperature,
over the temperature range of 300 to
650 Kelvin.
</UL>

<B>Gas separation</B><BR>
The main objective of this study is to
look at applications of the silicalite-1
membrane in the field of air purification.
The silicalite-1 zeolite membrane is used
to remove, small amounts of, NO<SUB>x</SUB>, CO<SUB>2</SUB>,
Ar, Kr, and Xe from air. Permeation
experiments with mixtures of these gases
are performed to obtain separation
factors, as function of the
feed
composition and the temperature.<P>

<B>Modelling</B><BR>
The steady state and transient permeation
fluxes as well as the separation factors
are modelled with a concentration
dependent Fick diffusion model. The
various models for the concentration
dependence of the Fick diffusion
coefficient are derived from the Maxwell-
Stefan equations.<P>

<B>Conclusions</B><BR>
For the silicalite-1 zeolite an interesting
dependence of the one-component
permeation flux on the temperature is
found for nitrogen and krypton. The one-
component fluxes were found to be high.
The ideal separation factor, calculated
from these
fluxes, varies with
temperature.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
