<HEAD><TITLE>Metal supported zeolite membranes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Metal supported zeolite membranes</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> Drs. J.M. van de Graaf (Jolinde)<BR>
<B>Status:</B> Ph.D. Student<BR>
<B>Started:</B> March 1994<BR>
<B>External support:</B> SON/STW<BR>
<B>e-mail:</B> <A HREF="mailto:J.vandeGraaf@stm.tudelft.nl">J.vandeGraaf@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>A silicalite-1 membrane, supported on stainless steel, has been developed in the past
years at Delft University of Technology. The permeation of hydrocarbons and some
permanent gases has now been studied extensively under a wide variety of conditions.
The qualitative interpretation of these experiments is well understood and we are now
working on the development of models that describe both single and multi-component
experiments quantitatively.</I><P>

The use of zeolitic membranes in separation
or combined reaction and separation
processes is very attractive. Advantages of
using such type of membranes include their
ability to discriminate between molecules
based on molecular size and their thermal
stability. The large variety of zeolite types
could provide a tailor-made separation
medium for specific processes. Moreover,
the properties of zeolites of zeolites are
often easily adjustable, which makes them
very promising for use in catalytic
membrane reactors.<BR>
The affinity of the membrane for a certain
compound is very important in determining
the separation characteristics of the
membrane. For example, under conditions
were adsorption plays an important role
(e.g. low temperatures) the stronger
adsorbing component will always permeate
preferentially over the more weakly
adsorbing species in the mixture. At high
temperatures or for mixtures of weakly
adsorbing species the selectivity is
governed by the mobility of the
components in the zeolite framework.<BR>
Figure 1 shows the results of permeation
experiments with binary mixtures of ethane
and ethene. As can be seen, the separation
selectivity is highly concentration
dependent. From these data, diffusion
coefficients for ethane and ethene were
calculated using the Maxwell-Stefan
description for surface diffusion. These
diffusivities were compared to diffusivities
determined from unary permeation
experiments using the same model.
Deviations of up to a factor two between
binary and unary diffusivities were found.
Clearly, an extension of the model is
needed in order to be able to predict multi-
component permeation behaviour on the
basis of one-component permeation data.
This is the subject of current research.<P>

<IMG SRC="jolinde1.gif"><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 12/09/96</CENTER></H6>

