<HEAD><TITLE>Metal loss from heterogeneous catalyst; a catalyst deactivation study with radiotracers</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Metal loss from heterogeneous catalyst; a catalyst deactivation study with radiotracers</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> Maurice Hermans<BR>
<B>Status:</B> A.I.O.<BR>
<B>Started:</B> November 1992<BR>
<B>Support:</B> IRI-DUT.<BR>
<B>Co-operation:</B> Radiochemistry at Interfaculty Reactor Institute (IRI), (prof. dr.ir J.J.M.de Goeij, ir Z.I. Kolar), DUT.<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>At the Delft University of Technology
(DUT) a methodology is being
developed to quantify of the amount
of metal, volatilized out of a
heterogeneous catalyst.</I><P>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Loss of (catalitically active)
components through the gas phase is one
of the possible origins of catalyst
deactivation in heterogeneous catalysis.
Examples of this behaviour are;<BR>
<UL>
<LI>platinum loss from autoexhaust catalyst,
<LI>potassium loss from ethyl benzene
dehydrogenation catalyst
<LI>the probable loss of for instance copper
from soot oxidation catalyst, presently
being developed for diesel engines and
<LI>chromium loss from oxidation catalyst
used for the oxidation of Volatile
Organic Compounds (VOC).
</UL>

<B>Background</B><BR>
The emitted (through
volatilization) catalyst components are
economical and environmental
undesirable. (For instance downstream
blockages in a plant or release of metals
in the environment.)<BR>
Measuring the minute flows of
metals carded away by the gas flowing
through the catalyst bed is still a
problem. The radiotracer method can
solve this problem; small amounts of
(catalitacally active) radioactive metal
components are easily detected and
determined.<BR>
For the radiotracer method, one
component of the catalyst has to be
labelled with a suitable radionuclide.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
The catalyst preparation (carded
out at the IRI) is performed with one
precusor which is irradiated with thermal
neutrons from the IRI "Hoger Onderwijs
Reactor". With this radioactive precusor,
a catalyst is prepared using a modified
incipient wetness method. After drying
and calcination, the catalyst is "aged"
with a mixture of N<SUB>2</SUB>, O<SUB>2</SUB>, CO<SUB>2</SUB>, CO, H<SUB>2</SUB>
and H<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>(g)</SUB>.<P>
The amount of metal volatilized
during the ageing experiment, is collected
and determined by measuring the
radioactivity.<P>

<IMG SRC="maurice1.gif"><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
