<HEAD><TITLE>Kinetics of fluid catalytic cracking</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Kinetics of fluid catalytic cracking</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> Ir. M.A. den Hollander (Marion)<BR>
<B>e-mail:</B> <A HREF="mailto:M.A.denHollander@stm.tudelft.nl">M.A.denHollander@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
<B>Status:</B> Ph.D. Student<BR>
<B>Started:</B> May 1995<BR>
<B>External support:</B>	 KSLA<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<I>A micro riser that has been built will be used to study and model the kinetics of fluid
catalytic cracking under industrial relevant conditions.</I><P>

Fluid Catalytic Cracking (FCC) is one of
the most important oil conversion
processes for the production of gasoline
range hydrocarbons. A typical industrial
FCC unit consists of a riser reactor of
about 20-40 metres in height in which the
residence time of both oil and catalyst are
typically 5 seconds. In this time the
catalyst is deactivated by coke deposition
and the deactivated catalyst is transported
to a regenerator to burn off the cokes,
thus providing the heat that is needed for
the endothermic cracking reactions in the
riser.<BR>
Small changes in the performance of an
industrial FCC catalyst have an huge
influence on refinery economics.
Therefore, it is very important that new
catalysts can be tested under conditions
that closely match industrial cracking
conditions. Furthermore, once cracking
kinetics and mechanisms are known,
improvements in reaction conditions can
be made on a theoretical base instead of
by trial and error.<P>

The in our laboratory redesigned micro
riser is an FCC catalyst testing
equipment that can be used to test
relatively small amounts of catalyst
under industrial relevant conditions. The
most striking features of the micro riser
Outline of the micro riser

are its folded reactor with a length
variable between 0.5 and 30 m and the
dilution of the hydrocarbons with
nitrogen.<P>

The micro riser shall be used to study and
model cracking kinetics. At present
preliminary     experiments     with
commercial feeds and catalysts are done.
The results of these experiments will be
compared to data of a pilot plant and an
industrial riser reactor.<P>

<IMG SRC="marion1.gif"><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
