<HEAD><TITLE>Catalyst deactivation in hydrodemetallisation</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Catalyst deactivation in hydrodemetallisation</H2>

<B>Promovendus: </B> Ir. J.P. Janssens<BR>
<B>Started: </B> February 1992<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> KSLA<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Heteroatoms, such as sulphur, nitrogen,
oxygen and metals, are catalytically
removed from heavy oil residua during
hydrotreating processes. The metals,
vanadium and nickel, present in these
residua remain and accumulate in the
reactor as solid deposits on the catalyst
surface.<BR>
Catalytic hydrodemetallisation of nickel
and vanadium compounds in crude oil,
with the simultaneous deposition of the
metals on the catalyst, is the most important phenomenon causing irreversible
catalyst deactivation in heavy oil
processing. The loss of catalyst activity
through metal deposition can be attributed
to both the obstruction of catalyst pores
('<I>pore plugging</I>') and the chemical changes
that occur, when the deposited metal
interacts with the original active phase of
the catalyst ('<I>active site poisoning</I>').<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
Objectives of this project are:
<UL>
<LI>assesment of HDM kinetics for model
organo-metal compounds (Ni- and VO-
porphyrins),
<LI>further clarification of the reaction
mechanism of model organo-metal
compounds,
<LI>modelling of catalyst deactivation
mechanisms such as pore plugging and
active site poisoning and characterisation
of metal deposits on catalysts.<P>
</UL>

<B>Results</B><BR>
A series of HDM kinetic experiments of
vanadyl-tetraphenylporphyrin is carried
out in a batch autoclave under industrial
conditions (350 &#176;C and 100 bar).<BR>

Kinetic parameters and activation energies
are determined for two catalyst systems,
V/Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB> and V/SiO<SUB>2</SUB>. Differences in
selectivity (hydrogenation versus hydrogenolysis) is observed for the two systems.
The effect of the addition of hetero-atom
containing compounds, such as quinoline,
dibenzothiophene, benzofuran, ammonia
and water, on the I-IDM reaction kinetics is
also studied. Experimental results show
that hetero-atom containing cornponds
have an inhibiting effect on HDM reaction
kinetics.<BR>
BioSym molecular modelling software is
used to eluddate the reaction mechanism
of tetra-phenylporphyrin. The molecular
modelling of the hydrogenation steps
shows at what point the porphyrinic
structure becomes unstable and releases its
metal atom. A new reaction mechanism on
a molecular level is proposed.<BR>
On the modelling of HDM catalyst
deactivation, results are obtained using
percolation concepts for the porous texture
of the catalysts (cubic tesselation and Bethe
network). Comparison of model
simulations and experimental metal
deposition profiles in catalyst particles
show qualitative agreement. Predictions on
the life-time of fresh and spent catalysts
can be made.<BR>
Characterisation of the initial metal
deposits on several hydrotreating catalysts
is carried out with High Resolution
Electron Microscopy (HREM). First results
show that there is a preferential metal
deposition in the surroundings of the
active phase.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
