</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Catalytic oxidation of particulates from diesel exhaust gas using a supported liquid phase catalyst</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Catalytic oxidation of particulates from diesel exhaust gas using a supported liquid phase catalyst</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> ir. Sytse J. Jelles<BR>
<B>Status:</B> Status:<BR>
<B>Started:</B> March 1995<BR>
<B>External support:</B> STW<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>In this project, the oxidation of
particulates from exhaust gas of
stationairy diesels is studied. The
possibilities of Supported Liquid Phase
Catalysts for this purpose will be
investigated.</I><P>

Diesel engines are fuel efficient
and have, compared with otto engines,
relatively low emissions of NO<SUB>x</SUB> and
unburnt hydrocarbons. The particulate
emission of diesel engines is high and
diesel particulates are considered to be
possibly harmful. The purpose of this
project is to develop a working system
for the removal of diesel particulates
from the exhaust gas.<P>

High particulate removal
efficiencies can be achieved with wall
flow monoliths. On these monoliths,
the particulates can be continuously
collected and combusted. For non-
catalytic, continuous particulate
combustion, the temperatures in the
exhaust gas are far too low to achieve
acceptable back-pressures. Increase of
back-pressure in time will lead to
malfunction of the engine. On the
other hand, temperature excursions can
occur during the combustion of the
accumulated soot, that could destroy
the filter system. Therefore, catalytic
oxidation at lower temperatures is
considered the most practical solution.<P>

From earlier research it was
concluded that the major problem in
catalytic particulate oxidation is the
realization of good contact between the
particulate and the catalyst. One way to
solve this problem is to add a catalyst
precursor to the diesel fuel. Another
possibility is the use of a Supported
Liquid Phase Catalyst. The soot must
then be forced into the liquid phase,
resulting in an intimate contact
between the soot and the catalyst.<P>

The performance of eutectic
salts as oxidation catalysts will be
examined in flow reactor equipment
and with TGA/DSC. Promising
eutectics following from these
experiments will be used to prepare
Supported Liquid Phase Catalysts, that
will be tested in the exhaust stream of
a small diesel engine. Based on these
experiments, in due time a prototype
particulate oxidation catalyst will be
built and tested with a sidestream of a
large industrial engine.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

