<HEAD><TITLE>Development of an internally tinned monolith reactor (IFMR) for hydrogenation processes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Development of an internally tinned monolith reactor (IFMR) for hydrogenation processes</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Paul Lebens (015 - 2784396)<BR>
<B>Supervision:</B> A.Stankiewicz, R. Edvinsson, and S.T. Sie<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> november 1994-november 1998<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Shell<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Abstract</B><P>

A new low pressure reactor for three-
phase hydrogenation processes is being
developed. The reactor is designed to
operated countercurrently.<P>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

Fixed-bed reactors belong to the most widely
used reactors for heterogeneous catalytic
reactions. The size of the catalyst particles,
which is determined by the balance between
pressure drop and diffusion limitation, is
generally about 0.8 to 3 mm. Cocurrent
operation is necessary to avoid flooding at the
linear velocities that are of practical interest.
Countercurrent operation would, however, be
more desirable since the reaction conditions
are more favourable in that part of the reactor
where it is needed most to convert the least
reactive compounds. Moreover, the
temperature profile will be less steep probably
reducing demands on interbed quenching and
heat exchange.<P>

<IMG SRC="paul1.gif"><P>

<B>Figure</B> Cross sectional view of single channel<P>

<B>Concept</B><P>

The internally tinned monolith reactor (IFMR)
is a new concept of a low pressure three-phase
catalytic reactor in which the gas flows
upward due to a pressure gradient not
impeding the liquid to flow downward due to
gravitational forces.<BR>
Reduction of momentum transfer between gas
and liquid is realised using a monolith
block with longitudinal 'fins' at the internal
channel surface. Capillary forces
will keep the liquid in the grooves between the
fins so that the gas can flow unhindered
through the centre part of the channel (figure)
Besides, the extra internal surface of the fins
will enhance the catalyst effectiveness in a
diffusion limited reaction.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><P>
The objectives of this project are to assess the
feasibility of the IFMR concept and to
optimise both the channel geometry and the
monolith configuration with respect to its
application in hydrotreating processes.<P>

<B>Subjects of research</B><P>
Experimentally, attention is paid to the
hydrodynamic behaviour of two-phase
countercurrent flow in single capillary tubes.
The theoretical aspects will mainly concern
modelling of the flow behaviour and
optimisation of the channel geometry. In the
future the investigations will focus on the
development of a cold-flow reactor model.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
