<HEAD><TITLE>Positron emission profiling of monolith catalysts applied to exhaust gas catalysis</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Positron emission profiling of monolith catalysts applied to exhaust gas catalysis</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> S.C. van der Linde<BR>
<B>Status:</B> PhD Student<BR>
<B>Started:</B> May 1994<BR>
<B>External support:</B> SON/NWO<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>Delft University of Technology in
conjunction with Eindhoven
University of Technology have
developed a system, using positron
emitters, with which transient kinetics
of exhaust gas catalysis can be
studied.</I><BR>
Exhaust gas usually contains toxic
gases such as CO and NO. These two
gases can be catalytically converted into
less harmful species by oxidation and
reduction respectively. Although theses
reactions have already been studied
extensively, little attention has been paid
to the transient kinetics.<BR>
The transient kinetics can be studied with
positron emission profiling. The technique
consists of the following. The catalyst, a
monolith, is first allowed to reach steady
state in the present feed composition. A small
amount (fmol) of a positron emitting species,
in this case <SUP>11</SUP>CO or <SUP>13</SUP>NO, is injected in the
gas stream to the catalyst. The isotope used
decays by emitting a positron, which travels,
at most, a few millimetres (in solid matter)
and then annihilates with an electron, thereby
producing two high energy photons. These
photons are emitted under an angle of 180&#176;
with respect to each other and can be
detected outside the reactor/furnace by two
detector banks. Because the photons are
detected coincidentally and energy sensitive,
the position of the annihilation event can be
reconstructed. In this way a profile of the
amount of the labelled species along the
length of the catalyst bed can be determined
as a function time (see figure 1 for an
example).<BR>
Information from these profiles, such as
surface concentration, rate constants, can
only be obtained by modelling of the
reactions because it is not possible to
discriminate between reactants and products
(e.g. <SUP>11</SUP>CO and <SUP>11</SUP>CO2) with the detectors. The
numerical method of lines (DSS2 package)
will be employed to solve the partial
differential equations (PDE) which describe
the reactions taking place on the catalyst
surface. To obtain quantitative data the
experimental data has to be fitted. Therefore
the PDE solvers have been coupled to
various minimisation routines, such as
Simplex, Levenberg-Marquardt. For example
from the data shown in figure 1, information
about the dispersion and flow in the tube can
be obtained.<BR>
The technique will be applied to the CO
oxidation and NO reduction over washcoated
monoliths with noble metals as the active
phase. Both <SUP>11</SUP>CO and <SUP>13</SUP>NO, which are now
readily available, will be used as labelled
tracers.<P>

<IMG SRC="linde1.gif"><P>

Figure 1. <SUP>11</SUP>CO Flow through a glass
tube filled with glass beads.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
