<HEAD><TITLE>Measurements and modelling of air purification in active carbon-beds (MAMAPAC)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Measurements and modelling of air purification in active carbon-beds (MAMAPAC)</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> Marco J.G. Linders<BR>
<B>Status:</B> PhD student<BR>
<B>Started:</B> May 1994<BR>
<B>External support:</B> Prins Maurits Laboratory (TNO Rijswijk), Biffchef GmbH (Germany)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>This project is concerned in gaining more fundamental insight in air purification
processes using activated carbon as the adsorbent. The application which is focused
on is the adsorption of (toxic) gases in gas mask canisters.</I><P>

Activated carbon is a cheap material that
can be made very porous and onto which
many (organic) compounds adsorb already
strongly at low concentrations. It is
frequently used in filters and clothing
materials which serve the protection of
military employees against chemical
weapons, and in many civil applications.<P>

<IMG SRC="marco1.gif"><P>

One of the major objectives of the project
is to develop a theoretical model which
simulates the fysisorption process. Aspects
which are considered are: internal and
external mass and heat transfer, which of
these mechanisms are rate determining under
which conditions; to obtain a better
understanding of the diffusion processes
inside the carbon particles: is macropore
diffusion (bulk + Knudsen) the main
mechanism or plays micropore (surface)
diffusion a more important role? Especially
the description of surface diffusion needs
further research.<BR>

A new approach to mass transfer is used
to model the process: the Maxwell-Stefan
theory (M-S). The main reasons to use the
M-S theory are that this theory is able to
predict diffusion against a concentration
gradient, which is not possible with Fick's
law, and that it provides an alternative way to
describe the mechanism of surface diffusion.<BR>
An important aspect of the project is to
examine the influence of water on the
adsorption behaviour. It has been shown that
water can have a negative influence on the
performance of the adsorption process.
Specially in air purification processes, water
is often present in a much higher
concentration than the components that have
to be adsorbed. The influence of water
vapour on the adsorption process should
therefore be closer looked at. The total
adsorption mechanism of water is not fully
elucidated but it is generally agreed that two
factors play an important role: the surface
chemistry and the porosity.<BR>
Some of the available experimental
methods are: 1) Headspace analysis to
measure adsorption isotherms (single and
multicomponent); 2) Thermogravimetric-
Differential Scanning Calorimetry coupled to
a mass spectrometer (TG-DSC-MS) to follow
both the mass adsorbed and the heat evolved,
and to measure diffusion coefficients.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
