<HEAD><TITLE>The catalytic oxidation of diesel-soot and exhaust gas cleaning</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>The catalytic oxidation of diesel-soot and exhaust gas cleaning</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> Guido Mul<BR>
<B>Status:</B> O.I.O.<BR>
<B>Started:</B> November 1992<BR>
<B>External support:</B> SON/NWO<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
One is interested in a catalyst for the
oxidation of soot particulates because: (<I>i</I>) diesel
engines can no longer meet the requirements of the
particulate (soot) emission standards, and (<I>ii</I>)
collection of soot in a monolithic filter and
simultaneous oxidation at diesel exhaust gas
temperatures (600 K) is considered to be the best
option to abate the emission of soot.<BR>
Within this project two types of catalytic
systems have been investigated: a Cu/K/Mo/Cl
catalysts and transition metal oxides. Several
experiments lead to the conclusion that a redox cycle
involving CuC1 and Cu<SUB>2</SUB>OC1<SUB>2</SUB> can explain the high
activity of the Cu/K/Mo/Cl catalyst. CuCl and
Cu<SUB>2</SUB>OCl<SUB>2</SUB> are formed by reaction of CuMoO<SUB>4</SUB> with
KCl, also yielding several potassium molybdates and
K<SUB>2</SUB>Cu<SUB>2</SUB>(MoO<SUB>4</SUB>)<SUB>3</SUB>. Although the active components are
stabilized and produced by the molybdates and KCl,
deactivation of the catalyst occurs due to evaporation
of the copper chlorides. Therefore research has been
focussed on transition metal oxides. Metal oxides
appear to be rather active soot oxidation catalysts,
once contact between the .catalyst and soot has been
established mechanically.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
Printex-U (a model soot purchased from
Degussa) and a metal oxide were mixed in a ratio of
1:1 by weight in a ball mill for one hour in order to
establish "tight contact", needed for a high activity.
Soot conversion levels of approximately 30% were
reached by heating the catalyst and soot in air for 15-30 minutes at 620-700 K (depending on the activity
of the catalyst).<BR>
Diffuse Reflectance Infrared Fourier
Transformed (DRIFT) spectra were recorded on a
Nicolet Magna 550 spectrometer equipped with a
DTGS detector and a Spectratech DRIFT accessory.
KBr was used as a diluent. Spectra are displayed in 8
cm<SUP>-1</SUP> resolution in absorbance reflectance mode
against a soot in KBr background.<P>

<IMG SRC="guido1.gif"><P>

<B>Figure 1.</B> DRIFT spectra of soot after catalytic
oxidation in air with several catalysts<P>

<B>Results and Discussion</B><BR>
DRIFT spectra after catalytic oxidation of
soot in air are shown in figure 1. Generally three
types of Surface Oxygen Complexes (soc) can be
identified with DRIFT after partial oxidation of soot
in air (<I>i</I>) ethers (1250 cm<SUP>-1</SUP>), (<I>ii</I>) quinones (1605 cm<SUP>-1</SUP>),
and (<I>iii</I>) lactones (1735 cm<SUP>-1</SUP>). CuO, Cr20<SUB>3</SUB>, and MoO<SUB>3</SUB>
clearly cause an enhancement in the amount of SOC
compared with non catalytic oxidation under similar
conditions. The spectra shown for Fe<SUB>2</SUB>0<SUB>3</SUB> and Co<SUB>3</SUB>0<SUB>4</SUB>
are similar to the one obtained after non-catalytic
oxidation. The behaviour of metal oxides can be
explained by two different mechanisms: (<I>i</I>) catalysts,
increasing the rate of formation of SOC are activating
oxygen in such a way that SOC is being formed by
some kind of spill-over mechanism. CO and CO<SUB>2</SUB> are
formed by decomposition of these complexes. (<I>ii</I>)
catalysts, which do not increase the amount of SOC,
are activating soot in such a way, that CO and CO<SUB>2</SUB>
are formed directly (by a redox mechanism).<P>

<B>Future</B><BR>
The interaction of several gases present in
diesel exhaust (CO, NO, NO<SUB>2</SUB>, N<SUB>2</SUB>O) with catalysts
and (partial converted) soot, will be investigated.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
