<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>The direct oxidation of propene to propene oxide</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>The direct oxidation of propene to propene oxide</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> T. A. Nijhuis (Xander)<BR>
<B>Status:</B> A.I.O.<BR>
<B>Started:</B> August 1993<BR>
<B>External support:</B> <BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>At the Delft University of
Technology we are working on a project
aiming to find a suitable catalyst for the
direct oxidation of propene to propene
oxide. This study is partially performed
using the new Multitrack system.</I><P>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Currently it is impossible to
produce propene oxide on a commercial
scale using a direct oxidation. The
existing routes are producing propene
oxide either using the chlorohydrin
process, producing large amounts of salts
and some chlorinated side products, or
using a hydroperoxide process. The
hydroperoxide process produces propene
oxide from a reaction between propene
and an organic hydroperoxide, resulting
in stoichiometric amounts of an alcohol
as a co-product. A lot of research has
been done on the direct epoxidation of
propene, but so far no viable route has
been found. All catalysts used either have
very low conversions or low selectivities.<P>

<B>The Multitrack system</B><BR>
The epoxidation of propene will
be studied using the new Multitrack
system. Multitrack is an advanced
version of the TAP (Temporal Analysis
of Products) system, used for studying
the transient kinetics of reactions. The
concept of Multitrack is giving a small
(100 ps) gas pulse to a reactor and
analyzing three masses simultaneously at
very high frequencies (up to 1 MHz).
Multitrack can operate at temperatures
from room temperature to 1200 K and at
pressures ranging from vacuum to 300
kPa.<P>

<B>The epoxidation of propene</B><BR>
Using the Multitrack system we
will try to determine the kinetics of the
various oxidation reactions of propene
(to carbon dioxide, propene oxide, and
acrolein). As a starting point for the
epoxidation of propene catalysts will be
used which show good results in the1
easier epoxidation of ethene. The main
problem in epoxidizing propene over a
standard silver catalyst used for the
epoxidation of ethene is the reactivity of
the gamma-hydrogen atoms. When propene
reacts with an oxygen atom on the silver
surface, an intermediate if formed which
can react to propene oxide. If the gamma-hydrogen atoms, however, can 'reach' an
other adsorbed oxygen atom, the more
favourable combustion will take place.
We will try to overcome this problem by
using catalyst with either very low metal
loading or with an atomicly disperse metal
loading, for example using a zeolite. To
oxidizing media to be used will be
dioxygen and nitrous oxide. Nitrous oxide
will mainly be used as oxidizing medium
to put atomic oxygen on an isolated site
catalyst. The catalysts will be tested both
on the Multitrack system and on a steady-state flow equipment.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
