<HEAD><TITLE>Design rules for sulfide catalysts. Catalysts for deep hydrodesulfurization of gasoil</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Design rules for sulfide catalysts. Catalysts for deep hydrodesulfurization of gasoil</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> Hank R. Reinhoudt<BR>
<B>Status:</B> Ph.D. Student<BR>
<B>Started:</B> December 1994<BR>
<B>External support:</B> STW, E.U.<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

Introduction<P>

The aim of the project is to establish
catalyst design rules for the a priori
selection of optimal active phase /
particle size / morphology / support
combinations for various specific
hydrotreating applications. Part of
the project is supported by the
European Union. It focuses on the
application of catalysts for deep
hydrodesulfurization of gasoils is a
main part of interest. Catalysts for
this field, capable of reaching a
sulfur level in gasoil well below 100
ppm are aimed at to meet future
regulations.<P>

Catalysts containing mixed
sulfides of CoMo, NiMo or NiW are
widely used in hydrotreating
processes to produce clean fossil
fuels. Their performance depends on
particle size, morphology and
interaction with the support material.
In a collaborative project [TUE (Van
Santen / De Beer) and TUD (Moulijn
/ Sie / Van Langeveld)] the effect of
preparation     and     sulfidation
(activation) on these parameters will
be studied.<BR>
Several preparation methods
such as ion exchange, gas phase
deposition, sequential and co-
impregnation, will be used to prepare
catalysts with different particle size
and/or morphology of the active
sulfide phase.<BR>
The    E.U.    project    for
development of catalysts for deep
HDS of gasoils is undertaken in co-
operation with universities from
Eindhoven, Karlsruhe, London,
Madrid/Bilbao
and, several industries. The refractoy sulfur
compounds in gasoil are mainly
alkylated DBT's. As catalysts
CoMo, NiMo and NiW sulfide
catalysts, known for their high sulfur
tolerance, and Pt, Pd and Ir metal
catalysts,    known    for    high
hydrogenation activity will be tested.
First test results indicate that NiW
and Pt catalysts may be interesting.<BR>
To gain more insight in the
kinetic reaction mechanism, for a
number of selected catalysts the
kinetics of thiophene and,
dibenzothiophene (DBT)
hydrodesulfurization (HDS),
chinoline      hydrodenitrification
(HDN), toluene hydrogenation will
be studied. The kinetics of those
catalysts will also be studied under
industrial reaction conditions in a
micro flow reactor system with
respect to the HDS, HDN and
aromatics hydrogenation of a straight
run gasoil.<BR>
The sulfidic active phase of the
selected catalysts will be studied
with in-situ FTIR, quasi in-situ
HREM and XPS.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
