<HEAD><TITLE>Process for the catalytic hydrogenolysis of CCl2F2 (CFC-12) into CH2F2 (HFC-32)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Process for the catalytic hydrogenolysis of CCl<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB> (CFC-12) into CH<SUB>2</SUB>F<U>2</U> (HFC-32)</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> Emile J.A.X. van de Sandt<BR>
<B>Status:</B> A.I.O.<BR>
<B>Started:</B> August 1992<BR>
<B>Researcher:</B> Andr&eacute; Wiersma<BR>
<B>Status:</B> A.I.O.<BR>
<B>Started:</B> October 1992<BR>
<B>External support:</B> TUDelft, AKZO Nobel B.V., VROM, EC, AlliedSignal B.V, KTI B.V., Johnson Matthey Plc.<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>At the Delft University of
Technology a catalytic process is being
developed to convert the waste CCl<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB>
(CFC-12) into the high value added
CH<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB> (HFC-32). With this process the
majority of the CFCs still in use can be
converted into a useful product (HFC-32)
using a selected palladium on activated
carbon catalyst.</I><P>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
CC1<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB> (CFC-12) and CCl<SUB>3</SUB>F
(CFC-11) have been identified as
substances which deplete the protective
stratospheric ozone layer, and, therefore,
their production and usage will be
prohibited by 1-1-1996 worldwide.
However, the depletion stratospheric
ozone will continue in spite of this
prohibition. This is caused by slow
diffusion of CFCs from the troposphere to
the stratosphere and the eventual emission
of still banked and used CFCs. It is,
therefore, of utmost importance to prevent
the CFCs which are still in use from being
emitted into the atmosphere. The
estimated banked quantities of CFCs are
2.1 million tons worldwide. The majority
(85-90%) of these CFCs are CFC-11 and
CFC-12. There is no dedicated destruction
process available for these CFCs other
than combustion (incineration), with a
very limited capacity. At Delft University
of Technology a process is being
developed which not only destructs
CC1<SUB>2</SUB>F<SUB>2</SUB> but at the same time makes a
valuable product (CH2F2 ~ HFC-32) from
it. With this process both CFC-11, which
can be converted into CFC-12 by use of
HF, and CFC-12 can be converted into
HFC-32.<P>

<B>Development of catalyst</B><BR>
Different noble metals on an
activated carbon support have been tested
as a catalyst for the hydrogenolysis
reaction of CFC-12 into HFC-32.
Palladium on activated carbon has been
selected as a very suitable catalyst. Using
this catalyst, a high selectivity to HFC-32
can be combined with a high conversion
(80-85% selectivity at 100% CFC-12
conversion). The stability of the catalyst
looks very promising, after stabilization of
the catalyst no deactivation was observed
for over 800 hours.<P>

<B>Development of process</B><BR>
A preliminary process design has
shown that the conversion of CFC-12 into
high added value product HFC-32 is both
technically and economically feasible.
Currently a kinetic model is being
developed for the selected catalyst and
integrated into a process design. Based on
this design a small pilot plant will be
constructed to test the catalyst stability for
over 2000 hours under simulated recycle
streams.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

