<HEAD><TITLE>The partial hydrogenation of aromatics with ruthenium catalysts</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>The partial hydrogenation of aromatics with ruthenium catalysts</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> Matthijs Soede<BR>
<B>Status:</B> AIO<BR>
<B>Started:</B> June 1991<BR>
<B>External support:</B> DSM<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>For the production of cyclohexanone, the
nylon-6 precursor, the route via
cyclohexene is an alternative for the
route currently used (see Fig 1). A
process running via the cyclohexene route
entails a considerable hydrogen saving
and can bypass the potential hazardous
cyclohexane route. So, a study has been
carried out for the batch-wise
hydrogenation of benzene to cyclohexene.</I><P>

<IMG SRC="matthijs1.gif"><P>

Figure 1. Present and alternative routes for the
production of cylcohexanone.<P>

The route via partial hydrogenation,
however, is thermodynamical very
unfavourable (yields less than 0.1%) and
a kinetic solution has to be found. High
yields in cyclohexene can be achieved
when the benzene is hydrogenated over a
ruthenium catalyst in an aqueous zinc
sulfate solution. Due to the chemisorption
of zinc salts, the surface of the catalyst is
partially covered by cations. Owing to this
the hydrophobicity of the ruthenium
particles is changed into hydrophilicity
and as a consequence a water layer is
formed around the catalyst particles.
Mass-transfer limitation of hydrogen,
benzene and cyclohexene at the
water/ruthenium interface is introduced.
According to this approach selectivities to
cyclohexene up to 80% and yields of 30-
45% are achieved.<P>

Aim is to investigate the catalytic
mechanism of the partial hydrogenation of
benzene. "Catalytic mechanism" means
both the chemical and the mass-transfer
phenomena. When the mechanism is fully
understood it might be possible to scale
this reaction up to continuous operation.<P>

Within this project not only benzene, but
also the hydrogenation of toluene and of
xylene are investigated. Also supported
ruthenium catalysts have been used to
enlarge the stability of the catalyst.
The results of this project will be
described in my thesis.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

