<HEAD><TITLE>Preparation of monolithic catalysts for fine chemicals production</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Preparation of monolithic catalysts for fine chemicals production</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> ir. Theo Vergunst<BR>
<B>Status:</B> AIO<BR>
<B>Started:</B> March 1995<BR>
<B>External support:</B> IOP Katalyse, IKA94061<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>In this project, the preparation of monolithic catalysts is studied The prepared
catalysts will be used in the selective hydrogenation of aromatic aldehydes into
aromatic alcohols.</I><P>

Monolithic supports are
continuous unitary structures, consisting
of many, mostly parallel channels,
separated by thin wails. A typical
configuration is a square cell geometry,
400 cells per square inch, wall thickness
of 0.17 mm and an inside edge length of
1.1 mm. The use of monolithic catalysts
is nowadays restricted to gas purification
applications, but monolithic catalysts can
be a serious alternative for stirred slurry
or trickle bed reactors in fine chemicals
production. The main advantages of
monolithic catalysts are a low pressure
drop, no need of separation of the final
reaction mixture from the catalyst, easy
upscaling, and short diffusion length in
the catalyst.<P>

The preparation of monolithic
catalysts can be divided in two steps.
Because the surface area of monolithic
supports made from cordierite is too low,
a thin layer (10-100 [&#181;m) of gamma
alumina is deposited on the channel
walls. This layer is called the washcoat.
This layer is applied by dipping a
monolithic support in a colloidal
suspension of aluminumhydroxide,
followed by drying and calcining. This
process can be repeated untill the desired
layer thickness is obtained. The surface
are is increased in this step to 30 m<SUP>2</SUP>/g.<BR>
The washcoat layer is in the
second step impregnated with metals,
such as nickel, palladium, and platinum.
Nickel is applied by deposition-
precipitation of nickelhydroxide.
Hydroxyl-ions are in-situ generated by
thermolysis of urea. Both palladium and
platinum are applied by adsorption of the
corresponding metalchloride.<P>

The prepared monolithic catalysts
are tested in the selective hydrogenation
of multifunctional components, such as
aromatic aldehydes. In this case, the
selective hydrogenation of benzaldehyde
into benzylalcohol, and the selective
hydrogenation of cinnamaldehyde (3-phenyl-2-propenal) into cinnamyl alcohol
(3-phenyl-2-propenol) will be studied.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
