<HEAD><TITLE>Conceptual design of industrial crystallizers</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Conceptual design of industrial crystallizers</H2>

<B>Ph.D. Student:</B> Ir. Sean K. Bermingham (Tel. (15) 2784352/5561)<BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> AKZO-Nobel, BASF, Bayer, Dow, DuPont, Purac, STW<BR>
<B>e-mail:</B> <A HREF="mailto:Bermingham@stm.TUDelft.nl">Bermingham@stm.TUDelft.nl</A><BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

This project is part of UNIAK 3, a project
to develop fundamental kinetic and
hydrodynamic models, as well as design
and control procedures for industrial
crystallizers. An outline of the UNIAK
project can be found in the section 'Delft
University of Technology, Laboratory for
Process Equipment'.<P>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The aim of this research project is to
improve the performance and
controllability of industrial crystallizers by
a better <I>design</I>. The intention is to come to
a systematic procedure for the conceptual
design of crystallizers, in which plant
specifications, empirical knowledge, and
general process models are combined. This
design procedure should be applicable to
different chemical compounds, different
crystallizer scales and geometry, and
different process conditions.<P>

<B>Experimental set-up</B><BR>
The UNIAK project has 3 crystallizers at
its disposal for experimental work. These
crystallizers differ in operation mode and
scale: a 970 1 draft tube baffled
crystallizer, a 2001 forced circulation
crystallizer, and a 22 I draft tube baffled
crystallizer. The proposed <B>GUDoC</B><SUP>1</SUP>-model
will be tested on these scales.<P>

<B>Simulation environment</B><BR>
SPEEDUP is used for dynamic simulations
of the crystallizer based on a
compartmental model. To determine an
adequate configuration of compartments,
computational fluid dynamics simulations
are performed with Fluent.<P>

<B>Project strategy</B><BR>
<OL>
<LI>Make an inventory of the empirical and
systematic design rules that are currently
available, and subsequently determine their
compatibility and short-comings.
<LI>Make a list of typical design
specifications, such as production capacity
and product
quality, but also
controllability.
<LI>Determine sensitivity of present UNIAK
compartmental crystallizer model, in order
to know the degree of detail desired from
CFD simulations and the resulting
compartmentalisation.
<LI>Collect experimental crystallizer data
from crystallizers with varying scale and
geometry, that have been operated with
different chemical compounds.
<LI>Use the resulting compartmental model
to evaluate different kinetic and physical
models, as well as control strategies.
<LI>The final step, will be the formulation
of a general design procedure for
crystallizers, which accounts for different
geometries and different chemical
compounds.

<B>Activities</B><BR>
A preliminary computer model for the
existing 200 1 and 970 1 crystallizers has
already been used in a detailed design-
study. Its validation is now in progress.
1Grand Unified Design of Crystallizers<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

