<HEAD><TITLE>Uncertainty modelling in chemical engineering</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Uncertainty modelling in chemical engineering</H2>

<B>Ph.D. student:</B> Folmer W. de Haan (Tel. (15) 2784383)<BR>
<B>e-mail:</B> <A HREF="mailto:F.W.deHaan@stm.TUDelft.nl">F.W.deHaan@stm.TUDelft.nl</A><BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Process knowledge is increasingly
captured in models. These models are
used in process development, design and
operations, i.e. in every phase of the life
cycle. In this life cycle modelling, the
way in which the uncertainties are dealt
with play a vital role.<P>

The nature of uncertainties differ for
each type of knowledge and knowledge
representation and for each model,
model objective, and model
representation.<P>

<B>Objectives of the project</B><BR>
The main objective is to create a
conceptual and computational framework
to deal with uncertainties in process
design and operations. That is: to
develop an appropriate taxonomy and
effective methods for quantifying
uncertainties and handling these in the
different applications of Chemical
Engineering models.<P>

<B>Procedure</B><BR>
We will concentrate here on design. The
practical way of dealing with uncertainty
is to allow for extra margins in the
design of apparatus and processes. These
depend on economy, criticality and often
safety. The first problem lies in
quantifying the extend of uncertainty and
its effect on operation and design.<P>

The second problem is the numerical
simulation of these uncertainties, where
Monte Carlo are an obvious answer (see
a previous report). Another approach is
borrowed from the statistics of
experimentation: response surface
methodology to reduce the computational
effort.<P>

<B>Practical Applications: a compressor network</B><BR>
Sofar the literature is still scarce with
respect to real life cases. We have now
exhaustively investigated the design of a
processing unit to deal with the input
from a highly fluctuating off-gas plant.
The finally chosen design was achieved
with relatively common software
(spreadsheets and ASPEN), but required
the use of considerable computing
power. However, it appears feasible to
extend the approach to more complex
cases.<P>

The case under consideration required
the choice of operating conditions, the
nominal design capacity and the number
of compressors in a compressor network.
For example, the best efficiency reached
with 1, 2 and 3 compressors were
respectively 80 %, 96 % and 99.4 % and
then the best scheduling, the optimal
operating pressure and the best design
was chosen in each case. It proved that
the cost-optimal simple design, if the
design were based on average load, was
actually loss making and that the cost-
optimal design with accounting for input
variability gave the winning edge.<P>

<B>Future activities</B><BR>
The theoretical basis is now further
being developed. Two other case studies
are in progress or will be executed. After
that we hope to come to a conceptual
framework for model-based design with
uncertainties.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
