<HEAD><TITLE>Optimization of heat exchanger networks in retrofit</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Optimization of heat exchanger networks in retrofit</H2>

<B>Ph.D. Student:</B> Ir. Jos L.B. van Reisen (Tel. (15) 2784348)<BR>
<B>co-sponsor:</B> NOVEM, DSM and Shell.<BR>
<B>e-mail:</B> <A HREF="mailto:Reisen@stm.TUDelft.nl">Reisen@stm.TUDelft.nl</A><BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Summary</B><BR>
In order to make more economical and
operable Heat Exchanger Networks
(HEN's), new designing strategies are
developed and tested that allow
incorporation of compact multi-stream heat
exchangers (CMSHE). These exchangers
make design easier and may yield 20%
more energy savings than possible with
conventional exchangers.<P>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Extensive exchange of heat between
process streams reduces utility usage but
increases investments for heat exchanging
equipment. Besides, the system becomes
more complex.<BR>
In a retrofit the newer design must also
take maximal advantage of the existing
equipment to minimize investments.<BR>
To find an optimal design that is
economical and operable, several systematic approaches have been developed. The
most important ones are Pinch Technology
and Mathematical Programming.<BR>
CMSHE have low area costs and a high
area efficiency. These properties give them
great opportunities in heat integration.
Practical limitations and fear for bad
operation prevent wide application so far.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The project aims are:
<UL>
<LI>Design strategies for the use of CMSHE
in retrofit.
<LI>Application of the strategies to practical
cases.
<LI>Consistency of preliminary design with
final equipment design.
<LI>Incorporation of operational aspects in
preliminary design, especially flexibility
and controllability.
</UL>

<B>Activities</B><BR>
A major effort was made to develop
software in order to implement one of the
earlier established design methods for the
placement of HEN's in retrofit. This is
now being tested on two industrial cases.
Recently, also debottlenecking designs of
HEN's - for increased capacity - has
become part of the study. The progress of
disturbances through a heat exchanger
network has also been studied.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
Significant progress was made with data-extraction, which proved to require a
systematic approach to error detection and
reconciliation. Another practical problem is
the existence of multiple utilities that
prompted a refining of the earlier
developed design procedure. The
disturbance studies possibly leads to a
framework, where their effect can be
predicted, but the theoretical foundation
still needs attention.<P>

<B>Cooperation</B><BR>
We have regular contacts with the
University of Manchester Institution of
Science and Technology (UMIST).
The study was originally initiated by the
Dutch Advanced Heat Exchanger Study
Group and funded by NOVEM<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

