<HEAD><TITLE>Process design studies</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Process design studies</H2>

<B>TwAIO's</B><BR>
Tel. (15) 2784351<BR>
e-mail: Grievink@stm.TUDelft.nl<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<I>The TwAIO opleiding Proces- en
Apparaatontwerpen</I> at the TUDelft has the
requirement that each candidate
participates in a team project and in an
individual design project. In the first case,
the emphasize lies on innovative
approaches with respect to alternative
process routes. In the latter case, the
design study complements research
projects in the university or, especially, in
industry. The research group Process
Systems and Control supervises (or has
supervised this year) a number of projects:<P>

<B>Natural Gas Liquids Recovery Centre</B><BR>
Options has been investigated to process
Natural Gas Liquids (NGL), produced
during crude oil production. This enable
marketing of valuable products, whilst
simultaneously reducing fuel wastage and
associated environmental pollution. (This
was a team project.)<P>

<B>Fuel Cells for off-gas</B><BR>
In this case-study a conceptual design of a
Molten Carbonate Fuel Cell System for the
off-gas stream of an electrothermal
Phosphorus plant has been made. Its
purpose was to explore and investigate all
consequences and practical constraints of
the implementation of this new technology
in an existing process. One product of this
work is a fuel cell simulation model
integrated with a modem flowsheeting
program.<P>

<B>Design of forced circulation crystallizers</B>
A case study has been performed on the
re-design of an existing 200 l forced
circulation crystallizer. The crystallizer
was donated by AKZO-Nobel and is
currently being modified at the
"Laboratory for Equipment in the Process
Industry". The crystalliser was originally
operating with Sodium Chloride, but will
now be re-designed to crystallize
ammonium sulphate. Within this context,
a generalized model for an arbitrary
crystalliser has been developed, which
should support future research in the area
of crystallizer design.<P>

<B>Optimising control of a plant</B><BR>
In an earlier project, a generalised
approach has been applied for the
identification of options to increase
product output of two monomer plants.
The behaviour of this system has been
further investigated with a dynamic model
with use of the software package
SPEEDUP. The major focus is now set on
a redesign of the control structure and
procedures in order to optimise the whole
system.<P>

<B>Optimisation of a steel manufacturing
unit</B><BR>
This is a case whereby a fundamental
operating model is developed of a specific
apparatus taking dynamics and heat
transport aspects into account. The model
should guide future experiments and
operation.<P>


