<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Methods for on-line use of process models</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Methods for on-line use of process models</H2>

<B>Ph.D student:</B> Ir. Bertjan Vos<BR>
Tel. (15) 2784383<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:B.J.Vos@stm.TUDelft.nl">B.J.Vos@stm.TUDelft.nl</A><BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Modeling is a tool which is frequently
used in process engineering. In the recent
past, most of the modeling applications
were off-line. However, the trend is, that
more and more process control applications
rely on models that are used on-line.<P>

The use of models in on-line applications
places great demands on the validity of the
models. Therefore, rigorous models are the
preferred choice. Disturbances, both
measured and unmeasured, influence the
process, with the consequence that the
model needs to be tuned frequently.<P>

This research focuses on the on-line use of
rigorous dynamic models, which are
mathematically equal to a set of
Differential and Algebraic Equations.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The objectives of this research can be
summarized as <I>the on-line validation and
use of DAE models to support plant
operation</I>.<BR>
In our perspective, the DAE model can<P>

<IMG SRC="bertjan1.gif"><P>

operate as an on-line base model from
which (linearized) sub-models or
information flows will be deduced to
support the (control) applications.<P>

This configuration is to be preferred
because it reduces the number of
independent models. Since the information
of the process is brought together in one
model, the result is that maintenance of the
model configuration is reduced.<P>

<B>Validation</B><BR>
The on-line validation involves on-line
parameter estimation based on a moving
window strategy. The optimization problem
that is the mathematical equivalent to the
on-line parameter estimation problem,
needs to be solved fast and robust, because
the time available is limited.<BR>
To ensure robustness, a method is
developed to control the condition number
of the optimization problem. This is done
by manipulating the set of parameters that
form the degrees of freedom.<P>

The discrepancies between model and data
form the basis to decide if the model is
valid. Current research is focussed on a
method to identify the discrepancies and to
connect them to the error sources.<P>

<B>Future Research</B><BR>
To test the practical value of the validation
strategies and methods, two case studies
are planned. The first case study will be a
simulated case. For this purpose, the
software applications SpeedUp and Matlab
will be used. After the simulated case a
small industrial case will be handled with
the improved software.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
