<HEAD><TITLE>PhD-projects Delft</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Particle Technology<HR></H2>

<TT><PRE>
Delft University of Technology
Department of Chemical Technology and Material Science
Julianalaan 136
NL 2628 BL Delft

telephone: +31 (0)15 278 3577
fax:       +31 (0)15 278 4452
internet:  <A HREF="http://cpt6.stm.tudelft.nl/welcome.html">http://cpt6.stm.tudelft.nl/Welcome.html</A>
</PRE></TT>

<HR>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../pic/home.gif"></A> PhD-projects Delft

<HR>

<B>Permanent staff</B><P>

<I>a: Scientific staff:</I><BR>
Prof. B. Scarlett, M.Sc.<BR>
Prof.dr. B.H. Bibo<BR>
Dr.ir. S.M. Lemkowitz<BR>
Dr.ir. J.C.M. Marijnissen<BR>
Drs. H.G. Merkus<P>

<I>b: Technical staff:</I><BR>
Ing. K.J. Bloos<BR>
H.D.F. Meijer, B.Sc.<P>

<I>c: Secretariat staff:</I><BR>
W.J.M. van 't Hof-v.d. Kraaij<P>

<B>Research Scientists</B><P>

<I>Post Doc:</I><BR>
Dr. J.P. Borra<BR>

<I>AIO, OIO:</I><BR>
Ir. J. Beekman<BR>
Ir. D. Camelot<BR>
Ir. A. Dahoe<BR>
Drs. M. van Drunen<BR>
Ir. E. Gommeren<BR>
Ir. C.J. Grootveld<BR>
Ir. R. Hartman<BR>
Drs. C. Heffels<BR>
Ir. M. v.d. Kraan<BR>
Dipl.Ing. F. K&uuml;hn<BR>
Ir. W. Oostra<BR>
Ir. I. Tuinman<BR>
Dipl.Ing. M. Weiss<BR>
Ir. A. Willemse<BR>
Ir. J.F. Zevenbergen<BR>
Ir. Zhoe Yue<P>

<I>Research Fellow:</I><BR>
Masashi Machida<P>

<B>Particle Technology Group</B><P>

The programme of research in particle technology concerns the manufacture, measurement and manipulation of particulate systems. Thus, we try to make particles with better defined properties: manufacture. We also try to improve the design of particle handling equipment: manipulation. The particles and equipment are connected by the common theme of particle and powder characterisation: measurement. At the technological level, the thesis of the group is that processes must have good quality control and be safe. The two objectives are best achieved by on-line measurement and control: automation. This is a broad objective and implies a broad programme. With the present number of AIO's and OIO's it will be possible to achieve the broad programme which was always envisaged. We are striving to achieve that in the following way.<P>

<I>a. Measurement</I><P>

The programme in measuring particle size is very active. We are developing techniques for very small particles, both wet and dry, and are active in the international standards activities. The measurement of particle size, on-line and in-line, in a form suitable for process control is a well established project. We are now extending our measuring activities into the field of process tomography with the long term aim of continuously monitoring particle concentration, velocity and size within processes. It is also urgent that the work on the mechanical properties of powders and particles be extended. A new biaxial shear cell has been developed. Problems which concern the flow properties of powders provide, perhaps, the most constant source of requests for help from the process industries.<P>

<I>b. Manufacture</I><P>

We are currently concerned with the manufacture of particles by crystallisation, spraying, milling, granulation and by gas phase reactions. In each case the requirement is to control the size and shape of the particles formed through on-line measurement and model based control.<P>

<I>c. Manipulation</I><P>

A priority is with the theme of safety and the current projects concerned with dust explosions and inhalation risks. The dust explosion project has created a most successful cooperation with TNO. We are active in trying to create a more formal structure in the field of dust explosions and wider, loss prevention, which will enable us to make this a special field in The Netherlands through the Stichting SILP.<BR>
Another special theme is the use of electrostatics in powder processing. The charge may be acquired by corona or tribocharging and used to collect classify or mix the particles.<P>

