<HEAD><TITLE>Production of an submicrometer, dense ceramic powder using the spray pyrolysis process</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Production of an submicrometer, dense ceramic powder using the spray pyrolysis process</H2>

AIO: Ir D. Camelot
Sponsor: TU delft
	
<HR SIZE=0>

For the production of advance ceramic materials, high purity, dense, homogeneous and
submicron particles are required. Moreover the size distribution of the powder should be
quite narrow in order to allow the formation of a dense and fracture free ceramic body
during the sintering process.<BR>
The spray pyrolysis process consists basically on the atomization of a precursor solution
into droplets which are driven by a carrier gas through an oven. Inside the oven the
solvent evaporates and intraparticle reactions occurs that lead to the product material.
This process exhibits many advantages for ceramic powder production. The control of
the homogeneity is achieved (in case of multicomponent powders) on a particle scale,
the purity is only dependent on the precursor purity (no contamination by grinding), the
amount of by-product is very low, the size distribution of the final powder is easily
controlled by the atomization process. But this process as been reported [1 ] to often lead
to hollow (non-dense) particle formation. This hollow shape being the result of the
quick evaporation of the solvent which generate a concentration gradient in the droplet
which in turn creates surface precipitation.<BR>
In this work, we are investigating a route to produce dense particles with this process. In
order to do so we induce a polymerization reaction in the precursor droplet while it is
evaporating and we subsequently calcinate the polymer formed in order to obtain the
desired metal oxide.<P>

<IMG SRC="camelot1.gif"><P>

Fig. 1 Experimental set up<P>

<IMG SRC="camelot2.gif"><P>

Fig. 2 Sn02 particles<P>

Solutions of Sn(Ac)<SUB>4</SUB> in absolute ethanol were sprayed in the system. As noted in the
literature [2] the humidity of the air is enough to hydrolyze the tin compound in
Sn(OH)<SUB>4</SUB> and this hydrolysis takes place very fast. Subsequently, the hydroxydes react
between them via oxolation and olation to give a gel. This gel is then calcinated to give
pure SnO2 particles.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1><B>REFERENCES</B><BR>
<B>[1] Messing G.L. et al. </B><I>J. Am. Ceram. Soc.</I><B> Vol 76 No 11 (1993) 2707</B><BR>
<B>[2] Ingebrethsen B.J. and Matijevic E. </B><I>J. Coll. Inter. Sci.</I><B> Vol 100 No 1 (1984) 1</B></FONT><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
