<HEAD><TITLE>Energy reduction in jet milling processes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Energy reduction in jet milling processes</H2>

AIO: ir. H.J.C.Gommeren<BR>
email: <A HREF="mailto:H.J.C.Gommeren@wbmt.tudelft.nl">H.J.C.Gommeren@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
Sponsor: Novem/Wedco<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

Jetmilling is a grinding process used
in many industries (inkts, paints,
cosmetics, plastics, pharmaceuticals) to
reduce the particle size of solid, but
brittle materials down to sizes varying
from 40 microns to 1 micron or even less.
Another name for jetmilling is fluid
energy grinding. After leaving a nozzle
high pressure air will expand in a
grinding chamber. High velocity air jets
transmit kinetic energy to the particles to
be ground. Size reduction is caused by
particle-particle collisions.<P>

<IMG SRC="gommeren1.gif"><P>

Figure: Jet mill chamber<P>

<B>Research intention</B><P>

In terms of energy consumption this
grinding process is the most inefficient of
all grinding processes. Jet mills use
between 800 and 4500 kWh per ton
ground product. The estimated total
energy use for air milling is about 600
million kWh in Europe and about 1000
kWh in the United States. The objective
of this project is to reduce the energy use
of this process by 50%.<BR>
The project that started in November
1992 is carried out jointly by the Delft
University . ' of Technology, Particle
Technology Group and the Process
Control Group.<P>

<B>Test plant</B><P>

For this purpose a new air mill
system will be developed. Main feature
of this new grinding plant will be an
operation control based on    on-line measurement of the produced
particle sizes. In case the product does
not meet the specification. The jet mill is
operated in a closed circuit configuration,
that means an external classifier is .<P>

<B>Experiments</B><P>

Pilot plant experiments are carried
out at the Laboratory for Process
Equipment. The f'lrst steps of the project
concentrate on implementing operation
controls.<BR>
Further experiments will be done to
validate and improve a computer model
that has been developed to predict the
setpoints of the solid feedrate and high
pressure air supplied to the jet mill. The
combination of setpoints is such that the
required specification of the end product
is achieved
at minimum energy
consumption.<P>

<B>Information</B><P>

For further information about this
project, please contact it. H.J.C.
Gommeren, Lab. for Process Equipment
at Delft University. Leeghwaterstraat 44
2628 CA, Delft, The Netherlands<BR>
Tel. 31-15-786628; Fax. 31-15-786975<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
