<HEAD><TITLE>An investigation of the droplet production mechanism in the delft aerosol generator</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>An investigation of the droplet production mechanism in the delft aerosol generator</H2>

OIO: Ir. R. Hartman,<BR>
Post Doc: Dr. J.P. Borra<BR>
Sponsors: SON/STW, Burgerscentrum<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

The process of electrohydrodynamic atomization (EHDA) disrupts a liquid, due to electric
acceleration, into fine droplets forming an aerosol. This aerosol can have, under certain
conditions, a narrow size distribution. The uni-polar droplet charge provides an additional
control parameter which can increase the efficiency of the end application by reducing
coagulation (e.g. combustion), increasing deposition (e.g.paint spraying) and allowing for
controllable trajectories (e.g. non-impact printing). In other applications where solutions are
sprayed in order to produce a monosized powder, (eg medicines, toner powder), the high
particle charge creates a technical problem. Evaporating charged particles can exceed the
Rayleigh charge limit and explode, creating a spray with a much wider size distribution.
Another problem is to allow the particles enough time to dry before collection. Both
problems can be solved by discharging the particles. The Delft Aerosol Generator (DAG)
presents such a capability. (Meesters, 1992). Figure I shows an improved version of the
DAG.<BR>
In this version, a negative corona at
the discharging needle produces negative ions
which discharge the highly positive droplets
produced at the nozzle. The gauze protects
the needle from the particles, which makes
longer periods of stationary operation
possible. The distance between the ring and
the gauze is variable, and the negative
potential on the needle controls the droplet
discharging rate. The outside diameter of the
nozzles used, ranges from 2 to 8 ram, and the
inner diameter ranges from 0.1 to 1 min. This
relatively large inner diameter prevents
clogging of the nozzles, even when aerosols
are produced with an average size below 10
&#181;m. The size range produced, nm to mm,
depends on the spraying mode and liquid used.<P>

<IMG SRC="hartman1.gif"><P>

Figure 1 improved Delft Aerosol Generator.<P>

The aim of this study is to design an spraying apparatus based on
electrohydrodynamic atomization that can meet with the required industrial production rates.
Since electrohydrodynamic atomization is limited in its liquid flow rate per nozzle, typically
10<SUP>-3</SUP> ml/s, these production rates can only be obtained by using an array of nozzles. Both
experimental and numerical work is done, to understand the atomization principle in the
DAG, and to design a pilot.<P>

REFERENCES
Meesters G.M.H., (1992). Mechanisms of Droplet Formation. PhD thesis, Delft University
of Technology.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
