<HEAD><TITLE>On-line raman spectroscopy during laser-cvp of Si3N4 powders</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>On-line raman spectroscopy during laser-cvp of Si<SUB>3</SUB>N<SUB>4</SUB> powders</H2>

AIO: I.L. Tuinman<BR>
Sponsor: OSPT<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The manufacture of technical ceramics inl flamc
aerosol reactors has received a lot of attcntion during the
past ten years. Usually it is very difficult to control
particle properties thus powder quality. in thcsc reactors.
The ability to monitor the process in-line certainly could
give an opportunity for improvement.<BR>
To achieve this a special laser aerosol reactor (fig. 1)
was developed for the production of Si<SUB>3</SUB>N<SUB>4</SUB>. The gases
enter the reactor through four concentric nozzles below
the laser beam. Silane (SiH<SUB>4</SUB>) and ammonia (NH<SUB>3</SUB>) are
used as precursors. The mixing of these reactants is
controlled with a small flow of inert sheath gas. N2. and
a large nitrogen flow through the outer nozzle serves as
a confining flow. carrier gas for the particles and as a
cooling agent. The gases are heated vcry quickly by
absorption of the radiation from a 160 W CO<SUB>2</SUB>-laser
beam which is focused with a ZnSe lens to the desired
beam width and a bright reaction flame results.<BR>
Particle growth in the flame has been studied wilh
photon correlation spectroscopy and electron microscope
studies of samples from the flame (Tuinman et al.
1995). We now report on the monitoring of the process
with Raman spectroscopy.<P>

<B>Raman Spectroscopy</B><BR>
When a monochromatic light beam is focused on a
sample, which may be liquid, gaseous or solid. light
scattering occurs. Most of the scattered light has the
same frequency' as the incident light. This ellistic
scattering gives rise to the Rayleigh line. Upon inelastic
collisions, i.e. a photon gains or loses energy in the
scattering process, species specific frequency shifts
occur. This is termed Raman scattering.<P>

<IMG SRC="tuinman1.gif"><P>

<B>fig. 1</B> Top view of the reactor and Raman spectroscopy set-up<P>

The spectroscopy set up is also shown in fig. 1. The
scattered light is collected and focused on a
monochromator entrance slit with the aid of two lenses
and two mirrors. The monochromator disperses the
spectrum and the intensity as a function of wavelength
is measured with a diode array at its exit. A holographic
notch filter blocks the intense Rayleigh scattered light.
The intensity of the Raman signal is:<P>

<IMG SRC="tuinman2.gif"><P>

with Is h nu the signal power in watts, h Planck's constant,
nu the seatiered light frequency, d sigma / d omega is the differential
scattering cross section in cm<SUP>2</SUP>/sr, N<SUB>nu,J</SUB> the number
density of scattering species in the initial vibration-
rotation energy level, I<SUB>0</SUB> h nu<SUB>0</SUB> is the laser intensity, eta the
collection efficiency, omega the solid angle of the collection
optics in sr and l is the length of the laser beam over
which the scattered light is detected. The temperature
dependence of N<SUB>nu,J</SUB> is given by the Boltzman
distribution. Hence. if two or more lines of one species
are measured. both the concentration and temperature
profiles in the reactor can be determined.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
Fig.2 shows the Raman spectra taken in the reactor
during production as a function of height above nozzles.
The change in concentration of the major species as a
function of place in the reactor is obvious. The SiH<SUB>4</SUB>, N<SUB>2</SUB>
and NH<SUB>3</SUB> first mix as a result of diffusion and when
crossing the CO<SUB>2</SUB> laser beam silane and ammonia react,
so the corresponding lines disappear.<P>

<B>References</B><BR>
Tuinman I.L. et al. (1995), Partec 4th international
congress optical particle sizing, pp. 195-203.<P>

<IMG SRC="tuinman3.gif"><P>

<B>fig. 2</B> Raman spectra taken at different heights above<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

