<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>On-line chemical analysis of single particles</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>On-line chemical analysis of single particles</H2>

AIO: M. Weiss<BR>
Sponsors: Stichting voor Scheikundig Onderzoek Nederland (SON) / Stichting voor Technische Wetenschappen (STW)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
It is often useful to know the size and
the chemical composition of small par-
ticles. The Particle Technology Group
at Delft University of Technology has
developed such an instrument.<P>

<B>Experimental Setup</B><BR>
Particles are sampled into the vacuum
chamber of a TOF mass spectrome-
ter by a differentially pumped nozzle
system. The aerosol beam intersects
with the beam of a helium-neon laser
whereby the particles are scattering
light. A part of the scattered light is
detected by a photo-multiplier. With
the aid of the photo-multiplier signal
a second laser is triggered. This sec-
ond laser is an excimer laser (running
at 308 nm) that vaporizes the particles
and ionizes the fragments.<P>

<IMG SRC="weiss1.gif"><P>

The generated ions are accelerated into
the flight tube of the TOF mass spec-
trometer. The mass spectrum detected
with the aid of multi channel plates
gives information on the chemical com-
position of the particle.<P>

<B>Planned Data Processing</B><BR>
It is planned to apply several kinds
of classification and clustering algo-
rithms. With those algorithms it
might be possible to find and differen-
tiate between classes of particles (for
example particles containing sulphur,
particles containing lead etc.). This
would yield a unique on-line measure-
ment system for size and composition
of single particles.<P>

<B>Results and Conclusions</B><BR>
The following figure shows mass spec-
tra we obtained from anthracene par-
ticles.<P>

<IMG SRC="weiss2.gif"><P>

For high energies of the ionization laser
the anthracene molecule breaks down
to small carbon fragments. Below a
certain threshold however the molecule
stays intact.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
