<HEAD><TITLE>Development of an on-line measurement and control system for fine grinding and dispersion processes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Development of an on-line measurement and control system for fine grinding and dispersion processes</H2>

AIO : Ix. A.W. Willemse<BR>
Sponsor: IOP Verf<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

1. INTRODUCTION<P>

The objective of wet grinding and dispersion processes during paint production is to incorporate particles homegeneously into a liquid system. Many technical properties of a paint dispersion
depend on the degree of dispersion attained. In this project, the dispersions consist of a solvent
containing pigments, fillers and binders.<BR>
Not only the optical properties of dispersed pigmented systems change as a function of particle
size. Moreover, oversized or poorly dispersed particles generally adversely affect the application properties of the dispersion. For example, large particles can disturb the surfaces of paint,
leading to poor gloss.<P>

In paint industry, the process of the dispersion of pigments is still mainly controlled by empirical methods. These methods however are time consuming and often not very precise, moreover, as the demands on product quality are rising, the process should be controlled more
accurately. For such a process, a reliable measurement system is required. As the dispersion
process is mainly a deagglomeration process, further dilution before measurement is very
dangerous, since this usually results in breakup of the agglomerates. Therefore, an on-line
measurement technique capable of measuring particle diameters in highly concentrated dispersion has to be developed.<P>

2. MEASURING TECHNIQUES<P>

<I>PCS</I><BR>
For measuring in highly diluted samples in the sub-micron area, Photon Correlation Spectroscopy (PCS) is a well-suited measuring technique. Particles suspended in fluids exhibit Brownian motion, due to collisions with fluid molecules. The frequency of this random motion is
higher as the particle size decreases. Laser light scattered by these particles therefore also
fluctuates with time, where the frequency of the fluctuations is dependent on the particle size;
or more precisely, on their diffusion coefficient. We are using optical fiber PCS to be able to
measure diffusion coefficients in the actual paint. With optical fiber PCS we are able to measure even in this highly concentrated dispersions as this technique uses backward light scattering..<P>

<I>EBS</I><BR>
For measuring particle size in the micrometer region, Enhanced BackScattering (EBS) might
be applicable. This measuring systems determines the enhanced backscatter peak, which is
caused by constructive interference of two waves transversing through the same set of particles
in opposite directions. This enhancement cone contains information about the particle size of a
sample. As this information is gathered in the backscatter direction, it is possible to determine
this cone in highly concentrated dispersions.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
