<HEAD><TITLE>Extreme control in cold rolling</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Extreme control in cold rolling</H2>

AIO : M. Trijssenaar	(015-782658)<BR>
m.trijssenaar@stm.tudelft.nl
Sponsor: Hoogovens<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction.</B><P>

Cold rolling is the process in which steel
sheet is reduced in thickness from hot rolling
exit thickness (order 1 mm) to its final
thickness (order 0.2 mm), below the
recristallization temperature of steel. In order
to cool the steel and rolls, to lower the
friction and to prevent 'pick-up' between rolls
and sheet, the contact between rolls and sheet
is lubricated with an oil-in-water emulsion.
The emulsion is sprayed onto the steel and a
lubricating layer of fluid is sheared into the
roll bite by the velocity of the surfaces.<BR>
Contrary to the lubrication with pure oil,
lubrication with emulsions is not quite
understood. In existing models of cold rolling
lubrication the lubricating fluid is assumed to
be one phase. The exact composition of a
lubricating film formed by an emulsion, and
the mechanism by which this film is formed,
is not known.<P>

<B>Experimental.</B><P>

Experiments were performed on the pilot
size cold rolling stand of Hoogovens. Rolling
force and roll velocity are kept constant,
while the reduction factor r (1-ratio of outlet
and inlet thickness of the sheet) is varied by
adjusting the inlet and outlet tensions on the
sheet. A sheet is passed four times, with r =
±0.40, ±0.30, ±0.21, ±0.21. As also the
oilfilm, with the steel, is reduced in thickness
during each pass, oil on the surface must be
replenished from the emulsion. Measured oil
film thicknesses on the sheet after each pass
are shown to be constant, which means the
amount of replenished oil is a function of
reduction factor.<P>

<IMG SRC="trijssenaar1.gif"><P>

The hydrodynamic model for lubrication [1]
is verified for pure oil lubrication of cold
rolling [2] and describes the film thickness
well. As it is often assumed that emulsion
lubrication gives a pure oil lubricating film,
this model is compared with the
measurements of the emulsion experiment.
Also, the theoretical film thicknesses are
calculated, using parameters for emulsion
under high shear and high pressure
conditions. Hydrodynamic lubrication theory
obviously
cannot explain emulsion
lubrication.<BR>
Replenishment of oil can be achieved by
wetting of the steel surface by the oil in the
emulsion. This effect has been observed.
However, in order to explain the insensitivity
of the oilfilmthickness for reduction, wetting
properties of the oil-water surface, changing
with rolling conditions, i.e., shear, must be
taken into account.<P>

[1] Wilson, W. R. D., Walowit, J.A. (1971)
<I>Trib. Cortv., InsIn Mech Engrs</I>, 164-172<BR>
[2] Neumann, W., Kuiper, C. (1995) <I>Intern
Rapport Hoogovens</I>.<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
