<HEAD><TITLE>Coagulation kinetics</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Coagulation kinetics</H2>

AIO: S. Shulepov, Msc. (015-278 26 58)<BR>
shulepov@stm.tudelft.nl<BR>
Sponsor: TUD<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction.</B> Using a theoretical model
based upon the scaling concept in
description of heterogeneous systems, the
dependence of the colloid stability
against BrownJan coagulation as a
function of the surface roughness
parameters has been analysed (OSPT'93).
The qualitative correlation between
experimental data and theoretical
modelling was obvious (OSPT'94).
However, the quantitative agreement can
only be discussed if this surface
roughness is measured and analysed
independently of the construction of the
stability diagram.<P>

<B>Experimental.</B> The criterion (OSPT'93)
was derived which separates stability
curves strongly affected by the surface
roughness from those slightly sensitive to
its characteristics. The boundary between
these two regimes is around a value L =
lambda<SUP>2</SUP> / delta d = 1, where lambda is the lateral
characteristic size (half-wave) of surface
details, delta is the half-height, and d is the
particle diameter.<BR>
A set of experiments on coagulation
kinetics was carried out for colloidal gold
dispersions with the particle size on the
nanometer scale. The diagram shows that
the stability of rather small particles is
almost independent of particle size. For
bigger particles, the particle size affects
stability ratio (W). However, this effect is
less pronounced than it is expected
following the standard DLVO theory.<P>

<IMG SRC="shulepov1.gif"><P>

Moreover, the intercept of stability
curves suggests the different critical
coagulation concentrations for colloidal
particles of different radii.<P>

<B>Surface roughness characterization.</B> The
following procedure was established to
extract the roughness parameters entered
into the criterion. We started from the
high contrast electron micrographs of
particles representing our sols. The
profiles were electronically traced and
analysed, using images with
magnification of about 500 000.<P>

<IMG SRC="shulepov2.gif"><P>

To describe the surface features, the
lateral "yardstick" of 7 nm was chosen.
The latter is commensurate with the
range of colloidal forces in the
concentration interval (5<= c <= 30 mmol/L)
where the slope of logW-logc curves
remains constant. In such a way, the
characteristic size of lambda was chosen and
the vertical size delta of surface details with
that lateral size was measured using the
actual particle profile. The characteristics
obtained were substituted into our
criterion, and the results are given in
Table.<P>

<IMG SRC="shulepov3.gif"><P>

<B>Conclusions.</B> The criterion derived allows
to judge whether the surface roughness
must be accounted for describing stability
of colloidal particles against coagulation.
For such a model suspension as colloidal
gold it shows a rather good agreement
between theoretical anticipation and experimental results.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

