<HEAD><TITLE>Adhesion and polymer adsorption at metal/coating interfaces</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Adhesion and polymer adsorption at metal/coating interfaces</H2>

<B>PhD student</B> drs. S.G.O. de Haas (015-785353)<BR>
<B>Sponsor</B> IOP-Coatings / Adhesion Institute TU Delft
<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Aluminium and its alloys are often used in
aerospacial, car and building industry
where a good adhesion of a coating on
aluminium is very important. Ageing of
anodized aluminium, before applying a
coating, reduces the adhesion quality.
Investigation of the reasons for this
reduction will permit us to identify the
parameters for optimal adhesion on aluminium.<BR>
E. Margarita observed that ageing of the
aluminium results in a lower aluminium
surface energy ('activity') and a brittle
aluminium oxide structure ( see elsewhere
in this book).<BR>
A lower surface activity is expected to
decrease the polymer adsorption on this
surface. Polymer adsorption involves a loss
of entropy caused by a less favorable
polymer conformation. Interaction of the
polymer with the activated aluminium
surface involves an energy gain which has
to compensate for the entropy loss for
adsorption to occur.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
A polyvinylchloride/vinylacetate (87/13)
melt is pressed against aluminium of
different age after pretreatement, and then
it is cooled down. Subsequently, the
aluminium and aluminium oxide are
dissolved in a sodium hydroxide solution
and adsorption of acetate groups at the
interface is measured by contact angle
measurements on the polymer plate. This
enables us to calculate the surface energy,
a measure of adsorption according to
Pennings [1]. The polymer plates were also
studied by fractography on a SEM in order
to observe
the polymer penetration into the porous
oxide layer.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
The polymer penetrates into the pores of
the anodisation layer. This penetration is
deeper in the pores of a fresh substrate,
see figure 1.<P>

<IMG SRC="haas1.gif"><P>

<B>Figure 1.</B><I> Penetration depth versus aluminium
exposure time</I><P>

This observation can be explained by a
decreased polymer adsorption on an
exposed surface, see figure 2.<P>

<IMG SRC="haas1.gif"><P>

<B>Figure 2.</B> <I>Polymer surface energy versus
aluminium exposure time.</I><P>

Decreased polymer adsorption corresponds
to less wetting and cappilairy suction.
Inferior polymer penetration leaves a
greater part of the porous oxide layer
unprotected against formation of a brittle
structure. This is a plausible explanation
for the reduced adhesion quality.<P>

[1]
J. Pennings, Adsorption of Vinyl
Copolymers from melts and solutions,
thesis, Eindhoven (1982).<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
