<HEAD><TITLE>Adsorption of reducing agents on metals</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Adsorption of reducing agents on metals</H2>

AIO: Mamix ten Kortenaar (015-2781485)<BR>
Sponsor: TUD<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I><B>Objective</B></I><P>

Electroless plating is an autocatalytic
process in which metals are deposited on
a substrate by a reducing agent. The
reducing agent is oxidized on the
catalytic substrate and released electrons
are consumed by metal ions present at
the interface. The deposited metal layer
propagates the catalytic oxidation of the
reducing agent resulting in an
autocatalytic growth of the metal film.
Electroless plating is applied in the
manufacture of printed circuit boards
and protective coatings. It is a cheap and
attractive way to metallize various
substrates. However, the detailed
mechanism of electroless metallization
has still not been elucidated and this
often makes it an empirical matter. An
enhanced understanding may improve
kinetic control of selective microscale
metallization processes.<P>

<I><B>Methods</B></I><P>

The adsorption and exchange of
formaldehyde (reducing agent) is studied
on different catalytic metals. This is
primarily done by using radioactive
labeled formaldehyde molecules. The
experimental equipment needed is
currently built at the Interfaculty Reactor
Institute. The concept is derived from a
setup constructed recently at the
University of Illinois. The equipment
enables one to study adsorption (in-situ)
at the liquid-solid boundary down to 1%
of a monolayer. Adsorption rate,
adsorption isotherms as well as exchange
can be measured as a function of pH,
potential, time,     temperature and
concentration. In principle any adsorbate-
adsorbent combination can be studied,
provided that a convenient tracer
molecule is available. The method is
based on a 'press down' procedure as is
depicted schematically below. By
pressing down a smooth substrate with
adsorbed (radioactive) molecules on a
flat glass scintillator, most of the solution
is squeezed out. The glass scintillator
then converts detected g-particles in a
light pulse, which is sent to a
photomultiplier tube. The quantity of
adsorbed molecules is obtained rapidly
by subtracting background signals. The
method also enables one to study
exchange of the adsorbate with non-
labeled equivalent molecules in solution.<P>

<I><B>Data Processing and Prospects</B></I><P>

The exchange rate measured is simulated
by compartimental analysis and should
yield a convenient physical model which
describes    the    different    'kinetic
compartments' in the adsorption process.
The model yields the time of residence of
a formaldehyde molecule on the metal
substrate examined. These times are
supposed to be characteristic of the
(electro)catalytic activity of the metal.
The activity estimated can be used for
rate laws which lead to an enhanced
insight of the metal deposition process.
In addition, electrochemical as well as
spectrosopical techniques are used in
order to verify the model postulated.<P>

<IMG SRC="kortenaar1.gif"><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
