<HEAD><TITLE>Effectivity of the washing process</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Effectivity of the washing process</H2>

AIO: A.M.D.E. Timmerman (015-782638 / A. Timmerman@stm.tudelft.nl)<BR>
Sponsor: IR-TNO<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

In the detergency industry the washing process
is characterised by the 'Sinner-factors':
energy, temperature, chemistry and time.
Departing from these factors the washing
process can be optimalized. If, however, the
backgrounds of the Sinner factors are known,
it will be possible to optimize the washing
process from a more fundamental point of
view. From earlier research it was concluded
that a soiled textile could never be cleaned in
a normal washing process if the most
important mechanism governing the mass
transfer from fabric to detergent solution were
diffusion. Therefore, in this research it is
supposed that there is a flow both along the
fabric-surfactant solution interface and in the
fabric yarns.<P>

<B>Theory</B><P>

During the washing process fabrics are moved
and deformed permanently. By stretching the
fabric, liquid (particularly a suffactant
solution) is squeezed from pores in the yams.
Our first hypothesis is that the deformation of
the fabric and the flow in the yams causes, in
case of a very concentrated surfactant
solution, a local surfactant supersaturation at
the fabric-surfactant solution interface. This
local supersaturation in its turn could cause
instabilities, which might cause flow along the
fabric-liquid interface. This flow along the
interface may be advantageous for the
effectivity of the washing process.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><P>

It is our objective to find evidence for flow
along the liquid-fabric interface. In order to do
so the following experiment will be carried
out: surfactant solutions of different
concentrations are pushed through a narrow
capillary. The flow through the capillary is
measured. It is envisaged that highly
concentrated solutions (about 3 times the
critical micelle concentration) will flow
through the capillary more quickly than more
diluted solutions. This indicates that there is
slip at the wall of the capillary in the case of
highly concentrated solutions.<P>

In order to get an indication of the force with
which the solution should be pushed through
the capillary another preliminary experiment
will be carried out:<P>

Yarns are impregnated with a solution of
magnesium sulphate in water. The yams are
placed in water and subjected to a small strain
in a tensile strength tester. The force needed
to do so can be divided in a visco-elastic
component and a friction force along the yarn.
This force is caused by the outflow of the salt
solution. If the yam is elongated very slowly
the flow from the yam is very small and the
force needed for the same elongation will be
smaller than in case of fast elongation. The
flow can be found by measuring the increase
in conductivity of the water in which the yam
is placed. It is assumed that the instabilities at
the interface, mentioned earlier, can only exist
when mass transport due to convection is large
enough. The difference between the force
needed to cause a certain strain in case of flow
from the yam by convection, and the force
needed to cause the same strain at a very low
elongation velocity gives an indication of the
forces that are involved in the flow of liquid
along a yam. In its turn this gives an indication
of the force with which surfactant solutions
should be pushed through the capillary.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
