<HEAD><TITLE>Improvement of cohesive and adhesive properties of whey proteins</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Improvement of cohesive and adhesive properties of whey proteins</H2>

AIO : A.A.C.M. Rutten (015-278 26 36)<BR>
Term : Sept. 1995 - Sept. 1999<BR>
Sponsor: IOP Industrial proteins / Borculo Whey Products / National Starch & Chemical BV<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

It is expected that on a short term the
supply of whey proteins at the world
market will increase. Therefore, it is
essential to develop new applications of
whey proteins. Non-food applications
are preferred, because there is no
competition with other proteins, as in
the food sector, but with synthetic
polymers. Very interesting fields of
application are adhesives and coating/films. The knowledge about the
use of whey proteins in these
applications is very limited. Especially,
knowledge about their adhesive and
cohesive properties and their water
sensitivity is required to develop these
applications.<BR>
The aim of this project is to gain
knowledge about the relation between the
adhesive and cohesive properties of whey
proteins and their structure in order to
improve their performance in this respect.<P>

<B>Description of the project</B><P>

In this project the emphasis will be on
beta-1actoglobulin because it is the most
abundant protein in whey and much is
known about its structure, which greatly
facilitates the interpretation of the results
in structural terms. In a later stage of the
project other proteins and lactose will be
included.<BR>
The structure of the beta-1actoglobulin will
be changed by thermal and especially
chemical modifications, as well as by the
use of organic solvents, water-miscible or
not. To attain strong adhesion with a
surface, the globular protein molecules
have to unfold themselves. The natural
tendency towards depletion of these
molecules has to be compensated by
polar interactions of functional groups in
the protein chain with the substrate.
These functional groups may be already
present in the protein chain and become
available by the unfolding process, or
they may be introduced or amplified by
modification. The quality of the solvent
will influence the conformation stability
(compliance) of the protein.<BR>
Functional properties, such as adsorption
behaviour, film forming, adhesive
strength and mechanical properties of the
films, will be studied, as well as the
degree of denaturation, hydrophobicity
and the aggregation behaviour. These
properties will be related to the polarity
of both solvent and substrate.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
