<HEAD><TITLE>PhD-projects Delft</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Laboratory for Applied Thermodynamics and Phase Equilibria<HR></H2>

<TT><PRE>
Delft University of Technology
Department of Chemical Technology and Material Science
Julianalaan 136
NL 2628 BL Delft

telephone: +31 (0)15 278 2667
fax:       +31 (0)15 278 8047
</PRE></TT>

<HR>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../pic/home.gif"></A> PhD-projects Delft

<HR>

<H2 ALIGN=center>Delft University of Technology
Laboratory for Applied Thermodynamics and Phase Equilibria
</H2>

<B>Permanent sraff</B><BR>
Prof.Dr.Ir. J. de Swaan Arons<BR>
Dr.Ir. H.J. van der Kooi<BR>
Dr.Ir. Th.W. de Loos<BR>
Dr.Ir. C.J. Peters<P>

<B>Laboratory Assistants</B><BR>
L.J. Florusse<BR>
J.H.F. Grondel<BR>
W. Poot<P>

<U><B>Research theme</B></U><BR>
Thermodynamic models for processes with or without chemical conversion, normally at high pressures (<4000 bar; < 400 degrees Celcius).<BR>
The task of applied thermodynamics is to provide maximum information on required thermodynamic properties for applications in a wide range of pressure, temperature and composition. The challenge is to accomplish this from a minimum number of experimental data and from a thermodynamic model which contains essential information on the molecular properties of the system and which relies on the sound principles of molecular and statistical thermodynamics.<P>

<U><B>Research topics</B></U><BR>
<B>Retrograde condensation of natural gas</B><BR>
This research concentrates on collecting experimental data and modelling the results for possible liquid separation on pressure reduction during production transportation and storage of natural gas.<P>

<B>Phase and interfacial behaviour of gas condensates</B><BR>
Many reservoir fluids have characteristics between natural gas and oil. Such fluids may separate into various phases such as vapour, one or two liquid, asphaltenes, wax and hydrates. This research focuses on observing, modelling  and predicting phase behaviour and, when ever possible, interfacial tensions and concentration profiles.<P>

<B>Enhanced oil recovery</B><BR>
Phase equilibria of interest for enhanced oil recovery by low concentration surfactants Funded by Shell.<P>

<B>Polymer solutions</B><BR>
Determination of phase equilibria and stability limits (with pressure pulse induced critical scattering, PPICS) of fluid phases composed of polymers and near critical solvents. Support from DSM and DOW.<P>

<B>Aqueous two-phase systems</B><BR>
The development of the non-fat-food industry depends on insight in the theological and phase behaviour of aqueous solutions of carbohydrates and proteins. Models will be developed to predict phase behaviour of biopolymers of practical interest in aqueous solutions of varying acidity and salt content.<BR>
Cooperation with University of Leiden and Unilever Research, funded by STW and Unilever,<P>

<B>Thermodynamic analysis of processes</B><BR>
The second law and its application is central in this activity. By identifying and evaluating the forces that drive important industrial processes (to be), critical assessment can be made of the quality of engineering performance. The research content of these studies relates closely to the process' design. Examples mainly concern processes with a great environmental impact.<P>

<B>Near-critical processing</B><BR>
Studies are made of enhanced volatility and solubility of low volatile solutes, enzymatic reactions and crystallization in solvents near their critical point. Phase behaviour measurements and modelling is carried of aqueous electrolyte systems at near-critical conditions.<P>

<B>Fundamental studies</B><BR>
- The study of possible improvements in the performance of equations of state of practical importance, by basing their parameters on experimental data of sound velocity and specific heat.<BR>
- Simultaneous description of interfacial and bulk phase behaviour of binary and multicomponent mixtures.<BR>
- The study of hydrogen bonding and self-assembling systems.<BR>
- Fluid multiphase equilibria in selected ternary systems of interest for supercritical processes.<P>

<U><B>Research Scientists</B></U><BR>
<B>PhD students</B><P>

P. Cornelisse (2)<BR>
E. Fl&ouml;ter (1)<BR>
V.V. de Leeuw (1)<BR>
G. van Lieshout (3)<BR>
S. Rudoph (3)<BR>
K. Gauter (1)<BR>
P.J. Smits (2)<BR>
R. Stevens (1)<BR>
