<HEAD><TITLE>Cumulative exergy analysis of cleaning processes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Cumulative exergy analysis of cleaning processes</H2>

Dr X. Zhao<P>

Laboratory of Applied Thermodynamics and Phase Equilibria<BR>
Faculty of Chemical Technology and Materials Science<BR>
Delft University of Technology<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER><B>INTRODUCTION</B></CENTER><P>

Energy depletion is one of the most-
mentioned issues in the public media as well
as in the academic world. However, the
energy concept itself sometimes is quite
confusing. One Joule of electricity and one
Joule of internal energy of the sea water is
equal, but not equivalent. Only with exergy
concept, the valuable quality of energy can
be evaluated fairly and reasonably. Exergy
analysis as a useful tool is therefore broadly
accepted and used in many areas, especially
exergy-consuming industries such as power
generation and chemical engineering.<P>

The goal of this project is to provide an
insight into the exergy consumptions of
different cleaning processes. We consider
here conventional water washing, large scale
industrial washing, washing with ultrasonic
enhancement,     membrane-filtration
application to laundry water regeneration,
solvent cleaning, supercritical solvent
cleaning. In the mean time, some other
topics of interest are included. They are:
comparison of frequent washing with
intensive washing, exergy consumption
related to washing machine production, life
time cycle of textile exergy, and so on.<P>

<CENTER><B>METHODOLOGY</B></CENTER><P>

The processes in washing machines are not
complicated, even not very exergy-intensive.
But the exergy consumption prior to the
cleaning activities is far beyond this. Before
any washing appliances start working,
electricity must be generated in power
stations, water needs to be treated in water
plants and pumped into our homes, detergent
has to be prepared from hydrocarbon
feedstock and a lot of other raw materials in
chemical plants. All of these processes
consume exergy and much more so than the
theoretical minima that can be calculated
with thermodynamics.<P>

The methodology of this project is based on
Cumulative Exergy Consumption (CExC).
All processes related to cleaning activities
are taken into account, from the mining of
raw materials to the wastewater treatment.<P>

<CENTER><B>RESULTS</B></CENTER><P>

1) In general, the exergy consumption
related to heating and detergent may take a
dominant part of the total exergy
consumption of a washing process. 2) At
current stage, most newly proposed cleaning
processes are not as exergy-effective as
conventional water washing process. 3)
Membrane filtration water regeneration is a
promising technique to be app1ied to washing
processes. It not only recycles water, but
also regenerates part of detergent. By doing
so, it can partly solve the environmental
problem as well. 4)Washing machine may
account for about 10% of exergy consumed
in washing activities.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
