<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Thermodynamic modelling of inhomogeneous systems</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Thermodynamic modelling of inhomogeneous systems</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. Peter Cornelisse<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> NWO/SON<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

The PhD project I participate in consists of
the theoretical description of inhomogeneous
systems, in which there has been a growing
interest in the last few decades. The major
aim is the calculation of the equilibrium
properties of interfaces, of which the most
important quantity is the interfacial/surface
tension. Under certain conditions, this
tension is believed to play an important role
in the exploration of oil wells. Existing
theories commonly used in industry are not
capable of describing various interfacial
phenomena like wetting and low interfacial
tension behaviour. On the other hand,
existing theories that can handle these
aspects require large computational efforts.
In the present PhD project I have tried to
find a theory that can predict most
important phenomena with the smallest
possible computational burden. The main
reason why it is desirable to predict
interfacial tensions instead of measuring
them is that the latter approach is time and
money consuming.<P>

<B>Approach</B><P>

Two different theories are used for
model ling the interfaces, which differ in the
way the Hellholes free-energy of the
system is represented. In the first model,
introduced originally by J.D. van der
Waals, the free-energy consists of two
contributions. The first is a homogeneous
free-energy density evaluated at the local
density, while the second is a non-local
contribution represented by the gradients in
density. The local free-energy was model led
by a modem equation of state like the model
of Pend-Robinson (PR), used for non-polar
and non-associating species, or the
Associating Perturbed Anisotropic Chain
Theory (APART), used for polar and
associating species. The accuracy that can
be achieved for pure fluids with these
models is always better than 3 percent. For
mixtures the results were found somewhat
less accurate; the accuracy for typically
gas condensate mixtures was always less than
3 percent, while the accuracy for systems
containing water was always less than 10
percent.<P>

<IMG SRC="cornelisse1.gif"><P>

<I>The interfacial tension of the
water/ethanol mixture at 1 bar.</I><P>

One problem of the theory of van der Waals
is that the wetting transitions that have been
described using the PR and APART model
are always of second order. Therefore to
model first order wetting transitions, which
are much more common in nature, another
theory needs to be used. The theory that has
been selected for this purpose is a
perturbation theory of inhomogeneous fluid.
In this theory the free-energy is composed
of a contribution due to purely repulsive
interactions, and an attractive contribution.
The accuracy of the results appears to be
comparable with the results obtained with
the modified gradient approach.
Additionally it was shown that with the
second theory indeed first order wetting
transition can be obtained.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
