<HEAD><TITLE>Solid-fluid and vapor-liquid equilibria of binary reservoir model fluids</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Solid-fluid and vapor-liquid equilibria of binary reservoir model fluids</H2>

<B>Ph.D.-student:</B> E. F1&ouml;ter (015-278-3927)<BR>
Delft University of Technology<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

In this investigation we try to gain some insight into the phase behavior of high pressure gas
condensate reservoir fluids. Because of their unusual high reservoir pressures (p > 50 MPa), these fluids
are also called hyperbaric reservoir fluids. In some North Sea gas condensate fields pressures above 100
MPa and temperatures close to 470 K are found. These methane-rich reservoir fluids can be near-critical
and may contain significant amounts of high molecular weight hydrocarbons. Various phenomena as wax
formation, and very high dew-point pressures could be explained by the presence of the heavy
hydrocarbon fraction. Many aspects of the phase behavior of gas condensates can be studied by
investigating the phase behavior of simple asymmetric binary model systems. Therefore, we investigated
vapor-liquid and solid-fluid equilibria of four different systems being all composed of methane and a
heavy hydrocarbon constituent. These are tetracosane, 1-phenyldodecane, phenanthrene, and
cholestane.<P>

<HR SIZE=0>

In the investigated pressure and
temperature range qualitatively the same type of
phase behavior was found for the four systems.<P>

<IMG SRC="floter1.gif"><P>

<B>The system methane + tetracosane</B><P>

The experiments were carried out using
autoclaves which allow to apply pressures up to
400 MPa and temperatures up to 473 K. Since
we work according to the synthetic method the
phase behavior is determined for various p-T
sections.<P>

<B>The solid-fluid equilibrium</B><P>

<IMG SRC="floter2.gif"><P>

The lines of the two-phase equilibria
were calculated based on the equation below.<P>

<IMG SRC="floter3.gif"><P>

Where dh<SUB>f</SUB> and dv<SUB>sl</SUB> were assumed to be
constant. The activity coefficient of the solute
was calculated from the Peng-Robinson EoS
with kij=0.07.<P>
Since the model to describe the phase
behavior of asymmetric systems is aiming for the
description of multicomponent mixtures the data
base is now extended to ternary mixtures with
the emphasizes on the possible formation of
mixed crystals.<P>

