<HEAD><TITLE>Fluid multiphase behaviour of certain ternary mixtures</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Fluid multiphase behaviour of certain ternary mixtures</H2>

<B>Ph.D.-student:</B> <I>Dipl.-Ing. K. Gauter</I> / tel.: **31 015 782118<BR>
Laboratory of Applied Thermodynamics and Phase Equilibria, Delft Technical University
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

Near-critical phenomena become more and
more important for chemical process
engineering. For example, supercritical
distillation is an already applied separation
technique. Therefore, knowledge of near-
critical phase behaviour of complex mixtures
is a prerequisite to investigate.<BR>
For binary mixtures, many investigations
have been made. Their phase behaviour has
been    classified by Scott and Van
Konynenburg [1]. Experimental results of
more complex mixtures are rare, even for
ternary systems already. In general, the phase
behaviour of complex mixtures cannot be
derived fully from binary data. Patton et. al.
[2] found for the ternary mixture (carbon
dioxide + tetradecane + decanol) in a certain
composition range a different kind of phase
behaviour than the both binary subsystems
(carbon dioxide + tetradecane) and (carbon
dioxide + decanol) would suggest.<BR>
Further investigations on ternairy systems
containing near-critical carbon dioxide have
been made in this project. The fluid phase
behaviour has been examined by measuring
critical end-point lines. Transitions of different
types of binary fluid phase behaviour into each
other were observed via ternary systems.
Coming from one binary subsystem, one solute
is gradually substituted by the other one until
the other binary subsystem is reached. The
mole fraction of the solvent (carbon dioxide)
is kept more or less constant.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><P>

Experiments were done, for example, for
some mixtures (carbon dioxide + o-nitrophenol + n-alkanol). Here the results for
the system with heptanol as the alcohol are
shown. The results are shown in a T,x<SUP>*</SUP><SUB>NP</SUB>-diagram, where x<SUP>*</SUP><SUB>NP</SUB> is the mole fraction of
nitrophenol on a carbon dioxide-free basis.<BR>
All measurements are done with the so-called
Cailletet-apparatus. With this equipment phase
transitions can be
observed visually
at fixed overall
composition.
For comparison,
Patton et. al. [2]
found a dosed
loop of critical
end-points inside
the three phase
region of the system (carbon dioxide +
tetradecane + decanol).<P>

<IMG SRC="gauter1.gif"><P>

<B>Conclusions</B><P>

The phase behaviour of the ternary mixture
(carbon dioxide + tetradecane + decanol)
observed by Patton et. al. [2] seems to be a
general phenomenon. For (carbon dioxide + o-nitrophenol + heptanol) nearly the same
qualitative results were found. Differences are
due to the different types fluid phase
behaviour of the binary subsystems (carbon
dioxide + tetradecane) and (carbon dioxide +
o-nitrophenol).<BR>
In addition, in nitrophenol-systems a solid
phase occurs at lower temperatures.
Therefore, the line of critical end-points going
to these low temperatures cannot be measured
further. For consistency 0f the theory, this line
should continue to one of the axis. Since the
visible part of it bends into the direction of the
axis x<SUP>*</SUP><SUB>NP</SUB>=1, the line can be expected to end on
this axis. Considering only fluid phase behaviour, this means that the binary system (carbon dioxide + o-nitrophenol) should have a
third critical end-point, which is hidden under
a solid phase (type IV instead of type V).<BR>
Since types I and V fluid phase behaviour
cause inconsistencies in the transformation
schemes with other types, further research will
focus on this aspect.<P>

1 Scott, R. L. and Van Konynenburg, P. H., 1970,
Discuss. Faraday Soc., 49:87-97<BR>
2 Patton, C. L., Kisler, S. H. and Luks, K. D., 1993,
ACS Symposium Series No. 514, 55-56<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
