<HEAD><TITLE>Thermodynamics of lactic acid for process design and application</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Thermodynamics of lactic acid for process design and application</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. George P. van Lieshout<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Purac (Gorinchem, The Netherlands)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Understanding the phase behaviour of
chemical species is very important in
process design. Sizes and thus investment
costs of separation equipment depend
directly on the position of the phase
equilibria of the mixtures to be separated.
If one of the species in the mixture is a
reactive compound, both chemical and
thermodynamical behaviour must be
taken into account simultaneously.<P>

<B>Components in aqueous lactic acid
solutions</B><BR>
Lactic acid is, when pure, a white crystalline solid with a melting point of
53 &#176;C. When it is molten or dissolved in
water, it starts to react, and intermolecular esters are being formed.<P>

<IMG SRC="lieshout1.gif"><P>

The mean degree of polymerization of
lactic acid will change as a result of the
reactions occuring. The ester formation
proceeds until equilibrium has been
reached.<P>

<IMG SRC="lieshout2.gif"><P>

<I>Mean degree of polymerization (n) of
Aqueous Lactic Acid in Equilibrium</I><P>

<B>Liquid-Liquid Equilibria</B><BR>
The influence of the degree of polymerization of lactic acid on the liquid-liquid equilibria of water-organic solvent-lactic acid systems has been investigated.<P>

The distribution coefficient of lactic acid
between a water layer and a solvent layer
is defined as:<P>

<IMG SRC="lieshout3.gif"><P>

<I>Influence of the degree of polymerization
(n) on the distribution coefficient K</I><P>

<IMG SRC="lieshout4.gif"><P>

<I>Influence of the degree of polymerization
(n) on the miscibility gap in water-organic solvent-lactic acid systems</I><P>

