<HEAD><TITLE>Prediction of the phase behaviour of oil + water + surfactant systems under the influence of temperature and pressure</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Prediction of the phase behaviour of oil + water + surfactant systems under the influence of temperature and pressure</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> E. S. J. Rudolph<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Shell Exploration and Production, Rijskwijk<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Experiments have shown that besides
the temperature also the pressure influences
the phase behaviour of oil + water + surfactant
systems.<P>

<B>Objective</B><BR>
The goal of the project is to develop a
model which is able to predict the
experimentally found phase behaviour as a
function of the temperature and the pressure.<P>

<B>Background</B><BR>
The temperature and the pressure
influence not only the macroscopic phase
behaviour but also the structures of the
agglomerates which are found in the different
phases.<BR>
A model for the description of the
global phase behaviour has to combine the
global and structural behaviour.<P>

<IMG SRC="rudolph1.gif"><P>

<B>Theory</B><BR>
The model of Safran et al. [1] is used
as a base for the description of the global
phase behaviour of oil + water + surfactant
systems.<BR>
The model follows the so-called bending
energy approach. The phase equilibrium is
determined by minimizing the Gibbs free
energy which consists of a mixing entropy and
a bending energy contribution. The latter
describes the energy cost of the bending of the
surfactant layer which is responsible for the
structures found in microemulsions.<BR>
The pressure and temperature
influence is incorporated into the model by the
change of the characteristic properties like the
spontaneous curvature, the rigidity, and the
saddle-splay cosntant. Further, the
'distribution' of the surfactant over the water
and oil micro-phases is depending on the
temperature and the pressure.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
Different g<SUP>E</SUP>-models and equation of
states were used to describe the 'distribution'
of the surfactant with changing temperature
and pressure. The predicted phase behaviour
shows the right qualitative dependence on the
temperature and the pressure.<P>

<IMG SRC="rudolph2.gif"><P>

Experiments were performed to
determine the spontaneous curvature with
changing temperature and pressure.<P>

[1] S.A. Safran, D. Andelman, M.E. Cates, D. Roux;
J. Chem. Phys. 87 (12), 1987<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
