<HEAD><TITLE>The phase behaviour and modelling of aqueous electrolyte systems at near- and supercritical conditions</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>The phase behaviour and modelling of aqueous electrolyte systems at near- and supercritical conditions</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> ir Peter Jan Smits (+31 15 2782118)<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> NWO/SON<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>INTRODUCTION</B><P>

The thermodynamic properties of near-critical and
supercritical aqueous systems are of great importance in
many chemical and reservoir engineering applications, such as
supercritical water oxidation processes, hydrothermal
conversion of biomass, and steampower generation. Aqueous
systems at high pressures and temperatures are also
encountered in many geological processes.<P>

<B>OBJECTIVES</B><P>

The aim of this project is to develop an equation of
state based on the Associated-Perturbed-Anisotropic-Chain-
Theory (APACT) to explore the modelling of the fluid phase
behaviour of binary and ternary mixtures in which polar and
hydrogen bonding components and salts may be present. The
equation of state should be usable in the near-critical and
supercritical region of the solvent (water), The advantage of
equations of state based on statistical mechanics over the
ones currently in use in industry, is that different types of
molecular interactions can be taken into account explicitly
(e.g., hydrogen bonding).<BR>
After a literature search had shown that there are
hardly any experimental data to test our model, it was decided
to start a series of experiments to investigate the fluid phase
behaviour of systems with the characteristics mentioned
before. Experimental work on the phase behaviour of mixtures
comprising H<SUB>2</SUB>0, NaCl and either CF<SUB>4</SUB> or CClF<SUB>3</SUB> is currently in
progress.<P>

<B>RESULTS</B><P>

PVT calculations for pure water using APACT have
been performed over a large range of pressure and
temperature. The agreement between experimental data and
calculations is very satisfactory. The next figure shows a
graphical representation of some selected calculated
isotherms.<P>

<IMG SRC="smits1.gif"><P>

The extent of hydrogen bonding in water has been
modelled as a function of temperature and pressure. The
results have been compared with results obtained using
equations of state in which the phenomenon of hydrogen
bonding is taken into account in a different way. In
comparison with these alternative predictions (no reliable
experimental data are available), it appears that APACT
slightly overpredicts the extent of hydrogen bonding, as can
be seen from the following figure.<P>

<IMG SRC="smits1.gif"><P>

Vapour-liquid equilibrium calculations have been
performed for the binary systems H<SUB>2</SUB>O/CH<SUB>4</SUB> and H<SUB>2</SUB>O/C<SUB>2</SUB>H<SUB>6</SUB> over
large ranges of pressure and temperature, The agreement
between experimental data and calculations is satisfactory,
Some selected results are shown in the following figure.<P>

<IMG SRC="smits3.gif"><P>

In addition, APACT has been modified for the
treatment of mixtures of water and non-dissociated NaCl. In
the near future, phase equilibrium calculations for the system
H<SUB>2</SUB>O/CH<SUB>4</SUB>/NaCl will be performed using a modified APACT.<P>

<B>LITERATURE</B><P>

Sinits, P.J.; Economou, I.G.; Peters, C.J.; De Swaan
Arons, J. <I>J. Phys. Chem.</I> 1994, 98, 12080.<BR>
Economou, I.G.; Peters, C.J.; De Swaan Arons, J. <I>J. Phys.
Chem</I>. 1995, 6182.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
