<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Enzymatic reactions in near-critical fluids</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Enzymatic reactions in near-critical fluids</H2>

<B>Ph.D.-student:</B> Ir Rob M.M. Stevens<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Delft University of Technology<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
For performing enzymatic reactions in
near-critical fluids a lot of information
besides the enzyme- and reactor-kinetics in
near-critical fluids should be known. One
tool to provide this information is
thermodynamics. Therefore the research
project focuses on integrating three
disciplines: Thermodynamics, Enzymology
and Reactor-engineering.<P>

<IMG SRC="stevens1.gif"><P>

<B>Reaction engineering and enzymology</B><BR>
The kinetics of an enzymatic reaction in
near-critical carbon-dioxide are compared
with the kinetics in an organic solvent. The
comparison is based on a combination of
conventional kinetics and thermodynamics.
Thermodynamics provides tools to describe
the influence of pressure, temperature,
solvent and water activity on the enzyme's
activity. By modelling the enzyme's kinetic
parameters with thermodynamic activities
instead of concentrations, the solvent
influence is described.<P>

<B>Thermodynamics</B><BR>
Thermodynamics also provides all the
information on the dependency of the
solubility data and vapour-liquid equilibria
of multi-component systems containing
CO<SUB>2</SUB> and bio-molecules on pressure and
temperature. This dependency should be
known, before any conclusions can be
drawn from the influence of P and T on the
enzyme and the chemical reaction
equilibrium. The solubility of the low-
volatile bio-molecules in carbon dioxide is
measured in a (semi-)continuous flow-
apparatus. Both the composition of the
vapour- and the liquid phase can be
determined. An Equation of State with G<SUP>E</SUP> -
mixing rules will be used to model the
phase-behaviour.<P>

<B>Future aspects</B><BR>
Before enzymatic reactions in combination
with near-critical extraction are applied in
industrial applications, a lot of
thermodynamic    information    (both
experiments as models) should be provided
on multi-component phase-equilibria in
combination with chemical reaction
equilibria.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
