<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Kinetic resolution in organic solvents</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Kinetic resolution in organic solvents</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> A. Wolff, M. Sc. ((015) 278 23 30)<BR>
<B>Promotor:</B> Prof. dr.ir. J.J. Heijnen<BR>
<B>Supervisors:</B> Dr.ir. A.J.J. Straathof ((015) 278 23 30), Dr.ir. J.A. Jongejan ((015) 278 23 71)<BR>
<B>Institute:</B> Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> January 1993 - January 1997<BR>
<B>Financed by:</B> Netherlands Foundation for Chemical Research (SON, procestechnologie)<BR>
<B>OSPT:</B> BSDL-sector: Industrial Biotechnology - bioprocess development<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

In enzymatic kinetic resolution reactions the enzyme converts one of the two substrate
enantiomers in a racemic mixture, leaving the other in an enantiopure form. This is one of the
most important methods to obtain pharmaceuticals and agrochemicals that are not contaminated
with the "wrong" enantiomer. The wrong enantiomer will be inactive (but not harmless from an
environmental point of view) or causing undesirable side effects.<BR>
Many examples are known of enzymatic kinetic resolution reactions which are carded out in
organic solvents; enzymes have been shown to be active not only in aqueous solution but (at the
proper conditions) also in organic solvents. These solvents may be required when the substrates
or products show a low aqueous solubility or when a hydrolysis reaction is to be reversed.
So far the choice of the organic solvent has been empirical or based on the enzyme stability or
reaction equilibrium. For kinetic resolution, however, the ratio of reaction rates of the
enantiomers is of prime importance. In this project kinetic models of enzymatic reactions in
organic solvents will be set up and applied to optimize kinetic resolution processes for interesting
compounds. Questions to be answered are: Which organic solvent? Which type of reactor?
Which process variables have to be controlled?<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The aim of this research project is to develop kinetic models for enantioselective enzymatic
reactions in organic solvents and to use these models for process development.<P>

<B>Results and current research</B><BR>
Experimental systems to study a suitable enzymatic kinetic resolution and an asymmetric
hydrolysis reaction have been developed. The methods to determine the enzymatic
enantioselectivity have been improved.<BR>
A theory, which relates the enzymatic activity and enantioselectivity to the thermodynamic
activity of the solute in different solvents, correctly explains the experimental data that have been
obtained so far.<BR>
Because there seem to be no clear advantages in the addition of cosolvents for the asymmetric
hydrolysis of particular esters with a low water-solubility, a suspension process is being
developed.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
