<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Enzymatic hydrolysis in organic solvent</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Enzymatic hydrolysis in organic solvent</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. M.J.J. Litjens ((015) 278 23 30)<BR>
<B>Promotor:</B> Prof. dr.ir. J.J. Heijnen<BR>
<B>Supervisors:</B> Dr.ir. A.J.J. Straathof ((015) 278 23 30)<BR>
<B>Institute:</B> Delft Unversity of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> October 1995 - October 1999<BR>
<B>Financed by:</B> Strategic Progranune ABON/Min. Econ. Affairs<BR>
<B>BSDL-sector:</B> Industrial Biotechnology - bioprocess development<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

Enzymatic hydrolysis of esters is being applied widely, a.o. in the area of production of chiral
compounds. Usually the processes are carded out in a multi-purpose stirred tank. Most esters are
ill-soluble in water. Therefore hydrolysis is often carried out in a water - organic solvent
biphasic system. Enzymes, in particular lipases, are well-suited for ester hydrolysis. When
immobilized enzymes are used the number of phases is three, whereas the performance of the
reactor would be simpler with only two phases. The water phase may be left out. In conventional
processes it is being used as: 1. reservoir for the reaction water; 2. driving force for reaction
kinetics and -equilibrium; 3. product reservoir.<BR>
Ad 1: Reaction water can be fed to the reactor according to the requirements, without forming a
water phase. Ad 2: The kinetics and the equilibrium of the reaction are (a.o.) determined by the
thermodynamic activity of water, which has a fixed value in a water-saturated solvent. The
amount of water in the system does not matter. Ad 3: The product (the carboxylic acid or the
alcohol) sometimes preferentially is obtained by downstream processing of an organic phase
instead of a water phase, e.g. when the separation from water is troublesome (glycidol, 2,3-butanediol) or when it is unstable in water (glycidol).<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The aim of this research project is to show that ester hydrolysis without a separate water phase is
a feasible process when, e.g., trimethyl amine is used as the base:<P>

R<SUP>1</SUP>-CO-O-R<SUP>2</SUP> + H<SUB>2</SUB>0 + NMe<SUB>3</SUB> --~ R<SUP>1</SUP>-CO-OH.NMe<SUB>3</SUB> + R<SUP>2</SUP>OH<P>

The ion-pair of carboxylic acid and amine may be separated easily from the organic solvent by
precipitation. Subsequent evaporation of the triethylamine by heating of the ion-pair may allow
recycling of the amine. When immobilized enzyme is being used, the number of waste streams
will thus be reduced when compared to conventional processes.<P>

<B>Results and current research</B><BR>
This project will start in October 1995.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
