<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Process design for integrated phosphorus and nitrogen removal from waste water</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Process design for integrated phosphorus and nitrogen removal from waste water</H2>

<B>Post-doc:</B> Takahiro Kuba ((015) 278 15 51)<BR>
<B>Supervisors:</B> Dr.ir. Mark C.M. van Loosdrecht ((015) 278 16 18), Prof. dr.ir. J.J. Heijnen ((015) 278 23 41)<BR>
<B>Institute:</B> Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> January 1993 - January 1996<BR>
<B>Financed by:</B> STOWA, NOVEM<BR>
<B>BSDL-sector:</B> Environmental Biotechnology - N/P-removal<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

Phosphorus and nitrogen have to be removed from waste water, because these substances induce
eutrophication of closed water areas. In conventional waste water treatment processes by
activated sludge, a problem is the interference between P and N removing bacteria. For both P
and N removal processes organic carbon is required. In municipal waste water organic carbon is
not enough for P and N removal. Therefore in practice, sometimes carbon sources are added to
the waste water to establish complete P and N removal. In our previous research it has been
shown that it is possible to accumulate denitrifying P-removing bacteria (DPB) which can
remove simultaneously P and N. The bacteria have high potential for P and N removal in
comparison with ordinary P- or N-removing bacteria. This type of bacteria reduces the
requirement of carbon source making addition of extra carbon source to the treatment process is
not necessary.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
This project is aimed at developing a process based on the simultaneous P and N removal by
DPB. The studies are carried out in laboratory scale sequencing batch reactors (SBRs) in which
the bacteria undergo different environmental conditions; anaerobic, anoxic, settling period and so
on. The research is done using synthetic waste water and enrichment cultures of DPB.<P>

<B>Results & current research</B><BR>
To obtain nitrate as an electron acceptor for DPB, nitrification should be introduced into the
system. The systems with the nitrification process can be divided into two types; (1) single
sludge processes: DPB coexist with nitrifiers, and
all of the sludge goes through all stages such as
anaerobic, aerobic and anoxic phases, (2) two
sludge processes: DPB are separated from
nitrifiers, for instance, combination with a
nitrification SBR (Figure). Current results and
research topics are:<BR>
(1) It has been found that DPB already
occur to a large extent in a real fewage treatment
plant of the 1-sludge modified UCP-type (Holten).<BR>
(2) Integration of nitrification and denitrifying P-removal
in the two sludge system has been succesfully at labscale.<BR>
(3) Formulation of a process model of denitrifying
dephosphatation for process design and control
purposes has started.<BR>
(4) Effect of the cycle time on
the phosphorus removal process is under investigation<P>

<IMG SRC="kuba1.gif"><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
