<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>The use of artificial intelligence techniques for the control of fermentation processes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>The use of artificial intelligence techniques for the control of fermentation processes</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. H.J.L. van Can ((015) 278 50 25)<BR>
<B>Promotors:</B> Prof. ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben, Prof. dr.ir. J.J. Heijnen<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Ir. C. Hellinga ((015) 278 50 25)<BR>
<B>Institute:</B> Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> October 1992 - October 1996<BR>
<B>Financed by:</B> Delft University of Technology<BR>
<B>OSPT</B> BSDL-sector: Industrial Biotechnology - bioprocess development<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

Models can be very useful for the optimisation and control of biotechnological processes.
Accurate, white box models based on knowledge of the process are usually not available. The
development of such models is severely hindered by:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>the complexity of the bioconversion
<LI>the nonlinear characteristics of the process
<LI>batch and fed-batch way of operating the process
<LI>changing process characteristics
<LI>the necessity of many time consuming experiments in order to determine the parameters of the model
</UL>

Therefore, it is usually not possible to develop accurate white box models in a reasonable
amount of time. Nonlinear black box techniques like neural networks and fuzzy logic are
inherent nonlinear and do not need an a priori model structure. These black box techniques are
therefore potentially very suited to deal with the above mentioned problems.<P>

<B>Aim</B><BR>
In this project nonlinear black box modelling techniques are used for the optimisation and
control of biotechnological processes. Apart from purely black box models, attention will be paid
to the combination of black box models and first principles models. The aim of this project is to
develop a method, which makes it possible to build a model of a process within a reasonable
amount of time and with a limited amount of experiments.<P>

<B>Research topics</B><BR>
A model predictive controller based a neural network was developed and tested for the control of
the pressure in a fermenter. Future research will focus on the optimisation and control of the
enzymatic conversion of Penicillin G, using black box techniques.<BR>
This project is carried out in close cooperation with the Control Laboratory of the Faculty of
Electrical Engineering.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
