<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Control of waste water treatment plants</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Control of waste water treatment plants</H2>

<B>Researcher:</B> Ir. C. Hellinga ((015) 278 50 25)<BR>
<B>Promotor:</B> Prof. dr.ir. J.J. Heijnen, Prof. ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Dr.ir. M.C.M. van Loosdrecht ((015) 278 16 18), Prof. ir. H.B. Verbruggen (Fac. of Electrical Engineering, DUT)<BR>
<B>Institute:</B> Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> April 1995 - April 1999<BR>
<B>Financed by:</B> DUT<BR>
<B>BSDL-sector:</B> Environmental Biotechnology - control<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

Municipal waste water treatment plants almost invariably use activated sludge to remove or
convert organic matter from the city's waste streams. The main objectives for controlling such
plants are 1) to get maximum purification at minimum costs -energy and/or chemical additions-
(short term goal) and 2) maintaining the relevant microbial populations inside the plant (long
term goal). To deal with the large fluctuations in the influent-composition and flow rate with
varying microbial activity, the plants are commonly considerably overdimensioned. This reduces
the need for complex control schemes to reach these goals. However, with increasing stricter
legislations for the effluent composition, new investments for plant extensions, or better
measurement and control strategies are becoming necessary. Because improved control will
often be the cheaper alternative, there is a world-wide attention for new developments in this
area.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
This project will focus on two items:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>improving the observability of the dynamical behaviour waste water treatment plants by
using off-gas analyses,
<LI>developing new control strategies based on modern modelling and control techniques
(Artificial Neural Networks, Fuzzy Control, Model Based Predictive Control)
<LI>Developing control strategics for the SHARON process
</UL>

<B>Results and current research</B><BR>
The project is currently (1995) in the start-up phase. Gas phase measurements (oxygen and
carbon dioxide) will be carried out in a large (450.000 p.e.) underground waste water treatment
plant in Rotterdam. Recent research results in the area of Artificial Neural Networks and Model
Based Predictive Control, will be used for this application. Contacts with the leading German
IFAK software company (SIMBA) have been established for model and software development.
For the SHARON process a model structure has been established and validated, which describes
nitrification/denitrification as a function of environmental conditions (pH, NH<SUP>4+</SUP>, NO<SUB>2</SUB><SUP>-</SUP>, O<SUB>2</SUB>,
methanol). Currently a control procedure is set-up to achieve optimal feeding patterns of waste
water and methanol.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
