<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Three phase suspension reactors</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Three phase suspension reactors</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. Marc H. van der Jagt ((015) 278 10 06)<BR>
<B>Promotor:</B> Prof. ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Dr.ir. R.G.J.M. van der Lans ((015) 278 10 06)<BR>
<B>Institute:</B> Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> 1992 - 1996<BR>
<B>Financed by:</B> Ministry of Economic Affairs (IOP-MBT)<BR>
<B>OSPT</B> BSDL-sector: Industrial Biotechnology - bioprocess design<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

The background of the research was the successful development of a wet soil cleaning reactor
(picture). Basically the tapered formed reactor integrates a classification of coarse relatively
slight polluted fractions like sand and fines as well as biological treatment of the fines.
Essential for the process economics at full scale is the energy which is needed to attain a state of
suspension. Suspending particles is the limiting part of the process.<P>
The research aims at the development of a model which relates the power necessary to establish
a suspension in pneumatically agitated multiphase systems and the characteristics of a suspension
such as particle concentration and concentration distributions. The reactor serves as a model
validation tool.<P>

<B>Theory</B><BR>
In our view three mechanisms play a role in the
particles distribution. Sedimentation on one
hand is counteracted by particle entrainment
by the liquid flow and turbulent dispersion due
to the same flow on the other. In very densely
concentrated systems there is not really a
separate liquid and solids phase but one
pseudo monophase with its hydrodynamic
properties determined by the solids fraction.
As a result in such a system dispersion is
dominating and determines the concentration.<P>

<IMG SRC="jagt1.gif"><P>

Dually Injected Turbulent Separation Reactor<P>

<B>Present state of the research and future</B><BR>
Since the model parameters are flows and
particle concentrations verification is done by reasonably simple physical measurements with
electromagnetic and optical probes.<BR>
One of the results is that the solids dispersion coefficient in multiphase systems is not equal to
that of the liquid and furthermore it is not a constant but varies locally because of a local
changes in turbulence. Besides the experiments carried out in the described reactor multiphase
behaviour is investigated in bubble columns. For that purpose a bubble column was constructed
with variable air and recirculation water injection possibilities. Next on the programme are
polydisperse measurements with basalt and sand in the column equipped with a conical sparger.
It will be done to explore operation limits and in order to link the results in the described
tapered reactor with bubble column literature and the own findings.<P>


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

