<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Regime analysis of fungal fermentations</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Regime analysis of fungal fermentations</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Cui Yi Qing, MSc ((015) 278 23 63)<BR>
<B>Promotor:</B> Prof. ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Dr. ir. Rob G.J.M. van der Lans ((015) 278 10 06)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> September 1992 - September 1996<BR>
<B>Institute:</B> Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
<B>Financed by:</B> Unilever<BR>
<B>BSDL-sector:</B> Industrial Biotechnology - metabolic pathway engineering<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

Fungal fermentation is an important industrial process. Its scaling-up from laboratory to
production scale may influence not only the biomass growth but also its morphology which is
often controlled as a prerequisite for industrial application. Mycelial morphology in submerged
fermentations is usually classified as one of two extremes: individual filamentous mycelia, giving
highly viscous and pseudoplastic fermentation broths, and dense, spherical colonies called pellets,
probably having internal mass transfer limitation.<P>

<IMG SRC="qing1.gif"><P>

Hydrodynamic conditions, fungal
morphology, fungle growth, and
formation and secretion of the products
are related to each other and their
interaction is are very sensitive in scale.
It is almost impossible to keep the same
hydrodynamic conditions in the
bioreactors at different scales. Therefore, it becomes important to investigate the scale-up of
fungal fermentation in order to control the morphology and growth in the industrial process.<P>

<B>Aim, scope and set-up of research</B><BR>
The objective of this project is to develop a method for the rapid scale-up of fungal fermentation
processes from laboratory or pilot plant scale to production one. For this purpose, the following
research topics are focused on in this project.<P>

<UL>
<LI>
<I><LI>Process and regime analysis of fungal fermentation.
<LI>Fungal fermentation in synthetic medium
<LI>Fungal fermentation in complex medium
<LI>Relation between fungal morphology and growth
<LI>Simulation and scale-down</I>
<UL>
<LI>mechanical force effect on morphology and growth.
<LI>effects of other subprocesses (such as oxygen transfer and mixing) on fungal fermentation
</UL>
<I><LI>Oxygen transfer and consumption in multi-phase systems
<LI>Mixing behaviour of industrial fermenters
<LI>Power dissipation in bioreactor
<LI>Mechanical force quantification
<LI>Modelling fungal fermentation process
<LI>Development of method for scale-up</I>
</UL>
Fermentation of <I>Aspergillus awamori</I> in a stirred bioreactor with an industrial solid substrate is
used as a model system.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
