<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Scale-up of centrifugal partition chromatography</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Scale-up of centrifugal partition chromatography</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. M.J. van Buel ((015) 278 23 61)<BR>
<B>Promotor:</B> Prof. ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Ir. L.A.M. van der Wielen ((015) 278 23 61)<BR>
<B>Institute:</B> Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> August 1992 - August 1996<BR>
<B>Financed by:</B> DUT<BR>
<B>BSDL-sector:</B> Industrial Biotechnology - bioprocess development<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

Centrifugal Partition Chromatography (CPC) is a batch-separation technique in which the
separation mechanism is based on the difference in distribution of components over two
immiscible liquid phases. A CPC-column consists of several cartridges in which channels are
engraved, attached to a rotor. The less dense stationary phase is kept in the column by means of
a centrifugal field which exploits the density difference with the mobile phase, while the mobile
phase flows through the stationary phase. Components introduced as a mixture into the mobile
phase, distribute differently over the two phases, and consequently leave the column separated.
Due to the moderate separation conditions, sensitive compounds such as proteins can also be
separated without deterioration. A variety of liquid two-phase systems is available, ranging from
organic solvents to aqueous two-phase systems, which makes it possible to fine-tone the column
filling for a specific component. Hence, CPC has a number of advantages over classic
chromatographic separation methods. CPC therefore can be a promising alternative to
conventional preparative chromatographic methods.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The aim of this project is to develop a model for CPC that allows prediction of the separation
behavior. The model will be used as a basis for scale-up and improvements of CPC. Important
phenomena for modelling of CPC are the hydrodynamics of the liquid flow through the
channels, and the mass transfer in the biphasic system.<P>

<IMG SRC="buel1.gif"><P>

<B>Results & current research</B><BR>
Two simple models have been developed for CPC
separations. Important parameters in these models are
the partition coefficients of the components over the
two phases and the mass transfer coefficients. The
influence of the process variables such as flow rate,
rotational frequency and type of phase system on the
model parameters is investigated. Further work will be
done on the separation of components which are
difficult to separate by conventional methods such as
diastereomers. Future work will consist of separations
under non-linear conditions (overloading of the column
or carrier enhanced separations) and optimisation of the
column geometry.<P>

This project is performed in close collaboration with the section Pharmacognosy (group
Verpoorte) of Leiden University and with various industrial partners.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
