<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Thermodynamics of biomolecules in separation processes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Thermodynamics of biomolecules in separation processes</H2>

<B>Post-doc:</B> Dr. M. Gude ((015) 278 21251)<BR>
<B>Promotor:</B> Prof. Ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Ir. L.A.M. van der Wielen ((015) 278 23 61)<BR>
<B>Institute:</B> Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> January 1994 - June 1995<BR>
<B>Financed by:</B> EU Human Capital and Mobility programme<BR>
<B>BSDL-sector:</B> Industrial Biotechnology - bioprocess development<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

For biochemical processes, knowledge of the solubility and partitioning behavior of biomolecules
is of particular importance to the design of extraction and crystallisation equipment. In this work,
the phase behavior of alpha-amino acids in mixtures of water and aliphatic alkanols was modelled.
The goal of this work was (1) to develop a simple model which allows the correlation of
partition coefficients and mixed-solvent solubilities of amino acids in aqueous mixtures of
organic solvents and (2) additionally provides a framework for their prediction in solvent
systems in which no experimental data for these quantities are available.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
A convenient thermodynamic formulation using a simple
excess Gibbs energy expression was used to model the
solubilities and partition coefficients of amino acids in
aqueous alkanol solutions. Making use of readily available
binary information, the model contains a single, solute
specific, ternary interaction parameter which can be related
to hydrophobicity scales of amino acid side-chain moieties
reported in the literature. As illustrated in the figures below,
the solubilities of amino acids in aqueous ethanol (Figure 1)
and isomeric propanol solutions and their 1-butanol/water
partition coefficients (Figure 2) were correlated successfully with the model.<P>

<IMG SRC="gude1.gif"><P>
<IMG SRC="gude2.gif"><P>

Using only the interaction parameters obtained from lower
alkanol water systems, the partition coefficients of amino
acids in the important 1-octanol/water system were
accurately predicted from the model. Additionally, the
partition coefficients of amino acids in multicomponent
solvent systems, such as the ternary solvent systems water + ethanol + 1-butanol and water + methanol + 1-octanol can
be estimated from the model.<P>

<B>Current research and future work</B><BR>

Experimental and theoretical work has been initiated to
study the influence of pH, temperature and the presence of solutes, such as other amino acids or
salts, on the phase behavior of amino acids in aqueous mixtures of organic solvents. Once these
important features are understood and incorporated into the model it will be applied to the
modelling of the phase behavior of more complex molecules, such as peptides, antibiotics, or
drugs. This project is performed in close collaboration with the section Pharmacognosy (group
Verpoorte) of Leiden University and with various industrial partners.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
