<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Compact centrifugal adsorption technology (CAT-technology)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Compact centrifugal adsorption technology (CAT-technology)</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. M.A.T. Bisschops ((015) 278 21 51)<BR>
<B>Promotor:</B> Prof. ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Ir. L.A.M. van der Wielen ((015) 278 23 61)<BR>
<B>Institute:</B> Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> December 1993 - December 1997<BR>
<B>Financed by:</B> IOP Milieutechnologie - Preventie<BR>
<B>OSPT</B> BSDL-sector: Industrial Biotechnology - bioprocess development<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

Adsorption is an attractive method for separating low concentrated components from large
aqueous streams. It can thus be applied in the recovery of products and in the purification of
waste water. However conventional adsorption equipment usualy has the disadvantage of being
voluminous and sometimes yields large pressure drops. A much more efficient mass transfer
process can be obtained by applying very small adsorbent particles in counterflow with the
liquid. However gravity does not yield satisfactory sedimentation rates for obtaining
countercurrent flow. Therefore a centrifugal force has to be applied.<BR>
Some of the advantages of very compact adsorption equipment are:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>small space requirements allow the application on sites with lack of space
<LI>small resin inventory saves investments costs and allows the application of more expensive,
more selective adsorbents
<LI>short contact times between the phases can reduce product degradation, which often occurs
in the recovery of sensitive biotechnological products from aggressive media
</UL>
Furthermore it is advantageous if adsorption processes are not sensitive to fouling, do not yield
high pressure drops and are flexible in capacity and type of adsorbent.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The aim of this project is to develop a technology, in which micro-adsorbents (particle diameter
in the range of micrometers) can be applied in countercurrent flow with the liquid. Although the
technology shows some analogies with countercurrent centrifugal extraction, a well established
separation process, specific centrifugal adsorption equipment has to be designed. Important
phenomena in such a two-phase system are the hydrodynamics, mass transfer and process
dynamics.<P>

<B>Results and current research</B><BR>
An experimental setup has been constructed
for studies in moderate centrifugal fields (up
to 30 g). The influence of several variables
on the hydrodynamics will be investigated in
this unit. Furthermore a second centrifuge
will be designed for experiments in high
centrifugal fields (up to 10000 g). Future
work will concern (1) mass transfer kinetics
and adsorption equilibria, (2) process design,
scale-up and modelling, (3) process evaluation
under industrial conditions.<P>

<IMG SRC="bisschops1.gif">

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
