<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Integrated reaction and separation in centrifugal partitioning chromatography</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Integrated reaction and separation in centrifugal partitioning chromatography</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. M. Aarnink ((015) 278 51 23)<BR>
<B>Promotor:</B> Prof. ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Ir. L.A.M. van der Wielen ((015) 278 23261)<BR>
<B>Institute:</B> Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> April 1994 - April 1998<BR>
<B>Financed by:</B> Research School Process Technology (OSPT)/Min. Econ. Affairs<BR>
<B>OSPT</B> BSDL-sector: Industrial Biotechnology - bioprocess development<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

The integration of reaction and separation may have several advantages over separate reaction
with subsequent purification or isolation of the product. The potential advantages are:<BR>
</UL>
<LI>improved yields,
<LI>improved purity,
<LI>decreased number of units of operation,
<LI>decreased total working volume
</UL>
Centrifugal Partition Chromatography (CPC) is a novel chromatographic method which looks
promising also for performing integrated reaction and separation. In a CPC two immiscible
liquids, a mobile and a stationary phase, are brought into contact. Due to the special internal
geometry of the CPC-device, a theoretical number of plates can be achieved varying from
several hundreds to thousands in a relative modest volume (< 1 Liter).<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The objective of this project is to demonstrate the capability of CPC as a unit operation in the
field of integrated reaction and separation.<P>

<B>Results and current research</B><BR>
Attention is drawn towards the use of aqueous two phase systems (ATPS) as reaction media
because of the Bio-compatibility of these systems. Current research focuses on the use of PEG-salt-water systems with low polymer length (Mw < 10000). Initial experiments will be performed
on the hydrodynamic stability of
such systems including measurement
of their viscosity. The production of
chiral amino acids via enantioselective enzymatic hydrolysis of
acylated amino acids is a relevant
model system, other model systems
are under consideration.<P>

<IMG SRC="aarnink1.gif"><P>

This project is performed in close
collaboration with the section
Pharmacognosy (group Verpoorte) of
Leiden University and with various
industrial partners.<P>


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
