<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>More efficient process chromatography (MEP)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>More efficient process chromatography (MEP)</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Drs. J. Houwing ((015) 278 51 23)<BR>
<B>Promotor:</B> Prof. ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Ir. L.A.M. van der Wielen ((015) 278 23 61)<BR>
<B>Institute:</B> Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> April 1995 - April 1999<BR>
<B>Financed by:</B> IOP Milieutechnologie - Preventie<BR>
<B>BSDL-sector:</B> Industrial Biotechnology - bioprocess development<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

The purification of high value biotechnological products such as pharmaceuticals generally
requires multiple chromatographic separations. Design and optimization of cascades of
chromatographs of various type is a troublesome task. The unit operations as such are
fundamentally complex and optimization of each individual unit demands a compromise between
chromatographic performance (resolution, capacity) and environmental/economic considerations
(magnitude of eluent streams). An additional problem is the extremely short time for
development of separation process. Commercial constraints demand that the time interval
between (non-optimized) laboratory bench separations and the first preparative scale production
for clinical trials is kept to a minimum. FDA requirements and corresponding regulations do not
allow for technological optimization afterwards. Therefore, rapid process design and optimization
methods based on a biochemical engineering approach based on a minimum of information
(product and matrix characteristics) should assist in this stage.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The general objective is the enhancement of resolution and capacity and the reduction of eluent
streams by employing complex operation modes and feeding strategies. This concerns the
exploitation of non-linear effects such as displacement chromatography and gradient elution.
Complex feeding strategies are two-way/flow reversal, parametric pumping, simulated
countercurrent, recycle. The application of countercurrent and simulated moving bed
countercurrent systems for the separation of the peptides and proteins will be evaluated.<P>

<B>Current Research</B><BR>
Current research concerns the development of more 'transparent models', which contain the
essence of information required for the design and optimization of integrated, multi-step
processes but do not demand the computational efforts corresponding to rigorous, first principles
calculations.<P>

Within this project, the department closely collaborates with the Department of Technical
Chemistry (prof. J.A. Wesselingh) of Groningen University and with several Dutch industries in
the form of a Platform for Process-Chromatography.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
