<HEAD><TITLE>Volatile salts as clean auxiliary materials in bioseparation processes (VOLSALT-process)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Volatile salts as clean auxiliary materials in bioseparation processes (VOLSALT-process)</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> ir. M. van Berlo ((015) 278 23 61)<BR>
<B>Promotor:</B> Prof. ir. K.Ch.A.M. Luyben<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Ir. L.A.M. van der Wielen ((015) 278 23 61)<BR>
<B>Institute:</B> Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> July 1995 - July 1999<BR>
<B>Financed by:</B> Strategic Programme ABON/Min Economic Affairs<BR>
<B>BSDL-sector:</B> Industrial Biotechnology - bioprocess development<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

Salts are abundantly used as auxiliary materials in biotechnological processes such as
precipitation, aqueous two-phase extraction, and chromatography. Unfortunately, they are often
difficult to recycle and the development of alternative process concepts is required to meet
economic and legal constraints in the future.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The proposed research concerns the development of alternative processes with salts that are more
easily recycled than their conventional counterparts and which therefore are more
environmentally friendly. In the project a systematic evaluation takes place of process conditions
on the basis of fundamental knowledge, constraints of possible applications and the development
of suitable process equipment for this new technology. Some promising applications are
indicated schematically in the figure below.<P>

<CENTER>Applications of Volatile Auxilary Components</CENTER><BR>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="berlo1.gif"></CENTER><BR>

<B>Current research</B><BR>
The project involves the systematic evaluation of existing processes with substantial salt
production and development of feasible alternatives using the <B>VOLSALT</B>-concept. For a
systematic and generic process design, a thermodynamic description of the corresponding
complex multi-component systems containing electrolytes is being developed. Simultaneously, an
experimental set-up that allows equilibrium and kinetic measurements under pressure with
mixtures of CO<SUB>2</SUB> and NH<SUB>3</SUB> is currently being constructed. The research is performed in close
collaboration with the Dept. of Applied Thermodynamics and the Laboratory of Equipment for
the Process Industries (API) of Delft University of Technology.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
