<HEAD><TITLE>Design of a biofilm airlift suspension reactor for integrated nitrification and denitrification</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Design of a biofilm airlift suspension reactor for integrated nitrification and denitrification</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. Wim A.J. van Benthum ((015) 278 15 51)<BR>
<B>Promotor:</B> Prof. dr.ir. Sef J. Heijnen<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Dr.ir. Mark C.M. van Loosdrecht ((015) 278 16 18)<BR>
<B>Institute:</B> Delft University of Technology, Kluyver Laboratory for Biotechnology, Department of Biochemical Engineering<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> November 1993 - November 1997<BR>
<B>Financed by:</B> IOP-MT, DUT<BR>
<B>BSDL-sector:</B> Environmental Biotechnology - biofilms/N-removal

	
<HR SIZE=0>

In the near future complete nitrogen elimination from waste waters will be required. Complete
nitrogen removal requires the circulation of the waste water through aerobic and anaerobic zones.
For the oxidation of ammonium (nitrification) a reactor has been developed based on biofilms
formed on small carriers (d=0.3 mm). These carriers are kept in suspension in an airlift reactor.
This process has several advantages over the conventional flocculated sludge process:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>low sludge (biomass) production;
<LI>high volumetric conversion capacity due to high active biomass concentration (up to 30 g/l);
<LI>small area requirement (10% of conventional process);
<LI>sludge has a low growth rate, leading to good nitrification, even at low temperatures.
</UL>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
This project is aimed at integrating the denitrification process in a biofilm airlift suspension
reactor. Therefore an anoxic compartment has to be created in the reactor, with a large exchange
flow of waste water and biofilm particles between aerobic and anaerobic compartments. An
example (BASE reactor) is given in the figure below.<P>

<B>Research topics</B>
<UL>
<LI>Choice of an optimal reactor geometry. The central aspect will be a controllable and
reliable circulation between the compartments, with the possibility of up-scaling.
<LI>Hydrodynamic characterization of the BASE reactor (two and three phases).
<LI>Study of the effect of fluctuating aerobic/anoxic conditions on the (de)nitrification in
biofilms. This study must support the design of the residence time in and exchange rate
between both reactor compartments.
<LI>Setting-up a process and reactor model for the treatment process, with special emphasis on
scale-up and control of
the reactor.
<LI>Testing of the
designed system
for the nitrogen
elimination
capacity.
</UL>

<IMG SRC="benthum1.gif"><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
