<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Cell elongation effects on polyurethane foam aging</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Cell elongation effects on polyurethane foam aging</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Dipl. Phys. Klaus H. Brodt<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> dr. ir. Gerard C.J. Bart<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> May 1991 - November 1994<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Delft University of Technology<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>INTRODUCTION</B><P>

An important property of closed cell polyurethane foams as applied in thermal insulation is
their thermal aging behaviour. One of the governing parameters of the aging process is the
so-called geometrical factor. It is defined as the
ratio of the gas permeability of the foam and
of the solid polymer. Here the elongation effect on the geometrical factor will be outlined
for a truncated octahedron or tetrakaidecahedron model of a foam cell, see figure 1. This
model is considered as the best regular cell for
representing foam properties. With this cell
the complete space can be filled. Further each
cell has fourteen neighbours which is close to
the mean number of neighbours in a real foam.
With this model permeation in a direction not
equal to the main mass flow direction is also
important, the so-called staggering effect.<P>

<IMG SRC="klaus1.gif"><P>

<B>CALCULATED RESULTS</B><P>

When the model foam is elongated in one direction with factor epsilon, the cell dimensions perpendicular to the elongation direction are to be
multiplied by 1 / sqrt(epsilon) for three-dimensional foam
models. This in order to keep the cell volume
constant. Also we want to preserve the same
foam density after elongation. This means a recalculation of the constant membrane thickness
for each elongation.<BR>
These calculations are carried out for an elementary cell of the foam having the characteristic properties of the foam and bounded by
isobaric and no-flow surfaces. For the tetrakaidecahedron model the conductance is proportional to the sum of the conductances of the
different parallel connected membranes and finally corrected for the shape of the elongated
cell. The calculated results shown in figure 2,<P>

<IMG SRC="klaus2.gif"><P>

indicate that elongation effects can speed up aging considerably. In the tetrakaldecahedron the
hexagon membrane is oblique, so it contributes
to the mass flow. With elongation the hexagon
not only becomes thinner but also larger and
becomes the dominant factor in the elongation
effect on the geometrical factor.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
