<HEAD><TITLE>PhD-projects Delft</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Research Group Physical Technology<HR></H2>

<TT><PRE>
Delft University of Technology
Faculty of Applied Physics
Kramers Laboratorium voor Fysische Technologie
Prins Bernhardlaan 6
NL 2628 BW Delft

telephone: +31 (0)15 278 5000
fax:       +31 (0)15 278 2838
internet:  <A HREF="http://klft.tn.tudelft.nl:8080/index.html">http://klft.tn.tudelft.nl:8080/index.html</A>
</PRE></TT>

<HR>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../pic/home.gif"></A> PhD-projects Delft

<HR>

<H2 ALIGN=center>Delft University of Technology</H2>

<H2 ALIGN=center>Research Group 'Fysische Technologie'</H2>

<B>Permanent staff</B><BR>
Prof.dr.ir. H.E.A. van den Akker<SUP>*</SUP><BR>
Dr.ir. J.J. Derksen<SUP>*</SUP><BR>
Dr.ir. C.R. Kleijn<BR>
Dr. R.F. Mudde<P>

<B>Research Scientists</B><BR>
ir. R.A. Bakker<SUP>*</SUP><BR>
ir. J.S. Groen<SUP>*</SUP><BR>
ir. R.W. van den Berg<BR>
ir. M.G.D. Fokke<BR>
ir. A.J. Hoekstra<BR>
ir. K.J. Kuijlaars<BR>
ir. D. Lathouwers<BR>
ir. H.J.W.M. Legius<BR>
ir. M. Okkerse-Ruitenberg<SUP>*</SUP><BR>
ir. H. van Santen<BR>
ir. B.C.H. Venneker<BR>

<SUP>*</SUP> participating in OSPT<P>

<B>Research Themes</B><P>

<I>Fluid flow and transport phenomena in single-phase process equipment</I><P>

The group 'Fysische Technologie' is studying laminar and turbulent flow in process equipment such as stirred vessels, chemical vapour deposition reactors, and cyclones; in addition, mould filling by liquid metals is being investigated.<P>

While the ultimate interest of the group is in developing and optimising process equipment (with a view to flow behaviour based performance), in many cases it is of paramount importance to increase our understanding of flow phenomena and to improve both our computational and experimental techniques of studying them. The more detailed descriptions of turbulent swirling flows of turbulent free convection flows, and of flows with a free surface are very challenging research topics indeed. Particular attention is further paid to the non-linear dynamics of flows (such as precessing and periodic motions, flow excursions, and chaos-like phenomena).<P>

Generally, all research projects in this area comprise both an experimental and a computational component. Whereas 2-D Laser-Doppler Velocimetry (LDV) remains the favoured technique for measuring velocity fields in turbulent flows, Particle Image Velocimetry (PIV) is used increasingly: in particular for tracking fast phenomena during mould filling simulations with water. Laser-Induced Fluorescence is exploited for studying micromixing. These two latter techniques still require dedicated optical arrangements as well as the development of software for extensive data manipulations. Finally, correlation techniques are being developed for processing signals from optical and scintillation detectors. Many numerical computations are still done with the general purpose codes FLUENT and FLOW-3D; to an increasing extent own extensions to commercial codes or completely new codes are being written.<P>

<I>Multiphase flow in process equipment</I><P>

The main strive of the group 'Fysische Technologie' is to develop a comprehensive view on two-phase flow, based on continuum mechanics, that allows for a proper description of bubbling systems (bubble columns, fluidised beds, stirred vessels) with a view to scaling-up two-phase reactors and contactors for the chemical process industries. The dynamic behaviour of swarms of bubbles, both in liquids and in fluidised beds, is to be modelled confidently. The dynamic behaviour of two-phase flows in pipeline systems (with a view to pulsations and vibrations) is another challenging research topic. In some cases (stirred vessels and bubble columns), a more detailed understanding of two-phase flow behaviour is also looked for by means of computational methods.<P>

In addition, experimental techniques are developed, preferably non-intrusive ones, for gathering data in bubbling systems. These data concern local values of variables such as bubble velocities, bubble sizes, and bubble hold-up, under a wide variety of operational conditions. The experimental techniques comprise methods of processing signals obtained by optical, radiation, and pressure measurements, as well as imaging techniques.<P>

<I>Industrial cleaning</I><P>

Tank cleaning (ships, storage, chemical reactors). Paint removal by blasting. Ultrasonic cleaning.<P>

<B>Industrial Research</B><P>

Many projects received and receive support from industry: Shell, DSM, Unilever, Gist-brocades, Akzo, Biothane, Purac, Coberco, Toftejorg, etc.<BR>
Further support was received from VROM and Economische Zaken (IOP's), and from the EC (ESPRIT),<P>

