<HEAD><TITLE>Micromixing: application of a cylindrical stretched vortex model in a stirred tank reactor</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Micromixing: application of a cylindrical stretched vortex model in a stirred tank reactor</H2>

<CENTER>OiO: ir. Remko A. Bakker<BR>
Kramers Laboratorium voor Fysische Technologie<BR>
Telephone: 015-2787084; e-mail: <I>remko@klft.tn.tudelft.nl</I><BR>
sponsor: SON</CENTER>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

For the prediction of the products of multiple
chemical reactions in a liquid phase reactor
operated under turbulent flow conditions
micromixing effects can be of major
importance. Especially when fast and slow
reactions are competing an accurate description
of micromixing is necessary. For this purpose a
new model is developed, called the Cylindrical
Stretched Vortex (csv) model. This model
describes the flow at the smallest scales of
turbulence, the Kolmogorov length lambda<SUB>k</SUB>=(nu<SUP>3</SUP>/epsilon)<SUP>1/4</SUP>
and time t<SUB>k</SUB>=(nu/epsilon)<SUP>1/2</SUP> scales (epsilon is the dissipation
rate of the turbulent kinetic energy, k).
Micromixing is characterized best using the
vorticity equation. Based on results in the
literature on Direct Numerical Simulations
some approximations are used in the vorticity
equation leading to the following cylindrical
vorticity distribution omega(r,t) as a function of
radius r and time t:<P>

<IMG SRC="remko1.gif"><P>

and where (alpha=C/t<SUB>k</SUB> is the rate of strain in the
axial direction of the vortex. The initial
circulation of the vortex, omega<SUB>c</SUB> depends on the
local Taylor microscale Reynolds number as
omega<SUB>c</SUB>=18 nu Re<SUB>lambda</SUB><SUP>1/2</SUP>. This Reynolds number can be
connected to the local k and epsilon as
Relambda=(15 k<SUP>2</SUP>/epsilon nu)<SUP>1/2</SUP>. The behaviour of the
micromixing flow field depends strongly on this
Reynolds number and on alpha. Both parameters
depend on the k and alpha values. These values are
determined for a stirred tank reactor equipped
with a Rushton impeller using Computational
Fluid Dynamics (CFD). The micromixing
model is connected to the CFD-results by
tracking the micromixing zone through the
reactor based on the average velocity field and
on the random velocity field. The local values
of epsilon and k are used for determining the local
behaviour of the micromixing. When the Re<SUB>lambda</SUB> is
low, then the micromixing flow field can be
simplified to a single strained layer originating
from the feed pipe, as the vorticity is merely
curling an initially flat layer. At higher Re<SUB>lambda</SUB>
multiple layers are formed from one initially flat
layer. The low Re<SUB>lambda</SUB> approximation, applicable in
the region above the impeller of the stirred
vessel, is described by a one-dimensional
strained layer, causing a decay in the thickness
delta of the layer as:<P>

<IMG SRC="remko2.gif"><P>

Using this flow field in a chemical species mass
balance the yield of the second (slow) reaction
of two parallel competing reactions (a fast and a
slow reaction) is calculated as a function of the
impeller speed N and compared with
measurements from literature (see figure). The
CSV results with C=0.25 show a much better
agreement with the measurements than the
conventional multi-layer EDD model from
literature. For high Re<SUB>lambda</SUB>. regions the full two
dimensional mass balance need to be solved.
This will be the topic of future publications.<P>

<IMG SRC="remko3.gif"><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

