<HEAD><TITLE>Scaling up two-phase reactors hydrodynamics of bubble columns and bubbling fluidized beds</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Scaling up two-phase reactors hydrodynamics of bubble columns and bubbling fluidized beds</H2>

<CENTER>AiO: ir. Joost S. Groen<BR>
Kramers Laboratorium voor Fysische Technologie<BR>
Telephone: 015-2787084; e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:joost@klft.tn.tudelft.nl">joost@klft.tn.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
Sponsor: DUT (commissie Beek stimuleringsruimte)</CENTER>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

Research is being carried out into the non-stationary behaviour of bubble columns and
bubbling fluidized beds of various diameters. With
the help of Laser Doppler Anemometry, glass fibre
probes and sets of pressure transducers, combined
with various signal processing and correlation
techniques insight is gained as to the dynamic and
local behaviour of the bubbly flow in both
reactors.<P>

LDA is used to study the liquid velocity
fluctuations in bubble columns. Whereas the time-
averaged values of the liquid velocity closely
resemble literature values, the actual flow field
shows a strongly fluctuating character, as can be
seen in figure 1, where the probability density
function(pdf) over a short time period is shown,
together with the pdf at the same place but several
seconds later.<P>

<IMG SRC="joost1.gif"><P>
<CENTER><I>Figure 1.</I></CENTER><P>

In this way it is possible to describe the average
liquid flow field in terms of typical velocities: the
liquid velocity fluctuates between a couple of
typical values which depend on the column
geometry and the gas throughput.<P>

Sets of glass fibre probes are used to study the
appearance of bubble swarms. Cross correlation
techniques are applied to the sets of signals. A
typical example of such a cross correlation
function is shown in figure 2.<P>

<IMG SRC="joost2.gif"><P>
<CENTER><I>Figure 2.</I></CENTER><P>

A simple model is used to fit these cross
correlation functions. From this model, it is
possible to obtain parameters of bubble swarms
such as size and velocity. Bubble swarms appear
to have a size typically of the column diameter.
With these data a simple model describing axial
dispersion in bubble columns is presented. Axial
dispersion coefficients are modelled as the
product of the typical velocities and the typical
bubble swarm size. The agreement of the results
of this model with existing literature data and
empirical models is strikingly good.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>J.S. Groen, R.F. Mudde and H.E.A. van den Akker, 1995,
Trans. I. Chem. Engrs., 73, accepted.<BR>
J.S. Groen, R.G.C. Oldeman, R.F. Mudde and H.E.A. van
den Akker, 1996, submitted to <I>ISCRE 14</I></FONT><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
