<HEAD><TITLE>Development of an oxy-acetylene combustion torch reactor for chemical vapour deposition of centimeter-size diamond plates</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Development of an oxy-acetylene combustion torch reactor for chemical vapour deposition of centimeter-size diamond plates</H2>

AiO: Ria Okkerse-Ruitenberg<BR>
Kramers Laboratorium voor Fysische Technologie<BR>
Telephone: 015-2781400 / 040-2474959<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<I>To design a reactor for the production of centimeter-size diamonds a 2D model of an oxy-acetylene torch combining flame hydrodynamics and chemistry will be developed.</I><P>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The optical properties of monocrystalline diamond makes it an attractive material for applications in the optical industry. It has a wide transmission range from the UV to the far infrared which makes it interesting for windows and lenses in this entire region. It's high thermal conductivity makes it a good candidate for heat sinks in electronic devices. However, monocrystalline diamond in the sizes needed by the optical and electronic industry is not readily available on the market .<P>

<B>Aim of the project</B><BR>
The objective of this project is to develop a new generation of "large scale" CVD reactors on the basis of flame burners suited for large area growth of single crystalline diamond. The development and design occurs by means of detailed computer simulations of both hydrodynamics and chemistry, supported by experimental data from KUN, Nijmegen.<P>

<B>Research topics</B><BR>
In this project a simulation model for diamond CVD by means of an oxyacetylene flame will be developed. The model will consist of :<BR>
a) a gas phase chemistry model<BR>
b) a surface chemistry model<BR>
c) a hydrodynamics model<BR>
A gas phase reaction kinetics model will be obtained from a combination of existing literature data in hydrocarbon-oxygen-nitrogen reactions. The reactions will be screened by means of a sensitivity analysis to abstract the most important ones.  Assuming that the chemistry on the surface is similar to alkane chemistry, it will be possible to estimate surface chemistry  rate constants.<BR>
The partial differential equations describing the transport phenomena and the production and destruction of chemical species in the flame will be solved numerically by means of a control-volume based finite difference technique. In a first stage of the project, a single 2D stationary and cylindrical symmetric flame will be studied. These simplifications will allow to include a complex reaction mechanism involving several dozens of species and of elementary steps. Later various options for scale-up will be considered, e.g.multi-nozzle systems. This involves more complex geometries, which, in combination with detailed chemistry, will require the use of high-performance parallel computers.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 19/03/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
