<HEAD><TITLE>PhD-projects Delft</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Laboratory for Process Equipment<HR></H2>

<TT><PRE>
Delft University of Technology
Laboratory for Process Equipment
Leeghwaterstraat 44
NL 2628 CA Delft

telephone: +31 (0)15 278 6678
fax:       +31 (0)15 278 6975
e-mail:    <A HREF="mailto:secr.api@wbmt.tudelft.nl">secr.api@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A>
internet:  <A HREF="http://dutw409.wbmt.tudelft.nl/">http://dutw409.wbmt.tudelft.nl/</A>
</PRE></TT>

<HR>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../pic/home.gif"></A> PhD-projects Delft

<HR>

<B>Scientific staff</B><P>

<I>Permanent staff:</I><BR>
Prof.dr.ir. J. de Graauw<BR>
Prof.dr.ir. G.M. v. Rosmalen<BR>
Prof. B. Scarlett MSc<BR>
Dr. O.S.L. Bruinsma<BR>
Dr. Z. Olujic<BR>
Dr.ir. H.J.M. Kramer<BR>
Ir. A.F.M. Paijens<BR>
Dr. G.J. Witkamp<P>

<I>Post doc's:</I><BR>
Dr. C. Domingo<BR>
Dr. R.M. Geertman<P>

<I>PhD and design students:</I><BR>
Ir. A.M. Berends<BR>
Ir. G.R.M. Breembroek<BR>
Ir. A.M. Diederen<BR>
Ir. P.J. Diepen<BR>
Drs.ing. K. van Dijk<BR>
Ir. Fakhri<BR>
Ir. H.J.C. Gommeren<BR>
Drs. C.M.G. Heffels<BR>
Ir. J.H. ter Horst<BR>
Ir. M.L.J. van Leeuwen<BR>
Ir. J.P. Muusze<BR>
Dipl.-Ing. A. Neumann<BR>
R.S. O'Meadhra M.Sc.
Ir. L. van Oord<BR>
Ir. H. Oosterhof<BR>
Ir. E.J.A. Schweitzer<BR>
Ir. G.F. Woerlee<BR>
Ir. F.E. Wubbolts<BR>
Ir. G. van Zee<BR>
Ir. T. Zijlema<P>


<B>Research Domain</B><P>

The research activities of the Laboratory for Process Equipment are aimed at developing better separation processes and equipment and improving systematic design knowledge and generic tools, with particular emphasis on advancing the state of the art of scale-up and scale down. The ultimate goal of our research effort is to contribute to the development of a process technology that will meet more stringent social requirements with respect to safety and environmental protection.<BR>
Most of our research projects are devoted to the development of mathematical models that can be used for optimization, design and control of separation processes and equipment. This requires integration of our engineering/technological approach with fundamental and other related applied disciplines which occurs through close collaboration with TU Delft laboratories for aero- and hydrodynamics, particle technology, process integration and process control, as well as trough joint research ventures with laboratories from other Dutch and foreign universities and research institutions. Nearly all of our projects are carried out in close cooperation and with financial support of national and international process industries and equipment manufacturers,<P>

<B>Research activities</B><P>

A short summary is given of the research topics and targets.<P>

<I><B>A</B> Industrial Crystallization and Precipitation</I><BR>
- optimization of the separation efficiency, i.e. purity and yield<BR>
- improvement of particulate product properties, e.g. crystal size distribution<BR>
- production of particles with specific shapes and sizes<BR>
- modelling of crystallizers and precipitators<BR>
- reduction of energy consumption and solid wastes<BR>
- control of the formed hydrate or polymorph type of salts<BR>
- control of crystal quality<P>

<I><B>B</B> Supercritical Fluid Technology</I><BR>
- assessment of the hydraulic limits of operation in SFE<BR>
- optimization of SF-processes, e.g. minimize consumption of supercritical fluid and energy<BR>
- development of reliable design rules<BR>
- advocate the introduction of this novel technology in process industry<BR>
- application of supercritical solvents as reaction media<P>

<I><B>C</B> Novel separation processes</I><BR>
- develop extractive crystallization: water binding as alternative for distillation<BR>
- explore the application of distillation in combination with vapour permeation<BR>
- investigate emulsion and supported liquid membrane extraction processes<BR>
- development of equipment for a continuous fibre sorption process<P>

<I><B>D</B> Distillation, absorption and extraction</I><BR>
- scaling up rules in boiler feed water de-aeration<BR>
- development new packing geometries and a mass transfer model for structured packings<BR>
- development of high performance droplet separators<BR>
- establishing design rules for spray columns<P>

<I><B>E</B> Miscellaneous</I><BR>
- energy reduction in jetmilling processes<P>

