<HEAD><TITLE>Control and design of industrial crystallizers (UNIAK III)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Control and design of industrial crystallizers (UNIAK III)</H2>

<B>AOI's:</B> 4 (1 vacancies)<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Herman. J.M. Kramer<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> <BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> Akzo-Nobel, BASF, DOW Benelux, DuPont, PURAC, BAYER and STW.<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction:</B><BR>
Crystallization is a separation methods
frequently used in industry. The knowledge
necessary for an optimal operation of the
crystallization process is, however,
inadequate for automac control and mainly
based on experience. In practice this often
leads to problems in producing crystals on
specification and to unstable process
behavior. Also the design of industrial
crystallizers is mainly based on experience
which leads to conservatism and to long
periods of troubles shooting during the
start-up of a new plant.<BR>
In the Laboratory for Process
Equipment it has been shown, that the
crystallization process of a 1000 k
ammonium sulfate producing, evaporative,
draft tube baffled crystallizer can be
monitored by an on4ine measurement of
the Crystal Size Distribution (CSD), that
the process can be described by a dynamic
model based on first principles and that the
process can be stabilized and controlled.<BR>
For this new project two main
objectives have been formulated. The <B>first</B>
is the improvement and generalization of
the observation and control systems for
crystallization processes, which is necessary
for the implementation of automatic control
systems in industrial plants. Generalization
of the control strategy involves the
stabilization and optimization in <B>batch</B> and
<B>continuous</B> crystallizers of the product
quality, which includes not only the crystal
size distribution, but also the filterability
and purity of the product. For this purpose
the crystallization models must be refined
and generalized with respect to different
materials, crystallizer geometry and scale of
operation The <B>second</B> objective for the
project is to improve the performance and
the controllability of industrial crystallizers
by a better design. The intention is to come
to a systematic procedure for the
conceptual <B>design</B> of industrial crystallizers
in which plant specifications, empirical
knowledge, and generalized process models
will be combined.<BR>
Fot. r Departments of Delft
University of Technology, will work
together in this project in close cooperation
with the industrial sponsors to form a
multi-disciplinary team perceiving the
objectives of the project The main research
items will be:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>the development of fundamental
crystallization models, generalized for
material properties, process conditions
and hydrodynamics.
<LI>the extension of the on-line
measurement technique to obtain more
detailed knowledge of the product
quality.
<LI>the development of compartment and
overall process models based on
knowledge of the hydrodynamics inside
the crystallizer
<LI>the development of efficient process
actuators for batch and continuous
processes.
<LI>the exploration of the techniques for a
conceptual design and analysis for
industrial crystallizers.
</UL>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

