<HEAD><TITLE>Crystallization kinetics in industrial scale crystallizers</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Crystallization kinetics in industrial scale crystallizers</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Dipl.-lng. Andreas M. Neumann<BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> AKZO-Nobel, BASF, Bayer, Dow, DuPont, Purac, STW<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

This study is part of UNIAK III project, a
multi-disciplinary research project aiming to
develop new control and design procedures
for industrial crystallizers.<P>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The models available for design and scale-
up of industrial crystallizers simulating the
crystallization process are mainly input-
output models, where the crystallizer is
treated as a well mixed vessel. As a result,
these models still have an empirical character.
making them less reliable for design
procedures of crystallizers with different scale
of operation or geometry. Consequently, for
the reliable design of industrial crystallizer a
more detailed insight into the local
crystallization processes that take place in the
crystallizer is required.<P>

<B>Project Objectives</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Development of fundamental kinetic
models for a number of materials to give a
quantitative description of nucleation,
attrition, growth and agglomeration under
well defined process conditions such as
supersaturation, slurry density and flow
velocity in the crystallizer. Validation over
a range of process conditions.
<LI>Compartmentization of the crystallizer
based on hydrodynamic models and
validation using different measurement
techniques.
<LI>Modeling of the overall dynamics of the
crystallizer based on the detailed models of
the compartments.
</UL>

<B>Project Strategy</B><BR>
The strategy to achieve the objectives is
schematically depicted in figure 1. It will first
be employed by using ammonium sulphate as
the model substance. Later, additional
substances will be used. The experimental
facilities used are a 970-1 Draft Tube Baffled
(DTB) crystalizer, 200-1 Forced Circulation
FC and a 22-1 DTB crystallizer. In addition,
further developments and improvements in
measuring techniques and Computational
Fluid Dynamic simulations will be carried out.<P>

<IMG SRC="neumann1.gif"><P>

Figure l: Project Strategy<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
