<HEAD><TITLE>Control and dynamic modelling of industrial crystallizers</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Control and dynamic modelling of industrial crystallizers</H2>

Ph.D. student: ir J.P. Muusze; e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:j.p.muusze@wbmt.tudelft.nl">j.p.muusze@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A><P>

Sponsors: Akzo-Nobel, BASF, Bayer, Dow, Dupont, Purac, STW<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

This part of the UNIAK III - project is
primarily focused on the dynamic modelling
and design of control systems.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Development of a generalised dynamic
process model.
<LI>Design of observation and control systems
for industrial continuous and batch
crystallizers.
<LI>Analysis of the possibilities of the design
of a crystallizer to enhance the
controllability of the process.
</UL>

<B>Dynamic modelling</B><BR>
The dynamic behaviour of the CSD in an
industrial crystallizer is influenced by several
complex crystallization processes like
attrition, nucleation and growth of crystals.
On the other hand the processes kinetics will
be strongly related to hydrodynamic
phenomena which depend on the geometry
and scale of the reactor. A model based on the
first principles of crystallization is chosen as a
major tool for controller and observer design.
In the previous phases of UNIAK, this model
is derived from a step wise modelling
procedure and optimised with experimental
plant data. Now this model will be extended
and generalised through refining of the
kinetic models and through
compartmentization of the crystallizer.<P>

<B>Controller design</B><BR>
<I>Continuous control</I><BR>
A stabilising control structure has been
developed in the previous phase, which uses
reconstructed CSD parameters as input and
classified fine particle removal systems as
output. This simple controller shows a strong
damping of the oscillations present in the
CSD. In a next step more sophisticated
controllers are studied which improve the
quality of the final product. All data for
optimisation of dynamic models and
validation of controllers are obtained from
three different pilot plants, of which the 970 1.
evaporative draft-tube baffled crystallizer is
shown in the figure.<P>

<I>Batch control</I><BR>
The present knowledge of the start-up
behaviour of industrial crystallization
processes will be used to develop control
strategies based on non- linear process
models, making use of a dynamic observer.
The main challenge herein lies in the
estimation of the starting distribution and the
trend of the supersaturation and in the
implementation of the agglomeration models.
Also the development of efficient process
actuators will be important in this respect<P>

<B>Process actuators and controllability</B><BR>
In order to enhance the control lability of the
process, the possibilities of for example
product classification as a full-fledged control
input for the process will be studied. The
possibilities and efficiency of this control
input will be analysed experimentally and
theoretically.<P>


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
