<HEAD><TITLE>Conceptual design of (industrial) crystallizers</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Conceptual design of (industrial) crystallizers</H2>

Scan Bermingham (OIO)<BR>
Sponsors: AKZO-Nobel, BASF, Bayer, Dow, DuPont, Purac, STW<BR>
Tel. 015 - 784532 / 785561<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:Bermingham@stm.tudelft.nl">Bermingham@stm.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

This project is part of UNIAK 3, a project to
develop fundamental kinetic and hydrodynamic models, as well as design and
control procedures for industrial crystallizers.<P>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The aim of this research project is to improve
the performance and controllability of
industrial crystallizers by a better <I>design</I>. The
intention is to come to a systematic procedure
for the conceptual design of (industrial)
crystallizers, in which plant specifications,
empirical knowledge, and general process
models are combined.<BR>
This design procedure should be applicable to
different chemical compounds, different
crystallizer scales and geometry, and different
process conditions.<BR>
To achieve this, empirical and fundamental
design rules, kinetic models and hydrodynamic models need to be studied for
general validity, as well as compatibility.<P>

<B>Experimental set-up</B><BR>
The UNIAK project has 3 crystallizers at its
disposal for experimental work. These
crystallizers differ in operation mode and
scale: a 970 L draft tube baffled crystallizer, a
200 L forced circulation crystallizer, and a 22
L draft tube baffled crystallizer. Most of the
experiments have so far been performed with
ammonium sulphate. Recently experiments
with adipic acid and citric acid have been
initiated.<P>

<B>Simulation environment</B><BR>
Speedup is used for dynamic simulations of
the crystallizer based on a compartmental
model. To determine an adequate configuration of compartments, computational fluid
dynamics simulations are performed with
Fluent.<P>

<B>Project strategy</B><BR>
<OL>
<LI>Make an inventory of the empirical and
systematic design rules that are currently
available, and subsequently determine
their compatibility and short-comings.
<LI>Make a list of typical design specifications, such as production capacity and
product quality, but also controllability. A
complete definition of product quality
may prove to be quite difficult.
<LI>Determine sensitivity of present UNIAK
compartmental crystallizer model, in
order to know the degree of detail desired
from CFD simulations and the resulting
compartmentalisation.
<LI>Collect experimental crystallizer data
from crystallizers with varying scale and
geometry, that have been operated with
different chemical compounds.
<LI>Use the resulting compartmental model to
evaluate different kinetic and physical
models, as well as control strategies. The
simulations will be performed primarily in
SPEEDLIP, and the results will be
compared with experimental data from
the UN1AK crystallizers.
</OL>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
