<HEAD><TITLE>Cooling crystallization of explosive compounds</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Cooling crystallization of explosive compounds</H2>

PhD student: Ir J.. ter Horst (e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:J.H.terHorst@wbmt.tudelft.nl">J.H.terHorst@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsor: TNO Pyrotechnics, TU Delft
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

An unintentional initiation of explosives
can be prevented by lowering the sensitivity of
the explosive towards sudden shocks. Recently
it has been shown that the quality of RDX
crystals is an important factor in determining the
sensitivity of this organic explosive. When a
shock wave hits the crystal, the defects
(inclusions and dislocations) can form hot spots
after which detonation takes place.<P>

<IMG SRC="horst1.gif"><P>

<B>Aim</B><P>

It is the objective
of this research project
to control and improve
RDX product characteristics (mean size, crystal size distribution
(CSD), purity, defect content) by varying the
operating conditions during crystallization on a
bench scale. This means that batches of RDX
crystals with a given mean crystal size, purity,
CSD and defect content should be made in a
reproducible way.<P>

<B>Background</B><P>

To improve the quality of RDX crystals
and thus to lower the sensitivity, the relation
between internal perfection and morphology of
the RDX crystals and the crystallization process
has to be fundamentally understood.<BR>
In order to understand the morphology of
RDX crystals, a Periodic Bond Chain (PBC)
analysis is carried out. The mechanisms of
crystal growth are examined by measuring the
growth rate of the different crystal faces in
solvents with different RDX solubilities. The
RDX crystals are examined for inclusions, line
dislocations, cracks and other defects. This
defect content is influenced by the super-
saturation, temperature, choice of solvent,
hydrodynamics, concentration of impurities,
etc.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><P>

RDX crystals are made by cooling
crystallization from solution. On a small scale of
several mililitres the growth rate and the
morphology of the RDX crystals will be
investigated. The mechanisms of growth will be
deduced from the growth rate measurements
and the morphology will be compared with the
theoretical morphology from the PBC analysis.
From these observations the influence of the
mechanisms of growth and solvents on the
defect content can be deduced. Impurities are
added to investigate the influence of this on
morphology and defect content.<BR>
On a 2 litre scale the crystallization proces
will be optimized with aid of the results of the
small scale experiments. Here the hydro-
dynamics and attrition in the crystallization
reactor will have a strong influence on the
produced crystals.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
