<HEAD><TITLE>Energy-saving in crystallisation processes by applying water binding or extraction as an alternative to evaporation</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Energy-saving in crystallisation processes by applying water binding or extraction as an alternative to evaporation</H2>

PhD-students: Ir. TG. Zijlema (e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:t.g.zijlema@wbmt.tudelft.nl">t.g.zijlema@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A>)<BR>
Sponsors: Novem B.V., Akzo Nobel<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

For the production of well soluble salts which
have only a slight dependency of their solubility
on temperature, evaporative crystallisation is a
widely applied technique. This technique is
rather energy-consuming. In the Netherlands
alone approximately 15 PJ is spent yearly for
NaC1 and Na<SUB>2</SUB>CO<SUB>3</SUB> production. This is equivalent
to approximately 5*10<SUP>8</SUP> m<SUP>3</SUP> natural gas per year.<BR>
Extractive Crystallisation could be a more
energy efficient alternative to evaporative
crystallisation, because in the extractive
crystallisation process the energy intensive
solvent evaporation step is avoided. In extractive
crystallisation the driving force for crystallisation
is created by the addition of an extractant to the
solvent (usually water), which reduces the
sodium chloride solubility. The additive is
chosen in such a way that it binds strongly to
water at for instance 5 &#176;C (crystallisation
temperature) but separates from water at for
instance 20 &#176;C (regeneration temperature).
These temperatures are for NaCl formation using
dimethylisopropylamine (figure 1). For Na<SUB>2</SUB>CO<SUB>3</SUB>
production 1-propanol would be used at a
crystallisation temperature of 180 &#176;C and
regeneration at 90 &#176;C.<BR>
It has been demonstrated by Weingaertner et al.
that the process could be economically feasible
for NaCl or Na<SUB>2</SUB>CO<SUB>3</SUB> production.<P>

In order to identify and test suitable extractants
for the extractive crystallisation of sodium
chloride, crystallisation experiments are carded
out in a 1 litre continuous crystalliser. Important
data are: the extractant percentage in the salt
product, particle size distribution of the salt
crystals and product yield.<BR>
To be able to test extractants under a wider
variety of circumstances an additional
experimental setup has been built at the
laboratory for process equipment. With this
experimental setup it is possible to perform
continuous crystallisation experiments on a 1 to
10 litre scale in the temperature region of- 10 to
200 &#176;C at pressures up to 20 bar.<P>

Parallel to the crystallisation experiments the
feasibility of an extractant recovery from the
water/NaCl/extractant mixture by a temperature
induced liquid-liquid phase split is investigated.<P>

<IMG SRC="zijlema1.gif"><P>

<B>Figure 1</B> Simplified scheme of the extractive
crystallisation process for NaCl.<P>

<B>Reference</B><P>

Weingaertner, D.A.; Lynn, S.; Hanson, D.N.
<I>Extractive Crystallization of Salts from
Concentrated Aqueous Solution</I>; Ind. Eng.
Chem. Res. 1991, Vol. 30, No. 3,490-501.


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
