<HEAD><TITLE>The continuous gas anti solvent process</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>The continuous gas anti solvent process</H2>

PhD: Ir. F.E. Wubbolts (f.e.wubbolts@wbmt.tudelft.nl)<BR>
Sponsors: NWO/SON, Delft university<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
To crystallise a solute from a solution, a
certain level of supersaturation must be
attained This is for instance provoked by
evaporation of the solvent or cooling of the
solution. Another method that finds wide
industrial application is the addition of a liquid
anti-solvent that is miscible with the solvent
and in which the solute is insoluble. In the Gas
Anti-Solvent (GAS) process, a gaseous
instead of a liquid anti-solvent is added to
control the level of supersaturation.<P>

<B>Gas Anti-Solvent Precipitation</B><BR>
In the GAS process the anti-solvent gas is
dissolved in the liquid solvent at a high
pressure. As the pressure increases the
molefraction the gas in the liquid phase
increases and the the equilibrium solubility of
the solute decreases. Precipitation of the
dissolved compound thus occurs. Compared
to a proces that uses a liquid anti-solvent, the
motherliquor in the GAS process has a lower
viscosity and diffusion coefficients are thus
higer. It is expected that with this process a
product with less solvent inclusions is formed
compared to conventional anti-solvent
crystallisation processes<P>

The level of supersaturation in the precipitator
strongly depends on the composition of, and
the pressure on the liquid phase. Therefore in
a GAS process the level of supersaturation can
be varied by changing the process condions.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
In a previous project<SUP>(1)</SUP> the GAS technique was
studied as a batch process at conditions up to
100 bar and 65&#176;C. In this project the
equipment for a continuous GAS process will
be constructed. Different equipment for
mixing of the solution with the anti-solvent,
like a mixed vessel, a T-mixer and a spray-
column can be tested.<P>

The first model-compounds will be the same
as before in the batch equipment: anthracene,
phenanthrene and the polymer
PPO
(2,6 dimethyl - 1,4 phenylene ether).
The influence of the process- and mixing
conditions on the product's particle size and
size distribution will be studied.<P>

It appears that the execution of the different
unit operations, in particular washing of the
product and filtration at high pressure, need
much attention. The unusual properties of the
motherliquor during solid phase formation
may give rise to interesting effects in heat- and
mass tranfer phenomena.<P>

<B>Results of the batch experiments</B><BR>
In the batch equipment CO: has been used to
precipitate various organic compounds and a
number of polymers from solvents like
toluene, ethanol, cyclohexane and butanol.<P>

The size of the organic precipitate could be
influenced by the rate at wich the pressure in
the autoclave was increased. By applying a
pressure-pulse a large number of smal particles
could be formed. When the pressure was
increased further at a lower rate the size of the
small particles increased.<P>

The polymer PPO was succesfully precipitated
from toluene. It appeared that the process
conditions had a strong influence on
agglomeration of the precipitate.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1><SUP>(l)</SUP>E.M. Berends, <I>Supercritical Crystallization:
Tim RESS and the GAS-process</I>. Ph-D thesis. Delft
University of Technology, 1994</FONT><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
