<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Ultrapurification with hydraulic wash columns</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Ultrapurification with hydraulic wash columns</H2>

PhD-student: Ir. Lianne van Oord (e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:L.vanOord@wbmt.tudelft.nl">L.vanOord@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A> / te1:015-2783647)<BR>
Sponsors: TNO-ME, DSM, Cindu Chemicals B.V., NOVEM<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>
This research is part of the project Fractional
Cooling Crystallization II, in which research is
carded out on large scale separation and
ultrapurification of organic compounds by
melt suspension crystallization. In the downstream processing of melt suspension
crystallization, wash columns are in particular
appropriate to separate the pure crystals from
the impure mother liquor. The separation
efficiency is very high due to the displacement
of the mother liquor by a wash liquid, which is
the pure melt in the case of melt
crystallization. A product purity of 99.9% and
higher can be obtained.<P>

<B>The TNO-Thijssen hydraulic wash column</B><P>

The research focuses on a hydraulic wash
column, consisting of a tubular vessel,
containing one or more filter tubes to remove
the mother liquor (Figure 1). The crystal
slurry is pumped into the top of the column
and moves through a short settling zone.
Filtration of the mother liquor through the
crystal bed causes a pressure drop over the
bed, forming the transport force, that moves
the bed downwards. At the bottom of the
column a rotating knife scrapes off the
crystals, which are caught by a circulating
stream of melt. The major part of the melt is
withdrawn as product, while due to an excess
pressure in the reslurry chamber, a small
amount of wash liquid is forced into the
bottom of the crystal bed. Adhering mother
liquor is replaced by this countercurrent
stream of wash liquid, so only incorporated
impurities remain in the final product. The
wash liquid will crystallize on the downward
moving crystal bed, because of the
temperature difference between the pure melt
and the crystals in equilibrium with mother
liquor. By this a barrier for the mother liquor
is formed.<P>

<IMG SRC="oord1.gif"><P>

<B>Figure 1:</B> Schematic drawing of hydraulic washcolumn.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><P>

The aim of the project is to gain more insight
in the phenomena taking place in the wash
column in order to be able to scale up the pilot
hydraulic TNO-Thijssen column to industrial
dimensions. Design rules will be derived from
developed models. Development of a control
strategy and automation of the wash column
will also be part of the project.<P>

<B>Experimental facilities</B><P>

To validate developed models experiments are
carried out at the Delft University of
Technology and at TNO-ME in Apeldoorn,
using caprolactam/water mixtures and
p-xylene mixtures as model systems
respectively.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
