<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Fractional suspension cooling crystallization</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Fractional suspension cooling crystallization</H2>

PhD-student: Ir. P.J. Diepen (e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:P.J.Diepen@wbmt.tudelft.nl">P.J.Diepen@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A> / tel: 31 15 2783647)<BR>
Sponsors: STW, TNO-ME, GMF-Gouda, DSM, Cindu Chemicals B.V.<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

Introduction<P>

Fractional Suspension Cooling Crystallization
(FSCC) is a technique, that can be used for large
scale separation and ultrapurification of organic
compounds. The energy consumption of FSCC-processes is low, because of the high selectivity of
crystallization and the relatively low latent heat of
fusion. Furthermore, the use and regeneration of
toxic or explosive solvents can be avoided. Thus,
fractional cooling crystallization can be regarded as
an environmentally and economically promising
technique for wide industrial application, for e.g.
the production of monomers and pharmaceutical
compounds.<P>

<B>Aim</B><P>

The aim of this project is to establish design rules
for FSCC-processes. Optimization of the process is
aimed at improvement of the purity and the crystal
size distribution of the product, which determine to
a large extent the separation efficiency.<P>

<B>Experimental facilities</B><P>

<IMG SRC="diepen1.gif"><P>

Fig. 1. GMF Cooling Disk Crystallizer (CDC).<P>

At the Delft University of Technology a pilot plant
has been built containing a GMF Cooling Disk
Crystallizer (CDC), Fig. 1. The CDC is a
crystallizer trough, which is divided into eight
compartments by seven cooling elements. In this
way, a cascade of crystallizers is obtained without
the need for slurry handling within this cascade.
The CDC is easily scaled-up and has a relatively
large cooling area.<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

A model for the CDC has been derived, that
describes the growth and nucleation kinetics in the
CDC. The crystallization kinetics determine the
crystal size distribution (CSD) in each
compartment. With this CSD, the permeability is
calculated via a porosity model and a modified
Kozeny-Carman equation. The permeability was
measured and compared with calculated values.
The calculated permeabilities are in agreement with
the experimental results. The permeability increases
with decreasing water content, and increasing
residence time. An example of the crystal mass
built-up and permeability increase as a function
of the compartment of the CDC is found in
Fig2. As can be seen the model describes the
experiments satisfactory.<P>

<IMG SRC="diepen2.gif"><P>

Fig.2. The crystal mass and permeability in each
compartment of the CDC.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
