<HEAD><TITLE>Liquid membrane extraction of heavy metal ions from solid-containing process streams II</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Liquid membrane extraction of heavy metal ions from solid-containing process streams II</H2>

<B>PhD-student:</B> Ir. Anke Berends (<A HREF="mailto:A.M.Berends@WbMT.TUDelft.NL">A.M.Berends@WbMT.TUDelft.NL</A>)<BR>
<B>Phone:</B> 015 - 2786372<BR>
<B>Project leader:</B> Dr. G.J. Witkamp<BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> Senter, Onderzoeksstimuleringsruimte (comm. Beek)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Liquid membrane extraction is a technique that
can be used to remove trace amounts of
contaminants from process streams. A liquid
membrane is a thin layer of liquid separating two
phases. Often, the membrane is organic and the
phases placed on either side are aqueous. One of
these phases is the contaminated process stream,
the other is the strip phase in which the
contaminant should be concentrated. To
facilitate the transport of the contaminant, an
extractant is added to the organic phase. The
extractant forms a complex with the
contaminant, which is soluble in the organic
phase. During the extraction the formed complex
diffuses to the other side of the membrane, where
the contaminant is released. The extractant
diffuses back to the feed phase, where the entire
process can start again. By choosing an
appropriate chemical composition for the strip
phase, a lasting high driving force for transport
can be realized. The required amount of organic
phase in the system is low, enabling the use of
highly selective (often expensive) extractants.
In order to supply the necessary stability to the
membrane, it can be absorbed into a porous solid
support, yielding the so called Supported Liquid
Membrane (SLM) technique. This technique will
be investigated during this project.<BR>
Due to the additional stability, the technique is
(more) suitable for application in solid
containing process streams. Currently, no such
technique is available for industrial application.
An example of such an application of this
technique is the extraction of contaminants
during the recrystallization step of a solid, thus
yielding purer crystals.<P>

<B>Aim</B><BR>
Aim of the project is to develop the SLM
technology and to describe the transfer
phenomena taking place. Ultimate goal is to
develop a process that is ready for application in
the industry for the removal of heavy metal ions
from solid containing process streams.<P>

<B>Experimental set up</B><BR>
Experiments are conducted in a transverse flow
hollow fiber module from Twente University.
The organic phase is absorbed into the pores of
the fibers, while the feed and strip phase flow on
the shell and lumen side respectively. The figure
shows a schematic representation of the module.<P>

<IMG SRC="berends1.gif"><P>

Schematic representation of the transverse flow
hollow fibre module.<P>

With this set up, preliminary extractions of
cadmium from an acidic, chloride containing
solution have been established. In order to clarify
the extraction mechanism, a flat sheet membrane
set up is also available.<P>

<B>Future work</B><BR>
Research will focus on increasing the stability of
the membrane for model systems which
approach actual industrial conditions. To be able
to treat slurries, the effect of solid particles on
the membrane will be studied. The optimum
process module design will be determined as a
function of the slurry characteristics, such as the
particle size distribution. Finally, a model
describing the process will be developed.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
