<HEAD><TITLE>Liquid membrane extraction of heavy metal ions from solid-containing process streams I</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Liquid membrane extraction of heavy metal ions from solid-containing process streams I</H2>

<B>PhD-student:</B> Ir. G.R.M. Breembroek (<A HREF="mailto:G.Breembroek@wbmt.tudelft.nl">G.Breembroek@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A>)<BR>
<B>Phone:</B> 015-2786372<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Senter; Onderzoeksstimuleringsruimte (comm. Beek)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Liquid membranes can be used to extract trace
amounts of heavy metal ions from process
streams. The liquid membrane is a thin layer of
organic phase, separating two aqueous phases.
To achieve metal ion extraction, an extractant is
solved in the organic membrane phase. It acts as
a shuttle, extracting the metal ion from the feed
phase and releasing it again at the other side of
the membrane. In this way, extraction and stripping are performed in one process step. Advantages of the process are the lasting driving force
and the low organic inventory.<BR>
The liquid membrane may be established by absorbing the organic phase into a solid support,
which is called a supported liquid membrane or
SLM-system. The second type of liquid membrane is called emulsion liquid membrane or
ELM, which is a water in oil emulsion, stirred in
the third water phase. The stability of liquid
membranes is as yet unsatisfactory to allow their
industrial application.<BR>
The main subject of this research is the investigation of the influence of various process parameters on the extraction rate in various liquid membrane systems. The cadmium extraction, which
may be very useful to prevent the uptake of this
impurity in CaSO<SUB>4</SUB> 2H<SUB>2</SUB>0 crystals, is used as a
model system for this goal, but the extraction rate
of other ions, e.g. Cu, Pb and chromate is also
studied.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="breembroek1.gif">
The SLM process was studied using a lab-scale
SLM vessel-pair and a hollow fiber module,
varying several reactant concentrations and the
flowrate of the feed phase. The ELM process was
tested in a rotating disc contactor and in a spray
column. The experimental setup includes a homogenizer in which the emulsion is prepared,
and an electrostatic splitter, in which the emulsion is separated in
the loaded stripping phase and the
organic    phase,
which is recycled
to the homogenizer. The extraction rate was
measured as a
function of internal
and external droplet size and carrier
concentration.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
The transportation rate is dependent on a number
of steps: 1. the transport through the aqueous
phase which is influenced by the flow pattern in
the contactor; 2. the reaction rate, determined by
the concentrations at the interface; 3. the diffusion through the organic phase, which depends
on the geometry of the liquid membrane. All
these factors will be included in the model that
describes both ELM and SLM extraction. Some
results are shown below.<P>

<IMG SRC="breembroek2.gif"><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
