<HEAD><TITLE>Compact separation equipment using sorption by fibers</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Compact separation equipment using sorption by fibers</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ph.D. Student: Ir. A.M. Diederen, e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:a.m.diederen@wbmt.tudelft.nl">a.m.diederen@wbmt.tudelft.nl</A><BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Ministerie van Economische Zaken<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction.</B><P>

For the separation of low concentrations of
dissolved pollutants from large quantities of
water, traditionally granular activated carbon
adsorption is applied. The concerning
equipment is voluminous. In theory, the
application of highly porous fibrous sorbents
instead of granular sorbents in a moving
instead of a fixed or fluidized bed can reduce
the equipment size considerably.<P>

<B>Research aim</B><P>

The main goal of the project is the technical
realization of a demonstration unit to show the
possible advantages over existing techniques
and to review potential industrial applications.<P>

<B>Applications</B><P>

If the equipment size is reduced considerably
without raising the operational costs, this new
separation technique has good perspectives for
applications in treatment or in-process
recycling of waste water, especially when
available space is limited. A typical example is
the tertiary treatment of produced water on
oil-rigs (100 m<SUP>3</SUP>/hr).<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

A laboratory-scale separation unit has been
constructed (1 m<SUP><SUP>3</SUP></SUP>/hr). An annular fibrous bed
fixed on an inner drum rotates clockwise,
countercurrent to the fluid flow, in a static
outer drum. The sorbent is transported
continuously through a sorption section and a
regeneration section (steam). Constructive
measures have been taken to enforce
countercurrent flow.<P>

In order to predict the working porosity of a
(slack) fibrous sorbent submitted to fluid flow,
a model has been developed relating the
permeability, compressibility and wall-friction
of the sorbent. The compressibility can be
determined with a 2-axis compression bench,
specially made for highly porous materials.<P>

<IMG SRC="diederen1.gif"><P>

<B>Current research program</B><P>

The separation efficiency of the apparatus is
currently being tested for the removal of
toluene and other organic solvents dissolved in
water. A gas chromatograph is linked to the
effluent stream to detect the solvents with a
resolution of 1 PPM.<BR>
Additional experiments are needed to
investigate axial dispersion. The mass-transfer
model, made for continuous counter-current
fiber sorption, has to be verified or modified.
Besides polymeric fibers also permeable
polymeric foams are being tested for the
removal of solvents from water.<BR>
A scale-up study must point out whether this
new separation technique can be competitive.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
