<HEAD><TITLE>Design of a deaerator for boiler feed water</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Design of a deaerator for boiler feed water</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. Antoine Paijens (Email: <A HREF="mailto:A.F.M. Paijens@WbMT.TUDelft.nl">A.F.M. Paijens@WbMT.TUDelft.nl</A>)<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Stork Boilers<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Almost every thermal power cycle includes a
deaerator as is illustrated in figure 1 .The
deaerator serves three functions:
<UL>
<LI>removal of dissolved gases
<LI>pre-heating of boiler feed water
<LI>buffering of pre-heated boiler feed water.
</UL>

<IMG SRC="paijens1.gif"><P>

To improve the design knowledge deaeration,
Stork Boilers started a research project to the
operation of their sprayer-type deaerator at the
Laboratory for Process Equipment of the TU-Delft.<P>

<B>Operation of a sprayer-type Deaerator</B>
<UL>
<LI>Water is heated up to saturation conditions in
the spray zone. Dissolved gases are removed
by steam stripping.
<IMG SRC="paijens2.gif">
<LI>Stripping steam is injected in the bubble zone
below the water surface. Steam raising from
the bubble zone condenses on the subcooled
droplets in the spray zone. Thus, the non
condensable gases are concentrated in the
spray zone and vented to the atmosphere near
the sprayer.
</UL>

<B>Research program</B><P>
The research for the optimal process conditions
and design of the deaerator is performed by both
experimental and theoretical work. Experimental
research is performed at two experimental setups:
<UL>
<LI>a sprayer setup enclosing a 45 segment of the
spray zone of a 360 tonnes/hr sprayer
<LI>a full scale 100 tonnes/hr deaerator.
</UL>
The theoretical research is aimed at modeling the
dominating physical phenomena in the deaeration
process:
<UL>
<LI>the particle size distribution of the dispersed
phases
<LI>the heat and mass transfer velocities at the
phase-interfaces
<LI>the spatial concentration distribution of the
dissolved gases in the continuous phases.
</UL>

<B>Results:</B><P>

<IMG SRC="paijens3.gif">
<UL>
<LI>The number of transfer units of the spray
zone has been measured for a wide range of
process conditions.
<LI>Bases upon validated assumptions of the
spatial concentration distribution of oxygen in
the steam in the spray-zone, a (tanks-in-series) model of the mass transfer in the spray
zone has been developed.
<LI>Measurement of the residence time distribution in the bubble zone indicates that it behaves almost fully backmixed. CFD simulations of the water flow in the tank elucidate
the effect of steam injection on the concentration distribution in the bubble zone. Figure
3 shows the simulated distribution of a tracer
that has been injected in the feed water stepwise in time. Only one steam distributor is
applied in this CFD model, generating both
bypass and backward flows.
</UL>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
