<HEAD><TITLE>Drying behaviour of deformable porous media</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<H2>Drying behaviour of deformable porous media</H2>
<H3><I>a Mechanistic Approach</I></H3>


Ph.D-student: ir. Bas Kroes<BR>
tel	--31 40 247 3660<BR>
fax 	--31 40 244 6104<BR>
email	<A HREF="mailto:TGTCBK@CHEM.TUE.NL">TGTCBK@CHEM.TUE.NL</A><BR>
</TD><TD><IMG SRC="bas.gif"></TD></TR></TABLE>

<TABLE><TR><TD><IMG SRC="tue.gif"></TD><TD>
Laboratory of Separation Processes and Transport Phenomena<BR>
Eindhoven University of Technology</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER><B>INTRODUCTION</B></CENTER><BR>
Drying of porous materials is often accompanied by shrinkage. Shrinkage and deformation depend on moisture concentration gradients in the medium. The concentration gradients can be predicted when drying kinetics are known. To work out a good drying kinetics model the diffusity of the medium has to be known as a function of moisture content. To attain this it is important to give a fundamental description of microscopic transport phenomena in the porous medium. The ultimate goal of this project will be a good prediction of the apparent diffusity based on material properties and micro structure. This will result in a fundamental description of micro and macro behaviour of a large number of porous deformable media during a drying process.<P>

<CENTER><B>ASPECTS</B></CENTER><BR>
Many porous media exist. In this study three types of clays will be used, because extensive information about these clays is available [1]. By mixing up these clays it is possible to vary material properties and structure in a controlled way.<BR>
A fundamental physical-mathematical model, which predicts drying behaviour has been developed. The model will be verified by experiments with various structured media i.e. various mixtures.<P>

<CENTER><B>EXPERIMENTAL: INPUT PARAMETERS</B></CENTER><BR>
It is necessary to determine input parameters for the model, i.e permeability, sorption isotherms, capillary pressure etc. as a function of temperature and moisture content. The influence of mixing clays on the input parameters is examined. An example of this is given in the figure mentioned below.<P>

<IMG SRC="bas1.gif"><P>

<I>Change of sorption behaviour as function of mixratios of WON and SON clay</I><P>

<CENTER><B>RELATIONSHIP PARAMETERS</B></CENTER><BR>
A network model is being developed to relate the input parameters to structure properties, obtained by mercury porosimetry and sorption experiments. Permeability and capillary pressure, for example, will be related by means of structure. 

<CENTER><B>EXPERIMENTAL VALIDATION</B></CENTER><BR>
<OL>
The validation of the mathematical physical model will be based on:
<LI>drying curves. They represent the water loss as a function of time.  
<LI>measuring moisture concentration profiles during a drying experiment at regular intervals. This will be done by using the NMR-imaging technique.
</OL><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>[1] Ketelaars, A.A.J., <I>Drying Deformable Media; Kinetics, Shrinkage and Stresses</I>, Ph.D-thesis, Eindhoven University of Technology, 1992</FONT><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

