<HEAD><TITLE>Design and optimisation of a sludge incineration and gasification plant</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Design and optimisation of a sludge incineration and gasification plant</H2>

R.D. students: ir. H.J. Scholten & ir. A.G.J. Weekers (--31 40 2473753 & --31 40 2472175)<P>

Laboratory of Separation Technology and Transport phenomena<BR>
Eindhoven University of Technology<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER><B>INTRODUCTION</B></CENTER>
Sludge incineration and gasification are
techniques to reduce the volume of sewage
sludge that remains after cleaning
household waste water. The total capacity
of existing sludge incineration plants in the
Netherlands is about 150,000 ton dry solids
per year (t ds/y). Because the prognose for
the year 2000 will be a sludge production
of 400,000 t ds/y [1], the total sludge
treatment capacity must be increased.<P>

<CENTER><B>OBJECTIVES</B></CENTER>
At this moment the costs for sludge
incineration are about hfl 650,- per ton dry
solids [1]. There is a trend to further
reducing the costs of sludge incineration by
optimizing the process.<BR>
Another way to treat the sludge is to
gasificate the sludge. A study towards
sludge gasification can show if gasification
can be economically competitive with
incineration of the sludge.<BR>
Both processes will be modelled with the
flowsheeting programm SpeedUp. The
computer models can be used to investigate
the influence of varying sludge
characteristics on<BR>
<UL>
<LI>the mass flow, temperature, pressure
and composition of all streams
<LI>the global dimensions of the used
apparatus
<LI>the annual costs.
</UL>

<CENTER><B>MODEL</B></CENTER>
The model, implemented in SpeedUp,
contains mass and energy balances,
equations for the dimensioning of the
apparatus and cost calculation functions.
Optimal design of the process gives
minimum annual costs (hfl per ton ds).<P>

<CENTER><B>RESULTS</B></CENTER>
The annual sludge treatment cost strongly
depend on the performance of the dryer.
Increasing the dry solids content will
reduce the capital costs of the apparatus
behind the dryer, because of the reduced
water vapour content of the gases.
However the investment costs for the dryer
will increase more than linear. So there
will be an optimum dry solids content after
drying (see figures).<P>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="scholten1.gif"></CENTER><P>

[1] Viies, A.W. van der, Marvelde, J.H.B. te, I Water Science
and Technology, v. 25, n. 4-5, pp. 307-314, 1992.<P>

