<HEAD><TITLE>Design rules for fluidized bed driers for drying materials with a diffusion limited drying behaviour</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Design rules for fluidized bed driers for drying materials with a diffusion limited drying behaviour</H2>

AIO-2: Ir. W.G.E. van Ballegooijen (--31 40 2473753)<P>

Laboratory of Separation Technology<BR>
Eindhoven University of Technology<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER><B>INTRODUCTION</B></CENTER><BR>

Fluidized beds are often used in industry
for drying of granular materials. Several
design rules of the lump parameter form
for calculating the drying process in a
fluidized bed drier are available. These
design rules can lead to a not optimal
design [1]. Especially when materials
with a high internal resistance against
water transport are dried. Drying times
calculated with the existing design rules
for this type of material are too long.
Longer drying times then necessarily
result in fluidized bed driers with a too
large capacity, or products that are dried
to a lower humidity than desired. When
designing a fluidized bed drier with the
existing design rules, a not economical
optimal design is made when drying
materials with a high internal resistance
against water transport.<P>

<CENTER><B>ASPECTS</B></CENTER><BR>

There are many materials with a high
internal resistance against water transport.
In this study granular silicagel will be
used, with various diameters. A model
describing the drying of silicagel in a
fluidized bed will be developed. Drying
times calculated with this model will be
verified with experiments in a laboratory
scale fluidized bed drier.<P>

<CENTER><B>EXPERIMENTAL</B></CENTER><BR>

It is necessary to determine input
parameters for the model, for instance,
material properties like, diffusion
coefficients, density, porosity and sorption
isotherms. Also drying curves, giving the
weight loss of the drying material during
drying, are measured on the experimental
fluidized bed drier. The experimental setup
is shown in Figure 1. Drying air is
obtained by using pressurized air, which
can be moistened with steam. In an
electrical heater the air is heated to the
drying temperature. The hot drying air<P>

<IMG SRC="ballegooijen1.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 1. The experimental fluidized bed
drier.</I><P>

enters the fluidized bed through an air
divider plate, which gives a uniform
velocity distribution. During drying, the
temperature of the bed and the humidity of
the exiting drying air will be measured.
Measuring the particle moisture content
during drying, gives the drying curve.<BR>
Validation of the model will be based on
these measured drying curves. The model
will be used to derive better design rules
for the design of a fluidized bed drier.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>[11 Kerkhof, P.J.A.M., <I>A test of lumped-parameter
methods for the drying rate in fluidized bed driers,</I>
Eindhoven University of Technology, IDS94, 8-1994</FONT><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
