<HEAD><TITLE>Design rules for the flocculation of sewage sludge</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Design rules for the flocculation of sewage sludge</H2>

AIO-2: it. Piet Jacobs (--31 40 2472175)<P>

Laboratory of Separation Technology<BR>
Eindhoven University of Technology<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER><B>INTRODUCTION</B></CENTER><BR>
Sewage plants produce enormous amounts
of sewage sludge. In 1990, the
Netherlands produced 10 millions cubic
metres sludge. Mechanical dewatering
reduces this volume by a factor of eight,
by increasing the average dry solid content
from 3 to 23 % mass. This volume
reduction lowers the costs of transport and
further processing.<BR>
Flocculation is a crucial step in the
dewatering process. The fine particles (1 -
5 &#181;m) are sticked together with a
positively charged high molecular weight
polymer (PE) into flocs of several
millimetres. In this way the free water can
be separated from the solids by filtration.<P>

<CENTER><B>FLOCCULATION PROCESS</B></CENTER><BR>
An instantaneous mixing of the sludge with
the flocculant (PE) enhances the efficiency
of the process, this can be achieved in
valve. A stirred vessel is often used for
the growth of the flocs. Sufficient shear
has to be applied to increase the number of
collisions between the colloidal sludge
particles. This increases the flocculation
rate. On the other hand, a too high shear
rate leads to floc breakage.<P>

<CENTER><B>OBJECTIVES</B></CENTER><BR>
The goal of this project is to determine
design rules for the flocculation process.
The following parameters are of interest:
<UL>
<LI>mixing intensities
<LI>residence times
<LI>type of equipment

<CENTER><B>CRITERIUM</B></CENTER><BR>
Criterium for a well flocculated sludge is
a maximum filtration velocity. This
velocity is measured by a filtration
expression cel<SUP>1</SUP>.<P>

<CENTER><B>EXPERIMENTAL</B></CENTER><BR>
Sludge of the RWZI 's-Hertogenbosch is
used as a model sludge. Flocculation
experiments are performed on pilot scale,
500 1/h sludge.<P>

<IMG SRC="jacobs1.gif"><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>[1] E.J. La Heij, <I>An analysis of sludge filtration and
expression,</I> Ph.D-thesis, Eindhoven University of
Technology, 1994.</FONT><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
