<HEAD><TITLE>Modelling quality in spray drying</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Modelling quality in spray drying</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> ir. Frank Kieviet (040-472359)<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> prof. dr. ir. Piet J.A.M. Kerkhof<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> 1992-1996<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Unilever<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Spray drying is a process in which a liquid
feed containing a solid (dissolved or suspended) is sprayed into hot air. The solvent
evaporates and a dry solid in the form of a
powder is formed.<BR>
The scale-up of spray drying processes is a
very complex matter due to the large number
of parameters that are involved and due to the
fact that most parameters are interrelated.
The objective of this research project is to
develop models that can be used to scale up
spray drying processes (rather than the scale
up of the spray drying equipment).<P>

<B>Approach</B><BR>
In the scale up of spray drying processes, we
are focusing on product quality. Parameters
concerning product quality are moisture
content, thermal degradation, aroma retention
and such. These parameters depend solely on
the temperature and moisture history of the
particles. In turn, these histories depend on
the air temperature and humidity a particle
experiences on its way through the tower.<P>

<IMG SRC="kieviet1.gif"><P>

These histories can be calculated using computational fluid dynamics: starting from the
air flow pattern, the particle trajectories are
calculated. Interaction (heat, mass and momentum) between particles and air are calculated and are added to the source terms in
the flow field calculations. After some of
these iterations, a two way coupled air flow
pattern and temperature and humidity profiles are calculated.<P>

<B>Experimental validation</B><BR>
The air flow pattern is measured using a hot
wire system (in absence of spray). Temperatures and humidities in the spray drying
chamber are measured using a device we developed that separates the wet particles from
the the airstream that is led to the temperature
and humidity sensor.<BR>
Particle temperature and moisture histories
are checked using a temperature-time-integrator. This is a compound (alpha-amylase)
that is added to the feed of the spray dryer
and degrades under influence of increased
temperature.<P>

<B>Progress</B><BR>
We have measured temperature and humidity
profiles. They agreed well with the CFD predictions.<BR>
The air flow measurements using hot wires
showed some phenomena we can not yet
model adequately using the CFD models
(slow fluctations). Due to low air velocities
in combination with large fluematious, it
proved to be impossible to measure the air
flow directions accurately.<BR>
We have measured particle residence time
distributions. The particle residence times are
determined mainly by wall deposition, which
can not be modelled. We have measured gas
phase residence time distributions as well,
but the distributions have not been imple-
mented in the CFD model yet.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
