<HEAD><TITLE>Ultra filtration of multicomponent mixtures</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Ultra filtration of multicomponent mixtures</H2>
<H3><I>modeling mass transfer</I></H3>

<B>Phone:</B> 040 247 23 59<BR>
<B>E-mail:</B> <A HREF="mailto:tgtcfp@tc0.chem.tue.nl">tgtcfp@tc0.chem.tue.nl</A> or <A HREF="mailto:Frank_Pijpers@msn.com">Frank_Pijpers@msn.com</A><BR>
<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. P.G.W.F. Pijpers<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Prof. Dr. Ir. P.J.A.M. Kerkhof<BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> Gist-brocades, X-Flow, Unilever, Akzo-Nobel, Stork-Wafilin<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Ultrafiltration is a pressure driven
separation process used for concentration of solutions and size-selective
separations of macromolecules and
colloidal particles from low molecular
weight species.<BR>
Research efforts are concentrated on
modeling mass transfer during ultrafiltration of aqueous multicomponent
systems.<BR>
As a model situation for multicomponent mixtures a ternary system consisting of dextran, polyethylene glycol
and water is used.<P>

<B>Approach</B><BR>
Roughly two different mass transfer
regions can be distinguished: the polarization layer just outside the membrane and the membrane itself.<BR>
For modeling mass transfer in the polarization layer we use a multicomponent boundary layer model with in
which turbulent diffusivities are incorporated to account for turbulence effects [Kerkhof, 1995].<BR>
For modeling mass transfer inside the
membrane we have chosen to use the
'standard' Maxwell-Stefan equations
where the membrane-component diffusivity accounts for the friction between the components and the membrane, without distinguishing between
viscous and diffusive contributions as
is customary [Kerkhof, 1995].<BR>
Two aspects can be distinguished in
experimental work: the determination
of parameters (e.g. activities) and validation of the mass transfer models. For
the latter we have built a fully computer controlled tubular crossflow
module in which ceramic Carbosep<SUP>&reg;</SUP>
membranes are applied.<P>

<B>Progress</B><BR>
Currently a computer model is under
development for simulation with, and
validation of the used mass transfer
models.<BR>
The thermodynamic properties (i.e.
activity coefficients) are determined
with a membrane osmometer.<BR>
From measurement of membrane permeabilities (by determination of pure
water flux) we found that due to the
composition of the active membrane
layer (zirconium oxide - titanium oxide) pH and ion strength dependent
electrostatical effects occur when the
crossflow velocity is zero. These effects are not observed when crossflow
is applied.<P>

<B>Future</B><BR>
Further adoption of mass transfer models, determination of thermodynamic
and physical properties.<P>

<B>Literature</B><BR>
Kerkhof P.J.A.M., A modified Maxwell-Stefan model for transport
through inert membranes: The Binary
Friction Model.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
