<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Scale-up of electrokinetic separation processes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Scale-up of electrokinetic separation processes</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> ir. Erik van Nunen (+31 40 2472359)<BR>
<B>Supervisors:</B> prof.dr.ir. Piet J.A.M. Kerkhof, dr.ir. Krzysztof J. Ptasinski<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> april 1992 - oktober 1995<BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> Akzo-Nobel, Unilever, STW, IVO, Tholen Ingenieursbureau<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In this project, we study the scale-up of
the electrokinetic separation of amphoteric components such as amino acids
and proteins from aqueous solutions.
The separation module consists of four
compartments that are separated by
means of membranes. The module is
sealed off at both sides by electrodes.
The feed solution flows continuously
through one of the compartments and
depending on the solution pH, the amphoteric components migrate towards the
membranes due to the applied electric
field. When adjusting the solution pH so
that the amphoteric components migrate
in different directions, they can be separated.<P>

<B>Modelling</B><BR>
For this separation process, we have developed a mathematical model that
describes the transport of amphoteric
components in an electric field while
they participate in rapid dissociation-association reactions. Furthermore, the
axial dispersion of the solution is implemented in this model to take scale-up
effects into account. This model is applied for the separation of the amino
acid methionine. The effect of the axial
dispersion on the separation efficiency
is shown in the following figure.<P>

<IMG SRC="nunen1.gif"><P>

<B>Experimental results</B><BR>
The separation of methionine from an
aqueous solution is also studied experimentally at different feed concentrations, applied electric currents and feed
flow rates. The separation efficiency of
methionine as function of the applied
current using a feed concentration of 0.1
M methionine, a feed pH of 10.5 and a
feed flow rate of 25 1/hr is shown in the
following figure.<P>

<IMG SRC="nunen2.gif"><P>

This figure shows that the separation
process is limited to an electric current
of 28 A. Applying a higher current results in watersplitting phenomena at the
membrane due to depletion of ions. This
causes pH changes in the module and an
increase in the potential difference
across the module. The limiting current
can be increased by increasing the feed
flow rate.<P>

<B>Conclusions</B><BR>
The mathematical model can describe
the large scale electrokinetic separation
of amphoteric components and will be
verified experimentally in different modules. This model can be used to deduce
general design rules of the separation
module for separating different amino
acids. We will also perform some preliminary experiments for separating different proteins.<P>


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
