<HEAD><TITLE>Diffusion coefficients in liquid systems</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Diffusion coefficients in liquid systems</H2>

AIO: Ir. I.M.J.J. van de Ven - Lucassen<BR>
Sponsor: SON<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The    measurement of diffusion
coefficients in liquid systems is difficult
and time consuming; the scarcely
available data are not very accurate.<P>

In literature many equations have been
proposed relating the diffusion coefficient
in a liquid mixture to other properties of
the mixture.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The purpose of our work is:
<UL>
<LI>to develop a model based on molecular
interactions, predicting the diffusion
coefficient in a liquid mixture as a
function of composition and
temperature
<LI>to develop an automated instrument
for the measurement of diffusion
coefficients in liquid mixtures over a
wide range of conditions (temperature,
concentration)
<LI>to test the accuracy of the model on
experimental data
</UL>

<B>Apparatus</B><BR>
The instrument employs the principle of
Taylor dispersion. The experimental
setup of the standard HPLC equipment
has been fully automated.<BR>
The implementation of a second
(UV)detector enables us to measure the
concentration/time curves of two solute
components in ternary systems almost
independently. Software has been
developed for calculating the diffusion
coefficients from the
measured
concentration/time curves.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1><B>Figure 1.</B> Experimental setup: SV: selection valve;
D: degasser; A: autosampler; RI: refractive index
detector</FONT><P>

<IMG SRC="ven1.gif"><P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
<I>Measurement of Diffusion Coefficients</I><BR>
Experiments on the methanol+water
system (25 &#176;C and 35 &#176;C) and the
ethanol+water system (25 &#176;C and 40 &#176;C)
show an accuracy of 0.5 to 1.5 %.<BR>
Test experiments were performed on two
ternary systems (ethyl benzene - acetone -
water, glucose - acetone - water).<BR>
<I>Modelling</I><BR>
The modelling of molecular diffusion in
liquid systems is based on the use of the
GROMOS package for Molecular
Dynamics. A subroutine has been
developed for simulating diffusion. MD
simulations have been done for the binary
system glucose - water.<P>

<B>Literature</B><BR>
Van de Ven-Lucassen, I.M.J.J.; Kieviet,
F.G.; Kerkhof, P.J.A.M. <I>Fast and
Convenient Implementation of the Taylor
Dispersion Method,</I> J.Chem. Eng. Data,
<B>1995</B>, 40, 407-411<BR>
Van Gunsteren, W.F.; Berendsen, H.J.C.
Biomos b.v. Groningen<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

