<HEAD><TITLE>The chemical vapour deposition of molybdenum from molybdenum hexafluoride: kinetics and reactor modelling</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>The chemical vapour deposition of molybdenum from molybdenum hexafluoride: kinetics and reactor modelling</H2>

Researcher: Edwin Orij<BR>
Status: AIO-4<BR>
Started: October 1991<BR>
External support: NWO/SON<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>A kinetic study to the Low Pressure Chemical Vapour Deposition (LPCVD) of
molybdenum on silicon from MoF<SUB>6</SUB> and H<SUB>2</SUB> is performed using a microbalance reactor
setup.</I><P>

The deposition of molybdenum on silicon from MoF6 and He is studied in situ using a
microbalance setup equipped with a mass spectrometer. Figure 1 shows a typical mass
increase versus time curve measured with the microbalance:<P>

<IMG SRC="orij1.gif"><P>

<B>Figure 1.</B> Typical mass versus time curve.
+ experimental, __ calculated with the
model.<P>

The deposition rate is time dependent,
which is explained by the significant
contribution of the reduction of MoF<SUB>6</SUB>
by Si. The overall reactions are:<P>

<IMG SRC="orij2.gif"><P>

A model taking into account both deposition routes and in particular diffusion of Si through
the growing layer allows to describe the observations quantitatively. The relative importance
of two routes was assessed and the kinetics of the reduction by H<SUB>2</SUB> could be distinguished
from the overall growth kinetics. The kinetic parameters of this proces were finally assessed
using non-linear regression methods in combinations with theoretical methods. The kinetic
model was used for the modelling of this proces in commercial LPCVD reactors and for the
modelling of the filling of sub-micron sized trenches used in IC manufacturing.<P>

