<HEAD><TITLE>Design of a monolith reactor with improved light-off behaviour for automobile exhaust-gas purification</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Design of a monolith reactor with improved light-off behaviour for automobile exhaust-gas purification</H2>

Researcher: Ed R. van Selow<BR>
Status: AIO-2<BR>
Started: February 1994<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>In catalytic reaction systems, resonant behaviour can occur when feed composition
oscillations are imposed. This rate enhancement is due to the system being forced to
operate for part of each cycle in a region where multiple operating states could
potentially exist. As the catalytic CO oxidation has been shown to exhibit multiple
steady states, we applied this well-known concept to the so-called three-way catalyst.
Our simulation study reveals possible improvements of the reactor performance, if
under certain circumstances concentration oscillations are forced by an appropriate
control algorithm of the fuel management system.</I><P>

About 20 years ago, the monolith reactor was introduced as a means to convert
pollutants (carbon monoxide, nitrogen oxides, and hydrocarbons) in automobile
exhaust gases. On Pt/Rh catalysts, the oxidation and reduction reactions take place
simultaneously. This implies a strict air/fuel ratio control in order to obtain efficiency.<P>

From cold start of an engine it takes about two minutes before the exhaust gases have
brought the converter up to a desired operating temperature. During this warm-up
period, the converter is very inefficient and high levels of emissions reach the
atmosphere. When the converter is sufficiently hot, pollutant emissions drop
considerably. This phenomenon is called light-off. For a standard test method, the first
two minutes can contribute up to 75 %; of the total emissions of CO and hydrocarbons.
Therefore, the main focus of study is the reduction of cold-start emissions.<P>

A one-dimensional reactor model for mass and heat transport and transfer processes
is developed, as are kinetic models that incorporate elementary reaction steps for the
reactions of CO, NO, and hydrocarbons. By simulation, the effects of oscillatory
feeding on the conversions are assessed. It is observed that these forced oscillations
can increase the conversions of the harmful components significantly, when the
converter has not yet reached light-off.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
