<HEAD><TITLE>Modelling of the non-steady state deposition of molybdenum in a cold wall single-wafer reactor</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Modelling of the non-steady state deposition of molybdenum in a cold wall single-wafer reactor</H2>

Researcher: Marco de Wild<P>
Status: Research scientist<BR>
Started: September 1994<BR>
External support: EC<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>Modelling of a cold wall single-wafer LPCVD-reactor by developing computer codes
to describe the time-dependent deposition of molybdenum on silicon substrates.</I><P>

The Low Pressure Chemical Vapour Deposition of molybdenum on silicon from molybdenum
hexafluoride and hydrogen consists of the contribution of two different processes:<P>
<UL>
<LI>the reduction of molybdenum hexafluoride by silicon diffusing through the growing layer
<LI>the reduction of molybdenum hexafluoride by hydrogen on the surface
</UL>

<IMG SRC="wild1.gif"><P>

<I>The deposited layer thickness versus time at the
centre of the wafer. Process conditions. T=600K,
p<SUB>H2</SUB>=90Pa, p<SUB>MoF6</SUB>=5Pa, F<SUB>v</SUB>=l slm.</I><P>

The deposition rate is time dependent, which is explained by the significant contribution of the
non-selflimiting reduction of molybdenum hexafluoride by silicon. A numerical model taking
into account both deposition routes is developed to calculate the time-dependent deposition
rates. Computational Fluid Dynamics
codes such as Fluent and Phoenics
appeared to be a reliable tool for
calculating temperatures, gas phase
concentrations and flow characteristics
throughout the reactor. It also
calculates the molybdenum layer
thickness as a function of time and place
on the wafer. The figure shows the layer
thickness versus time at the centre of
the wafer. The high reaction rates of the
reduction by hydrogen compared with
the reduction by silicon are due to the
low partial pressures of molybdenum
hexafluoride above the wafer surface
and the negative order in molybdenum
hexafluoride. The time dependent behaviour in a cold wall single wafer reactor is mainly
caused by a decrease in the reaction rate of the reduction of molybdenum hexafluoride by
hydrogen. The time dependent behaviour of the reduction by silicon is only a minor effect.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
