<HEAD><TITLE>Modelling the step coverage of molybdenum chemical vapour deposition (CVD) in trenches in a single-wafer reactor</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Modelling the step coverage of molybdenum chemical vapour deposition (CVD) in trenches in a single-wafer reactor</H2>

Researcher: Herbert Terhorst<P>

Status: AIO-2<BR>
Started: December 1993<BR>
External support: -<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>Modelling of single-wafer CVD-reactors by developing computer codes to describe the
time-dependent deposition of molybdenum on patterned silicon substrates.</I><P>

Deposition of molybdenum is
achieved by reaction of molybdenum
hexafluoride with hydrogen as well as
with the silicon substrate. A pseudo
two-dimensional model is developed to
calculate     the     time-dependent
deposition profiles in trenches taking
into account both reactions as shown
in the figure. To specify the boundary
conditions at the trench opening, the
total pressure, the partial pressures of
the different species and
the
temperature have to be known.<BR>
Because of a significant
contribution of the reaction of
molybdenum hexafluoride with the
silicon substrate, the deposition rate is
time dependent. Computational Fluid Dynamics codes such as Fluent and Phoenics can be used to
calculate these time-dependent deposition rate by simulating the flow, temperature and
concentration profiles in a single-wafer reactor.<BR>
A link between the trench-scale and reactor-scale simulations (or the two time
dependencies) is necessary for the design and optimization of a single-wafer reactor for the
deposition of molybdenum layers on patterned substrates.<P>

<IMG SRC="terhorst1.gif"><P>

<I>A typical modelling result of the initial and resulting trench
profiles: 1) resulting trench profile after 837 s; 2) initial
trench profile (width 2*10<SUP>-6</SUP> m, length 10*10<SUP>-6</SUP> ~0; 3) resulting
molybdenum/silicon interface (due to reaction of
molybdenum hexafluoride with the silicon substrate);
Conditions: T = 600 K; P<SUB>MoF6</SUB> = 5 Pa and p<SUB>H2</SUB> = 100 Pa at
trench opening;</I><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

