<HEAD><TITLE>Noble metal catalysis for the selective treatment of waste water</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Noble metal catalysis for the selective treatment of waste water</H2>

Researcher: P. J. M. van Andel-Scheffer<BR>
Status: Post-doc researcher<BR>
Started: November 1993<BR>
External support: IOP-Milieu Preventie<P>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

Noble metal catalysts are not yet used for the (selective) removal of organic pollutants in waste water. The stability and high catalyst price may be pointed out as major reason. The performance of noble metal catalysts is strongly affected by heavy metals, either in a negative way (poisoning) or in a positive way (promotion). So, for a successful use of these catalysts in waste water treatment processes fundamental and quantitative knowledge about the reactivity towards organic pollutants and about the noble metal/heavy metal interactions is necessary.<BR>
The oxidation of phenol by means of oxygen in the liquid phase serves as a model reaction, a simplified reaction scheme is pictured in Figure 1. Carbon supported platinum catalysts (Pt/C) and lead and tin promoted ones are screened. Adsorption isotherms and catalyst reactivities under different process parameters (temperature, pH, concentrations) are determined.<BR>
For the investigation of noble metal/heavy metal interactions, a liquid phase pulse chemisorption technique was developed. By means of a HPLC system, see Figure 2, a solution containing the adsorbant is pulsed over an small amount of the adsorbent/catalyst. Using this technique adsorption/desorption processes can be studied in situ in the liquid phase.<BR>
Batch experiments revealed Pt/C-Pb adsorption isotherms. A feasibility study will show whether Pt/C catalysts can also be used for heavy metal removal from waste waters.<P>

<IMG SRC="andel1.gif"><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 22/03/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
