<HEAD><TITLE>Modelling of bifurcation phenomena during the oxidation of aqueous ethanol with oxygen on a carbon supported platinum catalyst</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Modelling of bifurcation phenomena during the oxidation of aqueous ethanol with oxygen on a carbon supported platinum catalyst</H2>

Researcher: Ludovit Jelemensky<BR>
Status: Post-doc researcher<BR>
Started: October 1992<BR>
External support:<P>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

Several heterogeneous catalytic reactions show bifurcation such as multiple steady-states or autonomous oscillations. These bifurcations form a challenge for modelling of and discrimination between different plausible reaction mechanisms. Bifurcations are often experimentally observed in gas-phase catalytic reactions and for electrochemical oxidation. On the other hand, in the case of oxidation of aqueous alcohol with gaseous oxygen, bifurcation has not yet been experimentally observed. The possibility of multiple steady-states during the oxidation of aqueous ethanol was studied.<BR>
The selective oxidation of aqueous ethanol by dioxygen over a platinum on carbon catalyst was investigated in a three-phase continuous stirred-tank reactor at a total pressure of 600 kPa, a temperature of 323 K, a pH of 8.4. Multiple steady-states were obtained by systematic changes in the start-up procedure. The upper steady-state is reached by a reductive start-up and the lower steady-state requires on a oxidative start-up, see Figure 1.<P>

<IMG SRC="ludovit1.gif"><P>

A model which sufficiently describes the experimental data is based on the assumption that three different forms of adsorbed oxygen exist on the platinum: hydroxyl, atomic oxygen and subsurface oxygen. Molecular oxygen in water reversibly adsorbs on the surface in the hydroxyl form. Thereafter adsorbed hydroxyl species reversibly are converted into atomic oxygen and finally a slow reversible oxidation of the metal surface layer by formation of subsurface oxygen occurs. Furthermore, the reactivities of these forms of oxygen with respect to ethanol and acetaldehyde are assumed to decrease in the order hydroxyl, atomic oxygen and subsurface oxygen. Figure 1 allows to compare the experimentalsteady-state disappearance rates of ethanol with model calculations. The latter consisted in solving the continuity equations for 3 liquid and 5 surface species.<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 19/03/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
