<HEAD><TITLE>The partial oxidation of methane to synthesis gas over noble metal catalysts</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>The partial oxidation of methane to synthesis gas over noble metal catalysts</H2>

Researcher: Joop C. Slaa<P>

Status: Post-doc researcher<BR>
Started: February 1994<BR>
External support: European Commission<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I>Catalytic Partial Oxidation of methane to synthesis gas is currently being
studied using Pt and Rh supported by alpha-Al<SUB>2</SUB>0<SUB>3</SUB>. The main points of interest
are (i) the reaction network and (ii) the intrinsic kinetics.</I><P>

The Catalytic Partial Oxidation (CPO) of methane to synthesis gas, represented by
the following reaction,<P>

<CENTER>CH<SUB>4</SUB> + 1/2 0<SUB>2</SUB> --> CO + 2 H<SUB>2</SUB></CENTER><P>

is an energy-efficient alternative to steam-reforming of methane, as it is a slightly
exothermic reaction dH<SUB>1300K</SUB>= -22 kJ mol<SUP>-1</SUP> for CPO vs. +228 kJ mol<SUP>-1</SUP> for steam
reforming). CPO may, however, be built up from a sequence in which a strongly
exothermic complete combustion of methane is followed by the strongly endothermic
reforming of the residual methane. In order to investigate the reaction mechanism and the
kinetics of this reaction, experiments are being carried out over both Pt/alpha-Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB> and Rh/alpha-
Al<SUB>2</SUB>0<SUB>3</SUB> in a tubular fixed bed reactor.<BR>
The reaction conditions were chosen such that intrinsically kinetic data are
obtained. Because strongly exothermic and endothermic reactions may be involved, several
precautions, such as dilution of the catalyst bed with inert material, are necessary to be
able to obtain intrinsically kinetic data. Furthermore, a reaction temperature higher than
1274 K is used in order to avoid the deposition of carbon on the catalyst; such a high
temperature is also favourable for the selectivities to CO and H<SUB>2</SUB>. In order to minimize gas
phase reactions and wall effects, a sintered Al<SUB>2</SUB>0<SUB>3</SUB> reactor tube is used, and the empty space
is filled with sintered Al<SUB>2</SUB>0<SUB>3</SUB>. The reactor is surrounded by a fluidized bed in order to
improve the heat transport between furnace and reactor. The set-up is being operated at
temperatures up to 1500 K and pressures up to 2 MPa.<BR>
Pt/alpha-Al<SUB>2</SUB>0<SUB>3</SUB> has been found to be a good catalyst for complete combustion, but not
for CPO. Therefore, the work now concentrates on Rh/alpha-Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>, which is stable and gives
good selectivities to CO and H<SUB>2</SUB>. Experiments in which the space time, W/F<SUB>CH4,0</SUB>, is varied,
result in oxygen conversions from 0 to 1, which allows analysis of the reaction network. A
complicated network appears to be needed in order to be able to describe the results
adequately.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
