<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>The partial oxidation of methane to synthesis gas over noble metal catalysts</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>The partial oxidation of methane to synthesis gas over noble metal catalysts</H2>

Researcher : <B>Rob. J. Berger</B><P>

Status : Post-doc researcher<BR>
Started : May 1993<BR>
External support : European Commission<P>

<HR SIZE=0>

The work is performed in the framework of the EC project JOU2 - CT92 - 0073 entitled : 'Conversion of Natural Gas to Synthesis Gas and C<SUB>2</SUB><SUP>+</SUP> Hydrocarbons' in which seven universities and one research organization cooperate. From 1996, it will be continued in new EC projects. In Eindhoven, the emphasis is on catalytic partial oxidation of methane by oxygen to synthesis gas over noble metal catalysts at temperatures above 1273 K and pressures up to 2 MPa.<BR>
Catalytic experiments using Pt and Rh supported on  alpha-Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB> are performed in a tubular fixed-bed reactor. Several precautions such as heating by means of a heated fluidized sand bath, using high linear gas velocities and by dilution of the catalyst bed with non-porous inert  alpha-Al<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB>, are taken to ensure intrinsic measurement of the reaction kinetics.<BR>
Since April 1995, a new fully automated setup for catalytic partial oxidation using a single noble metal gauze has been started up successfully. This setup allows measurements with linear gas velocities as high as 25 m/s. By using both a pyrometer and a Pt/Rh wire spotwelded to the gauze, the gauze temperature can be measured accurately at conditions where a large temperature difference of several hundreds degrees exists between the gauze and the gas.<BR>
Additional information concerning the reaction mechanism is obtained from Temporary-Analysis-of-Products (TAP) experiments using noble metal sponge as the catalyst.<BR>

<OL>
The main research goals of the project are :
<LI>	the investigation of the catalytic reaction mechanism and kinetics by performing catalytic experiments in order to develop a detailed reaction model;
<LI>	the investigation of the reaction kinetics of the homogeneous gas-phase oxidation of methane;
<LI>	to study the interaction between heterogeneous (catalytic) and homogeneous (gas phase) reactions and to investigate the possibility of multiple steady states in the reactor, i.e. the occurrence of hysteresis and ignition/extinction phenomena; this is done by combining the results of the items mentioned above and, starting in 1996,  by using Laser-induced fluorescence (LIF);
<LI>	development of advanced computer models for simulation of several reactor types on industrial scale such as different types of fixed bed reactors, monolithic reactors and gauze reactors. These models also include the effects of mass and heat transport phenomena and cover both the pellet scale and the reactor scale.
</OL><P>

Berger acts as project leader of the Eindhoven group which actually includes : Dr. Ir. J.C. Slaa, Dr. A. Baic, Ir. E.P.J. Mallens, Ir. C.R.H. de Smet, Ir. S. Hoogwater and several students.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 19/03/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
