<HEAD><TITLE>Continuous emulsion copolymerization reactors</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Continuous emulsion copolymerization reactors</H2>

Ph.D. student: Frank van den Boomen<BR>
Sponsor: European Union, IntelPol Bre2-CT 93-0523/ProjectNo. BE-7009<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In industry most emulsion polymerizations are
carried out in batch or semi-continuous reactors. During a batch emulsion copolymerization, composition drift occurs depending on
the difference in reactivity and water solubility
of both monomers. In principle it is possible to
produce copolymers with any desired chemical
composition distribution in a semi-continuous
reactor. For the production of large amounts of
polymer continuous reactors can be used. In
open literature almost no attention has been
paid to the continuous emulsion copolymerization reactors.<P>

Emulsion copolymerization experiments in a
series of three CSTRs are carried out to investigate the influence of the type of reactor on
the course of the reaction.<P>

<B>Experimental Results</B><BR>
In Figure 1 the conversions are presented as a
function of the dimensionless time which is
the ratio of the actual time and the mean residence time in one CSTR. In the stationary state
an almost constant ratio of the partial conversions of both monomers is obtained in each
reactor. Assuming that there is no influence of
the particle size or copolymer composition on
the monomer partitioning, copolymers with a
constant composition are produced in each
CSTR. The chemical composition of the co-polymer from each CSTR was also determined
with Gradient HPLC. The product streams of
CSTR 1, 2 and 3 contain copolymers with an
unimodal, bimodal and trimodal chemical
composition, respectively.<P>

<B>Future Work</B><BR>
The production of copolymers with a homogeneous composition at high conversions in a
series of CSTRs asks for addition of the more
reactive monomer to each reactor. A comprehensive simulation model is necessary to calculate the monomer addition rates to each
CSTR. The development of such a model is in
progress.<P>

<IMG SRC="boomen1.gif"><P>

Figure I Seeded continuous emulsion copolymerization of styrene and methylacrylate in a series of three
CSTRs. Conversion time curves: Overall conversion
(diamonds), MA conversion (squares), S conversion (circles).<P>

