<HEAD><TITLE>Mixing in a polycondensation reactor</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Mixing in a polycondensation reactor</H2>

AIO-2: Andr&eacute; Groot <I>[e-mail address: <A HREF="mailto:tgtcag2@chem.tue.nl">tgtcag2@chem.tue.nl</A>]</I><BR>
sponsor: Akzo Nobel<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Importance of mixing</B><P>

Mixing of reactants is rate determining
when rapid reactions occur <SUP>1)</SUP>. Interaction
between mixing and kinetics has an impact
on product quality. Akzo Nobel produces
fibers using polycondensation in a
solution. In this process polymerization
rates are high and mixing of the reactants
is very important.<BR>
Product specifications for this
desired polycondensate are stringent
because of its high performance
application. The polycondensation is
carried out in a semi-batch reactor. One of
the reactants is already present in the
reactor, the other reactant is added through
a nozzle. Heavy stirring equipment is used
as viscosity goes up rapidly with
conversion. Improvement of the mixing
performance offers the opportunity to
optimize product quality.<P>

<B>Objectives of the design project</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Improving the control over the
product quality by variation of the
operating conditions (short term);
<LI>Designing an improved semi-batch
reactor with higher capacity (long
term).
</UL>

<B>Approach</B><P>

The project is in a start-up phase and will
be covered by two AIO-2 design projects.
Akzo Nobel provided a down-scaled
perspex reactor (160 l). The initial research
will focus on mixing inside the reactor
from macroscale to microscale.<BR>
Macromixing characteristics will
be studied by residence time distribution
experiments. The respons of the system to
a pulse at the inlet will be determined
using conductometric measurements at the
outlet.<BR>
Flow visualization will be used to
obtain qualitative information concerning
different operation modes of the reactor,
mixing mechanisms, flow patterns and
initial mixing of the feedstream with the
bulk in the reactor. High speed digital
image acquisition (200 Hz) and processing
in combination with a lasersheet and
fluorescent tracers will give a high time
and space resolution.<BR>
In addition, Laser Doppler
Anemometry (LDA) measurements will
provide a time-averaged velocity pattern as
well as a distribution in local mixing
intensity (energy dissipation rates).<P>

Results from the experiments are to be
validated with process data from the
existing production site.    Design
calculations will be performed based on
the conclusions drawn from the initial
research.<P>

<SUP>1)</SUP>F.J.H. Jeurissen, J.G. Wijers, D. Thoenes,
<I>Initial mixing of feedstreams</I>, ICHEME
Symposium Series No. 136, Cambridge
UK 1994, <B>235-242</B>.


