<HEAD><TITLE>New zinc sulphide grades for HDTV phosphors: process and product development</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>New zinc sulphide grades for HDTV phosphors: process and product development</H2>

Twaio: G. Kieboom (<A HREF="mailto:tgtcgk@chem.tue.nl">tgtcgk@chem.tue.nl</A>)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Product development</B><BR>
Phosphors for high-resolution purposes such
as High Definition Television (HDTV) tubes,
require new grades of its raw material zinc
sulphide (ZnS).<P>

<B>Process description</B><BR>
ZnS is produced in a batch process by
precipitation between ZnSO<SUB>4</SUB> and H<SUB>2</SUB>S.
Initially, a stirred tank reactor contains water
and ammonia. Dissolved ZnSO<SUB>4</SUB> is obtained
by adding ZnO to sulphuric acid. After a
two-step purification, the ZnSO<SUB>4</SUB> is pumped
into the reactor which operates in H<SUB>2</SUB>S under
constant pressure. H<SUB>2</SUB>S is produced by
reaction between a Nails solution and
chloric acid. Stirring the reactor contents is
essential for the mixing of the reactants,
control of temperature and agglomeration,
and for keeping the ZnS in suspension. After
the reaction has been completed, the
suspension is separated by centrifugation.
The ZnS solids are dried in an oven at 150&#176;C.<P>

<B>Approach and targets</B><BR>
The influence of process variables such as
reactant feeding rate, temperature,
formulation, and stirring rate on the
properties of ZnS will be determined during
pilot scale experiments (50 dm<SUP>3</SUP>).
Subsequently, ZnS samples will be tested
for phosphor luminescent properties such as
colour point and lighting yield.<P>

Furthermore, scale-up parameters necessary
for the development of a continuous process
with increased production capacity, will be
determined from pilot batch experiments.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>ZnS grades suitable for HDTV~purposes
can be produced on pilot scale by
influencing the process variables
<LI>Stirring shows great influence on both
ZnS and phosphor properties
</UL>

<B>Future work</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>performing batch experiments with
production equipment (5.000 dm<SUP>3</SUP>), based
on the outcome of pilot investigations
<LI>determining the influence of agitator type
<LI>development of a continuous reactor
section consisting of a series of CSTRs
</UL>

<B>Designer's report</B><BR>
The final report will contain the following:
<UL>
<LI>results of the pilot and production scale
batch experiments
<LI>design of a continuous pilot facility
<LI>investment and product cost calculation
for a continuous production plant
</UL>

<IMG SRC="kieboom1.gif" ALIGN=left>This project is a joint programme with the department of Development
of Processes and Materials of Philips Lighting Maarheeze<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

