<HEAD><TITLE>Design specifications for suspension reactors</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Design specifications for suspension reactors</H2>

AIO-2:      Marian Rijckaert
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Suspending solid particles is one of the most
common processes occurring in mixing
equipment. A lot of research work has been
done to determine the critical impeller speed
(N<SUB>cs</SUB>) required to reach the complete
suspension state. Unfortunately, most of the
theories are only valid for a small range of
vessel geometries and sizes.<P>

<B>Objective</B><BR>
The objective of this work is to calculate the
impeller speed needed to suspend particles for
any vessel geometry and size.<P>

<B>Approach</B><BR>
<OL>
<LI>Find a criterion for the suspension of solid
particles.
<LI>Calculate the flow pattern in vessels of
different geometries and sizes with
computational fluid dynamics (CFD).
</OL>
Combination of the suspension criterion and
the calculation of flow patterns with CFD
can produce the critical impeller speed for
any vessel type and size.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
The experimental apparatus consists of a
baffled, flat-bottomed cylindrical perspex
tank, equal in diameter and height, with six-
bladed PBT impellets (see Figure 1).<P>

<IMG SRC="rijckaert1.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 1: Experimental set-up</I><P>

The critical impeller speed is determined
visually, according to the Zwietering
criterion, for several solid-liquid combinations. To establish a suspension criterion,
local velocities and velocity fluctuations are
measured at this impeller speed with Laser
Doppler Anemometry (LDA) in two solid-
liquid systems. LDA measurements in
suspensions are possible by matching the
refractive index of the solid (PMMA) with the
index of the fluid (dibutylphatalate and a
mixture of tetraline (40 vol%) and
turpentine).<P>

<B>Computational Fluid Dynamics</B><BR>
Flow patterns are calculated with two
commercial CFD packages (FLOW3D and
FLUENT) for the same tank geometries as
used in the experimental measurements. The
experimental data are used to validate the
calculated results. The experimental velocity
data in the outflow of the impeller are used as
a boundary condition for the bottom surface
of the impeller. The computational grid is
given in Figure 2. Grid-refinement is applied
at the bottom and the wall of the vessel,
where most of the particles suspend.<P>

<IMG SRC="rijckaert2.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 2: Computational grid</I><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
