<HEAD><TITLE>Radial heat transport in a pulsed packed column</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Radial heat transport in a pulsed packed column</H2>

AIO-2: Ir. P.J. ter Schegget<BR>
Sponsor: TUE<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Emulsion polymerization is an exothermic
reaction. When carried out in a tubular
reactor radial temperature gradients occur as
a result of poor radial mixing. For proper
product properties these temperature gradients have to be avoided. In a Pulsed Packed Column (PPC) the rate of convective
radial heat transport is considerably improved. For this reason PPC is a promising
reactor for continuous emulsion polymerization [1,2]. Scaling-up this reactor asks for
a detailed knowledge of the mechanism of
heat transport.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
A PPC equipment for measuring radial
temperature profiles has been built, see
figure 1. The process fluid is water, which
is heated by condensing steam in the jacket.<P>

<IMG SRC="schegget1.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 1: Experimental setup</I><P>

The column is packed with random stacked
packing of different shapes, materials and
hydraulic diameters.<P>

<IMG SRC="schegget2.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 2: Dimensionless temperature profile</I><P>

<B>Theory</B><BR>
Radial temperature profiles can be described
by enthalpy balances in axial and radial
direction over a cylindrical volume element.
The pseudo-homogeneous model is extended
by taken porosity and velocity profiles into
account [3]. In the model, heat transport can
be described by:
<UL>
<LI>lambda<SUB>r,eff</SUB>: effective radial heat conductivity;
<LI>lambda<SUB>a,eff</SUB>: effective axial heat conductivity;
<LI>alpha<SUB>w,eff</SUB>: effective heat transfer coefficient at the wall.
</UL>
The influence of pulsation velocity, net
liquid velocity and the packing on the radial
heat transport will be studied. For modeling
the heat transfer coefficient at the wall a
penetration or surface renewal approximation
will be used.<P>

<B>Design</B><BR>
The results will be used in the design of a
commercial scale PPC equipment for emulsion (co)polymerization.<P>

<B>Conclusions</B>
<UL>
<LI>Heat transport will be improved by increasing the pulsation velocity;
<LI>Heat transport will be improved by decreasing the net liquid velocity.
</UL>

<B>References</B><BR>
[1] Meuldijk, J., van Strien, C.J.G., van Doormalen,
F.A.C.H., and Thoenes, D., 1992, A novel reactor for
confinous emulsion polymerization. <I>Chem. Engng. Sci.</I>
<B>47</B>, 2603-2608.<BR>
[2] Mayer, J., Meuldijk, J., and Thoenes, D., 1994,
Emulsion polymerization in various reactor types:
Recipes with high monomer contents. <I>Chem. Engng.
Sci.</I> <B>49</B>, 4971-4980.<BR>
[3] Vortmeyer, D., and Schuster, J., 1983, Evaluation
of steady flow profiles in rectangular and circular
packed beds by a variational method. <I>Chem. Engng. Sci.</I>
<B>38</B>, 1691-1699.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

