<HEAD><TITLE>Hydrodynamics in continuous stirred tank reactors</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Hydrodynamics in continuous stirred tank reactors</H2>

Ph.D. student: it. J.H.A. Schoenmakers<BR>
Sponsor: TUE<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Precipitation of sparingly soluble salts is a
very fast chemical reaction influenced by the
local hydrodynamic properties in the reactor.
The creation of supersaturation in the
reaction zone due to turbulent mixing of the
feedstreams and the bulk contents of the
reactor has a significant influence on the
product properties of the precipitate.
Previous research showed that both feed
stream generated turbulence and stirrer
generated turbulence determine the
hydrodynamic properties in the reaction zone.<P>

<B>Approach</B><BR>
The reactor studied is a flat bottomed
continuous stirred tank reactor with four
baffles and a Rushton type stirrer. Properties
of the internal flowfield in the reactor are
studied using Laser Doppler Anemometry
(LDA), Planar Laser Induced Fluorescence
(PLIF) and Computational Fluid Dynamics
(CFD). The precipitation studied is the
formation of BaSO<SUB>4</SUB> from solutions of BaCl<SUB>2</SUB>
and Na<SUB>2</SUB>SO<SUB>4</SUB>.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
Detailed analysis of LDA measurements
showed that the flow in the vessel was
unstable with a characteristic timescale of
about 10 seconds. This phenomenon is shown
in figure 1.<P>

<IMG SRC="schoenmakers1.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 1: Average radial velocity for a point in
the bulk of the vessel as a function of time.</I><P>

This instability makes it inherently impossible
to give a well defined value of e.g. local
velocity and kinetic energy. Only an average
value with a spread caused by the unstable
behaviour of the flow can be specified.
Modelling of the flow in the reactor is done
using CFD. The Rushton stirrer is modelled
as a ting of computational cells where
measured values of velocity and turbulent
kinetic energy are prescribed. Results with
this model were within the range of the
mentioned variations due to flow instabilities.
The size of the reaction zone can be
visualised with PLIF. A first qualitative result
is shown in figure 2. Much effort is put in
acquiring quantitative results with PLIF.<P>

<IMG SRC="schoenmakers2.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 2: PL1F recording of feedstream mixing
in a continuous stirred lank reactor.</I><P>

<B>Future work</B><BR>
The CFD model will be extended with the
physical and chemical models associated with
precipitation of sparingly soluble salts. The
final objective of the research is to obtain
design rules for the precipitation of sparingly
soluble salts in continuous stirred tank
reactors.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

