<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Design specifications for precipitation reactors</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Design specifications for precipitation reactors</H2>

Twaio: J. Swuste (tgtcjs2@chem.tue.nl)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In this project we develop design
specifications for precipitation reactors that
produce solids with a desired mean particle
size. We varied reactor parameters and
measured the response of the average particle
size. Measurements were performed using a
Partec 100. This is a relatively new
measurement instrument capable of on-line
measurements in suspensions with a high
solid concentration. Coulter LS 130 data
were generated to check the Partec data and
test the accuracy and validity of this new
method.<P>

<B>Experiments</B><BR>
BaSO<SUB>4</SUB>(s) was continuously produced in a
CSTR in three configurations:<BR>
<OL>
<LI>BaC1<SUB>2</SUB>(aq) and Na<SUB>2</SUB>SO<SUB>4</SUB> (all) were fed to a
reactor filled with a Na<SUB>2</SUB>SO<SUB>4</SUB>-solution.
<LI>BaC1<SUB>2</SUB>(aq) and Na<SUB>2</SUB>SO<SUB>4</SUB> (aq) were fed to a
reactor filled with H<SUB>2</SUB>0.
<LI>BaC1<SUB>2</SUB>(aq) and Na<SUB>2</SUB>SO<SUB>4</SUB> (all) were fed to a
T-mixer and then fed to a reactor filled
with a Na<SUB>2</SUB>SO<SUB>4</SUB>-solution.
</OL>

In the first configuration we measured the
average chord length and the particle size
(distribution) as a function of impeller speed,
concentration, feed position, feed rate and
feed tube diameter. In the second and third
configuration the feed position, feed rate,
impeller speed and concentration was varied.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>The average chord length and the particle
size (distribution) was almost constant
with varying process conditions in
configuration 1.
<LI>The mean particle size differed for each
configuration. In configuration 2 & 3 the
particle size varied with changes in feed
concentration.
<LI>The Partec 100 was able to give
quantitative on-line information about the
mean particle size.
</UL>

<IMG SRC="swuste1.gif"><P>

<I>Mean Particle size (&#181;m) vs. Stirrer speed (RPM)</I><P>

<B>Conclusions</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>The mean particle size is not significantly
influenced by reactor parameters in
configuration 1.
<LI>The three configurations make it possible
to produce particles with a specified
mean particle size.
<LI>The Partec 100 can perform on-line
measurements at high solid
concentrations.
</UL>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

