<HEAD><TITLE>Micromixing analysis in a viscous liquid stirred with a double helical ribbon impeller</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Micromixing analysis in a viscous liquid stirred with a double helical ribbon impeller</H2>

OIO-2: Annemiek van der Zande<BR>
Sponsor: TUE<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Helical ribbon impellers have found many
applications in chemical industry, due to the
good mixing properties in high-viscosity
media. Characteristic features of this type
of impeller are a high circulation capacity
combined with strong shear, present in the
small region between impeller blades and
vessel wall. Yet, 'dead' zones are probable,
especially for non-newtonian liquids.<P>

<B>Objective</B><BR>
To gain more insight into (micro)mixing
phenomena in high-viscosity liquids.<BR>
Research work concentrates on:<P>
<UL>
<LI>flow pattern visualisation
<LI>detection of poorly- and well-mixed
regions of the impeller.
<LI>periodicity of circulation flow
</UL>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
In this research work the mixing behaviour
of a double helical ribbon impeller is
studied in a pseudoplastic liquid.<P>

<IMG SRC="zande1.gif"><P>

An instantaneous decolourizing chemical
reaction (I<SUB>2</SUB> + S<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>3</SUB><SUP>2-</SUP>) is used to measure
(micro)mixing rates over time.<P>

Spectrophotometric analysis of the iodine
concentration is done with a laser beam, of
which the position is varied along the vessel
radius. So (micro)mixing rates are measured in various regions of the vessel.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
Experiments have already given quite
promising results. Mixing is most effective
in the clearance between impeller blades
and vessel wall, whereas a poorly-mixed
zone is observed on the inside of the
impeller blades. Measured circulation times
show a broad distribution.<P>

<IMG SRC="zande2.gif"><P>

As a consequence, frequencies of phenomena like reorientation, stretching and
folding of fluid elements are also
distributed. Therefore, the time constant for
concentration levelling increases continuously with time and not periodically as on
a small scale.<P>

<B>Future work</B><BR>
Similar experiments will be performed in a
CSTR in which the influence of average
residence time, residence time distribution
and feed tube diameter on micromixing
rates will be considered.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
