<HEAD><TITLE>Recycling of plastic waste by high temperature pyrolysis</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Recycling of plastic waste by high temperature pyrolysis</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. R.W.J. Westerhout (Phone 053-4892927)<BR>
<B>Research period:</B> march 1993-1997<BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> IOP, University of Twente<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

The disposal of mixed waste poses a serious problem, because plastics are usually not bio
degradable. Dumping of plastics is therefore not an acceptable option, due to environmental
considerations. Incineration of plastic waste is a better and reasonably cheap option, but there are
a few major problems: the energy recovery is low, possible formation of dioxines and furans,
emmision of heavy metals and HC1. Due to these problems alternative methods for plastic waste
recycling are currently being developed. High temperature pyrolyis of plastic ware is one of the
most promising alternatives.<P>

<B>Objectives.</B><P>

The objective of this research project is the development, optimisation, technical and economical
evaluation of a process for the high temperature pyrolysis of mixed plastic waste, containing PE,
PP, PS and PVC. The main objective of the project is the development and characterization of
the main process reactor. Reactors being considered are the rotating cone reactor and the rotating
flat plate reactor.<P>

<B>Results/research topics.</B><P>

To characterize the main reactor the pyrolysis kinetics of the forementioned polymers, the
hydrodynamics and the heat transfer characteristics of the pyrolysis reactor have to be known. A
literature study has shown that the pyrolysis kinetics of the polymers is not well known at low
temperatures (< 450 &#176;C), while no data is available at high temperatures. The pyrolysis kinetics
of LDPE, HDPE an PP has been studied in great detail using TGA, LEFR and a novel
screenheater. In addition detailed models have been developed to describe the pyrolysis process.
The performance of the rotating cone pyrolysis reactor has been studied in detail. Our studies
have shown that very good product yields can be obtained in comparisation with other reactors.
(see figure)<BR>
Our future work will be concerned with the optimimization of the rotating cone reactor to further
improve the yields of the key components (e.g. ethene, propene, butene).<P>

<IMG SRC="westerhout1.gif"><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
