<HEAD><TITLE>Removal of hydrogen cyanide from gaseous streams by means of gas/liquid processes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Removal of hydrogen cyanide from gaseous streams by means of gas/liquid processes</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> ir. P.J. Boon (tel. 053-4892881)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> 11-1994 to 11-1998<BR>
<B>e-mail:</B> <A HREF="mailto:p.j.boon@utct.ct.utwente.nl">p.j.boon@utct.ct.utwente.nl</A>
<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The removal of HCN from gaseous
streams is necessary in processes dealing
with coal and petroleum handling. The
HCN production takes place by the
pyrolysis reaction of N-containing
organic substances found in natural fuel
products like pyridines and pyrroles.<P>

By processing coal and petroleum feed a
gaseous stream is formed which contains
besides HCN, impurities like H<SUB>2</SUB>S, CO<SUB>2</SUB>
and NH<SUB>3</SUB>. For the removal of H<SUB>2</SUB>S there
are several industrial processes available.
In most cases HCN is removed
simultaneously. Sometimes, however,
the presence of HCN complicates the
removal of H<SUB>2</SUB>S and in these cases it is
necessary to remove HCN prior to H<SUB>2</SUB>S.<P>

<B>Scope</B><BR>
The aim of this research project is to
develop a gas/liquid absorption process
suited for the selective removal of HCN
from a gaseous stream.<P>

<B>Research activities</B><BR>
The gas/liquid absorption processes that
have been selected for further research
are:<P>

1. <I>Absorption of HCN in water:</I> The
solubility of HCN in water is very high.
The solubilties are comparable with that
of NH<SUB>3</SUB> in water. This makes water a
favourable solvent for HCN removal.<P>
2. <I>Absorption of HCN in an
aldehyde/ketone solution:</I> In this case the
liquid phase contains a yet unspecified
aldehyde or ketone. The reaction of
aldehydes and ketones with HCN is as
follows:<P>

<IMG SRC="boon1.gif"><P>

The reaction is reversible.<P>

3. <I>Absorption of HCN in a polysulphide
solution:</I> The application of a
polysulphide solution for the removal of
HCN makes use of the fact that HCN is
readily oxidized to thiocyanates (HSCN)
in the presence of sulfur:<P>

<IMG SRC="boon2.gif"><P>

This is a fast and irreversible reaction.<P>

<B>Future direction</B><BR>
These three processes will be subject to
further investigation by means of
modelling and experimental research.
Experimental    research     includes
determination of reaction mechanism
and kinetics and the determination of
physical parameters. From the above
three processes the one best suited for
the purpose will be selected. This
process will then be experimentally
tested and validated.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
