<HEAD><TITLE>Modelling hydrodynamics and chemical reaction in gas - slurry reactors</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Modelling hydrodynamics and chemical reaction in gas - slurry reactors</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. E. Delnoij (Tel.: 053 - 4892890 / e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:E.Delnoij@ct.utwente.nl">E.Delnoij@ct.utwente.nl</A>)<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Dr. Ir. J.A.M. Kuipers<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> 1-11-1994 - 1-11-1998<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> DSM<BR>
<B>WWW:</B> <A HREF="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/~pk/delnoij.html">http://www.ct.utwente.nl/~pk/delnoij.html</A><BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Three phase systems find widespread application in the chemical, biological and process
industry; applications range from hydrogenation to production of hydrocarbons via Fischer
Tropsch synthesis. This applicability is mainly due to the advantages of three phase systems
over packed beds. For example: three phase reactors, and gas - slurry reactors in particular, are
generally very well mixed; resulting in excellent heat transfer characteristics. This makes gas -
slurry reactors very suitable for carrying out highly exothermic reactions. One major
disadvantage of gas - slurry reactors is the limited knowledge about three phase hydrodynamics
and the problems arising in scale up.<P>

This PhD project is aimed at reducing these disadvantages of gas - slurry reactors. Our first
concern is to model gas - slurry reactor hydrodynamics in a fundamental way. This model
development will be accompanied by an experimental program to validate the models. Ones
experimentally validated hydrodynamic models have been developed, a description of a suitable
chemical reaction will be added to the model.<P>

<B>Activities</B><BR>
Our attempts to model the hydrodynamics of a
gas - slurry reactor currently focus on bubble
behaviour in liquids. Two models are being
developed; one describing the homogeneous
bubbling regime of a gas - liquid bubble
column, the other model describes the rise of a
single, large bubble in a liquid. These models
will be extended to incorporate a description of
the solid phase present in gas - slurry reactors.<P>

<IMG SRC="delnoij1.gif"><P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
The first results obtained with the "homogeneous bubbling model" clearly indicate a number of
features of gas - liquid bubble columns; the model predicts the transient nature of the gas -
liquid flow and calculates realistic bubble and liquid velocities.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
