<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Application of hydrophobic particles for the removal of halogenated hydrocarbons and heavy metals from waste water</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Application of hydrophobic particles for the removal of halogenated hydrocarbons and heavy metals from waste water</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. G. Rexwinkel (053-4892935)<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Dr.Ir. A.B.M. Heesink (053-4893024)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> October 1993-October 1997<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> I.O.P. Preventie<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>

Instead of activated carbon, which has bad
regeneration    characteristics,    porous
polymer particles can be used for the
removal of halogenated hydrocarbons from
waste water. Adsorption at the surface of
these polymers is highly
reversible
allowing smooth regeneration.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The main objectives of this project are:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>Development of suitable particles for
the regenerative removal of halogenated
hydrocarbons and heavy metals.
<LI>Model development of the processes
that occur in the particles.
<LI>Model development of the processes
that occur in the contactor.
<LI>Revealing the dominating mechanisms
for mass transfer in packed beds.
</UL>

<B>Results</B><BR>
The adsorption of 1,1,1-trichloroethane and
1,1,2-trichloroethane on 0.7 mm Amberlite
XAD-2 and Amberlite XAD-4 particles,
was examined in a finite bath reactor.
Unexpectedly fast adsorption was
observed. This was found to be the
consequence of the hydrophobic nature of
the particles: The pores don't become
wetted and are filled with air instead of
water. Therefore, in case of volatile
hydrocarbons, intraparticle diffusion
proceeds fast enough to exclude
intraparticle mass transfer limitation.
External mass transfer instead of
intraparticle mass transfer appears to be
rate determining. The factors that decrease
the intraparticle mass transfer rate of
hydrophobic sorbents, i.e. volatility of the
halogenated hydrocarbons, wettability of
the sorbents, have been investigated.
Wetting of the sorbents was found to occur
below a critical contact angle which was
determined at 71° for Amberlite XAD-2
and 80° for Amberlite XAD-4. No
influence of the difference in volatility of
1,1,1-trichloroethane and 1,1,2-trichloro-
ethane on the total mass transfer rate was
observed.<P>

A single particle model which takes
intraparticle and external mass transfer into
account has been developed and fits the
finite bath data very well. As a result of the
experiments this model could be reduced
to a simpler model taking only external
mass transfer into account.<P>

<IMG SRC="rexwinkel1.gif"><P>

<B>Figure 1: Sorption rate of 1,1,1-trichloroethane
on XAD-4 at 298 K in the finite bath reactor</B><P>

<B>Conclusions</B><BR>
The results imply that future research in the
case of the removal of volatile halogenated
hydrocarbons with hydrophobic particles
should concentrate on the external mass
transfer resistance in various contactors.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
