</DOCHDR>
<ABBREV></ABBREV><HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Contacting in gas solids reactors</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Contacting in gas solids reactors</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> ir. R.H.Venderbosch 053-4893028<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Netherlands Energy Research Foundation ECN<BR>
<B>e-mail:</B> <A HREF="mailto:venderbs@utct.ct.utwente.nl">venderbs@utct.ct.utwente.nl</A><BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>INTRODUCTION</B><BR>
Turbulent and fast fluidized beds are favourable
reactors for rapid, exothermal reactions because
of the large specific surface area available for
reaction and short residence times for gas and/or
solids. One of the most promising claims of
these types of reactors is the excellent contacting
between the solids and the gas. In this PhD
project the contacting in these type of reactors is
investigated from a hydrodynamic as well as
from a kinetic and/or mass-transfer point of
view.<P>

<B>EXPERIMENTAL PROGRAMME</B><BR>
This study can be separated into four parts, viz.
the experimental determination of
<OL>
<LI>the kinetics of a model reaction in a fixed
bed,
<LI>the hydrodynamic behaviour of turbulent
and fast fluidized beds,
<LI>gas-solids mass-transfer coefficients in these
type of reactors and
<LI>the performance of the regeneration reaction
of a H<SUB>2</SUB>S-loaded adsorbent in a turbulent
fluidized bed.
</OL>

<B>PRESENT RESULTS</B>
<OL>
<LI>
In a 7 mm ID fixed bed reactor mass transfer
to Geldart's A type of particles is
investigated by means of the CO-oxidation
over Pt impregnated on alumina. An
important variable in the experimental work
is the degree in which the catalyst is diluted
with inert gamma-alumina particles. Results show
that contacting is maximal at infinite
dilution, while it decreases with decreasing
degree of dilution. These results are
interpreted with a simple model, which
accounts for clustering of particles.
<LI>
Solids hold-up measurements are carried out
in turbulent and fast fluidized beds by
different techniques: i) pressure gradients,
ii) quick-closing valves and iii) direct
measurement of the solids velocity by a new
contactless     method based on the
characteristic luminescence of phosphorous
material. It is demonstrated that solids-wall
friction for different types of particles is only
partially (Geldart's type B) or not at all (type
A) responsible for the deviation between
terminal falling velocities and evaluated slip
velocities. Results obtained by this newly
developed technique are completely
consistent with those derived by the quick-
closing valves, which provides strong
evidence in favour of the cluster instead of
single-particle concept for the flow of solids.
<LI>
Measurement of mass transfer numbers are
carried out in turbulent and fast fluidized bed
using the CO-oxidation reaction over a Pt/gamma-alumina catalyst. From the results it can be
concluded that the assumption of excellent
gas-solids contacting in these types of beds is
not valid. Observed mass transfer numbers
per unit volume of active catalyst,
represented as the Sherwood number as a
function of the particle Reynolds number,
show the same trend as for a packed bed. In
figure I it is shown that its values decrease at
a higher solids holdup and lower dilution
ratios (defined as m<SUP>3</SUP><SUB>inert</SUB>/m<SUP>3</SUP><SUB>cat</SUB>), which can
be attributed to the shielding of particles due
to formation of clusters or strands of
particles. This is confirmed by the
dependency of gas-solids contacting on the
kinetic rate constant per unit volume of
reactor.<P>

<IMG SRC="venderbosch1.gif"><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>Figure I.
Experimental Sherwood number on bitsis of the active
catalyst versus the solids holdup in a fast fluidized b~3d
Indicated is the dilution ratio,n, defined as m<SUP>3</SUP><SUB>inert</SUB>/m<SUP>3</SUP><SUB>cat</SUB></FONT>
<P>

<LI>
Due to the high bed-to-wall heat transfer
coefficients the turbulent fluidized bed is
expected to be an excellent reactor when
highly exothermic reactions are applied. In
future work the regeneration of a sulphur-loaded adsorbent is investigated.
</OL>


