<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Development of an integrated pilot plant for the flash pyrolysis of wood</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Development of an integrated pilot plant for the flash pyrolysis of wood</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> ir. Arthur M.C. Janse (053-4892935)<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> dr.ir. W.Prins (053-4892891)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> November 1993-November 1996<BR>
<B>Financial support:</B> CEC (Air Program), Novera, "de Schelde"<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

A continuous pilot plant for the flash pyrolysis of
wood to bio-oil with a design throughput of 10
kg/hr wood is being developed. This integrated unit
combines the flash pyrolysis process with the
combustion of the produced char to operate the
plant autothermally.<P>

<IMG SRC="janse1.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 1: Scheme and 3D-view of the continuous
pyrolysis pilot plant</I><P>

The core of the pilot plant (see figure 1) consists of
a rotating cone reactor. Sand and wood particles are
fed to the bottom of the reactor and move upwards
in a spiral way along the cone wall due to the
centrifugal force. Eventually, the solids leave the
reactor by passing the upper edge of the cone wall.
The sand particles are added to prevent fouling of
the cone wall and improve the heat transfer to the
biomass particles. A disadvantage of this first
generation cone reactor is that the sand particles
must be recycled continuously to the bottom of the
cone.<BR>
A new type of cone has been developed in which
the cone bottom plate is missing. By inserting the
cone in a fluidized bed, the sand particles are
soaked up automatically into the rotating cone,
move along the cone wall, and fall over the wall
back into the fluidized bed. In this way an internal
recirculation is realized.<BR>
A specific feature of this new cone type is the
possibility to recycle also partly converted biomass
particles. In this way, single pass conversion is not
necessary and somewhat coarser biomass feed can
be processed.<BR>
A second fluidized bed, called the combustor is
positioned around the cone reactor and its
belonging (first) fluid bed. This second fluid bed is
meant for the combustion of produced char. Sand
and char particles are transported from the inner
fluid bed to the combustor bed through an orifice.
The transport of hot sand from the combustor to the
cone vessel is realized with a riser, partly
submerged into the combustor bed. Additional
advantages of this pilot plant configuration are its
compactness and integrated character.<P>

<IMG SRC="janse2.gif"><P>

<B>Results</B><P>

Cold flow experiments with cones of several scales
showed very high sand transport capacities without
the use of much carrier gas, up to 1.5 kg/s for a pilot
scale cone (height 60 cm, cone angle 60&#176;). The
parameters which determine the sand transport
capacity have been investigated on a small scale.
Besides the cone dimensions, important parameters
are the cone rotational frequency, the gas velocity
and the height of the fluid bed outside the rotating
cone.<P>

The heat transfer characteristics of the rotating cone
reactor have been investigated, using the newly
developed fluoroptic measurement technique. The
cone reactor exhibits higher external heat transfer
coefficients (in the order of 500-1500 W/m<SUP>2</SUP>/K),
than normally encountered in fluidized beds.<P>

Other cold flow experiments in a cold full scale
version of the pilot plant revealed the possibility to
realize a constant sand recirculation between the
two reactor vessels and the easiness of this
operation. The hot version of the pilot plant is under
construction and will be started up in spring 1996.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
