<HEAD><TITLE>Discrete particle simulations of fluidised beds</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Discrete particle simulations of fluidised beds</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. B.P.B. Hoomans<BR>
Phone: +31-53-42948<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:b.p.b.hoomans@ct.utwente.nl">b.p.b.hoomans@ct.utwente.nl</A><BR>
<B>WWW:</B> <A HREF="http://www.ct.utwente.nl/~pk/hoomans.html">http://www.ct.utwente.nl/~pk/hoomans.html</A><BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

A discrete particle model has been
developed for the description of the
dynamics of gas-fiuidised beds. The
motion of the particles is directly
calculated from the forces acting on them
whilst inter-particle interactions are taken
into account. The particles are assumed to
interact through instantaneous, binary,
inelastic    collisions
with    friction.
Simulation techniques
from hard-sphere
simulations, which
are commonly
encountered in Molecular Dynamics, are
used to process a sequence of collisions.
The gas phase is modeled by instationary
conservation laws of mass and momentum.
This novel simulation technique offers a
unique possibility to study the influence of
the particle characteristics on the bed-hydrodynamics in great detail.<P>

<B>Aims of the project</B><P>

This project is a cooperation with the
Chemical Physics group of Dr. W.J. Briels.
An effort will be made to calculate
macroscopic properties of the particles (i.e.
viscosity)    from    three-dimensional
simulations at a microscopic level.<P>

Furthermore the two-dimensional model
will be extended
to a full three-dimensional version.<P>

Experimental validation of the models is of
crucial importance and will be part of the
project as well.<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

Bubble and slug formation at atmospheric
conditions    have    been    simulated
successfully with the two-dimensional
model.<P>

The simulations show a strong dependency
of the bed-hydrodynamics on the key-
parameters of the discrete particle model;
the coefficient of restitution and the
coefficient of friction.<P>

As an example a snapshot of the particle
configuration during the simulation of
bubble formation at a central orifice with
40,000 particles is given in Figure 1.<P>

t = 0.0500 s.<P>

<IMG SRC="hoomans1.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 1. Simulation of bubble formation
at a central orifice in a two-dimensional
bed (0.20 m width, 0.30 m height) with
40,000 particles (Ballotini glass, 850 &#181;m).</I><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
