<HEAD><TITLE>Mass transfer with complex chemical reaction in gas - liquid systems</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Mass transfer with complex chemical reaction in gas - liquid systems</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Rahul D. Vas Bhat<BR>
phone: +31-53-892979<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:r.d.vasbhat@ct.utwente.nl">r.d.vasbhat@ct.utwente.nl</A><BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<CENTER><B>Introduction</B></CENTER><BR>
Gas-liquid consecutive and two-step
reactions have, in the past years, been a
subject of mainly empirical and semi-
empirical studies These studies have
made assumptions that are not
observed in industrial practice
including isothermal absorption,
irreversibility of reactions and non-
volatility of the liquid phase. It is the
aim of this project to overcome these
shortfalls using detailed modelling and
experimental validation so that a better
understanding of the actual mass
transfer phenomenon may be obtained.
In addition, the knowledge obtained is
to be applied in understanding and
improving a running industrial process.
For this the manufacture of
monochloroacetic acid (MCA) has
been selected as a model system.<P>

<CENTER><B>Mathematical Modelling</B></CENTER><BR>
The flux model presented by <I>Versteeg
et al. (1989)</I><SUP>1</SUP> has been modified to
study reversible consecutive and two-
step reactions of general orders. At this
stage only isothermal absorption has
been modelled. As an example typical
results for consecutive reactions are
presented in <I>Figure 1</I>. The influence of
the reversibility on the enhancement
factor is clearly observed.<BR>
In addition, cases dealing with unequal
diffusivities of the reactants and loaded
solutions have also been investigated.<P>

<CENTER><B>Experimental Aspects</B></CENTER><BR>
Results obtained from the model need
to be experimentally verified. This is to
be done using model chemical systems,
namely, chlorination of p-cresol
(consecutive) and chlorine absorption
in NaOH (two-step).<P>

<IMG SRC="bhat1.gif"><P>

<FONT SIZE=-1><I>Figure l: Consecutive reversible reaction with
equilibrium constants Keql and Keq2.</I></FONT><P>

A stirred cell and a laminar jet reactor
have been set-up for this purpose. They
are presently being debugged using
CO<SUB>2</SUB> absorption in water/NaOH as
model systems.<BR>
As for the MCA system, initial
experiments with regard to kinetics of
formation are to be carried out after
which a detailed investigation into the
mass transfer aspects will be made. For
this a pilot plant is being constructed in
close co-operation with Akzo Nobel,
Hengelo.<P>

<CENTER><B>Future Direction</B></CENTER><BR>
Non-isothermal gas absorption will be
modelled. In addition, flux modelling
of the MCA system is to be carried out
which should give valuable insight into
the choice and operation of the reactor
best suited for manufacture of MCA.
Physical parameters required for
modelling this system will be
experimentally obtained including
vapor-liquid equilibrium data, kinetic
constants at the operating temperature
and diffusion coefficients.<P>

<SUP>1</SUP> <I>Chem. Engng. Sci., 1989</I>, <B>44</B>, 2295-2310<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
