<HEAD><TITLE>Mass transfer in (non-isothermal, chemically reactive) gas - liquid processes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Mass transfer in (non-isothermal, chemically reactive) gas - liquid processes</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. M.J.W. Frank<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> SON<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In this project the use of the Maxwell-Stefan (MS) theory for describing mass transfer
processes accompanied by heat effects and chemical reaction is studied. The Maxwell-Stefan
theory equals the driving forces and the resistance forces on each component and takes into
account all binary interactions. Especially for highly concentrated gas-liquid or vapour-liquid
systems, e.g. (reactive) distillation and absorption of a highly soluble gas into a liquid, it is
believed that the Maxwell-Stefan theory should be used instead of the classical Fick's law for
describing mass transfer.<P>

<B>Aims of the project</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>developing a transfer model (see figure 1), which can predict mass and heat transfer rates
through a vapour/gas-liquid interface in case a reversible chemical reaction with associated heat
effect takes place in the liquid using the Maxwell-Stefan theory.
<LI>implementing this transfer model into a stage model. With this stage model it is possible to
develop a column model, e.g. for describing a reactive distillation column. This last step will
however not be carried out as the study is concentrated on the fundamental aspects of the
transfer processes.
<LI>evaluating the Maxwell-Stefan theory by making calculations with the transfer model and
comparing the results with the results in case Fick's law is used.
<LI>experimental verification of the MS theory by carrying out experiments in a stirred cell where
NH<SUB>3</SUB> is absorbed into water. In this system heat effects play an important role and high
concentrations of the transported component will be encountered, which may necessitate the
use of the MS theory.
<LI>experimental verification of the MS theory for absorption of gas into organic solvents by
carrying out experiments in a stirred cell where NH<SUB>3</SUB> is absorbed into methanol.
</UL>

<B>Results</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Numerical simulations showed that Fick's law is not able to describe physical gas absorption
into a liquid mixture in case the gas has a high solubility, necessitating a drift correction, which
is present implicitly in the Maxwell-Stefan equation.
<LI>Numerical simulations showed that in case the MS-equation is used for describing mass
transfer with chemical reaction in a gas-liquid system the classical expressions for the
enhancement factor of mass transfer due to chemical reaction in the liquid phase, can still be
<LI>Absorption experiments of ammonia into water in a stirred cell showed that the MS-theory
predicts the mass transfer rates within 10% whereas Fick's law show errors up to 40% (see
figure 2).
</UL>

<IMG SRC="mfrank1.gif"><P>

<I>Figure l</I>.Schematic representation of the region near
the gas-liquid interface in terms of the film model.<P>

<IMG SRC="mfrank2.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 2</I>.1nfluence of liquid flow rate on absorption
flux of NH<SUB>3</SUB> in water. T = 25&#176;C, N<SUB>L</SUB> = 1 s<SUP>-1</SUP>.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
