<HEAD><TITLE>Mass transfer with chemical reaction in a G-L-L system</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Mass transfer with chemical reaction in a G-L-L system</H2>

Ir. D.W.F. Brilman<P>

tel.: 053-4893046<BR>
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:d.w.f.brilman@ct.utwente.nl">d.w.f.brilman@ct.utwente.nl</A><P>

Sponsor: SHELL (KSLA) / Twente University<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

A special case of multiphase reaction systems is the gas-liquid-liquid reaction system. Though
not very common, this reaction system can be found in large scale applications such as
hydroformylation, SHOP and hydrocarboxylation (Koch synthesis). These processes are all
commercialized succesfully. However, the fundamentals of the processes of mass transfer and
chemical reaction in these systems are not fully understood.<BR>
<I><B>Scope</B></I> of this project is to gain more insight in the processes of mass transfer with complex
chemical reaction in a gas-liquid-liquid system.<BR>
The Koch reaction { alkene (org.) + CO (g) + H<SUB>2</SUB>0 (aq) --> carboxylic acid } is chosen as an
industrial relevant demonstration system.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><P>

<UL>
<LI>Determination of the reaction kinetics and -mechanism of the demonstration system
<LI>Study of mass transfer in a gas-liquid-liquid system and
development of techniques for determination of mass transfer parameters
<LI>Model development for mass transfer and mass transfer with chemical reaction in a
gas-liquid-liquid system
</UL>

<B>Experimental work</B><P>
The Koch synthesis of pivalic acid is being studied using a high pressure autoclave, sulfuric
acid as catalyst system and an isobutene and (iso-)butanol feedstock. Influence of CO
pressure, temperature and catalyst composition and mixing is studied. The rate of protonation
and side reactions (in absence of co) are studied in a standard stirred cell contactor.<P>

A study of the mass transfer characteristics will be initiated in the near future. Some aspects of
this study involve RTD-studies, (simultaneous) determination of interfacial areas and the
effect of the presence of a dispersed liquid phase on micromixing behavior.<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

Preliminary results from the kinetic work show almost no influence of CO-pressure in the
range 20-70 bar CO on the rate of carboxylic acid formation from isobutanol, indicating that
CO-addition to the carbocation ( or -/catalyst complex) is not rate-determining.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
