<HEAD><TITLE>A catalytic membrane reactor for partial oxidation reactions</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>A catalytic membrane reactor for partial oxidation reactions</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. Hein Neomagus (053-4894338)<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Prof. dr. ir. Geert Versteeg (053-4893027)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> March 1994 - March 1998<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> GASTEC NV Apeldoorn<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

In the past years, a new type of membrane reactor has been developed. This reactor
is largely made up of two chambers, separated by a (catalytic active) membrane.
The reactants are introduced into the reactor on opposite sides of this membrane,
and will diffuse into the membrane, where they meet and will react. An advantage
of this way of operating is the great ability of self-regulation of the process, so that
this reactor is suited for reactions, where a
stringent stoichiometric flow of reactants
is required. A second advantage of this
reactor is that neither thermal runaways
nor explosive gas mixtures can occur.
This property makes the reactor attractive
for processing of fast, heterogeneous,
exothermic reactions.<P>

<IMG SRC="neomagus1.gif"><P>

A third application is to perform a partial
oxidation reaction in the reactor. Partial
oxidation reactions are carried out when
the desired component is an intermediar
in a sequence of reactions. It may be
possible to influence the selectivity of the
reaction, by inducting a pressure
difference between the two chambers. A
higher pressure on the 'oxidation-side' of the membrane causes the already
produced (and desired) products to be driven away from the oxidation zone and
therefore to be protected against further oxidation into undesired products (see
figure). After a kinetic research the partial oxidation of isobutene to methacrolein
and methacrylic acid is chosen as a model reaction to prove this principle:<P>

<IMG SRC="neomagus2.gif"><P>

The membrane reactor has also proven to be a successful catalytic burner for
methane and a deep investigation will now be done to clarify whether this reactor is
also a possible altemative for performing the partial oxidation of methane to
syngas, which is another interesting way to convert methane.<P>

<IMG SRC="neomagus3.gif"><P>

The transport phenomena occurring in the porous membrane are described by the
Dusty Gas Model based on Maxwell-Stefan diffusion.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B29-319</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000119-B028-213</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost95/ut/huizenga.html 130.89.50.60 19970216194231 text/html 3489
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 19:35:55 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
