</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Modular membrane slurry reactor</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Modular membrane slurry reactor</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> ir. P. Huizenga (053-4892890)<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> dr. ir. J.A.M. Kuipers (053-4893039)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> November 1993-November 1997<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> OSPT<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<I><B>General Project Description</B></I><P>

Slurry reactors have found widespread application for gas/liquid/solids contacting operations in the
chemical industries. The most important advantages of this reactor type are its excellent heat transfer
characteristics and the possibility of using relatively small particles. Further application is mainly
hampered by difficulties encountered in scale-up and particle separation from the liquid.<P>

The main goal of the research project is the development and description of a novel kind of reactor. This
type of reactor is expected to circumvent the problems mentioned before. The crux of the concept is a
modular configuration in which reaction and separation are performed simultaneously. Of the vast
number of configurations that could be envisaged, there is
one which seems very attractive. In this configuration, each
unit is box-shaped and possesses two permeable walls,
which retain the particles. Gas is fed to the bottom, while
liquid passes the unit in cross-flow. The configuration
developed allows countercurrent operation of the fluid
phases and easy plug flow approximation (tanks in series).
In first instance the project focuses on the description of a
single unit. This approach fits well into one of the central
research themes of the OSPT; small scale development of
industrial scale reactors.<P>

<IMG SRC="huizenga1.gif"><P>

<I><B>Progress</B></I><P>

<I>* Hydrodynamics:</I><BR>
A model has been developed describing the distribution of the solid phase between the cake layer on
the membrane and the slurry bulk. The model is based on a combination of penetration theory,
viscous resuspension theory and Kolmogoroff's theory of isotropic turbulence. This model has been
validated by performing experiments in a small gas/liquid fluidised bed with a permeable wall. In
these experiments the influence of gas velocity, permeate flux and liquid viscosity on the cake
resistance has been determined. Their simultaneous influence is reasonably well described by the
dimensionless number derived on the basis of the theory described above. The independence of filter
cake build-up on gas phase density also has been demonstrated by varying the molar mass of the
injected gas (He, N<SUB>2</SUB>, SF<SUB>6</SUB>). This result is also predicted by the theory developed.<P>

<I>* Chemical Reaction:</I><BR>
An inventarisation and characterisation of relevant industrial processes has been made. This involves
a.o. applicability of a membrane slurry reactor to the various processes. Also, a number of potentially
interesting reactor concepts have been generated. Finally, the applicability of the model reaction
chosen as a tool for measuring mass transfer has been proven.<P>

