<HEAD><TITLE>Coated adsorbents for pressure swing adsorption</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Coated adsorbents for pressure swing adsorption</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Drs Rick van der Vaart (053-4892876)<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Dr Ir Hans Bosch (053-4892862)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> December 1992-December 1996<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> SON/STW<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Objective</B><BR>
The last two decades have seen a tremendous
growth in research activities in the field of
adsorptive gas separation. One of the main
topics is the development of more selective
adsorbents [1]. This research attempts to
demonstrate the enhanced selectivity of coated
adsorbents. The availability of such a modified
adsorbent would make Pressure Swing
Adsorption (PSA) applicable to the separation
of a wider range of gas mixtures.<P>

<B>Introduction</B><P>
A mass transfer model is developed for a coated
tablet, which gives an impression of the
adsorption kinetics of coated adsorbents. The
experimental program focuses on the separation
of CH<SUB>4</SUB> and CO<SUB>2</SUB> with the following membrane
coatings on activated carbon tablets:<BR>
· cellulose acetate<BR>
· silicone rubber<BR>
· zeolite<BR>
The mass transfer model also incorporates mass
transfer resistance in the adsorbent. Therefore
also the kinetics of non-coated activated carbon
is being investigated<P>

<B>Modelling</B><BR>
The model takes both membrane resistance and
resistance inside the adsorbent tablet into
account. The accumulation inside the membrane
is being neglected and the extended Langmuir
equation is used for the accumulation in the
carbon particles that compose the tablet. Those
small (r<16 &#181;m) carbon particles are assumed to
be at equilibrium with the gas phase inside the
coated tablet. Both diffusive and viscous flow is
accounted for in the tablet gas phase.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
An extended experimental program to test the
model is executed. So far the model was
compared to the gravimetrical uptake
measurement of single gas carbon dioxide in a
cellulose acetate coated activated carbon tablet
for a pressure step from 1000-1010 mbar. The
membrane permeability was measured
separately prior to the kinetic measurement. The
experimental uptake curve and the calculated
curve are presented in Figure 1.<P>

<IMG SRC="rick1.gif"><P>

Figure 1. Experimental and calculated CO<SUB>2</SUB>
uptake curve for cellulose acetate
coated activated carbon after a
pressure step of 1000 to 1010 mbar.<P>

In Figure 2 the calculated selectivity of a coated
activated carbon to an equimolar mixture of
methane an carbon dioxide is plotted as a
function of time for several values of the
membrane permeability. The non-coated
activated carbon selectivity amounts to two. The
membrane selectivity is 15. The gain in
selectivity is obvious.<P>

<IMG SRC="rick2.gif"><P>

Figure 2. Coated activated carbon selectivity at
different membrane permeability (P/d
[mol/m<SUP>2</SUP>.s. Pa]; 1) 3*10<SUP>-7</SUP>; 2) 3(10<SUP>-8</SUP>;
3) 3*10<SUP>-8</SUP>.<P>

<B>Conclusion</B><BR>
Model calculations of the selectivity of coated
adsorbents show a promising gain in selectivity
compared to non-coated adsorbents.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
