<HEAD><TITLE>Isotherms from temperature-programmed desorption experiments</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Isotherms from temperature-programmed desorption experiments</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> vacature<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> dr. ir. H.Bosch (+31 (53)4892862)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> 1996-1999<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> SON<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
A new TPD method to determine a series of adsorption
isotherms from a limited number of experiments is investigated. It combines two older methods:
<UL>
<LI>a flow method for the measurement of adsorption isotherms, and
<LI>temperature-programmed reduction for the evaluation of
activation energies.
</UL>
The basic idea is to calculate the adsorption isotherm parameters from exit concentration profiles, which result from a
continuous temperature rise at a constant feed composition.<P>

<B>Objective</B><BR>
The goal of this research is to obtain reliable values of equilibrium adsorption model parameters from a small number
of dynamic TPD experiments.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
The adsorption of CO<SUB>2</SUB>/He mixtures on an activated carbon
(RB1, courtesy Norit) was studied in a packed bed. Prior
to a TPD run the isothermal breakthrough was used to determine the quantity adsorbed at the starting temperature.
During a TPD run the exit concentration was continuously
monitored as a function of a linear increase in temperature,
the feed composition was kept constant. Static gravimetric
and volumetric adsorption isotherms of CO2 were measured
for reference purposes.<P>

<B>Model</B><P>
The TPD response curves were modelled using a differential
mole balance equation:<P>

<IMG SRC="vacature1.gif"><P>

<B>Parameter determination</B><BR>
All modelled TPD response curves were fitted simultaneously to the experimental data to obtain dH and q<SUB>m</SUB>. b<SUB>0</SUB>
was calculated using the initial breakthrough experiments.<P>

<IMG SRC="vacature2.gif"><P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
TPD response curves and the modelling results are given in
Figure 1 for the experiments without mass transfer limitation. The feed mole fraction, the total flowrate, the heating rate and carbon particle diameter were varied. The
resulting values of the Langmuir parameters are: dH =
-28.3 kJ/mol, q<SUB>m</SUB> = 1.78 mol/kg, b<SUB>0</SUB> = 4.92.10<SUP>-7</SUP> kPa<SUP>-1</SUP>.

In Figure 2 TPD adsorption isotherms are compared with
reference results. As the latter were obtained from several laboratories, by different techniques and on different
samples from the same batch, the reference adsorption data
and TPD-Langmuir model agree well.<P>

<B>Conclusion</B><BR>
The heat of adsorption and the other parameters of a suit-
able simple adsorption model can be obtained from a small
number of TPD experiments.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
