<HEAD><TITLE>Flux enhancement of ultrafiltration membrane modules</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Flux enhancement of ultrafiltration membrane modules</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> ir. Jan Ophoff<BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> NWO/STW, Stork Friesland B.V.<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The membrane flux in Ultrafiltration and Microfiltration membrane modules is limited by concentration polarisation and fouling. To diminish these phenomena, cross flow velocity could be increased or turbulence promoters could be used. Both leads to a higher energy consumption.<BR>
A very promising method is to introduce vortices by centrifugal forces, e.g. in an annular gap between a stationary and a rotating cylinder (Taylor vortices) or in a curved pipe flow (Dean vortices).<P>

<B>Curved pipe flow</B><BR>
Vortices reduce the hydrodynamic boundary layer thickness and enhance the convective mixing between the bulk flow and the mass transfer boundary layer.<BR>
Consequently, the concentration polarisation and the fouling diminish. The advantage of these Dean vortices is that they are generated by the flow itself (no moving parts in the membrane module).<P>

<B>Flux increase</B><BR>
In literature, different researchers claim an  improvement of heat transfer or membrane flux, caused by centrifugal effects. They are listed in the table below.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
Based on the above, we developed a new membrane module. This concept is being patented. Preliminary results show a 
flux increase of 40 % for ultrafiltration membranes at Re = 1000, lambda = 0.005; f<SUB>c</SUB>/f<SUP>s</SUP> < 1.05.<P>

<IMG SRC="jan1.gif"><P>
 
<FONT SIZE="-1">In this table, l is the curvature ratio defined by: lambda = R<SUB>pipe</SUB> / R<SUB>curvature</SUB>;<BR>
f<SUB>c</SUB>/f<SUB>s</SUB> is the increase of the friction coefficient; the improvement factor is based on the increase of the Nusselt number or the flux increase compared to straight pipe conditions.</FONT><P>

<HR SIZE=0>

<PRE>
Address:University of Twente,
	dept. of 	Chemical Engineering
	P.O. box  217,7500 AE  Enschede
	The Netherlands
e-mail:	<A HREF="mailto:J.P.vanthul@ct.utwente.nl">j.ophoff@ct.utwente.nl</A>
fax: 	+31(0)53 489 48 21
</PRE><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 13/03/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
