<HEAD><TITLE>Cleaning of hard surfaces by aqueous detergent flows</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Cleaning of hard surfaces by aqueous detergent flows</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. Sander Rekveld (+31-53-4892930)<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Dr. ir. Imre G. R&aacute;cz (+31-53-4893019)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> October 1992 - October 1996<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Unilever Research Vlaardingen<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The cleaning of non-porous solid surfaces by a flowing
cleaning solution, is a process that is encountered
frequently in industrial and household practice, e.g., dish
washing or the cleaning of heat exchangers.<BR>
Current knowledge of the effect of hydrodynamics and
mass transfer on the removal of soil layers, especially
proteins, is largely empirical. Therefore, to increase the
understanding of removal processes in general, and of the
effect of aqueous flow on removal in particular,
experiments providing measurements of removal of soil
under defined hydrodynamic conditions are necessary.<BR>
A sensitive optical technique, dynamic in situ ellipso-
metry is used to monitor the removal of soil layers on
the molecular level. A parallel plate flow cell is used to
achieve defined flow conditions. The effect of surfactants
on the removal is also investigated.<P>

<B>Objective</B><BR>
The development of a mathematical model incorporating
mass transfer, surface reaction and hydrodynamics. The
model will be developed on the basis of measurements
of in situ removal in a parallel plate flow cell, because
no measurements under defined flow conditions, are
available in the literature.<P>

<B>Theory</B><BR>
The adsorption and desorption of proteins and their
removal by surfactants is modelled as a heterogeneous
reaction of the protein and surfactant molecules with the
surface.<P>

<IMG SRC="sander1.gif"><P>

for the surface concentration and<P>

<IMG SRC="sander2.gif"><P>

for the bulk concentration. With a the specific area
[l/m], the surface conc.[mole/m^2], c the bulk
conc.[mole/m^3], k the rate const.[m^2/mole/s] & [l/s]
resp., v the velocity in the x direction[m/s] and D the
diffusion coefficient[m^2/s].<BR>
The rate constants of the surface reaction are predicted
using the free energy of adhesion, as determined from
contact angle measurements on the surfaces and the
Sherwood number of the parallel plate channel.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
<I>Materials</I><BR>
Three types of model surfaces are used:<BR>
· Silicon dioxide surfaces; oxidised silicon wafers.<BR>
· Polymer surfaces; spin coated onto glass.<BR>
· Metal surfaces; vacuum deposited chromium.<BR>
Fibrinogen a blood protein is applied by spontaneous
adsorption from 300 mg/l solutions.<BR>
C<SUB>12</SUB>EO<SUB>5</SUB> a non-ionic surfactant is used to remove the
fibrinogen.<P>

<I>Methods</I><BR>
Total reflection ellipsometry is used to monitor the
adsorption and removal of fibrinogen from the surfaces.
The preparation of the surfaces is critical in obtaining
reproducible results. Therefore, after cleaning the
surfaces are characterised using both ellipsometry to
determine the optical properties and contact angle
measurements.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
The reproducible preparation of the surfaces and
application of the soil layers onto surfaces of different
surface energy is now possible.<BR>
Calculation of the free energy of adhesion between
surfaces and soil layers is possible from contact angle
measurements.<BR>
The experimental technique ellipsometry to measure the
thickness of the soil layer has been modified for our
parallel plate geometry<BR>
Preliminary time resolved in situ experiments during a
cleaning process from chromium surfaces in parallel
plate flow show complete removal of the fibrinogen
layer by C<SUB>12</SUB>EO<SUB>5</SUB> if equal concentration of protein and
surfactant are used.<BR>
More measurements are necessary to build and verify the
model equations.<P>

<B>References</B><BR>
van Oss, C. J. (1994). Interfacial Interactions in Aqueous
Media. New York, Marcel Dekker, Inc.<P>

<B>Acknowledgements</B><BR>
This project in sponsored and supported by Unilever
Research Vlaardingen.<P>

<SUP>*</SUP>) University of Twente, P.O. Box 217, 7500 AE, Netherlands. E-mail S.Rekveld@ctutwente.nl Phone +31-53 -4892930 Fax +31-53 - 4894821<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
