<HEAD><TITLE>Recycling of process streams in the textile industry using membranes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<IMG SRC="hul.gif" ALIGN=right>

<H2>Recycling of process streams in the textile industry using membranes</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. J.P. van t Hul<SUP>*</SUP><BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Dr.Ir. I.G. R&aacute;cz<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> March 1994 - March 1998<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Ministry of Economic Affairs (IOP-prevention)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<IMG SRC="hul1.gif"><P>

<HR SIZE=0>
 
<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In the textile industry a large amount of water and chemicals are used in order to meet the desired product qualities. This causes waste water, which is now usually treated in a municipal water purification. In the future this will be confronted with cost increment and restrictions. <P>

<B>Objective</B><BR>
The overall objective of this IOP prevention programme is to minimise the use of chemicals, water and energy. Membranes can be used for two purposes. Firstly process water and its energy can be recycled. Secondly waste can be concentrated for further treatment. Unfortunatelly a membrane process shows an unwanted flux decline in time. This complicates the design of such processes. The special objective of this research is to study this flux decline.<P>

<B>Preliminary results</B><BR>
The washing process after the dyeing process, where unfixed dyes are washed out has been chosen as topic of study. Calculations on the flowsheet of a modified   washing-process by using membranes (shown in the picture above)  showed a possible water saving of 70 percent compared to the original process.<P>


<B>Further research on membrane modules</B><BR>
An experimental unit has been constructed for testing membrane modules. Nanofiltration and reverse osmosis membranes in both spiral wound and tubular configuration can be used. By using two pumps the transmembrane pressure and the crossflow velocity can be varied independently. Flux decline can be described in terms of membrane compaction, concentration polarisation and / or fouling.<P>

<SUP>*</SUP> University of Twente, P.O. box 217, 7500 AE Enschede, Netherlands.<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:J.P.vanthul@ct.utwente.nl">J.P.vanthul@ct.utwente.nl</A> Phone 053-4892930 Fax: 053-4894821<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 12/03/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
