<HEAD><TITLE>Rapid pressure swing adsorption</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Rapid pressure swing adsorption</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> ir. Frank Foeth (+31(53)4892876)<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> dr. ir. H. Bosch<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> 1 June 1991 - 1 June 1996<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> eerste geldstroom<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Rapid Pressure Swing Adsorption is a cyclic
gas separation process in which each cycle
consists of three consecutive steps:<BR>
1. valve I open, valve 2 closed (feed step)<BR>
2. valve 1 closed, valve 2 closed (delay step)<BR>
3. valve 1 closed, valve 2 open (exhaust step)<BR>
A continuous product stream leaves the column.
The sequence generates pressure and
concequently concentration fronts which move
through the bed and effective separation is
achieved. Cycle times are 20 s or less.<P>

<IMG SRC="frank1.gif"><P>

<U>Basic process set-up</U><P>

The separation of methane from carbon dioxide
is investigated, which is important, e.g., in the
production of synthetic natural gas from landfill
gas. Heat effects are large and need to be taken
into account to describe this process.<P>


<B>Goal</B><BR>
To determine the influence of the various step
times, the type of adsorbent used and the feed
flow rate on the methane recovery and purity.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
Feed and delay times proved to be very im-
portant parameters. Some methane purity and
recovery results are shown in the contour plots
(points are actual measurements, total cycle time
= 6 seconds).<P>

<IMG SRC="frank2.gif"><P>

At longer cycle times, but at the same feed and
delay times (not shown) the puritiy is higher
and the recovery is lower.<P>

Decreasing the regeneration pressure in the
exhaust step improves the CH<SUB>4</SUB>/CO<SUB>2</SUB> separation.<P>

The RPSA process, including volumes of
vessels and flow resistances in valves, has been
modelled successfully. The numerical method
of lines was used to solve the resulting system
of partial differential equations. Special
features, e.g., sigmoid curves to simulate the
opening and closing of the valves and bi-
directional difference procedures were incorp-
orated to improve the stability of the calculation.<P>

<B>Project completion</B><BR>
The experimental program is being concluded
The resulting PhD thesis will be finished by
spring 1996.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
