<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Determination of non-flux-decline regions during ultra- and microfiltration</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Determination of non-flux-decline regions during ultra- and microfiltration</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. Emile Cornelissen (053-892957)<BR>
<B>Supervisor :</B> Dr. ir. Thonie van den Boomgaard (053-892965)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> November 1992 - November 1996<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Unilever Research Vlaardingen<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>1 Introduction</B><BR>
Membrane fouling is a common phenomenon during the application of crossflow micro- and ultrafiltration membranes. This fouling is partly reversible and partly irreversible and results in flux decline.<BR>
In this work a non-flux-decline regime bounded by the so-called critical transmembrane pressure is identified, in which membrane fouling can be <I>avoided</I>. The current research is focused on the dependency of this critical transmembrane pressure on membrane related factors such as membrane material and mean pore sizes.<P>

<B>2 Theory</B><BR>
As long as no fouling occurs, the permeate flux is linearly dependent on the transmembrane pressure. The pressure at which deviation of Darcy's equation occurs will be called the critical transmembrane pressure (dP<SUB>c</SUB>). At pressures larger than dP<SUB>c</SUB>, a limiting flux J<SUB>lim</SUB> is reached eventually if the resistance of the fouling layer is larger than the membrane resistance, which is usually the case in practical situations (Sridhar 1991; Field 1993) . With these two parameters the fouling can be described. The non-flux-decline region, however, can be described by only dP<SUB>c</SUB>.<P>

<B>3 Experimental part</B><P>

<I>3.1 Set-up</I><BR>
A cross flow microfiltration set-up was used in which the pressure and the cross flow velocity could be independently changed, by respectively  2 pumps. The permeate flow was collected in a vessel on a balance. When the permeate vessel was full, it was added again to the feed vessel.<BR>
A  flat plate type membrane cell was used with a rectangular feed channel (L = 140 mm, w = 20 mm and h = 1.6 mm). The cross-flow velocity is kept constant at v = 0.1 m/s (Re = 300).<P>

<I>3.2 Materials</I><BR>
Two different membrane materials were selected for filtration experiments; polysulfone (PSf) and polyvinylidenefluoride (PVDF). The following ultra- and microfiltration membranes were examined:<BR>
* PSf 50 kDa - 0.2 mm<BR>
* PVDF 10 kDa - 0.1 mm<BR>
A standard emulsion of Castor oil stabilised by a nonionic surfactant (polyoxyethylene(9)nonylphenol (POE-9np) from ICI) was prepared with a mean droplet size of d32 = 0.22 mm.<BR>

<I>3.3 Method</I><BR>
Pure water fluxes were determined at a transmembrane pressure of 2 bar for two hours, before and after the emulsion filtration experiments. Emulsion filtration experiments were performed at different pressures. At a pressure of 0.1 bar the cup mixing permeate flux was measured for 15 minutes. This procedure was repeated for each pressure increase of approx. 0.1 bar until 1 bar was reached.<P>

<B>4 Results and discussion</B><BR>
A typical result of an emulsion filtration experiment is depicted in figure 1 for the PSf membrane with a mean pore diameter of 0.18 &#181;m.<P>

<IMG SRC="emile1.gif"><P>
  
<I><B>Figure 1</B> Experimental fluxes versus time and  versus various pressures for a 0.1 mm PSf membrane pressure</I><BR>

From these figures two characteristic parameters can be obtained, i.e. the critical transmembrane pressure dP<SUB>c</SUB> and the limiting flux J<SUB>lim</SUB>. Below the critical pressure no flux decline is observed in time, as can be seen in figure 1.<BR>
The flux recovery (FR) was calculated as the ratio of the pure water flux after and before filtration, and it is a measure for the amount of irreversible fouling. For a flux recovery value of one, no permanent fouling occurs.<BR>
From figure 2a it can be seen that the critical transmembrane pressure (dP<SUB>c</SUB>) decreases with increasing mean pore diameter for both PSf and PVDF membranes. From these observations a correlation was found between dP<SUB>c</SUB> and FR (see figure 2b).<P>

<IMG SRC="emile2.gif"><P>
  
<I><B>Figure 2a</B> Critical transmembrane pressure versus the mean pore diameter</I><BR>
<I><B>Figure 2b</B>  Relation between the flux recovery and the critical transmembrane pressure</I><BR>

Furthermore from figure 2a it can be found that the critical transmembrane pressures for PVDF are lower than for PSf. This indicates that fouling is more severe for PVDF membranes than for PSf membranes.<P>

<B>5 Conclusion</B><BR>
A non-flux-decline region bounded by a critical transmembrane pressure can be found for the investigated membranes.<BR>
The non-flux-decline region increases if the mean pore size of the membrane decreases. Also the flux recovery increases with decreasing mean pore size, suggesting less permanent fouling.<BR>
The non-flux-decline region is larger for the polysulfone membranes than for the polyvinylidenefluoride membranes.<P>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Acknowledgements</B><BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1">The authors are grateful for the membrane samples supplied by dr. F.F. Stengaard from Dow Denmark Separation.</FONT><P>

<B>Literature</B><BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1">Field, R.W. (1993), Transport processes in membrane systems, Membranes in bioprocessing : Theory & Practice. J.A. Howell and R.W. Field, Glasgow, Blackie academic.<BR>
Sridhar, S. and P.K. Bhattacharya (1991), "Limiting flux phenomena in ultrafiltration of kraft black liquor", J. Membrane Sci. <B>57</B>: 187-206.</FONT><P>

