<HEAD><TITLE>Cyclonic small particle reactor with integrated filter</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Cyclonic small particle reactor with integrated filter</H2>

<B>AIO:</B> Ir. H. van der Veide (phone 053-4892530)<BR>
<B>Post doc:</B> Ir. E.A. Bramer<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> IOP-MT/Recycling<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

The rotational particle seperator is a new device capable to seperate small particles in a
very efficient way even at high temperatures. The RPS is composed of a cyclonic part and
an integrated filter element collecting the smallest particles. Considerable collection
efficiencies can be achieved for particles downto 0.1 micron. Because of the high
collection efficiency for micron particles the cyclonic part of the RPS can be used as a
reactor for small particles. Using small particles short reaction/capture times are achieved
resulting a compact reactor type. The working principle (three stages) can be explained as
follows.<P>

<IMG SRC="velde1.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><P>

<UL>
<LI>Injection of reactive particles into the polluted
gas stream at the inlet of the RPS.
<LI>Reaction/adsorption of the gaseous pollutants
with/on the small particles in the cyclone of the
RPS.
<LI>Separation of the reacted particles by the
cyclone and filter element of the RPS.
</UL>

The research project consists of the following parts
<UL>
<LI>High temperature dust cleaning of pyrolysis gases
<LI>Dehalogenation of pyrolysis gasses at high tempertaure
<LI>Cleaning of proces flows using powdered activated carbon
<LI>The development of a mathematical reactor model of the RPS (fluid
dynamics, mass transfer and reaction in a single particle)
</UL>

Results of the removal of HCI using
slaked lime are shown below. Depicted is
the conversion of HCI as a function of
the molar ratio Ca/CI. High conversions
of HCI are possible at short residence
times and small molar ratios.<P>

<IMG SRC="velde2.gif"><P>

Calculated separation efficiencies as a
function of flow for the cyclonic part
and the filter element of a RPS is given
in the figure below.<P>

<IMG SRC="velde3.gif"><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
