<HEAD><TITLE>Evaluation of the rotating gas cleaner</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Evaluation of the rotating gas cleaner</H2>

<B>Twaio:</B> Ir. J. Hajer<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> It. E.A. Bramer and Ir. H. van der Velde<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Ministry of Economic Affairs (IOP-prevention)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<IMG SRC="hajer1.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 1 The Rotating Gas Cleaner</I><P>

<B>Introduction</B><P>
A new technique for seperating small particles
from a gas stream is the Rotating Particle Separator (RPS).
 The main separation element of
a RPS is a rotating filter element. The filter
element consists of many axial channels with a
small hydraulic diameter parallel to the axis of
rotation. The gas, loaded with particles flows
through these channels. The particels migrate
towards the wall, due the centrifugal force.
With the RPS it is possible to clean gas flows
with high collection efficiency for particles of
approximately 0.1 &#181;m and larger.<BR>
When a cyclone is placed before the filterelement
 it is possible to use the RPS as a reactor
for gas cleaning (figure 1). At the inlet of the
cyclone, activated carbon, as a very fine pow-
der, is injected to a polluted gas. In the cyclone,
 the pollution (for example hydrocarbons)
is adsorbing to the activated carbon. In the
cyclone and in the rotating filter element the
loaded activated carbon is separated from the
gas. Clean gas leaves the reactor at the top,
the loaded activated carbon at the bottom. The
time, nessesary for reaching adsorption-equilibrium,
is very small because:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>small particles have a large specific area.
<LI>through the turbulent flow in the cyclone
the mass transfer in the gas fase is very fast.
<LI>the residence time of the particles in the
cyclone is large through the flow profile in
the cyclone.
</UL>
This leads to small reactor volumes of the Rotating
Gas Cleaner (RGC).<P>

<B>Aim</B><P>
The project is split in two parts:<BR>
<OL>
<LI>An economic evaluation between processes
where activated carbon is already used for
gas cleaning and new processes where activated
carbon is used, for gas cleaning, in
combination with the RPS.
<LI>A study on applications of other chemical
processes where it is possible to use micro-
particles in combination with the RPS. Special
 attention is taken to gas-solid reactions
where the conversion is limitated by internal/external
mass transfer. The use of very
small (micron) particles can take away such
limitations.
</OL>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
