<HEAD><TITLE>Exergy analysis in the industry</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Exergy analysis in the industry</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. R.L. Comelissen<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Prof. Dr. Ir. G.G. Hirs<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> Nov. 1993- Nov. 1997<BR>

Chair of Energy Technology<BR>
University of Twente<BR>
+31-53-489 4094<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

Exergy analysis is the combination of
the first and second law of thermo-
dynamics. In an exergy analysis the
losses represented the real losses of
work. Exergy is defined as the
maximum amount of work potential of
a system or a form of energy in relation
to the surrounding environment. The
basis of the exergy analysis has been
developed by the Gouy and Stodola in
a law, which has been named after
them, at the end of the former century.
This law states that the exergy loss
equals the entropy increase multiplied
by the ambient temperature.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><P>

In the industry exergy analysis is mostly
used in the field of electricity
production. In this Ph.D. work exergy
analyses will be used in the other parts
of the industry in which most attention
will be paid to the process industry.
Exergy analyses of industrial plants will
be performed in different case studies.
Difficulties in the method of exergy
analysis will be solved and a uniform
method for exergy analysis will be
developed. A first approach to
integrate life cycle analysis in the
exergy analysis will be made.<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

The first case study of an industrial
plant has been firfished: a crude oil
distillation plant. It has been presented
in the Second Law Analysis of Energy
Systems in Rome [1]. In this study is
shown that the total rational efficiency
of the distillation plant is 0.0518. The
biggest exergy losses are due to the use
of high quality fuel for the production
of middle quality heat and the
dissipation of low quality heat in the
environment. To stop the confusion
about the definition of exergetic
efficiencies a publication has been made
in which the three exergetic definitions
are compared. The advantages and
disadvantages of each method are
discussed. The publication is presented
at JETC IV in Nancy [2].<P>

<B>Future work</B><P>

Several exergy analysis of industrial
plants will be performed. The next one
is an air separation plant. The
integration of life cycle analysis and
exergy analysis will be presented in the
example of a heat exchanger.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1>[1] R.L. Comelissen, G.G. Hirs and T.J.
Kotas, <I>An exergy analysis of an oil distillation
process</I>, Second Law Analysis of Energy
Systems, 417-429, Roma, 1995.<BR>
[2] R.L. Cornelisssen, G.G. Hits and T.J.
Kotas, <I>Different Definitions of Exergetic
Efficiencies</I>, JETC IV, Nancy, 1995.<P>
</FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
