<HEAD><TITLE>Cyclone dipleg flow effects</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Cyclone dipleg flow effects</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. JH. Bouma (053 - 489 40 98)<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Prof.dr.ir. G.G. Hirs (053 - 489 25 30)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> September 1993 - September 1997<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Shell International Oil Products<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Diplegs of gas/solids separators in FCC
reactors and regenerators serve the purpose
of conveying the collected catalyst
downward towards or into a fluidised bed,
whilst simultaneously ensuring the pressure
levels in- and outside the dipleg bottom end
be equal. The nature of the downflow is
largely determined by the mass flow rate, the
particle size distribution, the pressure
difference top-to-bottom, the length and
diameter of the dipleg, and the inlet and
outlet conditions and configurations of the
dipleg.<BR>
The importance of understanding the
phenomena inside the dipleg relate to capital
costs (size of reactor vessels), operational
costs (stable flow reduces possibilities of
catalyst carry-over, thus minimising wear on
downstream components) and product
quality (a diminished carry-under of gas with
catalyst reduces on after-cracking, improving
product quality). Faulty dipleg design made
as a result of poor understanding and
prediction of the flow phenomena can lead to
very costly oversize of catcracker vessels or
to poor performance and reliability of the
unit, which is also highly detrimental to
refinery economics.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The main objective of the study is to improve
substantially by literature search, theoretical
and experimental investigation the
knowledge on the solids flow behaviour in
diplegs as required for correct designing and
operation of diplegs in various applications.
The study will address the flow nature, flow
stability, pressure buildup, gas carry-under,
effects of bottom termination devices, and
the effects of solids and gas properties,
operating conditions and system dimensions.<P>

<B>Experimental facility</B><BR>
In the course of three graduation projects
running up to the current project, a test
facility has been built, in which cracking
catalyst is circulated in a closed loop,
consisting of a buffer vessel, riser, cyclone,
dipleg and receptor vessel. Input parameters
are mass flux, pressure difference top-to-
bottom, dipleg diameter, dipleg termination
and powder properties. Measured quantities
include pressure profile, apparent densities,
gas carry-under, cyclone efficiency, as well
as determination of flow regimes and flow
instabilities.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
The graduation project preceding this project
had already yielded extensive information on
the occurrence of flow regimes and flow
instabilities. During the first year of the
current project, the emphasis has been on
determining the gas carry-under under
varying conditions. In the past year,
measurement of radial concentration and
velocity profiles has been added, using a dual
reflective optical probe with cross-
correlation. A one-dimensional model of
dipleg flow has also been developed, which
shows satisfactory agreement with the
experimental results.<P>

<B>Future work</B><BR>
In the near future, the effect of changing the
powder properties will be studied. Also,
further attention will be paid to the modelling
of dipleg flow.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
