<HEAD><TITLE>Thermodynamic analysis of the advanced energy conversion technologies</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Thermodynamic analysis of the advanced energy conversion technologies</H2>

<B>ir Mikhail Korobitsyn</B><P>

At University of Twente<BR>
Phone: 31-53-489.40.94<BR>
Fax: 31-53-489.36.63<BR>
Email: m.korobitsyn@wb.uwente.nl<P>

At ECN<BR>
Phone: 31-22-456.41.06<BR>
Fax: 31-22-456.34.89<BR>
Email: korobitsyn@ecn.nl<P>
	
<HR SIZE=0>
 
<B>INTRODUCTION</B><P>

In co-operation with the Netherlands Energy Research Foundation ECN a project on advanced energy conversion technologies has been started. The project is funded by the Dutch Energy and Environment Agency NOVEM.<BR>
The objective of the study is as follows: to identify and to develop to a market introduction the new and advanced energy conversion technologies which can provide higher efficiency and lower emissions. The assessment is based both on thermodynamic, and  on economic criteria. The work covers the following subjects:<P>

<B>COMBINED CYCLES</B><P>

No single cycle can provide maximum working temperature while rejecting heat at the lowest possible temperature level. Therefore, in order to approach a higher efficiency, a combined cycle is required with a high-temperature topping cycle and a medium- or low-temperature bottoming cycle. A number of different cycle combinations are listed and assessed in (4). They include systems based on gas turbines, fuel cells, Otto/Diesel and Stirling engines.<P>

<B>COGENERATION</B><P>

Combined generation of heat and power implies production of two different kinds of energy. To analyse the efficiency of a plant they should be brought to a common denominator. A comparative analysis of different criteria is given in (1). Another research subject in this field are the cogeneration schemes with improved flexibility which is accomplished by the use of steam recompression and water flashing.<P>

<B>ADVANCED CYCLES</B><P>

Several cycles were chosen for further consideration, among them: Gas turbine with the air bottoming (2), steam boiler with the air bottoming, an integration scheme of a gas turbine and a municipal solid waste incinerator (4).
In addition, a number of advanced gas turbine cycles are to be analysed. They include gas turbine cycles with partial fuel oxidation, chemically-recuperated gas turbine, and humid air turbine.<P>

<B>PUBLICATIONS</B><P>

<OL>
<LI>Hirs, G.G., Wagener, M.T.P.A., and Korobitsyn, M.A., "Performance Analysis of the Dual Gas Turbine Combined Cycle", in <I>Thermodynamics and the Design, Analysis, and Improvement of Energy Systems</I> (R.Krane, ed.), AES-Vol. 35, pp. 255-259, ASME Publications, 1995.
<LI>Korobitsyn, M.A. and Hirs, G.G., "Analysis of Cogeneration Alternatives", ASME Cogen-Turbo Power Congress, August 23-25, Vienna, Austria, 1995.
<LI>Korobitsyn, M.A., "An inventory of possible new and improved combinations of existing energy conversion technologies", NOVEM Project 248.101-013.1, Final Report, Utrecht, the Netherlands, May 1996.
<LI>Hirs, G.G., Korobitsyn, M.A., and Jellema, P., "Integration of a Gas Turbine and a Municipal Waste Incinerator", PowerGen America '96 Conference, Orlando, Florida, December 1996 (to be published).
</OL>

