<HEAD><TITLE>Municipal solid waste combustion</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Municipal solid waste combustion</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. R. Gort (053-892597/055-493289)<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Ir. M. Valk/Dr. ir. G. Brem (053-892558/055-493290)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> 1991 - 1995<BR>
<B>Cooperative research:</B> TNO-MEP, Apeldoorn<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Since 1991, TNO-MEP and Twente University
have performed a research programme on
municipal solid waste incineration. The goal of
the research is to optimize incinerators for
minimum emissions and maximum energy
efficiency by process integrated measures. The
research consists of a combination of
mathematical modelling and experimental
investigation on full-scale and pilot-scale
equipment. Within the programme a PhD-project
has been carded out to study the fundamentals
of the incineration process, concentrating mainly
on the combustion of the layer of solid waste
on the grate of the incinerator.<P>


<B>Experimental research</B><BR>
A laboratory grate rumace has been used to
investigate the process experimentally. A
schematic is given in the figure.<P>

<IMG SRC="gort1.gif"><P>

Experimentents have been performed on model
fuels, like wood cubes, coal and pelletised RDF
and on shredded municipal waste. Experimental
results cover gas composition and temperatures
at several positions within the fuel bed.
Furthermore, ignition and combustion speeds
have been determined. The ignition speed
within the fuel bed is an important variable for
combustion calculations. New insights in the
ignition and combustion phenomena of
municipal solid waste have been obtained.
Reaction regimes have been identified for
various fuel properties and process parameters.<P>

<B>Theoretical research</B><BR>
Several models have been developed to describe
the combustion within large scale incinerators
(including the furnace above the waste layer).<P>

The processes within the fuel bed have been
investigated into more depth, to predict ignition
and combustion speeds. An analytical model has
given rise to new ideas about the most
important phenomena during the propagation of
a reaction front in a packed bed. The validation
of the theoretical calculations on experimental
results gives confidence in the solution
procedure. The results have been reported in a
PhD-thesis<SUP>1</SUP> and several publications.<P>

<B>Spin-off</B><BR>
Based on the theoretical and experimental
results, a dynamic model and a training
simulator of an incinerator have been developed
by TNO-MEP, as a tool for operator training.<P>

<FONT SIZE=-1><SUP>1</SUP> Gott, R., <I>On the Propagation of a Reaction Front in a
Packed Bed, Thermal Conversion of Municipal Solid
Waste and Biomass</I>, Twente University, nov. 1995.</FONT>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
