<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Phd-projects Groningen</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Multi-component Mass Transfer<HR></H2>

<TT><PRE>
University of Groningen
Department of Chemical Engineering
Nijenborgh 4
NL 9747 AG Groningen

telephone: +31 (0)50 363 4483
fax:       +31 (0)50 363 4479
</PRE></TT>

<HR>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../pic/home.gif"></A> PhD-projects Groningen

<HR>

<H3>Multicomponent Mass Transfer</H3>

<B>Why work on Mass Transfer?</B><P>

Chemical engineers still describe mass transfer by methods developed about half way the nineteenth century. These methods are only adequate for binary mixtures, with a concentration gradient as the only cause of diffusion. Unfortunately, there are hardly any binary mixtures in chemical engineering. Have you ever seen a reactor with only two components? Or have you ever dealt with a membrane separation process separating one component from itself? Also, we are nowadays using processes where there are causes for mass transfer other then concentration gradients. In membrane processes, we often apply pressure gradients, and electrical gradients are always important in solutions.<P>

<B>What we are doing</B><P>

We are developing methods that allow engineers to describe such processes in a proper, but not too complicated manner. This means rewriting of multicomponent mass transfer theory (thermodynamics of irreversible processes) in a form that is accessible to engineers, using the theory to model existing (and new) processes and developing methods to measure and predict the parameters required to describe multicomponent mass transfer.<P>

<OL>We currently have four projects running, which focus on:
<LI>Diffusion in non-ideal ternary liquid mixtures (A.M. Bollen)
<LI>Diffusion in ultrafiltration processes (R. Noordman)
<LI>Diffusion in electrodialysis (C. Visser)
<LI>Diffusion in chromatography (J.C. Bosma)
</OL>

In addition, one of us (J.A. Wesselingh) is spending a fair bit of his time in developing teaching material for a proper multicomponent description of the classical separation processes of distillation, absorption and extraction.<P>

