<HEAD><TITLE>Salt rejections by a ZrO2 ultrafiltration membrane</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Salt rejections by a ZrO<SUB>2</SUB> ultrafiltration membrane</H2>

Promovendus: T.R. Noordman<BR>
Sponsor: Unilever Research Laboratorium Vlaardingen<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Aim</B><BR>
Determination of the role of electric interactions in
ultrafiltration of salt solutions and a theoretical
description of this based upon Maxwell-Stefan
equations.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
Solutions of potassium phosphates at pH values of
5.5 and 8.9 were filtered through a ZrO<SUB>2</SUB> membrane
(Carbosep® M2, NMWC l5kD) in the setup as
shown below. Crossflow velocity is set at either 1.1
or 4.2 m/s. TMP is varied from 0 to 4 bar. Permeate
flux and retention of the phosphate ions were
measured.<P>

<IMG SRC="noordman1.gif"><P>

<I>Recycle scheme used for ultrafiltration experiments</I><P>

<B>Model</B><BR>
Transport through membrane and boundary layer is
described by the Maxwell-Stefan equations. For the
membrane :<P>

<IMG SRC="noordman2.gif"><P>

For the boundary layer :<P>

<IMG SRC="noordman3.gif"><P>

Partitioning of the (ionic) solutes is described by the
Donnan equation :<P>

<IMG SRC="noordman4.gif"><P>

Solvent partioning is described by the osmotic
equilibrium equation:<P>

<IMG SRC="noordman5.gif"><P>

In addition, the electroneutrality equation should
hold anywhere in the system.<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

<I>- High Crossflow (4.2 m/s) :</I><P>

<IMG SRC="noordman6.gif"><P>

<I>Rejection of the divalent phosphate ion (pH 8.9, left) and of the
monovalent ion (pH 5.5, right). Concentrations varied from 5 to
40 mM.</I><P>

<IMG SRC="noordman7.gif"><P>

<I>"True" rejection at a filtrate flux of 300 l/m<SUP>2</SUP>hr</I> / <I>optimized parameters</I><P>

<I>- Low Crossflow (1.1 m/s) :</I><P>

<IMG SRC="noordman8.gif"><P>

The thickness of the boundary layer was optimized to be 11 &#181;m<P>

Rejection of the divalent phosphate ion (pH 8.9),
at low crossflow, concentrations varied from 5 to 40 mM<P>

<B>Conclusions</B><BR>
Rejections are strongly influenced by ionic strength
indicating the importance of electrical effects. The
Maxwell-Stefan model describes the rejections
provided that the Donnan equilibrium is corrected
for preferential phosphate adsorption, thereby in fact
increasing membrane charge at higher phosphate
concentrations. Concentration polarization is also
well described by the model.<P>

