<HEAD><TITLE>Recovery of acids and bases from brine waste water using electrodialysis</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Recovery of acids and bases from brine waste water using electrodialysis</H2>

<B>PhD:</B> Ir. C.R. Visser (050 - 3634462)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> November 1993 - November 1997<BR>
<B>Co-operation:</B>TNO (MW) - Delft, TNO (ME) - Apeldoorn<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> IOP<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

The aim of this project is the
development of a continuous process capable
of recovering acids and bases in a production
process in order to reduce salt emissions in
industrial waste waters. As environmental
legislation will probably tighten on waste
water the recovery of acids and bases from
salts can in particular cases become
economically interesting. Electrodialysis is
applied to produce acids and bases from salts
present in industrial waste water. The aim of
the university of Groningen is to become
experienced in the process in order for a
computer model to be developed, with which
optimal process conditions can be calculated.
TNO will do research into practical aspects
of this process, such as the pre-treatment of
waste water and membrane pollution.<P>

<B>Modelling the experiments</B><P>

A model description of the process
uses the Maxwell-Stefan differential mass
transfer equations to calculate the diffusion
inside the membranes and in both stagnant
fluid films on either side of the membranes.
The multi-component diffusion coefficients
(for the most simple system containing at
least seven components) will be calculated
from experiments with only one of the salts
(in solution) and one type of membrane
present. At the moment four partial
experiments are being carried out: diffus'1on
dialysis, electro-osmosis, pressure driven salt
fluxes and electric resistance measurements.
Results will be combined, again in a
computer model, to obtain the six diffusion
coefficients present in one salt-membrane
system. At the same time a number of
additional measurements are needed to obtain
the membrane equilibrium properties. To test
the computer model, a four-compartment
electrodialysis membrane stack was used to
produce hydrochloric acid and sodium
hydroxide from a sodium chloride solution.
Sodium sulphate was also tested.<P>

<IMG SRC="visser1.gif"><P>

<B>Stack configuration using mono-polar
membranes.</B><P>

The membranes used in the stack were the
Nafion 450 cation exchange membrane by
Dupont and two types of anion exchange
membrane by Solvay. Concentrations and
volumes were monitored in time for
comparison with theory. At the moment
experiments using bipolar membranes are
being prepared. A possible lower energy
consumption of bipolar membranes will be
investigated.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
