<HEAD><TITLE>More efficient process chromatography</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>More efficient process chromatography</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> ir. J. C. Bosma<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> august 1995 - July 1999<BR>
<B>Coöperation:</B> drs. ir. J. Houwing, TU Delft, vakgroep Bioprocestechnologie<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Ministerie van Economische zaken (IOP Preventie)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

The purification of high value bio-technological products usually requires multiple chromatographic separations. Design and optimisation of these cas-cades of chromatographs is trouble-some for various reasons:<BR>
· the mixtures to be separated are complex,<BR>
· the unit operations are complex,<BR>
· many different combinations of chromatographs are possible and<BR>
· for economic reasons the process development time is often short.<BR>
As a consequence most chromato-graphic processes are sub-optimal, only designed on a basis of purity and product recovery.<BR>
The aim of the project is the development of rational design methods for the separation of proteins on a process scale. These methods will be based on maximum purity and product recovery as well as on efficiënt use of adsorbent and minimum waste streams.<BR>
The research can be divided into three levels.<P>

<B>Compound properties level</B><P>

Knowledge of thermodynamic equilibria and (multicomponent-) mass transfer properties of the compounds to be separated is crucial. We will attempt to determine which properties are critical and rapid methods to measure them for a given mixture.<P>

<B>Chromatographic unit level</B><P>

Chromatographic unit processes (see <B>1</B>) will be researched to find optimal configuration and operating mode. We will attempt to maximise sample loading, optimise eluent composition (ionic strength, pH, cosolvent) and to evaluate complex feeding strategies (see <B>2</B>).<P>

<B>Process cascade level</B><P>

We are developing a flow-sheet-like program which will make rapid  cascade design possible. Initially the program will use relatively simple models but their complexity will increase.<P>

<B>1 chromatographic techniques</B><BR>
· gel filtration<BR>
· ion exchange chromatography<BR>
· hydrophobic interaction chromato-graphy<BR>
· affinity chromatography<P>

<B>2 feeding strategies</B><BR>
· displacement chromatography<BR>
· flow reversal chromatography<BR>
· parametric pumping<BR>
· simulated moving bed<BR>
· recycle chromatography<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 29/02/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
