<HEAD><TITLE>Phd-projects Groningen</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Multiphase Reactor Systems<HR></H2>

<TT><PRE>
University of Groningen
Department of Chemical Engineering
Nijenborgh 4
NL 9747 AG Groningen

telephone: +31 (0)50 363 4484
fax:       +31 (0)50 363 4479
</PRE></TT>

<HR>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../pic/home.gif"></A> PhD-projects Groningen

<HR>

<B>Permanent staff:<BR>
A.A.C.M. Beenackers<BR>
K.J. Ganzeveld<BR>
E.J. Stamhuis<P>

Research Scientist:<BR>
J.W. Veldsink<P>

Ph.D. students:</B><BR>
M.J. Bouma<BR>
G.H. Jonker<BR>
M. Sipkema<BR>
G.P. van der Laan<BR>
J.F. Demmink<BR>
J.E. Visser<BR>
C.J. Tijsen<P>


<B>RESEARCH THEMES:</B><P>

<B>Catalytic hydrogenation of unsaturated edible oils</B><BR>
The object of this project is to increase the stability of unsaturated edible offs and fats by reduction of the
number of double bonds by catalytic hydrogenation. Therefore the kinetics, diffusion and adsorption of new
heterogeneous catalysts will be studied.<P>

<B>Process design for the degradation of chlorinated aliphatic hydrocarbons by microbial cultures</B><BR>
Environmental surface and ground waters are increasingly contaminated by chlorinated aliphatic
hydrocarbons, such as dichloroethylene, trichloroethylene and perchloroethylene. The breakdown of these
xenobiotica can be achieved in anaerobic and aerobic fermentation processes and combinations of both. In the
aerobic fermentation a process called cometabolism, the conversion of the chlorinated compound due to the
aspecificity of a principal enzyme of the organism, is often involved. Optimal process design for this type of
aerobic trans-formations is the main goal of the research. Modelling a complete process in which an anaerobic
and an aerobic step are involved, is the second goal.<P>

<B>Starch derivatization</B><BR>
Native starches laek the required properties for various applications. For this reason a major part of the starch
is chemically modified. Modification can involve substitution of part of the hydroxyl groups by low-molecular
groups. Such derivatization reactions are often batch slurry-phase processes. A disadvantage of these
processes is the undesired but unavoidable side reaction with water of any substrate that reacts with starch.
The object is to search for novel continuous starch modification reactors with improved selectivity. Both gas-
solid fluid beds of special design to handle C-powders and continuous static mixer reactors are under
development<P>

<B>Desulphurization of gasmixtures</B><BR>
A new regenerative process for the removal of hydrogen sulphide from synthetic and natural gas mixtures (e.g.
bio-gas) is being developed. The direct product of the process is sulphur.<P>

<B>Fischer-Tropsch Synthesis</B><BR>
The present commercial reactors for Fischer-Tropsch synthesis of hydrocarbons, often multitubular reactors,
are not optimal for large scale operation. Since slurry reactors have several advantages, e.g. removal of
reaction heat and flexibility in operating conditions, a research project was started to obtain more insight into
the fundamentals of these processes by measuring the kinetics of the heterogeneous catalytic reactions involved
in different solvents.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 09/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
