<HEAD><TITLE>Advanced selective hydrogenation of lipids (ASHLI)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Advanced selective hydrogenation of lipids (ASHLI)</H2>

<B>Post-doc:</B> Dr. ir. J.W. Veldsink<BR>
<B>PhD-students:</B> ir. M.J. Bouma, ir. G.H. Jonker<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> EC, AIR-1 programme<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

Hydrogenation of vegetable oils in order to modify the physical properties, such as melting point, and increase the flavour stability of the oils has been performed at an industrial scale since the beginning of this
century. Increased knowledge of the required amounts of necessary fatty acids in human diets, improved
analytical techniques, and the development of a variety of customer products, require selective hydrogenation. Therefore, research on the hydrogenation process is still required and the ASHLI project aims to
contribute to a better understanding of this process.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><P>

<UL>
<LI>Hydrogenation of refined oils to any specified product
<LI>Optimise the hydrogenation process to a minimum amount of monoenic trans isomers
<LI>Enable to replace current oils, such as soybean and sunflower oil, with domestic European oils, such
as marine and rapeseed oil, which are highly unsaturated.
</UL>
The ASHLI-programme will therefore study the hydrogenation kinetics and diffusion and adsorption phenomena over commercial Ni-catalysts, develop new selective precious metal catalysts and develop a continuous monolith reactor.<P>

<B>Participants</B><BR>
<OL>
<LI>University of Groningen, Prof. A.A.C.M. Beenackers, the Netherlands
<LI>Chalmers University of Technology, Prof. N.-H. Schoon, Sweden
<LI>Technische Hochschule Darmstadt, Prof. J. Gaube, Germany
<LI>Unilever Research Laboratory, the Netherlands
<LI>Degussa A.G., Germany
<LI>Stazioni Sperimentale per le Industry degli Oil e Grassi, Italy
<LI>Fima S.A., Portugal
</OL>

<B>Research at University of Groningen</B><P>

In our laboratories, we study the kinetics of unsaturated fatty acid methyl esters and corresponding oils over
Ni-catalysts. The kinetic research comprises a study of hydrogenation, migration and geometric isomerisation of double bonds. To develop kinetic models, we study the effect of the number of double bonds per
molecule, position of the double bond(s) and chain length of the fatty acid.
Secondly, we study the physical adsorption of unsaturated fatty acids and hydrogen on Ni-surfaces. Differences in adsorption strength of different unsaturated fatty acids, among others, has been postulated to explain
the preferential hydrogenation of polyenes over monoenic fatty acids, but has never been demonstrated experimentally. Adsorption of unsaturated fatty acids is studied both on hydrogen-free and on hydrogen-covered
Ni-surfaces and the adsorption of individual components is studied as well as competitive adsorption in
mixtures.<BR>
Thirdly, the intraparticle diffusion coefficients of fats are directly measured by a chromatographic technique.
Intraparticle diffusion limitations of fats have often been mentioned to be responsible for decreased selectivities and apparent shunt reactions. However, reliable values of effective diffusion coefficients are not available,
owing to the small particle size of the catalyst. The small particle size obstructs a direct measurement of
the diffusivities because of the very short Fourier times.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
