<HEAD><TITLE>Aerobic cometabolic degradation of chlorinated ethenes</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Aerobic cometabolic degradation of chlorinated ethenes</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> E. Marijn Sipkema (050-3634190, <A HREF="mailto:e.m.sipkema@chem.rug.nl">e.m.sipkema@chem.rug.nl</A>)<BR>
<B>Supervisors:</B> K.J. Ganzeveld, W. de Koning<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> November 1993-November 1997<BR>
<B>Cooperation:</B> J.E.T. van Hylckama Vlieg, D.B. Janssen, RuG - Department of Biochemistry<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Chlorinated ethenes (CEs), such as trichloroethene, belong to a group of important pollutants that can successfully be
treated in bioremediation processes.
Aerobically many of these compounds can
only be converted by cometabolism. This
process, which is not growth-based, is intrinsically unstable, and therefore constitutes more of a technological challenge than
the better known growth-based processes.<P>

<B>Cometabolism</B><BR>
Cometabolism can be defined as the
inadvertent conversion of a non-growth
substrate as the result of the non-specificity of a cellular enzyme:<P>

<IMG SRC="sipkema1.gif"><P>

Aspects of concern in this process include:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>need for an additional growth substrate;
<LI>induction of the non-specific enzyme;
<LI>competitive inhibition;
<LI>use of energy (e.g. NAD(P)H, ATP);
<LI>formation of toxic intermediates.
</UL><P>

<B>Choice of a suitable organism</B><BR>
Of the organisms that have been shown
to be capable of cometabolic CE conversion, we have chosen two, based on literature data. Their characteristics are:<P>

<B>Methylosinus trichosporium OB3b</B><BR>
grown under copper limitation<BR>
++ very high specific CE activity;<BR>
++ broad CE substrate range;<BR>
+ cheap and harmless substrate;<BR>
- strong toxic intermediate-effects.<P>

<B>Burkhoideria cepacia G4</B><BR>
+ reasonably high specific CE activity;<BR>
++ resistance to CE shock loads;<BR>
- toxic growth substrate, e.g. phenol.<P>

<B>Kinetics measuring techniques</B><BR>
In order to obtain more accurate information
about rate kinetics, special measuring techniques have been developed.<BR>
Closed system batch studies are conducted
using well-conditioned chemostat grown cells.
In the chemostat itself, unsteady-state (pulse,
step) experiments are carried out to study the
concomitant processes of growth and CE
conversion.<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
Using the techniques described, experiments
have been conducted that led to the conclusion
that a cometabolism based bioreactor system is
best designed in two steps, with growth of the
organism being separated from CE conversion:<P>

<IMG SRC="sipkema2.gif"><P>

<B>Two step process</B><P>
From modelling studies it follows that for the
CE degradation step of the two step system the
most important design parameters are: inlet biomass concentration; residence time; type of mixing. If for these parameters acceptable values are
chosen, good performance is obtainable.
In the future, more kinetics studies will be carried out in order to further optimize the CE degradation characteristics of the organism in the
two step system. Also, the modelling predictions
will be verified in a small pilot scale experimental set-up (50 1).


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
