<HEAD><TITLE>Application of iron chelates in gas desulphurisation</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Application of iron chelates in gas desulphurisation</H2>

J.F. Demmink<BR>
A.A.C.M. Beenackers<BR>
Sponsor: SON	<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

H<SUB>2</SUB>S is removed from gaseous streams
by contacting with aqueous solutions of
ferric chelates at ambient pH (i.e. pH =
6-9). The absorption of hydrogen
sulphide is represented by:<P>

<IMG SRC="demmink1.gif"><P>

Since ferric chelate is converted to
inactive ferrous chelate, regeneration is
required:<P>

<IMG SRC="demmink2.gif"><P>

The resulting overall reaction now is:<P>

<IMG SRC="demmink3.gif"><P>

Since no iron chelate appears in
equation (5), it can be regarded as a
pseudo-catalyst.<P>

<IMG SRC="demmink4.gif"><P>

<I><B>figure 1.</B> stirred cell reactor</I><P>

In equation (2) and (4) Ln- represents
an organic ligand, usually EDTA
(ethylenediaminetetraaeetic
acid) or
NTA (nitrilotriacetic acid)<P>

The kinetics of both hydrogen sulphide
absorption and catalyst regeneration
have been investigated for iron
complexes of NTA in a stirred cell
reactor (figure 1). This year we have
determined most relevant kinetic
parameters. An interesting feature we
found is a strong pH-dependency of
reactivity in both reactions. This
phenomenon is consistent with the pH
dependent appearance (i.e. molecular
structure, stability and hydroxylation) of
iron chelates. An example is given in
figure 2.<P>

<IMG SRC="demmink5.gif"><P>

<I><B>Figure 2.</B> pH dependent absorption of H2S in
an aqueous solution of ferric EDTA chelate.</I><P>

A second phenomenon we observed is a
so-called "shuttle effect" caused by in
sire formed solid sulphur particles. A
new model has been derived to describe
this phenomenon for chemically inert
gassea. We are currently developing a
model for gas absorption enhanced by
particles as well as chemical reaction.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

