<HEAD><TITLE>Synthesis gas based slurry processes: Fischer-Tropsch synthesis</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Synthesis gas based slurry processes: Fischer-Tropsch synthesis</H2>

<B>PhD student:</B> Ir. G.P. van der Laan<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Prof. dr. ir. A.A.C.M. Beenackers<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The increase of the crude oil price and its
limited resources will cause a shift to coal and
natural gas as the primary energy source and
feedstock to the chemical industry. Coal and
natural gas can be converted into CO and H<SUB>2</SUB>
by coal. gasification or steam reforming
processes. Different reaction routes of syngas
to useful products are shown in the following
figure:<P>

<IMG SRC="laan1.gif"><P>

The conversion of a mixture of hydrogen and
carbonmonoxide (synthesis gas) to aliphatic
hydrocarbons was discovered by Franz
Fischer and Hans Tropsch in 1923. The
hydrocarbon synthesis is catalyzed by a
number of metals such as Co, Fe, and Ru.
Iron catalysts are most commonly used
because of their low costs. Also the more
expensive cobalt catalysts, with higher
activity and stability, are used in industry. The
process operates at a temperature of about
200 to 300 &#176;C and at 10 to 60 bar pressure.<P>

Present    commercial    reactors,    often
multitubular reactors, are not optimal for
large scale operation. Gasoline, methanol, and
higher alcohols for the automotive market will
ask for reactors with higher capacity. Slurry
reactors have several advantages over
conventional multi-tubular fixed bed reactors,
e.g. removal of reaction heat, flexibility in
operating conditions.<P>

<B>Theory</B><BR>
The Fischer-Tropsch synthesis can be
simplified as a set of simultaneous reactions.
Generally, water is believed to be the primary
by-product of the FT synthesis, and CO<SUB>2</SUB> is
produced by the WGS reaction:<P>

<IMG SRC="laan2.gif"><P>

where n is the average carbon chain length of
the product and m is the average number of
hydrogen atoms per hydrocarbon molecule.<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
The kinetic measurements are carried out in
an automated experimental set-up. Synthesis
gas from a cylinder is purified and enters the
slurryreactor. Analysis of the productstream is
performed by an on-line gaschromatographic
system. Another experimental set-up for
catalyst screening of interesting F-T catalysts
with a Packed Bed Reactor (PBR) is also
present.<P>

<IMG SRC="laan3.gif"><P>

<B>Future Work</B><P>
Experimental data will be generated in a
slurry reactor and a packed bed reactor.
Particular attention is given to the effect of
process conditions and the influence of the
solvent properties on product distribution and
catalyst activity. The experimental data will
be used to evaluate kinetic models and find
optimal process parameters.<P>

