<HEAD><TITLE>Phd-projects Groningen</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Physical Technology<HR></H2>

<TT><PRE>
University of Groningen
Department of Chemical Engineering
Nijenborgh 4
NL 9747 AG Groningen

telephone: +31 (0)50 363 4485
fax:       +31 (0)50 363 4479
</PRE></TT>

<HR>

<A HREF="index.html"><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="../../pic/home.gif"></A> PhD-projects Groningen

<HR>

<H2>TRANSPORT PHENOMENA IN GRONINGEN</H2>

<H3>Department of Chemical Engineering<BR>
University of Groningen</H3>

<OL>
The major interest of the research group on Transport phenomena concerns the influence of non linear material properties on transport process and their practical implications. This is reflected in the choice of research <B>topics</B>:
<LI>Processing of non-Newtonian liquids, like polymers or starchy materials, mostly in extruders.
<LI>Marangoni convection and its influence on mass transfer.
<LI>Two phase sold gas flows in powder technology.
</OL>

<UL>
The <B>permanent scientific staff</B> consists of:
<LI>Prof.dr.ir. L.B.P.M. Janssen
<LI>Prof.dr.ir. L.L. van Dierendonck (10%)
<LI>Dr. A.C. Hoffmann
</UL>

<UL>and the <B>permanent technical staff</B> of:
<LI>L. Bosgra
<LI>M. de Vries
<LI>Ing. J.H. Marsman
</UL>

<UL>The <B>research scientists</B> are mainly Ph.D Students (the number in parenthesis gives the subject of study):
<LI>Drs. D.J. van de Wal (1)
<LI>Ir. A.J. van de Goot (1)
<LI>Ir. Tj Molenkamp (2)
<LI>Ir. E.J. Troelstra (1)
<LI>Ir. G.P. Hartholt (3)
<LI>Ir. R. Hettema (1)
</UL>

<UL>Furthermore there are two guests as research fellows connected to the group:
<LI>Mr. J.L. Selo from Elf-Atochem (1)
<LI>Mrs. G Lamanna University of Napels (2)
</UL>

All Ph.D. students except one are externally funded.<P>

<B>Polymer and starch processing</B><BR>
As can be concluded from the list of researchers the most fruitful research area remains the flow of non-Newtonian liquids and more specifically the use of extruders as chemical reactors. In this research field we aim at a thorough understanding of the working of different types of extruders in order to use them as reactors for highly viscous media (&#181; > 100 Pa.s). Several subtopics can be distinguished in this area. The extruder can be used as a <B>polymerisation reactor</B> for synthetic polymers. The advantages are obvious: Because no organic solvents have to be added the process is environmental friendly. Moreover, no extra separation step is needed after the process. In co&ouml;peration with Dr. Vrijland (University of Twente) a study into the economic feasibility of reactive extrusion of methacrylates showed that this process is already competitive to classical polymerisation processes and it may be expected that this feasibility will increase considerably in near future. Various polymerisations and co-polymerisations are under investigation with industrial sponsoring. Fully 3-D computer models are under construction (together with industry) to facilitate scale up of reactive extrusion. A second sub-topic in this field is <B>reactive compatibilisation</B>. In this subject we aim at the formation of compatibilisers at the interface between two polymers by reaction during the mixing process. This will lower the interfacial tension and increase the miscibility. After a project where the fundamentals of this process have been studies we are now also investigating this technique for low cost improvement of the mechanical properties of clean plastic commingled wastes. The third topic concerning highly non-Newtonian materials is <B>starch processing</B>. It has been shown that modifications of starch can well be performed in an extruder. An interesting modification is the styrenation of starch to form a grafted block co-polymer. The resulting product can be used as compatibiliser between starch and poly-styrene, but the styrene-starch co-polymer as such has also remarkable properties, The strength of a co-polymer, consisting of 90% starch and 10% styrene reaches the strength of 80% of pure poly-styrene that only reduces to 40% after 30 minutes submersion in water. Another project in this field concernes thermoplastic starches. The starch is extruded with polyoles as molecular lubricants and the native water is evaporated. An amorphous, transparent and thermoplastic material remains, that can be used for production of bio-degradable disposables. This material can, like synthetic polymers, be re-extruded and injection moulded without significant loss of mechanical properties.<P>

<B>Marangoni convection</B><BR>
After the launch in 1994 of our experiment in space we have evaluated the results obtained. Simultaneous measurements of the flow profile and the concentration profile in several different geometries show clearly the existence of two types of convection in non-flat geometries (macro-convection and micro-convection) depending on the boundary conditions. The influence of Marangoni convection on the mass transfer in wetted wall columns and packed columns under "terrestrial" circumstances is under investigation. A fruitful spin off of this project is in the field of protein crystallisation in space, where we have supported research on the influence of Marangoni convection on the growth of these crystals under micro-gravity.<P>

<B>Powder Technology</B><BR>
In this research we want to optimise process equipment, like fluidised beds and cyclones, through a better fundamental knowledge of solid-liquid interactions. In the area of <B>fluidised beds</B> the rising of bubbles in Newtonian media as a precursor for bubbles in fluidised beds have been fully modelled numerically. General questions describing the particle transport in fluidised have been formulated and numerical solutions are under investigation. Experimentally we followed the movement of particles in fluidised beds and their behaviour in the vicinity of bubbles with an endoscope and subsequently we correlated these findings with the results of experiments we performed using X-ray equipment at the University College London. The influence of cohesiveness is varied in the experiments. Parallel, the particle residence time distributions in continuous beds have been tested and proven. Dr. Hoffmann has, in co-operation with the department of mathematics modified a computer code simulating the flow pattern in <B>cyclones</B>. In this way also with particle tracking a configuration under the cyclone can be simulated. This has given rise to a more accurate prediction of cyclone separation. This work will also be extended towards optimising hydro-cyclones for paper and pulp industry.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/01/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
