<HEAD><TITLE>Radical polymerisation in a Buss kneader</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Radical polymerisation in a Buss kneader</H2>

<B>PhD-student:</B> Ir. Erik Jan Troelstra (Tel.: 050-3637109)<BR>
<B>Supervisors:</B> Prof. Dr. ir. L. L. van Dierendonck, Prof. Dr. ir. L. P. B. M. Janssen<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> June 1993 - June 1997<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> AIO-network <BR>
<B>Co-Sponsors:</B> Buss AG (Basel), DSM (Geleen), KWF (Bern)<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The radical co-polymerisation of Butylacrylate (BA) and Hydroxyethyl-methacrylate (HEMA) is carried out in a Buss-Kneader. To be able to model the polymerisation process the polymerisation kinetics has to be known as well as reactor characteristics like heat transfer and residence time distribution. The polymerisation kinetics are studied at the École Polytechnique Féderale Lausanne (Switzerland).<P>

<B>Characterisation of the Buss-Kneader</B><BR>
<I>Residence time</I><BR>
Break through times were measured by injecting carbon black, suspended in 5 ml of the A/HEMA monomer mixture, at the inlet of the kneader under polymerisation conditions.<BR>
In Fig. 1 the measured break through time as a function of the volumetric flow rate, at constant screw speed, are compared with the calculated mean residence time assuming a constant degree of filling in the kneader.<P>

<IMG SRC="erikjan1.gif"><P>

<I>Fig. 1. Measured (+) and calculated (---) break through times (minutes) as a function of flowrate. N=285 rpm.</I><P>

<I>Heat transfer</I><BR>
The heat transfer coefficient was calculated using the penetration theory. Fig. 2 shows a parity plot of the calculated and the experimental overall heat transfer coefficient.<P>

<IMG SRC="erikjan2.gif"><P>

<I>Fig. 2 Parity plot of the theoretical and the experimental heat transfer coefficient. Open squares: Values measured with silicone oils with a kinematic viscosity of  0.5×10<SUP>-3</SUP>, 1.0×10<SUP>-3</SUP> and 5.0×10<SUP>-3</SUP> m<SUP>2</SUP> s<SUP>-1</SUP> at 25 &#176;C; Closed squares: Values measured with glycerol with a kinematics viscosity of 0.75×10<SUP>-3</SUP> m<SUP>2</SUP> s<SUP>-1</SUP> at 25 &#176;C.</I><P>

<B>Future studies</B><BR>
In order to create a reactor model to calculate temperature profiles and conversion over the length of the kneader the residence time distribution will be measured. Syropes with different viscosities will be used for this study.<P>

