<HEAD><TITLE>Modelling of mixing in the corotating twin-screw-extruder</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Modelling of mixing in the corotating twin-screw-extruder</H2>

<B>D.J. van der Wal, Sponsor: SON Prof. L.P.B.M Janssen (RUG)</B><BR>
<HR SIZE=0>

The time needed for decreasing the size
of the dispersed phase by break-up is
very short for thin threads. This is found
for many practical situations of
extrusion where polymers are mixed. In
spite of these very short break-up times,
poor mixing may occur when the final
(equilibrium) average size of the
dispersed phase of a blend attainable
(due to the critical Capillary number) is
large or due to an instable morphology.
Another reason for poor mixing is
coalescence.<BR>
The effectiveness of mixing of two
polymers is influenced by several
processes taking place in an
intermeshing corotating twin screw
extruder:<BR>
<OL>
<LI>The material is transported forward
away from the feeding section in the
transportation elements.
<LI>The material is heated or cooled by the
barrel temperature and heated due to
viscous dissipation.
<LI>The mixture of polymers is melted
(usually in a very short length).
<LI>The model to calculate all the values
needed for a complete understanding of
the process in the extruder has been
developed and validated, for blending
PS/HDPE.
</OL>

Mixing is strongly dependent on the
rotation speed of the extruder as seen in
figure 1.<P>

<IMG SRC="wal1.gif"><P>

If reactive compounding is performed
the size of the dispersed phase decreases
more as shown in figure 2.<P>

<IMG SRC="wal2.gif"><P>


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

