<HEAD><TITLE>The extruder as polymerisation reactor</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>The extruder as polymerisation reactor</H2>

<B>AIO:</B> A.J. van der Goot<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Shell<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Since the 1980's, the world's interest in
reactive extrusion is growing. This growing
interest is based on the fact that the extruder
can handle highly viscous materials, which
makes it suitable as chemical reactor for
polymers.<BR>
Historically, polymerisation reactions and
modification reactions of polymers have
been carded out in diluted systems. After
completion of the reaction, solvent has to be
removed, which is rather energy consuming.
Because of environmental restrictions in the
last 20 year, the reduction of energy
consumption and solvent emission has
become very important in chemical industry.
Since extruders can handle pure polymers,
no solvent is necessary, which makes
reactive extrusion processes environmentally friendly.<BR>
The possibilities for the use of an extruder
as polymerisation reactor were already
recognised in 1950. A patent of Dow
Chemical Company described the use of a
single screw extruder as main polymeriser.
After this patent, many other studies were
performed concerning the extruder as
polymerisation reactor. In Groningen, a lot
of research is performed on the radical
polymerisation of several methacrylates in
both counterrotating and corotating twin
screw extruders.<P>

<B>Objective of this study</B><BR>
The objective of this study is to investigate
the working domain of the counterrotating
twin screw extruder when used as a
polymerisation reactor. To do so, three
aspects are studied: The effect of
prepolymerisation, the effect of polymer
melt viscosity and the effect of the
polymerisation rate. The starting point of
this investiation is the copolymerisation of
styrene (st) with n-butylmethacrylate
(BMA).<P>

<B>Experimental</B><BR>
The extruder used was a counter-rotating
closely intermeshing twin-screw extruder
with a screw diameter of 40 mm and an L/D
of 15. The monomer mixture consisted of
50 mol% St and 50 mol% BMA. The
prepolymerisation was performed thermally,
the polymer melt viscosity was altered by
using divinylbezene (DVB), while the rate
of polymerisation was changed by replacing
part of BMA by maleic anhydride (Mah).<P>

<B>Results</B><BR>
The polymerisation of St-BMA is very
difficult to perform in the extruder.
Relatively low throughputs could be
obtained, when high conversions were
required. Especially the high die resistance,
which was needed for sufficient conversion,
limited the throughput.<BR>
Prepolymerisation and an increase in
polymer melt viscosity and polymerisation
rate enlarged the working domain, which
mean higher throughputs and a decreased
dependence on extruder parameters.
Especially the effect of the polymer melt
viscosity is remarkable, since it implies that
the residence time is not the only limiting
factor in reactive extrusion.<BR>
These experiments showed that product
properties influenced the process of reactive
extrusion strongly. Furthermore, the die
resistance turned out to be the most
important extruder parameter, and should
therefore be quantified in reactive extrusion.
A new theory, developed in this study,
accounts for the effects described above.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
