<HEAD><TITLE>Recycling of plastic waste by reactive extrusion</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Recycling of plastic waste by reactive extrusion</H2>

<B>PhD-student:</B> ir. Rienk Hettema (Tel.: 0503637109)<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> Prof. Dr. Ir. L.P.B.M. Janssen<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> august 1994 - august 1998<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> IOP-MT/Recycling<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>
 
<B>Introduction</B><P>

The steady growth in the use of plastic materials in packaging applications has caused a problem of solid waste disposal. Post-consumer recycling of plastics has therefore become necessary.<BR>
However, simple blends of incompatible polymer blends show a deterioration in impact performance and tensile properties due to a phase separated morphology. To improve these properties one must have an effective method for compatibilisation and toughening of a blend.<P>

<B>Objective</B><P>

The aim of this research project is to perform the blending and compatibilisation in an extruder by adding monomers and peroxides to a polymer melt. The monomers and peroxide are usually added at relatively low concentrations. For that reason they offer considerable economic advantages versus polymeric compatibilisers that are usually effective at higher concentrations.<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

The mechanical properties such as impact strength and elongation at break of a polymer blend of both polystyrene and polyethylene, and polyethylene and polypropylene improve significantly compared to a uncompatibilised blend.<BR>
The main improvement of the properties lies in the elongation at break and the impact strength. A reactive processed blend of polystyrene with polyethylene has nearly the same properties as high impact polystyrene. The blend of polyethylene has approximately the same properties as virgin material.<BR>
Process conditions have a strong influence on the final properties. A large energy input in the extruder, for example a large rotation rate of the screw, results in low values for toughness and  impact strength.<P>

<B>Conclusions</B><P>

Reactive extrusion can be a relatively cheap method for improving the properties of a polymer blend.<BR>
Not only an amorphous polymer blend but also a blend of two semi-crystalline polymers can be compatibilised by reactive extrusion. Strong influence of processing conditions is found, providing opportunities for optimization.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 03/03/96</CENTER></H6>

