<HEAD><TITLE>The influence of Marangoni convection on mass transfer</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>The influence of Marangoni convection on mass transfer</H2>

<B>PhD.Student:</B> Ir T. Molenkamp<BR>
<B>Supervisor:</B> prof. dr ir L.P.B.M. Janssen<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> October 1991-October 1995<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> NWO / SRON<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

Convection arising from surface tension
gradients along a liquid-liquid or a liquid-gas
interface is named Marangoni convection after
the 19th-century Italian physicist. These
differences in surface tension can be caused by,
for example, gradients in temperature or concentration. The research performed in our group
is focused on understanding the influence of
Marangoni flows, resulting from concentration
gradients, on the mass transfer coefficient.<P>

<B>Microgravity research.</B><P>

The influence of the Marangoni effect on mass
transfer is most pronounced in thin liquid films
(in foams, wetted packing material). In these
thin films, however, it is very difficult to
observe the convection patterns. Buoyancy
(Rayleigh convection) will dominate in thicker
films. This convection is driven by density
gradients resulting from the same concentration
or temperature gradients, which drive the
Marangoni convection. Buoyancy can be
reduced in a microgravity environment, which
makes it possible to study the Marangoni effect
in thicker layers. This is why various microgravity experiments have been performed in our
group, using the Space Shuttle, sounding
rockets and parabolic flights. In May 1994 we
have carried out a successful experiment on
board of a sounding rocket. The evaporation of
acetone from a 5 % acetone-water mixture was
studied in containers with differently-shaped
liquid-gas interfaces. Micro- as well as macro-convection was observed depending on the
shape of the interface. Micro-convection
patterns were characterised by the onset of small
roll cells, which later emerged into two big roll
cells that penetrated deeply into the bulk of the
fluid. The concentration in the containers was
monitored using interferometry. The
interferometry patterns have been converted
quantitatively into concentration patterns.
Qualitatively it can be said that large
concentration gradients were present between
roll cells, that concentration changes were
observed across the whole container
(approximately 2 cm deep) and that diffusional
concentration patterns were completely
destroyed by the convection. The results are
compared quantitatively with a numerical model
describing the convection and the mass transfer
in the container. In this model the convection-
diffusion equation, the continuity equation and
the Navier-Stokes equations are solved
simultaneously. The numerical model is
subsequently used to downscale the results to
small liquid layers. Enhancement of mass
transfer can be described as a function of Biot
number, Marangoni number and time. As a last
step, we are presently trying to summarize the
results in emperical equations that can easily be
used by process engineers. These equations will
be checked with published and own results
obtained in wetted wall columns.<P>

<IMG SRC="molenkamp1.gif"><P>

<I>Example of concentration pattern in V-shaped
container 294 seconds after start of the
experiment. Darker areas represent higher
concentrations. The top side is the liquid-gas
interface. The other walls are solid walls.</I><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl">OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 10/04/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
