<HEAD><TITLE>Dynamics of immobilized nitrifying microorganisms</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Dynamics of immobilized nitrifying microorganisms</H2>

<B>AIO:</B> Ir. E.J.T.M. Leenen<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> NOVEM; RIZA<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

To obtain more insight in the nitrification process in biofilm systems a model system was used. Pure cultures of nitrifying bacteria are entrapped in carrageenan gel beads. This system was used for the evaluation of mathematical models which describe substrate consumption and growth. Because the capacity is high and because it offers excellent possibilities to combine nitrification and denitrification, this system can be interesting for practical purposes as well.<BR>
To apply this system for treatment of domestic wastewater continiously changing environmental conditions should be considered. Therefore the dynamics of the model system and the stability of the gelbeads in wastewater have to be studied.<P>

<B>Aim of the research</B><P>

To develop and to test a dynamic reactor model for nitrification of domestic wastewater with immobilized microorganisms. The model is an important tool for the understanding of the process and for the design of compact reactor systems.<BR>
To develop and to test carrier materials on their stability in domestic wastewater.<P>

<B>Experimental procedures</B><P>

The effect of changes of successively temperature and nitrogen loadings on the reactor capacity will be studied. This will be done by the implementation of these effects in the existing models. Experimental model evaluation will be done in air-lift loop reactors.<P>

Carrageenan beads as used in the model system dissolve in sewage. By changing the chemical composition of a gel material, like carrageenan or alginate, the stability can be improved. Different gel materials in domestic wastewater will be examined on their stability.<P>

<IMG SRC="imke1.gif"><P>

Figure:
The effect of lowering the temperature on the macroscopic consumption rate of immobilized <I>N. agilis</I> cells.<BR>
(line = model predictions; plus and square = experimental results)<P>

<B>Results</B><P>

The existing model is extended by adding relations which describe the influence of temperature on the input parameters. It is shown that the model prediction and the experimental results agree very well (see figure).<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 01/03/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
