<HEAD><TITLE>Integrated nitrification and denitrification with co-immobilized cells</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Integrated nitrification and denitrification with co-immobilized cells</H2>

PhD-fellow: Engo. Vítor Alexandre Santos ; Period: October 1992 - December 1995<BR>
Promotor: Prof. Johannes Tramper ; Direct supervisor: Dr. René Wijffels
Sponsoring: JNICT, Portugal ; WAU, The Netherlands.<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>
 
<B>Introduction</B><P>

Nitrification readily occurs in gel beads with immobilized nitrifying bacteria. Due to diffusion limitation, the intervening bacteria will form a thin biofilm underneath the particle surface. The oxygen is all consumed within this layer leaving the bead core anoxic. Denitrification may thus occur in the bead core if suitable denitrifying bacteria are present and if organic substrate is available. Bacterial segregation in well defined areas of the beads can be achieved by formation of double-layer beads. In this way, this two-step bioconversion system can be conducted as single-staged.We call this system "The Magic Bead Concept" (see Figure).<P>

<B>Objectives</B><P>

- Production and characterization of double-layer beads for co-immobilization of micro-organisms;<BR>
- Characterization and evaluation of the "Magic Bead Concept";<BR>
- Dynamic modelling and experimental validation of this process, both at particle and reactor level.<P>

<B>Results and current research</B><P>

Several immobilization materials and techniques for the production of double-layer  beads have been tested and further developed. A procedure for the assessement  of mechanical stability of carrier materials correlating different rheological properties has been studied as well.<BR>
Integrated nitrification and denitrification with <I>Nitrosomonas europaea and Pseudomonas</I> sp. co-immobilized in double-layer gel beads was achieved at considerably high rates in air-lift reactors.<P>

<TABLE><TR><TD>
<IMG SRC="vitor1.gif"><P>
<FONT SIZE="-2">"Magic bead" concept. Bead core: denitrification; outer region: nitrification</FONT>
</TD>
<TD>
A dynamic model describing growth and substrate consumption within double-layer gel beads in an airlift loop raector has been developed. Experimental evaluation was done at reactor level by comparing predicted and measured macroscopic consumption rates, both in steady and dynamic conditions. Currently, we are further validating  the model at bead level. This is being done by the determination of biomass and substrate profiles within the particles using image analysis techniques and specific microelectrodes, respectively. <BR>
The study and characterization of this system will provide considerable insight on the processes involved in mixed-culture immobilized-cell systems. The approach followed is in principle also suitable to couple other oxidative and reductive bioprocesses having complementary metabolic routes.
</TD></TR></TABLE><P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 03/03/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
