<HEAD><TITLE>Development of mist reactors for solid-state fermentation</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<IMG SRC="frankj.gif" ALIGN=right>

<H2>Development of mist reactors for solid-state fermentation</H2>

<B>AIO:</B> Ir. F.J.I. Nagel (Tel.: 0317-483770)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> March 1995-March 1999<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> OSPT<BR>
<B>E-mail :</B> <A HREF="mailto:frank-jan.nagel@algemeen.pk.wau">frank-jan.nagel@algemeen.pk.wau</A>
	
<HR SIZE=0>
 
<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Solid -state fermentation as currently applied in the food industry and the waste-processing industry is still more an art than a technology. In both branches of industry, the physical and biological behaviour of solid state fermentation are poorly understood, and scale up is accomplished by trial and error. This project aims at a more procestechnological approach in solving problems ocurring in solid state fermentation. One of the most crucial problems of solid-state fermentation is the removal of reaction enthalpy of the metabolic oxidation process. This cannot be accomplished simply by convective transport, because the gas phase is a poor transport medium en there is no free-flowing water present. Therefore evaporation of water from the solid matrix is used for temperature control. Combined with the uptake of intracellular water during growth, the evaporation of water causes a decrease in water activity, which has a strong unfavorable effect on the growth of the fungi. For an adequate simultaneous control of temperature and water activity water addition to the solid matrix is necessary.<P>

<B>Aims of the project</B><BR>
This project aims at developing a fermentor capable of adequate simultaneous temperature and water activity control. Homogeneous water distribution will be achieved by introducing a dispersion of very small water droplets - a mist - into the fermentor. The outline of the research is as follows:<BR>

<UL>
<LI>Determine growth kinetics as a function of environmental conditions like temperature, water activity and substrate concentrations
<LI>Determine the effect of mixing on fungal biomassproduction in a fermentor
<LI>Select a suitable inert carrier 
<LI>Select a suitable mode of reactor operation (solid state mixer or structured bed)
<LI>Determine the physical behaviour of the fermentor (Droplet capture, mixing)
<LI>Validation of the combined physical and biokinetic model in a Mist-reactor
</UL>
 
<IMG SRC="frankj1.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 1: Diagram to determine the required Mist holdup for cooling in Solid-state Ferentation</I><P>


<B>Experimental setup</B><BR>

The experimental studies will be conducted using a model solid-state fermentation system, consisting of a non-biodegradable solid matrix with well defined physical characteristics (ion exchange resin, gel), an absorbed substrate solution (glucose) and a model organism with known physiology and kinetic parameters, <I><U>Rhizopus oligosporus</U></I>. Commercially available aerosol or mist generators with droplet diameters in the order of magnitude of 5-10 &#181;m and a narrow droplet size distribution will be used.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 13/03/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B29-362</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000119-B031-142</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost95/luw/zhu.html 130.89.50.60 19970216195202 text/html 4083
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 19:45:28 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.3
MIME-version: 1.0
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Wednesday, 23-Oct-96 06:54:41 GMT
Content-length: 3900
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Process development for microbial transglutaminase production in submerged and solid-state fermentation</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Process development for microbial transglutaminase production in submerged and solid-state fermentation</H2>

<B>PhD-fellow:</B> Zhu Yang<BR>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD><B>Supervisors:</B></TD><TD> Prof. J. Tramper, dr. A. Rinzema (Food and Bioprocess Engineering, WAU)</TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD> Ir. J. Bol (TNO Nutrition and Food Research Institute)</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<B>Project term:</B> September 1994 - April 1997<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> TNO<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>
                                                                        
<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Transglutaminase catalyses in vitro cross-linking reactions in various proteins. This enzyme has been used in attempts to improve the functional properties of foods. Up to now, commercial transglutaminase has been merely obtained from animal tissues. The complicated separation and purification procedure results in an extremely high price of the enzyme, which hampers a wide application in food processing. Recently, studies on the production of microbial transglu-taminase (MTG; EC 2.3.2.13) have been launched. The enzyme obtained from microbial fermentation has been applied in the treatment of various food proteins. Food treated with MTG appeared to have an improved flavour, appearance and texture. In addition, MTG can increase shelf-life and reduce allergenicity of certain foods. However, much work has to be done before this interesting enzyme can be produced on an industrial scale. Our project focuses on the development of an economical and practical process for MTG production.<P>

<B>Aim</B><BR>
The study is directed mainly to process development and optimization with respect to MTG production in order to improve the productivity and to reduce the cost as much as possible.<P>

<OL>
<B>Research</B><P>
<LI> Stoichiometric model<BR>
A stoichiometric model was developed for the application of medium design in MTG production by Streptoverticillium moba-raence. The model avoids dealing with all the metabolic reactions involved by simply lumping them into a single reaction. With the help of the analysis of the nutrients roles and biochemical knowledge of the microorganism, all stoichiometric coefficients in the model were calculated. Together with the experimental measurements, these coefficients were used for medium design. With this designed medium, MTG activity and specific productivity were increased significantly.<P>

<LI> Metabolic-fluxes analysis<BR>
In order to further understand the role of certain substrates in the synthesis of MTG, a matrix for metabolic-fluxes analysis has to be established. The expected results will indicate the bottle neck of metabolic pathways in biomass and/or MTG synthesis so that further improvement of MTG producti-vity can be worked in a rational manner.<P>

<LI> Solid-state fermentation<BR>
Advantages of solid-state fermentation (SSF) have made it attractive in the production of certain high value fine chemicals such as MTG. However, difficulties in physiological and kinetic studies still remain in process control, optimization and scale-up of SSF. A model using a mimic SSF system will be developed on the basis of an inert carrier to which the theory developed in submerged fermentation can be applied. Using this model, we expect to be able to optimize the SSF.
</OL>

<B>Reference</B><BR>
Zhu Y., Rinzema A., Tramper J. & Bol J. (1995) <I>Applied Microbiology and Biotechnology</I> , 44:277-282
Zhu Y., Rinzema A., Tramper J., & Bol J. (1996) <I>Biotechnology and Bioengineering</I>, (to appear)

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 20/02/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
