</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Mass production by solid-state fermentation of fungal conidia for biological control of plant pathogens and pests: technological aspects</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Mass production by solid-state fermentation of fungal conidia for biological control of plant pathogens and pests: technological aspects</H2>

<B>PhD-fellow:</B> July 1995 - July 1999<BR>
<B>Supervisors:</B> Prof. J. Tramper, dr. A. Rinzema (Food and Bioprocess Engineering WAU)<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> May 1995 - May 1999<BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> NWO-STW<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
<I>Coniothyrium minitans</I> is a promising biological control agent of <I>Sclerotinia sclerotiorum</I>. Its practical application depends on reliable methods for mass production of conidia. Production of conidia has only been successfully achieved in the laboratory by Solid-State Fermentation (SSF), i.e. cultivation of the fungus on moist solid particles in systems with a continuous gas phase. Although SSF is traditionally applied especially in the African food industry, the design of SSF systems is still based completely on trial and error. Design and scale-up methods needs insight in biokinetics and physical (transport) phenomena. In traditional SSF bioreactors, such as static beds, temperature and concentration gradients on reactor scale are likely to occur. Mixing can alleviate these problems, but not all fungi and solid substrates/supports can tolerate shear and collision forces. Another problem in SSF is the control of temperature and aw. Temperature control is primarily achieved by water evaporation. Because of this evaporative cooling problems can occur with respect to water exhaustion.<P>

<B>Aim</B><BR>
The aim is to establish rules for the design and scale-up of an SSF process for reliable mass-production of conidia.<P>
 
<B>Research topics</B><BR>
<I>Selection of solid substrate/support</I><BR>
A model SSF system could simplify the study of SSF and ease the control of product quality (conidia). Sporulation may be induced by nutrient limitation, therefore intra-particle gradients may be important. By using a well defined medium composition with an inert support, intra-particle gradients can easily be described and modelled.<P>

<I>Modelling kinetics of growth and conidia formation of Coniothyrium minitinas on solid substrates</I><BR>
The quantification and prediction of the interrelationships between the environment changes and fungal growth and differentiation is important to understand conidia production. To describe the diverse processes and interrelations, a mathematical model will be made. For the modelling of mycelium growth, three systems with increasing complexity are introduced (figure 1). When this is done,  sporulation will be modelled.<P>

<IMG SRC="jaap1.gif"><P>

<TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR><TD><B>Fig 1:</B></TD><TD> Different systems used for modelling SSF:</TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD>
1. Liquid covered with membrane;<BR>
2. Gel matrix covered with membrane;<BR>
3. Gel matrix without membrane.<BR>
</TD></TR></TABLE><P>

<I>Reactor design</I><BR>
Irrespective of the fermentor that is selected (mixed or static system) the main design problem with solid-state fermentation is the simultaneous control of temperature and moisture content. A mathematical model will be used to describe the dynamic behaviour of the reactor. This will facilitate the design and control of the fermentor.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 21/02/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
