<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Production of cellulase by Trichoderma reesei QM9414 on wheat bran in solid-state fermentation</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Production of cellulase by Trichoderma reesei QM9414 on wheat bran in solid-state fermentation</H2>

<B>PhD-fellow:</B> Jan P. Smits<BR>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD><B>Supervisors:</B></TD><TD> Prof. J. Tramper, Dr. A. Rinzema (Food and Bioprocess Engineering WAU)</TD></TR>
<TR><TD></TD><TD> Dr. H.M. van Sonsbeek, Ing. W. Knol (TNO Nutrition and Food Research)</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<B>Project term:</B> 1993-1997<BR>
<B>Sponsors:</B> TNO, Bavaria, Gist-brocades, Unilever, Quest International<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>
			
<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Although the solid-state fermentation (SSF) technique is ancient applied in the Far East for production of, for instance, tempeh and koji, knowledge of process engineering of SSF is underdeveloped in the Western hemisphere. The main problem in modelling and scale up of SSF is the biomass parameter. Biomass can not be separated from the substrate, and therefore not be determined. So, other parameters, like heat development, product formation and oxygen consumption, can not directly be correlated to biomass development.<P>

<B>Research</B><BR>
The aim of this research is to build up process engineering knowledge on SSF. The production of cellulases on wheat bran is used here as a model fermentation. Several stages can be indicated within this research:<BR>

<OL>
<LI> Definition of the system.
<LI> Study of kinetics.
<LI> Modelling of SSF in tray and packed-bed.
</OL>

The system chosen for research on kinetics is simple: inoculated wheat bran is incubated in Petri-dishes in a fixed-climate cabinet. Weight loss, glucosamine as the measure for biomass, oxygen consumption rate (OCR), carbon-dioxide production rate (CPR) and carboxy methyl cellulose hydrolysing enzyme activity (CMC-ase) production, as measure for cellulase production, are measured in the fermented bran. OCR and CPR are measured using the set-up as shown in Figure 1. All mentioned parameters can be determined accurately with a standard deviation of less than 10% of the measured value.<BR>
The measured activities are used to describe the kinetics. As an example, Figure 2 shows the development of OCR and glucosamine during SSF. Correlations between the kinetic parameters are described to by-pass the biomass determination.<P>

<IMG SRC="jan1.gif"><P>

Figure 1: Set-up for measurement of OCR and CPR.<P>

Combined with the influence of temperature and water activity on microbial kinetics and combined with physical parameters, such as heat and mass transport limitations, these results will be used to set-up a model which predicts CMC-ase formation, oxygen consumption and heat production in a tray and packed bed reactor.<P>

<IMG SRC="jan2.gif"><P>

Figure 2: Course of OCR (open symbols) and glucosamine (closed symbols) during SSF of wheat bran.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 20/02/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
