<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Development of a multi-phase fluid bed reactor for conversions in toxic organic solvents</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Development of a multi-phase fluid bed reactor for conversions in toxic organic solvents</H2>

<TABLE><TR><TD NOWRAP WIDTH=50%>
<B>PhD-fellow:</B> Erik van Zessen</TD>
<TD NOWRAP>tel: 08370-82240</TD>
</TR><TR><TD></TD><TD NOWRAP>e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:ErikvanZessen@prock@lmt.wau.nl">ErikvanZessen@prock@lmt.wau.nl</A></TD></TABLE><P>

Wageningen Agricultural University, Food Technology department, Food and Bioprocess Engineering Group
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Organic solvents can enhance the use of biological conversions of either toxic or poorly in water soluble substrates to the corresponding products. The higher solubility of the substrate in the organic solvent will give a higher concentration in the reactor. The same holds for the product. Besides, the higher solubility of the product in the organic solvent will make the downstream processing less complicatedly.<P>

<IMG SRC="erik1.gif"><P>

To make biological activity possible water has to be present either as a separate liquid phase or as trapped into a gel. The micro-organism will be immobilised for a number of reasons, of which the protection against the toxicity of the organic solvent is the most important. The essential nutrients for the micro-organism will dissolve far better in water than in the organic solvent. As a consequence there will be at least a three-phase system. Different reactor types has been studied in the past. None of them is superior to the other. In this project a liquid-liquid-solid fluidised bed will be used for good mixing reasons and the relative independence of the fluxes of both liquids on each other in comparing this to an air-lift or liquid impelled loop reactor. The micro-organism chosen will be probably a <I>P.putida</I>, which is able to oxidise styrene to styrenoxide.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
Development of a general design strategy for a three-phase fluid bed reactor in such a way that the production rate is as high as possible by understanding the different processes acting in this type of reactor.<P>

<B>Results & current research</B><BR>
<OL>
Future research will focus on:
<LI> immobilisation of the micro-organism, the acceptability of the micro-organism to organic solvents and substrate- productkinetics, 
<LI> hydrodynamics of the three phase fluidised bed, such as flow patterns of the different phases, drop size(distribution) of the dispersed phase, hold-up, etc., 
<LI> mass transport between the different phases, 
<LI> integration of the different processes and optimising the total microbial conversion.
</OL>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 20/02/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
