<HEAD><TITLE>Reactor design for the enzymatic conversion of solid maleate to solid D-malate in a solid/liquid-two-phase-system</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Reactor design for the enzymatic conversion of solid maleate to solid D-malate in a solid/liquid-two-phase-system</H2>

<B>PhD-student:</B> Marco Michielsen (tel: 08317-483435)<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> BSDL<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
D-malate is an optically active compound, that can be used as a synthon for the production of chemicals. <I>Pseudomonas pseudoalcaligenes</I> possesses the enzyme maleate hydratase. This enzyme is capable of catalysing the hydrolysis of maleate to D-malate. <I>Ps. pseudoalcaligenes</I> does not have a transport system for maleate. To facilitate transfer, the cell membrane is permeabilised. Both maleate and D-malate inhibit the enzyme. By addition of Ca<SUP>2+</SUP>, maleate and D-malate precipitate resulting in a decrease of the inhibition and the formation of a liquid/solid-two-phase-system. In this system, a high product concentration can be attained. When in a batch process Ca-maleaat was supplied as crystals, a 100% conversion was obtained.<BR>
A schematic view of the production of solid D-malate from solid maleate is given below:<P>

<IMG SRC="marco1.gif"><P>

Essential steps in this process are the solubilisation of the substrate Ca-maleate, the conversion, and the precipitation of Ca-D-malate.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
The project aims at the development of a continuous process for the conversion of solid Ca-maleate to solid Ca-D-malate in such a way that 1) the purity of the product is as high as possible, 2) the volumetric reaction rate is as high as possible, 3) the maleate conversion is as high as possible, and 4) the amount of Ca<SUP>2+</SUP> added to the system is as low as possible.<P>

<B>Strategy</B><BR>
Future research will focus on: 1) physics and thermodynamics of the crystals, size of the crystals, solubility of substrate and product as a function of temperature, pH, Ca<SUP>2+</SUP>-concentration, 2) kinetics of solubilisation and precipitation, 3) kinetics of the conversion (substrate and product inhibition), 4) integration of solubilisation/conversion/precipitation in a batch reactor, optimisation of reaction rates and yield, and 5) idem in a continuous system.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 20/02/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
