<HEAD><TITLE>Large-scale production of viral biopesticides in insect cell cultures</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Large-scale production of viral biopesticides in insect cell cultures</H2>

<B>Aio:</B> Ir. A. van Oorschot<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Commission of the European Communities<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><P>

Baculoviruses can be used for the control of insect pests. They are specific for only a few, related, insect species. From the environmental viewpoint, they form a good alternative to chemical pesticides. Another application is the use of baculoviruses for production of recombinant proteins in insect-cellcultures.<BR>
Baculoviruses have a typical biphasic replication cycle (see figure). In cell culture, infected cells first produce virus particles which are released into the medium. These extra cellulair viruses (ECV) are necessary to spread the infection to other cells. In a second phase, the infected cells produce occluded viruses or polyhedra.. Finally the cells lyse. The occluded viruses are surrounded by a polyhedrine matrix which is a relative good protection against the environment. These occluded viruses are used for the control of insect pests.<P>

<IMG SRC="arie1.gif"><P>

<B>Aim of the research</B><P>

The research aims at the development of a low-cost system on a large laboratory scale for the production of insect viruses in bioreactors.<P>

<B>Set-up</B><P>

To reach the highest number of occluded viruses per unit volume of medium, the following points will be worked out:<BR>
- Testing of the shear sensitivity of insect cells. Besides <I>Spodoptera frugiperda</I>, other cell lines like <I>Spodoptera exigua</I> and <I>Heliothus armigera</I> will be investigated. The testing will be carried out in airliftreactors with a maximum volume of 66 liter. The effects of shear protective agents like methylcellulose, pluronic and medium components like serum will be investigated.<BR>
- The cell growth and the production of viruses will be investigated more closely. By modelling the cell growth and the virus production, an optimisation can be carried out. Important parameters are multiplicity of infection (number of viruses per cell) in the inoculum, moment of infection (early mid or late exponential growth) and the quality of the virus.<BR>
-Different cell lines and baculoviruses will be investigated more closely with respect to their number of viruses produced and the number of cells reached per unit volume of medium.<P>

<B>Co-operation</B><P>

This project is a co-operation between Wageningen Agricultural University, Technical University of Darmstadt, Zeneca ltd Agrochemicals, and the university of Cordoba.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 20/02/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
