<HEAD><TITLE>Metabolic flux analysis in mammalian cells</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2><CENTER>Metabolic flux analysis in mammalian cells</CENTER></H2>

<CENTER>
H.P.J.Bonarius and J.Tramper<BR>
Dept.Food Science, Agricultural University Wageningen.<BR>
<BR>
In collaboration with:<BR>
Dr. G.Schmid. Dept.PRP-Biotechnology, Hoffmann-La Roche AG, Basel, CH.<BR>
Dr. E. Heinzle. Dept.Chemical Engineering, Federal Institute of Technology, Zh&uuml;rich, CH<BR>
</CENTER><BR>

The intracellular fluxes of mammalian cells can theoretically be determined by merely measuring the in- and outgoing metabolic rates of the relevant metabolites and the composition of the biomass. However, fluxes within circular pathways can not be calculated from these measurement data. Their stoichiometry is linear dependent. Additional information is needed to calculate these fluxes<SUP>1,2</SUP>. In the past, this information has been obtained experimentally by using <SUP>13</SUP>C- or <SUP>14</SUP>C-labeled substrates. In this research, both theoretical and experimental infromation is used in order to calculate the intracellular fluxes in mammalian cells. The final goal of this project is to determine what theoretical constraint(s) can be used in order to determine metabolic fluxes without using labeled substrates.<BR>
The CO<SUB>2</SUB> production rate, one of the above mentioned metabolic rates, is required for metabolic flux analysis. In mammalian cell culture its determination is troubled due to the bicarbonate in the culture medium. By developing a method to determine the CO<SUB>2</SUB> production rate<SUP>3</SUP>, we obtained an additional constraint in order to estimate the intracellular fluxes.<BR>
Additional constraints are required to determine the intracellular fluxes, since CO<SUB>2</SUB> is produced in more than one circular metabolic pathway. By introducing the "minimum-norm constraint", a theoretical constraint that is based on least-squares analysis, we estimated the metabolic flows<SUP>4</SUP>.<BR>
Currently, validation experiments are carried out. By measuring the isotopic disctribution of products such as CO<SUB>2</SUB> (using mass spectrometry), lactate, alanine, glutamate and proline (using <SUP>13</SUP>C-NMR spectrometry) of <SUP>13</SUP>C-glucose fed mammalian cells, experimental information is obtained to calculate all metabolic fluxes. These data will give us the experimental information that is required to test whether the minimum-norm constraint or other theoretical constraints can be used to determine metabolic fluxes.<P>

<IMG SRC="bonarius1.gif"><P>

1. Savinell, J.M. and Palsson, B.O. 1992. J. Theor. Biol. <B>155</B>: 215-242.<BR>
2. Vallino, J.J. and Stephanopoulos, G. 1990. In: Subhas, K.S. Frontiers in Bioprocessing, CRC Press, Boca Raton. pp. 205-219.<BR>
3. Bonarius, H.P.J., et al. 1995. Biotechnol. Bioeng. <B>45</B>: 524-535.<BR>
4. Bonarius, H.P.J., et al. 1996. Biotechnol. Bioeng. <B>48</B>: 321-341.<BR>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 18/03/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
