<HEAD><TITLE>The separation of the dispersed phase from stable oil-in-water emulsions using a hydrophobic membrane</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>The separation of the dispersed phase from stable oil-in-water emulsions using a hydrophobic membrane</H2>

<B>PhD-student:</B> Ageeth Lefferts<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Foundation for Chemical Research in the Netherlands<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
In this research, the possibilities to separate the dispersed phase from stable, secondary oil-in-water emulsions (d<SUB>32</SUB><10 m&#181;m) using hydrophobic membranes are investigated. Before permeation  of the dispersed phase can occur, the droplets have to be transported from the bulk to the membrane surface. Secondly, the droplets must coalesce with the membrane or the membrane wetting liquid.<P>

<B>Transport</B><BR>
A model has been developed in which the 5 most important transport mechanisms of oil droplets from the bulk to the membrane are described: gravitational settling, inertial impaction, interception, electrostatic attraction (or repulsion) and diffusive capture. Which transport mechanism is dominant depends on the emulsion properties, such as droplet size and density of the oil phase, and on process parameters, such as flow velocity, channel length, channel height and module type (hollow fiber, flat sheet or dead end configuration). As an example, the influence of the flow velocity on the experimentally determined <I>Sh</I>-number [-] in a dead end module is depicted in figure 1.<P>

<IMG SRC="ageeth2.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 1, Influence of the stream velocity on the Sh-number in a dead end module. The membrane is made of polypropylene with an average pore size of 0.2 &#181;m.</I><P>

<B>Coalescence</B><BR>
The model gives good predictions only if transport is the rate limiting step in the process because its theory is based on the assumption of ideal coalescence: once a droplet reaches the membrane, it coalesces directly and completely. In other words, the probability K<SUB>c</SUB> [-] that once a droplet contacts the membrane it coalesces, is 1. However, coalescence is a time dependent process; it takes time before the aqueous film between droplet and membrane breaks up. In figure 2, K<SUB>c</SUB> is calculated for the experiment of figure 1, by dividing the amount of droplets that coalesce with the membrane, calculated from permeation data, by the amount of droplets that theoretically contact the membrane.<P>

<IMG SRC="ageeth2.gif"><P>

<I>Figure 2, K<SUB>c</SUB> as a function of pump delivery for the dead end module.</I><P>

From figure 2, it is obvious that ideal coalescence does not occur at high stream velocities. The reason is that the droplet-membrane contact time is too short for completion of the film layer drainage. Other factors influencing the coalescence probability under investigation are emulsion properties (surfactant type and concentration, droplet size) and membrane material properties (pore size distribution and surface roughness).<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 29/02/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT25-B29-370</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA011-000119-B031-311</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://utct.ct.utwente.nl:80/~ospt/minipost95/luw/rob.html 130.89.50.60 19970216195416 text/html 2440
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sunday, 16-Feb-97 19:47:30 GMT
