<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Modelling of the influence of process treatment on the inactivation of antinutritional factors in animal feed</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Modelling of the influence of process treatment on the inactivation of antinutritional factors in animal feed</H2>

<B>PhD-student:</B> Rob van den Hout<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> May 1992-April 1996<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> TNO-Nutrition<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Beans are a good resource of proteins and energy for animals. But feeding of animals with raw beans have negative influences, like a decrease of growth and pancreatic enlargement. These negative effects are induced by the presence of antinutritional factors (ANF) in the bean. Some of the ANF such as trypsin inhibitors (TI) and lectines are heat-labile and can be inactivated by a heat treatment. However, heat treatment can also cause destruction of other proteins. Heat processing can be done by for example extrusion cooking, expansion and steam toasting.<P>

<B>Objectives</B><BR>
Aim of this research is to model the influence of process treatment on the inactivation of ANF in soy. Main parameters to be studied are temperature, moisture and shear.<P>

<B>Methodology</B><BR>
The decrease of the trypsin inhibitor activity (TIA) in soy during heat processing is followed as an indicator for efficiency of the heat treatment procedure. The inactivation kinetics of TI was measured and modelled as a function of temperature and moisture content (see figure).<P>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="rob1.gif"><P>
 
<I>Figure. Inactivation of TI (moisture content=0.23 g/g ds).</I></CENTER><P>

The biochemical (different TI's) and physical (water activity) mechanisms behind the inactivation kinetics of TI is examined. Next the inactivation kinetics model will be included in a process model for steam toasting. With this combination of the kinetics and process models it is possible to optimise the toasting process. Moreover the influence of shear on the inactivation of TI during extrusion cooking is investigated.<P>


<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 22/02/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
