</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Enantioselective membrane separation from self-assembled microheterogeneous media</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Enantioselective membrane separation from self-assembled microheterogeneous media</H2>

<TABLE BORDER=0>
<TR><TD Width=50%><B>Pieter Overdevest</B></TD><TD>Food and Bioprocess Engineering Group</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Albert van der Padt</TD><TD>Agricultural University Wageningen</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Klaas van 't Riet</TD><TD>PO Box 8129 / 6700 EV  Wageningen</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<HR SIZE=0>

<I>INTRODUCTION / AIM</I><BR>
Chiral compounds are often applied in agrochemical, food and pharmaceutical industries. Both the production of chiral compounds which can be labour intensive and the separation of a racemic mixture are possible options to obtain pure chiral products. Therefore, resolution of enantiomers is an important field in separation science. As a result of equal physical properties of these optical isomers, the separation needs to be fulfilled in a chiral environment to introduce diastereomeric interactions.<P>
 
This project aims to anchor chiral selector molecules in a microheterogeneous phase. These chiral selectors have different affinities for the two enantiomers. The different affinity of the chiral selectors and the application of ultrafiltration make enantiomer separation possible; unassociated enantiomers pass the membrane and complexed enantiomers do not pass (fig. 1). We aim at the description, application and optimisation of this separation process.<P>


<TABLE>
<TR>
<TD><IMG SRC="pieter1.gif"></TD>
<TD><IMG SRC="pieter2.gif"></TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP><B>Figure 1.</B> Resolution by membrane separation with the use of chiral selectors fixed in micelles. Micelles are unable to pass the membrane.</TD>
<TD VALIGN=TOP><B>Figure 2.</B> Enantiomer resolution using a micellar enhanced ultrafiltration system (MEUF).</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>

<I>EXPERIMENTAL / RESULTS</I><BR>
The concept of enantiomer separation as shown in figure 1 is applied in a micellar enhanced ultrafiltration process (figure 2). Using a capillair electrophereses system for the enantiomer analyses, we reproduced the experiments done by Creagh  who used an HPLC to analyse the enantiomer concentration.<P>

<FONT SIZE="-2"><SUP>1</SUP> Creagh, A.L., B.B.E. Hasenack, A. van der Padt, E.J.R. Sudhölter, K. van 't Riet. Biotech. bioeng., 44 (1994),  690-698.</FONT>

