<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Drying of lactic acid bacteria with maximum residual activity and stability</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Drying of lactic acid bacteria with maximum residual activity and stability</H2>

<B>PhD-fellow:</B> Ir. Leonie Linders<BR>
<B>Project term:</B> January 1992 - January 1996<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Unilever Research Laboratory<BR>

<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
Convective drying is an economically attractive method for preservation of starter cultures of bacteria. However, during drying two types of inactivation occur: thermal and dehydration inactivation. Thermal inactivation can be minimised by optimising process conditions. Dehydration inactivation, that is due to membrane damage, is the key problem. This research is focused on minimising the dehydration inactivation of <I>Lactobacillus plantarum</I>.<P>

<B>Objective</B><BR>
In this project the influence of different process parameters on the dehydration inactivation of <I>L.plantarum</I> is studied as well as the physical and physiological backgrounds.<P>

<B>Drying conditions</B><BR>
The choice of appropriate drying conditions can result in a considerable decrease in dehydration inactivation. The drying temperature in combination with the drying time are crucial parameters.<P>

<B>Carbohydrate protection; physical approach </B><BR>
The addition of carbohydrates can improve the residual activity of <I>L.plantarum</I> after dehydration. Maltose, sucrose en sorbitol are protective, whereas lactose, trehalose, glucose en fructose are not protective. Physical parameters like moisture content, water activity and moisture distribution are influenced by the addition of carbohydrates. However, calculations show that the protectivity of the carbohydrates can not be explained by changes in those physical parameters. Therefore it is important to take physiological effects into account.<P>

<B>Carbohydrate protection; physiological approach</B><BR>
In naturally occuring anhydrous systems like e.g. polls and seeds carbohydrates are known to interact with the membrane. It is suggested that the inactivation is caused by leakage of essential cell components through the membrane occurring during drying and rehydration. This leakage is related to the phase transition temperature of the membrane (fig 1). Through interaction of the carbohydrates with the membrane, the phase transition temperature is reduced, thus leakage is prevented. 
In analogy with this theory the phase transition temperature of the membrane is currently studied and the influence of protective and non-protective carbohydrates.<P>

<IMG SRC="leonie1.gif"><P>

Fig 1 	Membrane phase transition temperature as a function of moisture content<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 20/02/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
