<HEAD><TITLE>Modelling the microbial quality of foods</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Modelling the microbial quality of foods</H2>

<B>PhD-student:</B> ir. T. Wijtzes<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> TNO-Nutrition; Zeist, The Netherlands.<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>
	
<CENTER><B>Introduction</B></CENTER><BR>
The quality and safety of foods are often determined by the growth of microorganisms. Microbial growth is dependent on intrinsic properties, such as water activity and acidity, and extrinsic properties, such as temperature and oxygen availability. In recent years the interest in developing mathematical models to describe the growth of organisms as functions of controlling factors has increased. The mathematical models can be used to predict the change in quality of foods over time and can therefore be applied to estimate the shelflife of foods. The models help to decrease the required amount of costly and time consuming challenge tests and can be used for distribution chain optimisation. Another important feature of modelling is the acquisition of improved knowledge of the factors that determine food quality.<P>

<CENTER><B>Methods</B></CENTER><BR>
The change of microbial numbers in time in batch cultures usually displays a sigmoidal shape.<P>

<IMG SRC="wijtzes1.gif"><P>

Several parameters can be derived from this curve, of which growth rate &#181; (h<SUP>-1</SUP>) and lag time lambda (h) are the most important. 87 growth curves of microorganisms in response to different temperature acidity combinations were measured.<P>

<CENTER><B>Results</B></CENTER><BR>
On the basis of an extensive data set, it proved that the effect of temperature and the effect of acidity on bacterial growth rate could be multiplied.<P>

&#181; = b (T-T<SUB>min</SUB>)<SUP>2</SUP> x (pH-pH<SUB>min</SUB>)(pH-pH<SUB>max</SUB>)<P>

Some predictions of the model are shown below<P>

<IMG SRC="wijtzes2.gif"><P>


<CENTER><B>Implications</B></CENTER><BR>
The developed model consists of parameters that are well known to microbiologists, and that can be determined relatively easily.<P>

The developed model can be used to predict changes in food quality.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 21/03/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
