<HEAD><TITLE>Valorization of brewery spent grains</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<IMG SRC="erwin.jpg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=50>

<H2>Valorization of brewery spent grains</H2>

<B>PhD-student:</B> ir. E. Kuiper (tel.: -31-0317483701)<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Centraal Brouwerij Kantoor<BR>
<BR>
<TABLE BORDER=0><TR><TD><IMG SRC="w.gif" WIDTH=50 HEIGHT=50></TD>
<TD><BR>Department of Food Science<BR>
Food and Bioprocess Engineering Group</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B><CENTER>Introduction</CENTER></B><P>

During the brewing process several by-products are produced. <B>B</B>rewery <B>S</B>pent <B>G</B>rain is the residue of the malt and grain that remains after mash filtration (mainly husks and embryo parts).<P>

<IMG SRC="erwin1.gif"><P>

The presence of a large fraction of (hemi-) cellulose is the reason that BSG is only suitable as a feed for ruminants. BSG is used as a supplementary or complete cattle feed. BSG is now sold as a wet feed, which makes it necessary for the farmers to feed it within some weeks to the animals, before it spoils. Another option for the farmer is to ensile the BSG. The problem in both ways is that a lot of highly polluted water leaves the material into the soil. With the growth of the production of the breweries and the decrease in amount of cattle, it is necessary to develop alternative applications for BSG. Because of the composition of BSG, one of the most logical applications is that of a animal feed. In this case the badly digestible components should be separated, reduced or modified to make it suitable for monogastric animals.<P>

<B><CENTER>Aim of the research</CENTER></B><P>

The aim of the research is to develop a process line in which the BSG is valorized into a valuable product or ingredient in the animal feed market. Problems that have to be solved are the dewatering and the improvement of the digestibility of the fresh BSG.<P>

<B><CENTER>Research</CENTER></B><P>

<B>1.</B> Dewatering<BR>
Concerning dewatering, the research focuses on the principles of water holding capacity of the fibre-rich BSG in relation to its composition and structure. Processes like pressing, centrifuging, and (membrane)-filtration are evaluated for different types of BSG with different kinds of pretreatments (milling, extruding, etc.). In this research, attention is also paid to the effects on storage characteristics of these changes of the product.<P>

<B>2.</B> Modification of the fibre-fraction<BR>
To improve the digestibility of the BSG, the badly digestible fibre-fraction should be modified. Thermo-mechanical and enzyme-technological treatments and their influences on physico-chemical parameters are studied. Influences like temperature, pH, time, concentration, type of enzyme and specific surface area on the availability and digestibility of the fibre will be quantified. This means that the chemical composition of the fibre, the working mechanism of the enzymes and the influences within the process equipment are factors that influence the digestibility of the fibre. In this research this is the main relation that is studied.<P>

<B>3.</B> Process<BR>
The final studies in this project will deal with the development of some possible specific process designs for the valorization of BSG.<P>

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 21/02/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
