<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Modelling microbial interactions</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../../back/tile2.gif">

<H2>Modelling microbial interactions</H2>

<B>Post-doc:</B> Dirk Martens (Tel. 0317-484993)<BR>
<B>Post-doc:</B> Catherine B&eacute;al<BR>
<B>Sponsor:</B> Graduate school VLAG<BR>
	
<HR SIZE=0>

<B>Introduction</B><BR>
The growth of micro-organisms is usually studied in pure culture. However, in practice micro-organisms often are present in mixed communities consisting out of several species. Such mixed communities may for example be found in environmental technology, and food fermentations. Also in the case of food spoilage several spoiler organisms may be active simultaneously. Interactions between  micro-organisms lead to different growth characteristics for each individual species as compared to pure cultures of these micro-organisms. Consequently the occurrence of interactions between different micro-organisms may alter the shelflife of a product.<P>

<B>Aim</B><BR>
The objective of this study is to develop a general procedure to quantify the effects of microbial interactions through the combination of transport phenomena with the biological activity of the interacting micro-organisms.<P>

<B>Modelling approach</B><BR>
The environment is divided in a grid of micro-environments (Figure 1). Each micro-environment is characterized by a state vector (S) and the presence of equilibrium (e.g. pH)  and transformation processes (e.g. microbial activity and enzymatic reactions).<P>

<IMG SRC="dirk1.gif"><P>

<B>Figure 1.</B> General modelling approach.<P>

The state vector contains the variables of interest like temperature, pH, concentrations of micro-organisms and substrates. First the equilibrium state (S<SUB>Equi</SUB>) with respect to the equilibrium processes is calculated for each micro-environment. On the basis of the equilibrium state the transport rates (R<SUB>transport</SUB>) between the different micro-environments and the overall transformation rates (R<SUB>transform</SUB>) in each micro-environment are calculated. Based on these rates the new state of the system is calculated numerically a small time step later.<P>

<IMG SRC="dirk2.gif"><P>

<B>Figure 2.</B> Mixed culture at an initial pH of 6.<P>

<B>Research</B><BR>
To support the theoretical work the interaction between <I>Lactobacillus curvatus</I> and <I>Enterobacter cloacae</I> is studied as a model system. Both organisms compete for glucose, while the lactate produced by <I>L. curvatus</I> may inhibit the growth of <I>E. cloacae</I>. In addition, the growth of <I>E. cloacae</I> is inhibited by the pH decrease caused by the lactate. For both organisms the growth rate has been modelled as a function of the pH and the glucose and lactate concentration. With the growth-rate equations, Pirt's linear equation of substrate consumption and a constant yield of lactate on glucose for <I>L. curvatus</I>, the behaviour of both organisms is predicted in mixed cultures in erlenmeyers. In Figure 2 an example of a mixed culture at an initial pH of 6 is shown. In the future the study of the mixed cultures in erlenmeyers will be continued. In addition, transport will be incorporated in the models and the interactions will be studied in and on solid media.

<H6><CENTER><HR>&copy; OSPT - <A HREF="mailto:OSPT@ct.utwente.nl"> OSPT@ct.utwente.nl</A> - last modification 06/03/96</CENTER></H6>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
