Reengineering Distributed Learning Environments</A>(Sept. 1994)

<A NAME="software"></A><DT><STRONG>Software</STRONG></DT>
<DD><IMG SRC="../media/gifs/diabull.gif" WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10 HSPACE="5"><A HREF="../technology/software/neuron.html">Asymetrix's Neuron</A>
</DL>
</TD>

<TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT  WIDTH="440">
<IMG SRC="../media/gifs/1X17pix.gif" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH="17" HEIGHT="475">

<P>The concept of distributed learning integrates the interactive capabilities of networking, computing and multimedia with learner-centered teaching approaches such as collaboration, discovery learning and active learning. In tandem, these strategies enable us to develop new and empowering ways to use technology and to create more effective learning experiences for students in an "any time, any place" mode. In expanding understanding of distributed learning technology and benefits, the IAT offers outreach services including training and development services, topical papers and resource guides, satellite broadcasts and videos, and software tools. Find out more about our distributed learning activities and resources by following any of the links at left.

</TABLE>
</TABLE>
