<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>O</FONT>nline <FONT SIZE=+3>M</FONT>usic <FONT SIZE="+3">S</FONT>cholarship <FONT SIZE="+3">R</FONT>esources</FONT> </STRONG><BR>
Compiled by: Jane Duff Harris<BR>
Institute for Academic Technology<A HREF="http://wwwscout.cs.wisc.edu/scout/report/"><IMG SRC="../../media/gifs/scoutsel.gif" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=29 BORDER=0 ALIGN=RIGHT></A><BR>
</CENTER>
 <P>
This is a list of annotated links which we have found of interest in our Mellon Foundation sponsored work on information technology and music scholarship. 
<center>
<table>
<TR><TH COLSPAN=2>
<A name="begin">Table of Contents</A></TH></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=225 VALIGN=TOP</TR>
<A HREF="#MusProSoc">Music Professional Societies</A><BR>
<A HREF="#UnivMusLibrHomePages">Music Dept and Library Pages</A><BR>
<A HREF="#OnMusJour">Journal Web Sites</A><BR>
<A HREF="#DissLists">Dissertation Listings</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Research">Research</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Analysis">Analysis<BR>
<A HREF="#CorpusSites">Corpus Sites</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Composers">Composers</A><BR>
<A HREF="#DigiLibGen">Digital Libraries - General Sources</A><BR>
<A HREF="#DigiLibMus">Digital Libraries - Music</A><BR>
</TD>
	
<TD WIDTH=185 VALIGN=TOP>
<A HREF="#MIDI">MIDI</A><BR>
<A HREF="#AuthTools">Authoring Tools</A><BR>
<A HREF="#MusCodeSoftware">Music Code and Software</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Standards">Standards</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Cataloguing/Database">Cataloguing/Database</A><BR>
<A HREF="#NetTeach/MusEd">Net Teaching/Music Ed<BR>
<A HREF="#Evaluation">Evaluation</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Copyright">Copyright</A><BR>
<A HREF="#General">General</A><BR>
<A HREF="#Miscellaneous">Miscellaneous Music Sources</A><BR>
</TD>
</table>
</center>
</DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>
<DT><H3><A name="MusProSoc">Music Professional Societies</A></H3>
The following is a modest list of music professional societies that have a web presence. Of particular interest to us at the IAT are the Society for Music Theory (for its music cognition group), the College Music Society (for teaching and learning in higher education), and ATMI (for its focus on music technology).  For a fuller listing, see <b>Scholarly Societies and Organizations</b> at the <A HREF="http://www.rism.harvard.edu/MusicLibrary/InternetResources.html">Edna Kuhn Loeb Music Library at Harvard.</A><P>
<DD>

    <DL><p>

       <LI><A HREF="http://www.tc.umn.edu/nlhome/m111/compfrm/">American Composers Forum</A><P>

       <LI><A HREF="http://musdra.ucdavis.edu/Documents/AMS/AMS.html">American Musicological Society</A><BR>
Contains an <i>extensive</i> list of <A HREF="http://musdra.ucdavis.edu/Documents/AMS/musicology_www.html">WWW Sites of Interest to Musicologists</A>. This list is divided into the following categories:  Academic Job Listings; Dissertations; Music Libraries, Archives and Online Catalogs; Opera and Song; Church Music; Early Music; Instruments; Composers and Composition; Theory; Computer Music; Rock and Pop; Jazz; Music in Latin America; Folk and Ethnomusicology; Women in Music; Music Education; Music Therapy; Music Publishing; Other Interesting Links; Funny Music Stuff; How to Contact your Elected Officials; Insidious Term Papers for Sale; Orchestras; Choirs; Ensembles; a listing of Academic Institutions by country; Catalog of Music Resources; WWW sites; and Music FTP sites.<P>

       <LI><A HREF="http://www.music.org/atmi/">Association for Technology in Music Instruction (ATMI) Home Page</A><BR>
ATMI serves as a forum for the discussion of technical issues with respect to music instruction. Membership gets you the hardcopy newsletter as well as an annual directory of software. Thanks to Anne Parks of Duke University for the listing of urls from the <A HREF="http://www.duke.edu/music/atmiurls.html">1996 Atlanta conference.</A> See also David William's and Peter Webster's monthly online Q&A technology column <A HREF="http://www.music.org/sqk_blat/">Squeak and Blat.</A><P>

       <LI><A HREF="http://www.music.org/index.html">The College Music Society Home Page</A><BR>
CMS deals with issues in music and higher education including interdisciplinary concerns.  Here is a listing of urls from the <A HREF="http://www.music.org/ann/1996/intro96.html">1996 CMS/ATMI conference in Atlanta.</A><P>
       <LI><A HREF="http://www.cwru.edu/orgs/ema/">Early Music America Home Page</A><P>

       <LI><A HREF="http://www.mus.cam.ac.uk/ESCOM/">European Society for the Cognitive Sciences of Music</A><BR>
The aim of ESCOM is to further the study the perceptual and mental processes underlying musical experience and activity. Includes the free online <A HREF="http://www.mus.cam.ac.uk/ESCOM/E/NL9E/contentsE.html">ESCOM newsletter</A> as well as links to other sites containing information in the areas of auditory perception, cognition, and computers.<P>

                <LI><A HREF="http://www.music.ed.ac.uk/euchmi/galpin/">Galpin Society Home Page</A><P>

       <LI><A HREF="http://www.music.indiana.edu/tech_s/mla/index.htm">Music Library Association (MLA) Clearinghouse</A><BR>
A site containing documents of interest to music librarians. Includes <A HREF="http://www.music.indiana.edu/tech_s/mla/legcom/copyhome.htm">A Guide to Copyright for Music Librarians.</A><P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://boethius.music.ucsb.edu/smt-list/smthome.html?">Society for Music Theory (SMT)</A><BR>
In particular, in the annual meeting program pages, see the abstracts from the poster session on <A HREF="http://theory.esm.rochester.edu:80/smt-96.abstracts/cognition.research.html">New Cognition Research In Music Theory</A> given Saturday, 2 November 1996: 9:00-1:00.<P>
        
         <LI><A HREF="http://www.shef.ac.uk/uni/academic/I-M/mus/staff/wlw/srpmme/SRPMME.html">Society for Research in Psychology of Music and Music Education (SRPMME)</A><BR>
The aim of SRPMME is to provide an international forum for researchers in the psychology of music and music education. See especially the abstracts from the <A HREF="http://www.shef.ac.uk/uni/academic/I-M/mus/staff/wlw/srpmme/session_index.html">Perspectives on Music, the Mind and Education meeting.</A><P>     
        
        <LI><A HREF="http://rism.harvard.edu/sscm/">Society for Seventeenth-Century Music</A><BR>
Contains a free online <A HREF="http://www.sscm.harvard.edu/jscm/Welcome.html">journal</A> which includes graphical and musical examples.<P>
        
        <i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
        </DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>
<DT><H3><A name="UnivMusLibrHomePages">Selected Music Dept and Library Pages</A></H3>
These sites are included here because they contain a large number of links to diverse music resources on the internet.  The <A HREF="http://musdra.ucdavis.edu/Documents/AMS/musicology_www.html">AMS WWW Sites of Interest to Musicologists</A> contains an extensive listing of library and archive resources, as well as a listing of music institutions by country.
<DL><p>

     <LI><A HREF="http://www.rism.harvard.edu/MusicLibrary/InternetResources.html">Eda Kuhn Loeb Music Library, Harvard University Internet Resources for Music Scholars</A><P>

     <LI><A HREF="http://www.music.indiana.edu/music_resources/">Indiana University School of Music Worldwide Internet Music Resources</A><P>

     <LI><A HREF="http://www.sun.rhbnc.ac.uk/Music/Links/index.html">The Golden Pages: Links for musicians on the WWW</A> from Royal Holloway, University of London, Department of Music.<P>

     <LI><A HREF="http://www.siba.fi/Kulttuuripalvelut/music.html">Sibelius Academy Music Resources</A><P>

      <LI><A HREF="http://www.sun.rhbnc.ac.uk/Music/Links/musdepts.html">Music Department and faculty home pages</A> - Geoff Chew's comprehensive, worldwide listing of urls.<P>

<i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
<P>
</DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>
    <DT><H3><A name="OnMusJour">Journal Web Sites</A></H3>
The following is a partial listing.  (For a fuller list, see <A HREF="http://www.sun.rhbnc.ac.uk/Music/Links/journals.html">Ejournals for Musicians</A>.)  All are available free via email and/or the net, except Perception, Computer Music Journal and future issues of Sonances. Several take advantage of the multimedia potential of the Internet. Several have discussion lists available with them.
<DD>

    <DL><p>
                <LI><A HREF="http://www-mitpress.mit.edu/Computer-Music-Journal/">Computer Music Journal Home Page</A><BR>
A hardcopy journal at this time. The web site contains abstracts and contents of issues; several articles; audio files of computer music; source code of useful software; and references, both hard copy and www.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.inform.umd.edu:8080/EdRes/ReadingRoom/Newsletters/EthnoMusicology/">Ethnomusicology Research Digest</A><BR>
Contains an archive, a list of the digest issues, a list of multimedia files, and a WAIS search engine for the files.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://research.umbc.edu/efhm/">Ethnomusicology Online</A><BR>
Two issues available; includes graphics and sound; reviews.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.sscm.harvard.edu/jscm/Welcome.html">Journal of Seventeenth Century Music</A><BR>
Free via the WWW. Includes text, graphics, and audio clips. Second  issue, released December 1996, contains a thoughtful article on genre pairing of the passacaglia and chaconne by Dr. Alexander Silbiger of Duke University.<P>

       <LI><A HREF="http://library.berkeley.edu:8080/ucalpress/journals/mp/abstracts.html">Music Perception</A><BR>
This journal exists in hard copy, but one can view <A HREF="http://library.berkeley.edu:8080/ucalpress/journals/mp/tocs.html">Tables of Contents</A> and <A HREF="http://library.berkeley.edu:8080/ucalpress/journals/mp/abstracts.html">Abstracts.</A><P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://boethius.music.ucsb.edu/mto/mtohome.html">Music Theory Online</A><BR>
A publication of the Society for Music Theory. Extended articles and reviews. Available free both via email and the WWW.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.wu-wien.ac.at/earlym-l/Notitiae.Cantus/local.html">Notitiae Cantus</A><BR>
An international newsletter covering Gregorian and other Western chant. Available free via email.<P>

       <LI><A HREF="http://www.sonances.qc.ca/english.htm">Sonances</A><BR>
A new international music magazine with English and French formats; to contain reviews of musical events and materials, as well as an international schedule of musical events.<P>
Update: Sonances is in the process of modifying their mission. In the future, they will concentrate on 20th century music. <P>
The January 1997 issue contains an article by Jean-Michel Boulay,  <A href="http://www.sonances.qc.ca/janv97/english/ligeti.htm">A New Recording 
of Ligeti's Complete Works</A>. The article discusses  an international concert series in celebration of his 75th birthday, the forthcoming Sony Classical recording of his complete works (including a listing of the contents on each of the proposed thirteen disks), and biographical information. The article also notes that Ligeti has made changes to his opera <i>Le Grande Macabre</i> and to <i>Aventures</i>, which are included on the recordings.<P>

     <i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
    </DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>
<DT><H3><A name="DissLists">Dissertation Listings</A></H3>

<DL><p>

       <LI><A HREF="http://www.sun.rhbnc.ac.uk/Music/Archive/Disserts/index.html">Archive of Dissertation Abstracts in Music</A><BR>
International compendium of abstracts of dissertations in music both complete and in progress.  The list is alphabetical by author and contains links to abstracts.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.music.indiana.edu/ddm/">Doctoral Dissertations in Musicology-Online</A><BR>
	Contains dissertations recorded from 1996. Retrospective inclusion will occur in stages. Database is searchable by era, author, and term.<P>

         <LI><A HREF="http://boethius.music.ucsb.edu/mto/docs/diss-index.html">Music Theory Online (MTO) Dissertation Index</A><BR>
	Includes completed dissertations as well as dissertations in progress. With one exception, the dissertations date from 1990 onward. The list is arranged alphabetically by author and contains links to abstracts and outlines. <P> 

<i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
    </DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>
   
<DT><H3><A name="Research">Research</A></H3>

This category contains sources that refer to research accomplished both by traditional and technological means.

    <DL><p>

       <LI><A HREF="http://www.music.mcgill.ca/auditory/Auditory.html">Auditory World: Demonstrations and Experiments</A><BR>
Norma Welch's experiments at McGill.<P>

         <LI><A HREF="http://sparky.parmly.luc.edu/sandell/misc/muspsych.html">Bibliography on Methods of Psychomusicology</A><br>
Compiled by Greg Sandell.<P>


        <LI><A HREF="http://imr.utsa.edu/CAIRSS.html">CAIRSS</A> - Computer-Assisted Information Retrieval Service System.<BR>
This is a searchable bibliographic database of music research literature in music
education, music psychology, music therapy, and music medicine. It includes citations from 1,354 different journal titles.  There is a list of the journals indexed.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.music.yale.edu:/research/nets/nets.html">Modeling Musical Expectations:</A>  A Neural Network Model
of Dynamic Changes of Expectation in the Audition of
Functional Tonal Music.  Abstract. by Jonathan Berger. From the The Center for Studies in Music Technology at Yale.<P>

         <LI><A HREF="http://www.ifi.unizh.ch/groups/mml/musicmedia/rubato/rubato.html">RUBATO</A><BR>	Rubato is a research and education platform for analysis and performance of musical compositions. The Rubato platform implements the mathematical music theory and performance theory developed at the Multimedia Lab of the CSD at Zürich University during a Swiss National Science Foundation grant from 1992 to 1996.<P>

<i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
    </DL><p>
 <HR SIZE=6>
<DT><H3><A Name="Analysis">Analysis</A></H3>
The purpose of this section is to include substantial analyses of works for pedagogical purposes.
<DL><p>

      <LI><A HREF="http://mcnamee.graham.com/">Analyses of Music by Women</A><BR>
	The purpose of this site is two-fold: to provide analyses of music by women composers and to explore the benefits to music theory publishing of complementing text with music, images, and animation. <BR>
	As of fall 1996, the only analysis up on this site is that for the Piano Sonata II (1953) by Grazyna Bacewicz. The analysis is provided in multiple formats: QuickTime for Windows and Mac, Shockwave, two Java versions for monitors of varying size, and the original text and gif version.
<P>
	<LI><A HREF="http://sun1.rrzn.uni-hannover.de:80/musicweb/musicweb/demos/hempel/guide1en.htm">Weblication No 1: The Theme of Brahms' Haydn Variations, Op. 56 a and Op. 56 b, by Prof. Christoph Hempel.</A><br>From the Web Music Project at the Hochschule for Musik und Theatre in Hanover, Germany.<P>
<i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
</DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>
<DT><H3><A Name="CorpusSites">Corpus Sites</A></H3>
These sites may contain either the actual corpus or information about the corpus.
    <DL><p>
        
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.uncg.edu/~flmccart/amrhome.html">American Music Resource</A><br>
From the University of North Carolina at Greensboro.  This source includes over 800 bibliographies, lists and files. One can search on TOPIC (genre and style subdivisions) and SUBJECT (individuals - mostly composers).  The references include hard copy as well as internet sources.  There is a netography, which is a how-to essay with links for searching the net on musical topics.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://ccrma-www.stanford.edu/CCARH/Welcome.html">The Center for Computer Assisted Research in the Humanities (CCARH)</A><BR>
CCARH has created a database called <i>MuseData</i>. This database contains standard repertoire by Bach, Beethoven, Corelli, Handel, Haydn, Mozart, and Vivaldi which has been encoded for purposes of performance, print, and research.  The music is not available from this site.  See the hard copy journal <i>Computing in Musicology</i>, particularly volume 9, for further information on the encoding process and accompanying software.<P>
Update: Volume 10 of <i>Computing in Musicology</i> is now available.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.music.princeton.edu/chant_html/">The Gregorian Chant Homepage</A><BR>
Forthcoming at this site will be the Nassau Edition of Gregorian Chant. Contains an extended essay on the history of chant with many embedded links.<P>
	        
<LI>University of North Texas <A HREF="http://www.library.unt.edu/projects/lully/lullyhom.html">Lully Web Project Main Page</A><BR>
This site is a pilot for a multimedia thematic catalog of the
UNT Music Library's collection of first and second editions of theatrical works by the French Baroque composer Jean-Baptiste Lully. In addition, there is a listing of secondary sources germane to each work.  Included are some graphical images of the editions.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.let.ruu.nl/C+L/wiering/tmi_home.htm">Thesaurus Musicarum Italicarum</A><BR>
The aim of this project (based at the University of Utrecht) is to
publish a series of 16th and early 17th-century music treatises on CD-ROM.  Encoding of the texts will follow the TEI standard.<P>

         <LI><A HREF="gopher://iubvm.ucs.indiana.edu/11/tml">Thesaurus Musicarum Latinarum</A> Database for Latin Music Theory<BR>
The goal here is to incorporate the texts of all Latin treatises dealing with music theory from the medieval and early Renaissance periods. These treatises are organized by century, each of which has a search engine attached to it. <P>

<i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
    </DL><p>
