<HR SIZE=6>
  <DT><H3><A Name="DigiLibGen">Digital Libraries - General Sources</A></H3>
This category includes library association materials relating to digital libraries, projects related to digital libraries, and D-Lib magazine.
    <DL><p>

       <LI><A HREF="http://www.dlib.org/">D-Lib Magazine</A><P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://ukoln.bath.ac.uk/elib/">eLib Home page</A><BR>
In the UK, the principal digital libraries effort is through the Electronic Libraries Programme (eLib), funded by the Joint Funding Council's Libraries Review Group. This effort was mounted in response to increased pressures on library resources due to the increase in student numbers and the information explosion.  For descriptions of individual projects see, <A HREF="http://ukoln.bath.ac.uk/elib/flyers/">eLib project flyers/Web pages</A><P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.nlc-bnc.ca/ifla/">International Federation of Library Associations (IFLA)</A><P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.nlc-bnc.ca/ifla/II/diglib.htm">IFLA: Digital Libraries Resources, Research and Projects</A><BR>
Contains an extensive bibliography of links to articles; a listing of online periodicals related to digital libraries; links to conference proceedings; links to organizations; links to projects; links to library produced www resource guides; and links to databases and indexes.<P>

       <LI>Schatz, B. and Chen, H. (1996) <A HREF="http://www.computer.org/pubs/computer/dli/">Computer - Building Large-Scale Digital Libraries.</A> <i>Digital Library Initiative.</i><BR>
Discusses six digital library programs: University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, 
University of California at Berkeley, Carnegie Mellon University, University of California at Santa Barbara, Stanford University, and the University of Michigan. <P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www2.echo.lu/libraries/en/libnew.html">Telematics for Libraries</A><BR>
This program is sponsored by I*M Europe which acts as a medium for supporting the actions of DGXIII of the European Commission in stimulating the European electronic information services market and multimedia content industries. This site contains links to synopses of the many <A HREF="http://www2.echo.lu/libraries/en/projects.html">projects</A> under its auspices. These include <A HREF="http://www2.echo.lu/libraries/en/projects/cantate.html">Cantate</A>, <A HREF="http://www2.echo.lu/libraries/en/projects/harmonic.html">Harmonica</A>,  <A HREF="http://www2.echo.lu/libraries/en/projects/juke-box.html">Jukebox</A>, and <A HREF="http://www2.echo.lu/impact/projects/isbi/en/prop4050.html">MODE</A>, all of which relate to music.<BR>
In addition, there are other lists of links including those to <A HREF="http://www2.echo.lu/libraries/en/journals.html">journals relating to telematics</A> and to descriptions of <A HREF="http://www2.echo.lu/libraries/en/natpol.html">national programs and initiatives</A> for telematics.<P>

<i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
</DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>

 <DT><H3><A Name="DigiLibMus">Digital Libraries - Music</A></H3>
Below is a listing of current initiatives in the area of digital libraries in music.  With the exception of Indiana University's Variations Project, most are small pilot projects. 
<P>The issues encountered in the conversion of music resources and scholarship to electronic media are complex and wide-ranging. Up to this time, the primary focus has been on finding workable solutions to technical challenges.
<P>Future challenges lie in the areas of copyright and fair use (now under national and international debate), the problem of getting sufficient bandwidth to send CD quality sound across the Internet, accomplishing searches over multiple and diverse catalogues or databases, and the scaling up of databases that provide real-time access.
<DL><p>

<H3>United States</H3>
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.music.indiana.edu/variations/">VARIATIONS Project</A><BR>
The <i>Variations</i> project at Indiana University is the major digitization effort of a sound library in the United States and probably the world.  Indiana is in the process of converting their sound collection, in the form of LPs and CDs, to digital audio.  They are making this collection retrievable for listening through a web browser by linking the sound files to their online catalog (IUCAT) records. For details, see <A HREF="http://www.music.indiana.edu/variations/description_june96.html">David Fenske's D-Lib article</A><P> 

         <LI><A HREF="http://www.software.ibm.com/is/dig-lib/dlemi5.htm">IBM Digital Library: The EMI Digital Library Solution - Telstar</A><BR>
Telstar's aim is to create a secure, digitized sound library of its products for internal use.<P>
 
<H3>Canada</H3>
       
         <LI><A HREF="http://lecaine.music.mcgill.ca/MLF_Project/Html/MLF_Proposal.html">McGill University Music Library of the Future: A Pilot Project</A><BR>
McGill is digitizing materials related to Canadian composers: scores, audio exerpts, analysis, biographies, portraits, and general information. They are also doing research in the area of auditory percpetion. These <A HREF="http://www.music.mcgill.ca/auditory/Auditory.html">pages</A> contain demos and online experiments in which visitors can participate.<P>
  
<H3>United Kingdom</H3>
   
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.surrey.ac.uk/Library/research/PATRON.html">Project PATRON: a new Electronic Library Research initiative in the George Edwards Library</A><BR>
<i>Project Patron</i>, whose site is the George Edwards Library of the University of Surrey, has as its goal the provision of on-demand digital audio, video, scores, and text in the area of music and dance. Their aim is to relieve the pressure caused by in-person demand.<P>

<H3>European Community</H3>
The EC has taken a broader view of the issue of storage and retrieval of music sources. They have several projects in various stages.  Their orientation includes the commercial sector as well as music libraries. Efforts in this area include research centers, publishers and market-oriented suppliers, networking interests, performance rights agencies, and standards bodies. The issue of fair use, of such great importance to the American academic community, do not appear in their discussions of copyright.<P>

      <LI><A HREF="http://www.brad.ac.uk/~srmounce/can.html">CANTATE Project Home Page</A><BR>
The European Communities Libraries Programme's Computer Access to NoTAtion and TExt in music libraries (CANTATE) has just completed phase 1.  The aim of this project was to build a prototype for a system which would allow users to access music: sound to listen to (through a MIDI device) and score to download from music shops or libraries. If a user downloaded a score, a fee would be charged to the user to cover copyright.  Their findings are as follows.  Music publishers are not taking advantage of the potential of electronic format.  Libraries are partially automated but must deal with issues of acquiring materials versus providing online access.  Music shops would not need to maintain a large inventory, but would still provide hard copy. Standard Music Description Language (SMDL) will be the language for music encoding, but it has not developed as quickly as project members had supposed.  The web will be the distribution tool of the future. <BR>
For more detail on this project, see <A HREF="http://www.brad.ac.uk/~srmounce/can2.html">CANTATE Project details</A> and <A HREF="http://www.brad.ac.uk/~srmounce/can4.html">CANTATE summary.</A><P>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.svb.nl/project/harmonica/harmonica.htm">HARMONICA - New concerted action on music information in libraries</A><BR>
<i>The project is underway as of December 1996: this is its new web page.</i><br>Subscribe to their new listserv <A HREF="http://www.svb.nl/project/harmonica/harm_list.htm">Harmonica-L</A>.<P>
The European Commission's Directorate-General XIII (DGXIII) has funded Harmonised Access and Retrieval for Music-Oriented Networked Information - Concerted Action  (HARMONICA) through I*M (Information Market) Europe, an organization whose charge is to carry out directives from the DGXIII in the area of electronic information and the multimedia content industries. This project, which has just gotten underway this year is not an R&D project, but rather is charged with creating a human network for exploring pertinent issues.  Some of these issues include technical, existing and emerging standards (compression, SMDL, etc.), interfaces, network options, delivery systems for sound and score, cataloging, and copyright.
<P>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.ircam.fr/produits-real/multimedia/serveur-e.html">IRCAM - MUSICSERVE</A><BR>
Their aim is to develop a structured corpus of 20th century music materials, including texts, scores, photos, music recordings, videos and scientific publications and make them available over the Internet.  They are working in concert with the <A HREF="http://www.svb.nl/project/harmonica/harmonica.htm">HARMONICA</A> project.<P>
         
<LI><A HREF="http://www.sb.aau.dk/Jukebox/edit-report-1.html">JUKEBOX-Music Across Borders</A><BR>
<i>Jukebox</i> was also sponsored by the European Communities Libraries Programme.  Jukebox was a project whose aim was to explore making archives of sound and speech no longer commercially obtainable from libraries in several European countries available for searching and listening in real time across the Internet.<BR>
They encountered several challenges. They decided to store sound in uncompressed form, but found they had to compress it in order to send it over a narrow bandwidth such as ISDN.  They had significant problems with searching multiple catalogs for reasons of language differences, the special needs of music searchers (the need to search on genre, for instance), and different online catalog structures (See <A HREF="http://mediator.uni-c.dk/paragon/">Project Paragon</A>).  There were significant copyright problems most of which remain unresolved, particularly in dealing with cross-border situations. The conclusion was that in the future they would focus on the educational sector, as it would simplify copyright issues<P>

                  <LI><A HREF="http://www2.echo.lu/impact/projects/isbi/en/prop4050.html">Proposal 4050 - MODE</A><BR>
I*M Europe is also sponsoring the Music on Demand (MODE) project whose aim is to develop and implement a commercial delivery service for sound and eventually score.  Sound will be delivered by companies associated with the International Federation of Phonographic Industry (IFPI).
<P>         
        
        <i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
        </DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>
 <DT><H3><A Name="MIDI">MIDI</A></H3>
These  are sites which contain information about hardware, software, programming, and downloadable sequences.  
<DL><p>
        
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.eeb.ele.tue.nl/midi/index.html">MIDI Home Page</A><BR>
This is <i>the</i> site to begin with.  There are links to information on current technical concerns, links to an <A HREF="http://www.eeb.ele.tue.nl/midi/intro.html">Introduction</A> to MIDI, an <A HREF="http://www.eeb.ele.tue.nl/midi/midistat.html">Overview</A>, and a list of pertinent newsgroups.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.midiweb.com/">MidiWeb</A><BR>
For the MIDI community; includes lots of links.<P>

         <LI><A HREF="http://wwwedu.cs.utwente.nl/~hofste/midi/">Arjan Hofsté's introduction to MIDI</A><BR>
A good four-chapter introduction.<P>

         <LI><A HREF="http://www.midiweb.com/hww/hwidx.htm">Hardware and Software</A><BR>
From the MidiWeb page; under construction as of 5/96<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.midiweb.com/program.html">Programming MIDI</A><BR>Also from the MidiWeb page.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.cs.ruu.nl/pub/MIDI/">The MIDI Archive</A>: The large site at the University of Utrecht. <BR>
This site contains a lot of downloadable materials organized in the following categories: documentation, patches, programs, song files, information about MIDI, MIDI bibliography, and links to other web sites, and other archives. Most of these links take you to their original ftp site.  The song files have been removed temporarily, due to copyright problems connected with some of them.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.harmony-central.com/HyperNews/get/MIDI.html">The MIDI Forum</A><BR>
A HyperNews site. Ask your tough questions there.<P>
        
         <LI><A HREF="http://www.prs.net/midi.html">Classical MIDI Archives</A><BR>
This site contains almost 3000 MIDI files. Files considered to be good are marked with a paragraph sign.  Those that are recent are maked with a +. There are two ways to access files: through an alphabetical index and via a term search.  Some composers have their own pages.<P>
        
         <LI><A HREF="http://www.dtx.net/~raborn/">The Classical MIDI Connection</A><BR>
This site suffered a major disaster in November, 1996. The best way to get to sources appears to be to click on the historical period and then use the index.<P>

         <LI><A HREF="ftp://ftp.ircam.fr/pub/music/doc/MIDI/midi-files">The MIDI archive at IRCAM</A> in France.<BR>
This busy ftp site is difficult to access.<P>
        
         <LI><A HREF="http://www.channel1.com/users/gsilvis/">The Silvis "Woodshed"</A><BR>
A long list of downloadable classical music MIDI files, organized alphabetically by composer.<P>

         <LI><A HREF="http://www.isd77.k12.mn.us/resources/staffpages/shirk/midi.html">MIDI Resources for Teachers</A><BR>
A list of links to resources particularly useful for k-12.<P>
        
         <LI><A HREF="http://www.ceryle.com/bach/chorales.shtml#chorales">Bach Chorales</A><BR>
Are zipped for PC and stuffed for Mac.<P>
        
<B>MIDI newsgroups:</B><P>
          <LI><A HREF="news:comp.music.midi">news:comp.music.midi</A><P>
          <LI><A HREF="news:comp.music.research">news:comp.music.research</A><P>
          <LI><A HREF="news:alt.emusic">news:alt.emusic</A><P>
          <LI><A HREF="news:alt.music.midi">news:alt.music.midi</A><P>

<i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
         </DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>

<DT><H3><A Name="AuthTools">Authoring Tools</A></H3>
This category contains sites which supply links to authoring sites, FAQs on multimedia authoring systems, and specific authoring system sites.
    <DL><p>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.asymetrix.com/source/papers.htm">Asymetrix Insite Sources</A><BR>Makers of Toolbook.<br>
This is a site dedicated to papers on research in the use of technology in higher education. To date, the number of papers is modest.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.asymetrix.com/">Asymetrix Insite</A><BR>
The latest and greatest at Asymetrix.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.unc.edu/~slim/tbk.html">The Toolbook Pages</A><BR>
William McKee's collection of Toolbook applications, coding examples and resources.<P>

       <LI><A HREF="http://www.cap-media.com/">CAP-Media Demonstration Applications</A><BR>
Cap-Media is a tool which enables a user to capture timing points and synchronize captions and other events to those timing points. It also enables a user to build structural charts of a piece of music.<BR>
Scroll down to view/download Doug Short's Vivaldi <i>Seasons</i> application.  You must have the Sony Classics recording in order to run this application.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.mcli.dist.maricopa.edu/authoring/">Maricopa Community College Authoring Page</A><BR>
Lists of links relating to authoring languages (now, seemingly accessible only via a search engine), authoring listservs, multimedia centers, and commercial producers.<P>

         <LI><A HREF="http://www.tiac.net/users/jasiglar/MMASFAQ.HTML">Multimedia Authoring Systems FAQ</A><BR>
Contains links to multiple and single platform authoring tools; books; and an extensive list of pertinent usenet newsgroups.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.lancs.ac.uk/users/music/research/CTImusicNews3/modules.html" >TLTP Modules for Music</A><BR>
TLTP (Teaching and Learning Technology Programme) is the technology initiative in UK higher education. This site contains descriptions of their software applications for music. In particular, it contains a description of the authoring tool CD Tour Generator, a hypercard tool for capturing timing points and synchronizing captions to these points.<P>

        <i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
    </DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>

        <DT><H3><A Name="MusCodeSoftware">Music Code and Software</A></H3>
This category includes software repositories, reviews, and links to research centers developing software.
    <DL><p>
 
       <LI><A HREF="http://ccrma-www.stanford.edu/">CCRMA World Wide Web server</A> - The Stanford University Center for Computer Research in Music and Acoustics.<BR>
CCRMA explores the potential of technology to support composition and research. One can download selected <A HREF="http://ccrma-www.stanford.edu/CCRMA/Software/Software.html">software.</A>  In particular, see <A HREF="http://ccrma-www.stanford.edu/CCARH/Welcome.html">The Center for Computer-Assisted Research in the Humanities (CCARH)</A>, whose mission is to develop data resources and software for applications in musical history, theory,
analysis, performance, perception and cognition.<P>
               
         <LI><A HREF="http://www.lib.virginia.edu/dmmc/Music/Humdrum/humdrumFAQ.html">Humdrum FAQ</A><BR>
Humdrum (from CCARH) is a suite of tools for music research. There is also a 551-page softbound manual which describes 60 software tools
available for music research applications. These applications work with data in the Kern code.<BR>
See also <A HREF="http://www.lib.virginia.edu/dmmc/Music/Humdrum/hum_news1.html">Humdrum News, no. 1</A> - 1994 and <A HREF="http://www.lib.virginia.edu/dmmc/Music/Humdrum/hum_news2.html">Humdrum News, no. 2</A> - 1995.<P>

          <LI><A HREF="http://www.sunflower.org/~bhugh/musici.cgi">Music Instruction Software Page</A><BR>
	A list of links to freely available software and courseware on the net, categorized by platform.<P>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.hits.net/~pianist/piano.html">Piano Parlor</A><BR>
Click on computer software and this takes you to a list of links for software and reviews.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://imr.utsa.edu/TIME.html">Technology in Music Education</A> - software reviews.<BR>
Click just on Search Time to get to the search engine.<P>

<i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
    </DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>

    <DT><H3><A Name="Standards">Standards</A></H3>
The two standards for the digitization of music are HyTime, the Hypermedia/Time-based Structuring Language (ISO/IEC 10744:1992) and SMDL, the Standard Music Description Language (ISO/IEC CD 10743).    
<DL><p>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.techno.com/history.html">HyTime and SMDL</A><BR>
An article on the history of the linked development of the two standards.<P>

       <LI><A HREF="file://ftp.ifi.uio.no/pub/SIGhyper/1991-001">The ISO Standard for HyTime</A> - Hypermedia Time-based Structuring Language.<P>

<LI><A HREF="http://lecaine.music.mcgill.ca/~jude/conftalk/smdl.html">McGill discussion of SMDL</A> - contains an example of code<P>

       <LI><A HREF="http://www.techno.com/SMDL.html">SMDL</A> - Standard Music Description Language<P>
        
      <i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
    </DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>

    <DT><H3><A Name="Cataloguing/Database">Cataloguing/Database</A></H3>

    <DL><p>

         <LI><A HREF="http://mediator.uni-c.dk/paragon/">Paragon.</A><BR>
<i>Project Paragon</i>  is dealing with the catalog and searching problem identified by <A HREF="http://www.sb.aau.dk/Jukebox/edit-report-1.html">Jukebox</A>.  It has set up a common interface through the World Wide Web to three major sound archives.  This interface is based on the international SR (Search and Retrieve) standard already established for searching library online catalogues.  It will study the appropriateness of this standard as well as its American cousin Z39.50 for searching sound and media archives.  <i>Project Paragon</i> will use the sound archives involved in the <i>Jukebox</i> project.
<P>

<i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
     </DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>

 <DT><H3><A Name="NetTeach/MusEd">Teaching/Music Education Sources</A></H3>
This category contains links to projects concerned with technology and higher education, resources for use in higher education, and to examples of teaching on the web.
    <DL><p>

       <LI><A HREF="http://www.learner.org/content/acpbinfo.html">Annenberg/CPB Project </A><BR>
The mission of this project is to make quality college education more accessible to the American public through the use of technology.<P>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.uwex.edu/disted/home.html">Distance Education Clearinghouse</A><P>

<LI><A HREF="http://cte.uncwil.edu/et/cybrary.htm">Effective Teaching: Cybrary</A><BR>
Related to higher education.<BR>
Contains links to teaching and learning centers, their newsletters, cyberspace law; WWW search engines/archives/help finding and publishing online; online dictionaries, thesauri, and cyberpedias; books/hypertexts; higher education on line; by academic major; and museums.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/horizon/">Horizon Home Page</A><BR>
Horizon is co-sponsored by Jossey-Bass Publishers, the School of Education at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill and Sunsite.  Its mission to inform educators of changes in their disciplines which are, in particular, due to information technology.<P> 

<LI><A HREF="http://www.isd77.k12.mn.us/resources/staffpages/shirk/music.html">Internet Resources For Music Teachers</A><BR>
Contains links to music newsgroups, K-12 resources, commercial music sites, and midi resources.<P>

	<LI><A HREF="http://sun1.rrzn.uni-hannover.de:80/musicweb/musicweb/mwinfo/texts/welcome2.htm">Music Web</A><br>
The mission of music web is to create a database of objects (sound, text, image) and authorware for creating computer-aided music teaching materials.  It originated at the Hochschule fur Musik und Theater, Hanover, Germany. For an example of their work, see <A HREF="http://sun1.rrzn.uni-hannover.de:80/musicweb/musicweb/demos/hempel/guide1en.htm">Weblication No 1: The Theme of Brahms' Haydn Variations, Op. 56 a and Op. 56 b, by Prof. Christoph Hempel</A>.<P>
    
<LI><A HREF="http://orathost.cfa.ilstu.edu/classes/ORAT389.88Seminar/InternetModels/exhibits96.html">Student Exhibits 1996</A><BR>
From the  Illinois State University's College of Fine Arts.<BR>
Internet Models for Artistic Expression seminar (Art, Music, and Theatre).<BR>
Some of the links no longer work.<P>
                 
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.umassd.edu/cybered/distlearninghome.html">Welcome to CyberEd - umassdart</A><BR>
Online courses from the Division of Continuing Education at the University of Massachusetts Dartmouth and the University of Massachusett Lowell.  A good selection, but no music courses yet.<P>

                <LI><A HREF="http://www.utexas.edu/world/lecture/mus/">WLH - Music</A><BR>
Contains links to music courses whose materials are being delivered at least partly on the web.<P>

<i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
    </DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>
<DT><H3><A Name="Evaluation">Evaluation</A></H3>
This category includes links to articles on assessment and evaluation related to the use of technology mostly in higher education.  None of these articles has to do with music specifically.  

    <DL><p>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.learner.org/content/ed/strat/eval/ACPBRightQuestion.html">Annenberg: Educational Strategies Report</A><BR>
ASKING THE RIGHT QUESTION: What Does Research 
Tell Us About Technology and Higher Learning?  by Stephen C. Ehrmann
of the Annenberg/CPB Projects<P>

        <LI>From the <A HREF="http://www.learner.org/content/ed/strat/eval/vvs.html">Annenberg Project: Studies of Valuable, Viable Software</A><BR>
On Value, Viability and Success by Stephen C. Ehrmann, Ph.D.<BR>
Contains a list and review of software for teaching.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.learner.org/content/ed/strat/eval/evalflash.html">THE FLASHLIGHT PROJECT</A><BR>
This project is developing research tools for monitoring the relative success of the use of technology in education.<BR>
Included here are links to several articles on evaluation, an example of which is the link below.<P>
      
<LI><A HREF="http://www.bmgt.umd.edu/Business/AcademicDepts/IS/Learning/evalmeas.html">IS World Net: Technology-Supported Learning</A><BR>
This is the measurement and evaluation page of this group.  So far, there is one linked article.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.hoosiers.iupui.edu/paiimain/publicat.htm">IUPUI Planning And Institutional Improvement:</A><BR>
Modest list of hardcopy publications on assessment.<P>
    
<LI><A HREF="http://mime1.marc.gatech.edu/mm_tools/">Multimedia Development Tools</A><br>
This NSF funded project has developed tools to aid the analysis, design, management, 
production coordination, and evaluation phases of any interactive media project.<br>
See in particular the <A HREF="http://mime1.marc.gatech.edu/mm_tools/evaluation.html"> Evaluation Tools</A>.<P>
  
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.etc.bc.ca/lists/nuggets/EdTech_report.html">The Status of Technology in the Education System: A Literature Review</A><BR>From the Community Learning Network of the British Columbia Ministry of Education, Skills, and Training.<BR>
A lengthy article with an emphasis on distance education. Contains a lengthy, mostly hardcopy bibliography.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.icbl.hw.ac.uk/tltp/newsletter7/class.html">TLTP workshop on how to evaluate</A><BR>
Part of the UK Teaching and Learning Technology Programme.<BR>
Contains a summary of the workshop.<P>

<i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
    </DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>
 <DT><H3><A Name="Copyright">Copyright</A></H3>
Copyright in the digital world is a major issue.  This section is divided into information about copyright issues and agencies dealing with copyright issues in music.<P>

<B>Sites with Information about Copyright Issues</B>
    <DL><p>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.libraries.psu.edu/avs/fairuse/default.html">Fair Use Guidelines for Educational Multimedia and Related Documents and Links</A><br>
Includes links to the Multimedia Fair Use Document, a Background and Summary of the Guidelines, CONFU Interim Report to the Commissioner, and Information about the Consortium of College and University Media Centers (CCUMC) and PBS Fair Use Live Telecast set for February 20.<P>
<DL><B>Exerpts from the Proposed Guidelines:</B>
	<LI>Students and Educators may use <i>portions</i> of copyrighted materials for the creation of multimedia projects or teaching materials.  These materials may be used in distance learning as long as they are run over a secure network with limited access and that reproduction of copyrighted materials is prohibited. If the latter is not the case, the materials may be made available for 15 days only, then may be put on reserve in the library, but reproduction of copyrighted materials must be prohibited.  Educators may use these copyrighted materials up to 2 years after first class use.  After that time, they must secure copyright permissions.  
	<DL><i>Portions</i> of materials is defined as follows:
		<LI>Up to 10% or 3 minutes, whichever is less, in the aggregate of a copyrighted motion media work;
		<LI>Up to 10% or 1000 words, whichever is less, in the aggregate of a copyrighted work consisting of text material;  An entire poem of less than 250 words may be used, but no more than three poems by one poet, or five poems by different poets from any anthology may be used. For poems of
greater length, 250 words may be used but no more than three excerpts by a poet, or five excerpts by different poets from a single anthology may be used.		
		<LI>Up to 10%, but in no event more than 30 seconds, of the music and lyrics from an individual musical work;
		<LI>A photograph or illustration may be used in its entirety but no more than 5 images by an artist or photographer; when using photographs and illustrations from a published collective work, not more than 10% or 15 images, whichever is less;
		<LI>Up to 10% or 2500 fields or cell entries, whichever is less, from a copyrighted database or data table;</DL>
	<LI> There may be no more than two use copies of a multimedia project, only one of which may be placed on reserve.
	<LI>Educators and students are reminded to credit the sources and display the copyright notice © and copyright ownership information if this is shown in the original source, for all works incorporated as part of the educational multimedia projects prepared by educators and students, including those prepared under fair use. 
	<LI>Educators and students are advised that they must include on the opening screen of their multimedia program and any accompanying print material a notice that certain materials are included under the fair use exemption of the U.S. Copyright Law and have been prepared according to the multimedia fair use
guidelines and are restricted from further use. </DL><P>
		
	<LI><A HREF="http://www.public-domain.org">Union for the Public Domain</A> contains links to WIPO news including the texts of the copyright and performances treaties.<P>  

<LI><A HREF="http://www.music.indiana.edu/tech_s/mla/legcom/copyhome.htm">A Guide to Copyright for Music Librarians</A><BR>
A document of the Legislation Committee of the Music Library Association.<P>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.higgs.org/midi/MIDI-copyrights.html">Music, MIDI and Online Copyrights</A><BR>
Contains links to copyright articles and interviews. Updated occasionally.<P>

  <LI><A HREF="http://fairuse.stanford.edu/">SUL: Copyright & Fair Use</A><BR>
The Stanford University copyright and fair use site. Contains many links, in addition to a search engine for the site.<P>
      
<B>Agencies dealing with copyright and licensing</B><P>
<B>United States</B><P>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.ascap.com/">ASCAP Home Page</A><BR>
American Society of Composers, Authors, and Publishers: a performing arts licensing agency.  You can search their <A HREF="http://www.ascap.com/ace/ACE.html">database</A> of works by titles, authors, performers, or publishers.  ASCAP also has an <A HREF="http://www.ascap.com/new/nmts/licensing/licensing.html">Online License Agreement.</A><P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.bmi.com/">Welcome to bmi.com!</A><BR>
Broadcast Music Incorporated represents composers by collecting royalties for the performances and digital copying of their works. They have a searchable <A HREF="http://bmi.com/repertoire/index.html">music repertory database</A> for works which they license. One can search on title, writer, or publisher.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://nmpa.org/hfa.html">The Harry Fox Agency, Inc.</A><BR>Established by the National Music Publishers
Association to act as a clearinghouse and to monitor licensing of music copyrights.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.mpa.org/">Music Publishers Association</A><P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://nmpa.org/">National Music Publishers Association</A><BR>The NMPA is one of the major
performing rights licensing organizations in the United States, representing more than 600
composers.<P>
<B>Europe</B><P>

         <LI><A HREF="<LI><A HREF="http://www.imprimatur.alcs.co.uk/html/page18.htm" >Imprimatur Project Web Site - Project Partners Contact</A><BR>
This project was launched by the European Commission DG III.  Its The aim is to devise and recommend processes to protect and trade all types of intellectual property.  The US participant is the Interactive Multimedia Association. <P>

<i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
    </DL><p>
<HR SIZE=6>

          <DT><H3><A Name="General">General</A></H3>

    <DL><p>

<LI><A HREF="http://altavista.digital.com/">AltaVista: Main Page</A><P>

 <LI><A HREF="http://info.ox.ac.uk/ctitext/publish/comtxt/ct13/ahds.html">Arts and Humanities Data Service</A><br>
Funded by the  Joint Information Systems Committee (JISC) of the Higher Education Funding, UK.  The purpose of the AHDS is to address issues which surround the collection, description, preservation, and distribution (through cataloguing) of electronic resources resulting from scholarly research in the humanities. Issues of standardization in order to ensure seamless access will also be addressed. 
<P>

                <LI><A HREF="http://www.ruf.rice.edu/~brownlib/music/music.html#major">Catalogs of Libraries</A> with significant music collections.<BR>
From Rice University.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://chronicle.merit.edu/">The Chronicle of Higher Education: ACADEME THIS WEEK</A><P>
        
        <LI><A HREF="http://www.ceth.rutgers.edu/info/ann/humannounce.html">HUMANIST Announcements</A><P>

              <LI><A HREF="http://www.ahip.getty.edu/intro_imaging/0-Cover.html>Introduction to Imaging</A>, by  Howard Besser and Jennifer Trant published by the Getty.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.jstor.org">JStor Project</A>, in which back issues of <i>Speculum</i> and many other journals are being put online. They are available only to institutions who have purchased a site license.  The project provides digital photographs of each page in each article as well as the ability to search by full-text, author, abstract, and/or title.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://home.netscape.com/home/internet-search.html">Net Search</A><P>
        
                <LI><A HREF="file:///Q|/VERA/INDEX.HTM">VERA: IAT Library's Web Page</A><P>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.music.org/sqk_blat/lists.html#software">Webster/Williams ATMI web links</A><BR>
Contains a music technology bibliography, favorite web sites, links to software and upgrades, <P>

<i><A HREF="#begin">Back to Contents</A></i>
    </DL><p>  
  <HR SIZE=6>
     
      <DT><H3><A Name="Miscellaneous">Miscellaneous Music and Related Sources</A></H3>

    <DL><p>

 <LI><A HREF="http://www.ens-lyon.fr/~esouche/danse/dance1.html">Ballets Russes</A><BR>
Links to images organized by dance season and an article on Diaghilev<P>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.public.iastate.edu/~flng_info/medieval-fr.html">French Middle Ages on the Web</A><BR>
An <i>extensive</i> list of links to text and image sites.<P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.jazzcentralstation.com/jcs/station/newsstan/history/index.html">History of Jazz</A><BR>
<i>Extensive</i> site - if you are a jazz fan, don't miss this one.<P>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.nycballet.com/RepNotesIndex.html">NYCB Rep Notes Index</A><BR>
New York City Ballet notes on their ballet repertoire, organized alphabetically by dance title.<P>

       <LI><A HREF="http://copper.ucs.indiana.edu/~lneff/libretti.html">Public-Domain Opera Libretti and Other Vocal Texts</A><P>

        <LI><A HREF="http://www.wsu.edu:8080/~wldciv/world_civ_reader/" >World Civilizations Reader</A><P>

            </DL>
