<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>P</FONT>artnership for <FONT SIZE=+3>D</FONT>istributed <FONT SIZE=+3>L</FONT>earning </FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>

<P><FONT SIZE=+1><STRONG>What's New?</STRONG></FONT>
<UL><LI><A HREF="part0796.html">Agenda for the Meeting of July 15-16, 1996</A></UL>

<P><FONT SIZE=+1><STRONG>Important Documents</STRONG></FONT>
<UL>
<LI>The <A HREF="partrfp.html">Request for Partners</A> document offers a detailed explanation of the goals and benefits of the Partnership program.
<LI><A HREF="sloan.html">Interim Report to the Alfred P. Sloan Foundation</A> on Requirements for Using the World Wide Web for Distributed Learning.
<LI><A HREF="part1095.html">Summary of the Meeting of October 16-17, 1995.</A>
<LI>Meeting of the <A HREF="nawlins.html">NLII in New Orleans</A> - January 21-23, 1996.
<LI><A HREF="nlii-pr.html">Progress Report</A> to the Educom National Learning Infrastructure Initiative, January 1996
<LI><A HREF="part0296.html">Summary of the Meeting of February 19-20, 1996</A></UL>

<CENTER><P>[ <A HREF="#overview">Overview</A> | <A HREF="#origin">Origin</A> | <A HREF="#members">Members</A> | <A HREF="#projects">Projects</A> | <A HREF="#moreinfo">More Info</A> ]</CENTER>

<P><FONT SIZE=+1><STRONG><A NAME="overview">Overview</A></STRONG></FONT> 

<P>The Partnership for Distributed Learning offers 20-30
institutions and organizations a close working relationship with
the IAT's research and solutions development efforts, as well as
with other institutions of higher education and commercial
organizations interested in leveraged development of Web-based
distributed education.  The focus of the Partnership is the use
of Web-based tools for delivering content, enabling new modes of
communication among instructors and students, and managing the
instructional process in a credit-bearing, distributed context.

<P>Participating institutions subscribe to a "seat at the table,"
at which the consortium shapes and reports its efforts to
understand and prototype distributed instruction.  Partner
institutions have the opportunity to propose projects and to
invest  and participate in projects proposed by other Partners,
including the IAT.

<P><FONT SIZE=+1><STRONG><A NAME="origin">Origin</A></STRONG></FONT>

<P>The partnership was announced under the aegis of EDUCOM's
<A HREF="http://educom.edu/program/nlii/.index.html">National Learning Infrastructure Initiative</A> in January 1995. 
Organizational meetings were held in March and July at which the
original concept was refined and from which was issued a revised
Request for Partners. During the organizing period, research and
information gathering on asynchronous learning and the
requirements for Web-based delivery of distributed education, as
well as the July meeting, were partially funded by a grant from
the <A HREF="http://www.sloan.org/">Alfred P. Sloan Foundation</A>.  The <A HREF="part1095.html">first business meeting</A> of
the Partnership was held at the IAT on October 16 and 17, 1995.

<P><FONT SIZE=+1><STRONG><A NAME="members">Members</A></STRONG></FONT>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.acadiau.ca/">Acadia University</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.multimedia.calpoly.edu/">California Polytechnic State University/CSU</A>
<LI>Florida Community College at Jacksonville
<LI>IBM Higher Education
<LI>Indiana University
<LI><A HREF="http://www.dl.kent.edu/">Kent State University</A>
<LI>Lotus Development Corporation
<LI>Montgomery County (PA) Community College
<LI>Prentice-Hall/Simon & Schuster
<LI>Sam Houston State University
<LI>San Mateo Community College District
<LI>Sinclair (OH) Community College
<LI>University of Alberta
<LI><A HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/">University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill / IAT</A>
<LI>University of Pittsburgh
<LI><A HREF="http://www.usu.edu/">Utah State University</A>
<LI>Virginia Commonwealth University
</UL>

<P><FONT SIZE=+1><STRONG><A NAME="projects">Current Projects</A></STRONG></FONT>

<P>
At the October 1995 meeting, the Partners agreed to undertake
three projects:

<OL>
<LI>Web Course in a Box (lead institution: Virginia Commonwealth
University)

<LI>Elementary Math Education Tools & Modules (lead institution:
Indiana University)

<LI>JAVA-Based Math Applets (lead institution: UNC/IAT)
</OL>

<P>The Partners also committed to two future projects: one to
develop distributed course management systems, the other
JAVA-based math development tools and archive.

<P><FONT SIZE=+1><STRONG><A NAME="moreinfo">More Information</A></STRONG></FONT>
<P>
If you have specific questions about this program, contact Lowell Roberts at <A HREF="mailto:lowell_roberts@unc.edu">lowell_roberts@unc.edu</A> or 919-405-1928.

