<HEAD>
<TITLE>Distributed Learning Environment Update</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>


<CENTER>
<B>Distributed Learning Environment
Technology Update<BR>
by<BR>
Steve Griffin<BR>
Institute for Academic  Technology<BR>
steve_griffin@unc.edu</B>
</CENTER>

<HR>

<P>
Originally presented at the League for Innovation Conference in
Kansas City, MO., November 6, 1995.
<HR>

<P>
<H4>Overview</H4>

Distributed Learning Environment - students and instructor(s) interacting via a digital network from different places and at a convenient time for each participant.<P>

<H4>Why Should Educationaal Institutions Care about DLEs?</H4>

I suggest that DLEs should be taken very seriously by educational institutions for three reasons:

<UL>
<LI>DLEs are consistent with the information access paradigm shift where information goes to people rather than people going to information repositories (libraries).
<LI>DLE technology barriers are falling away.
<LI>Financial pressure make DLEs inevitable.
</UL>

<H4>Reference</H4>
An excellent presentation of the impact of DLEs in education can be found in &quot;Electronics and the Dim Future of the University&quot;, Eli M. Noam, Science 10/13/95.<P>
He cites the following teaching areas that will be the most negatively impacted.<BR>
<UL>
<LI>Mass undergraduate and professional education
<LI>Highly specialized and advanced fields
</UL>
<P>
And, least impacted: <BR>

<UL>
<LI>Contact-intensive areas, such as selective and tutorial-based liberal arts education
<LI>Skill training that requires hands-on instruction and feedback
<LI>Small, stable fields of graduate study not lucrative for commercial providers
</UL>


<H4>Web links to Educational Course Material</H4>

The following URL contains a collection of links to examples of Web-based instruction.

<CENTER><A HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/library/liblinks/courses.html">http://www.iat.unc.edu/library/liblinks/courses.html</A>
</CENTER>
<P><P>
<H4>Enabling Technologies</H4>

The key technologies that form the basis for DLEs are: the Internet, Compelling Content, Collaborative Software, and Management Software.<P>

<EM><STRONG>Internet</STRONG></EM><P>
<UL>
<LI>Protocols - TCP/IP and HTTP
<LI>Increased bandwidth - ISDN - 1996+; ATM - 1997+<P>
</UL>

As Microsoft Network AOL, Compuserve, AT&amp;T, your local cable company expand their coverage and Internet services, the home as a site for interactive learning becomes possible.
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Compelling Content</STRONG></EM><P>

Compelling content includes one or more of the following characteristics:
<P>
High knowledge transfer value, such as video and audio; Simulation and Virtual Reality; and Interactivity.
<P>
<EM>Digital Video Challenges</EM><P>
<A HREF="tek7fig1.jpg"><IMG SRC="tek7fig1.gif"></A>
<P>

<EM>Digital Video Solutions</EM><P>

Some solutions to distributing video on the Internet are:

<UL>
<LI>Xing <A HREF="http://www.xingtech.com/streams/index.html">Streamworks</A>
<LI>IP Multicast (<A HREF="http://www.mbone.com/techinfo/">MBONE</A>)
<LI>TCP/IP reservation protocols
</UL>

<P>
Utilizing existing CDs or laserdiscs of digital video can be played via web page links.  Check the IAT software section on our Web site in January for more information on this technology.
<P>
Also for more information on Digital Video Networking, see a <A HREF="teknote7.html">presentation</A> given in November at Educom 96 in Portland, Oregon.
<P>
<EM>Audio Solutions</EM>
<P>
The following products allow you to listen to audio as it comes across the network.<P>
       <ul> 
            <li><A HREF="http://www.prognet.com/">Progressive Networks (RealAudio)</A>
            <li><A HREF="http://www.dspg.com/">DSP Group, Inc. (True Speech)</A>
            <li><A HREF="http://www.vocaltec.com/">VocalTec (IWave)</A>
            <li><A HREF="http://www.xingtech.com/">Xing Technology (StreamWorks) Streamworks provides much higher fidelity but requires more bandwidth.</A>
        </ul>

<STRONG><EM>Simulation and Virtual Reality</EM></STRONG><P>

<A HREF="http://vrml.wired.com/">VRML</A> (Virtual Reality Modeling Language) is a standard for describing a 3-dimensional space.  Most CAD and 3D design tools are now adding the capability to produce files contains VRML versions of the 3D spaces.  Most of the Web browsers will begin or are incorporating support for VRML data within web pages.<P>

<STRONG><EM>Interactive network-aware applications</EM></STRONG><P>

The Web is very good at displaying pictures, text, and supporting navigation via hyperlinks.  However, to support the levels of interactivity that will be required in future online content, new technologies are required that provide local interactivity on the computer without involving the Web server for each interaction.  Two important technologies that will support this type of interactivity are Blackbird from Microsoft and <A HREF="http://java.sun.com/">JAVA</A> from Sun Microsystems.

Both Blackbird and Java require new development or substantial changes to existing applications.  To support more traditional applications two additional technologies are available.  First, Netscape has announced "Plug-Ins" which allow one to "play" certain applications within the context of the Webpage.  Secondly, the IAT has developed, <A HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/iat/software/webapp/">WebApp</A>, an accessory for Web browsers that automates the process of downloading and running software distributed via the Web. 

<H4>Collaborative Software</H4>

For information on collaborative software see the Web Collaboration FAQ: <BR>

<A HREF="http://union.ncsa.uiuc.edu/HyperNews/get/www/collaboration.html"><CENTER>http://union.ncsa.uiuc.edu/HyperNews/get/www/collaboration.html</CENTER></A><P>

<EM>Real-time Collaboration Tools</EM><P>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.worlds.net/">World chat and Alpha World</A> - 3D navigation and chat.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.tribal.com/">POWWOW</A> - text and audio chat, Web page touring, and a convenientt email ID-based means of establishing dialogue.
<LI><A HREF="http://www2.ncsu.edu/eos/service/ece/project/succeed_info/dtvc_survey/products.html">Desktop video conferencing software</A> may include real-time text or audio collaboration as well as video and shared whiteboard capabilities.  Most desktop conferencing software assume a LAN connection.  Increasingly desktop conferencing software will support Internet protocols but may not be able to provide the same level of features given the challenges of distributing streaming media across the Internet.
</UL>
<P>
<P>

<EM>Asynchronous Collaboration Tools</EM><P>

Real-time collaborative tools are extremely interactive but the requirement that all contributors be "online" simultaneously can be difficult to acheive, especially for participants who are separated by large geographic distances and associated time zones.   In order to support instruction where learners are not "learning" at the same place or same time, Asynchrounous collaboration tools are required.

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.lotus.com/home/notes.htm">Lotus Notes</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://hiltop.ostech.com/read-me">WebNotes</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.softarc.com/">FirstClass</A>
</UL>

<P>
<H4>Management Software</H4>

Software is required to manage and facilitate the student's admission into and progress through an electronic course.  Some existing management systems are:

<UL>
<LI>LearnLinc
<LI><A HREF="http://www.mdcc.edu/synergy/psi.html">Project Synergy Integrator</A>
</UL>
<P>
Some schools are beginning to use the Web for instruction and in the process are creating their own management systems out of necessity.  Others are creating more elaborate systems with funding from various sources with the hopes of creating a product that can be used by other institutions for free or fee.  Currently no standards exist that allow for the use of content from one system with another management system.
<P><EM>Distributed Course Management Standard</EM> - Educom, Miami-Dade Community College and other organizations are developing the "Distributed Course Management Standard" that will enable the exchange and use of content, diagnostic, testing, and report modules from publishers, educational institutions, and individual instructors.  Information on this standard and how your organization can participate will be available at this site in January.<P><HR>

Send comments to: <A HREF="mailto:steve_griffin@unc.edu">steve_griffin@unc.edu</A>
</BODY>

</HTML>
<BR>
