<HR>
<CENTER><H2>"Mapping the Future: <BR>New Routes to Learning Productivity"</H2>

<P><B>Original Broadcast Date:</B> Thursday, May 9, 1996
<BR>[ <A HREF="#overview">Overview</A> | <A HREF="#speakers">Key Speakers</A> | <A HREF="#materials">Supplemental Materials</A> | <A HREF="#video">Video Ordering Info</A> ]
</CENTER>
<P><HR><P>

<H3><A NAME="overview">Overview</A></H3>

<P>Shrinking budgets. Increasing enrollments. These dual phenomena challenge universities and colleges across the country to find innovative and cost-effective ways to teach the "baby boomer" offspring and the growing number of adult students who need to develop new skills and competencies.

<P>In this video, you'll see ways that schools are confronting these challenges while extending access and maintaining quality. You will visit schools demonstrating three different models using technology to deliver instruction both on-campus and at a distance.
<UL><LI><B>Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University</B> is developing a Cyberschool concept - "constructing a new type of college out of the social interactions made possible by new technologies."
<P><LI><B>Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute</B> has created a new "studio" approach to college physics and calculus courses. To provide a more efficient and effective way of handling large enrollment lab courses, RPI redesigned the whole teaching and learning process.
<P><LI><B>The Education Network of Maine</B> has re-engineered organizational policy and process to implement a statewide distance education system. Using a variety of technologies, they deliver instruction to over 2,600 students at 101 sites across the state.</UL>
<P>Join in the exciting work on these projects in EDUCOM's National Learning Infrastructure Initiative (NLII) as we track the institutions and companies creating new national collaboration that will transform education and stimulate the development of new approaches for educating students.

<H3><A NAME="speakers">Key Speakers</A></H3>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="../../graves/graves.html">William H. Graves</A> - Founder of the IAT and Chief Information Officer for the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill
<LI>James Mingle - Executive Director of the State Higher Education Executive Officers (SHEEO)
<LI>Diana Oblinger - IBM Academic Programs Manager
<LI>Carol Twigg - Vice President of EDUCOM
<LI>With additional commentary from:
<BR>Molly Broad and Tom West - California State University
<BR>Susan Driscoll - HarperCollins Publishers
<BR>Douglas Van Houweling - University of Michigan
</UL>
<H3><A NAME="materials">Supplemental Materials</A></H3>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="../../../guides/irg-33.html">New Routes to Learning Productivity: Readings and Resources</A> - Contains links to institutions featured in the broadcast as well as key speakers bibliography. </UL>

