<HR>
<CENTER><H2>"From Reality to Virtuality: <BR>New Tools for Distributed Learning"</H2>

<P><B>Original Broadcast Date:</B> Thursday, March 21, 1996
<BR>[ <A HREF="#overview">Overview</A> | <A HREF="#speakers">Key Speakers</A> | <A HREF="#materials">Supplemental Materials</A> | <A HREF="#video">Video Ordering Info</A> ]
</CENTER>
<P><HR><P>

<H3><A NAME="overview">Overview</A></H3>

<P>Virtual reality isn't just for computer scientists anymore!

<P>In this video we will talk with pioneers of virtual reality, explore some of the worlds they have created, and hear their assessment of virtual reality as a means for creating dynamic and engaging learning environments.

<P>While virtual reality has been portrayed as one of the most promising and sophisticated ways of creating immersive, interactive learning environments, the sophistication and high cost of such technology have presented barriers for educators. Now, with the rapidly improving capabilities of 3D modeling software and the advent of Virtual Reality Modeling Language (<A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/Computers_and_Internet/Internet/World_Wide_Web/Virtual_Reality_Modeling_Language__VRML_/">VRML</A>) for designing Web-based virtual environments, virtual reality is becoming a feasible option for educators.

<P>Virtual reality is already being used by educators to create many types of learning environments: from interactive models of historically significant environments like Pompeii, to simulated events that would be too costly or too dangerous to experience in real life, to "hyper-collaborative" worlds that allow participants to "teleconference" into and interact with others from around the globe. 

<P>Join us as Tom Furness, one of the forerunners of immersive virtual reality, and others demonstrate how virtual reality can be used to create learning environments that draw the learner into an absorbing world . . . perhaps some day to explore the far side of the moon, to engage in a dramatic dialogue with Shakespeare, or even to work alongside Marie Curie in her laboratory.  

<H3><A NAME="speakers">Key Speakers</A></H3>
<UL>
<P><LI><A HREF="../../graves/graves.html">William H. Graves</A>, Director of the IAT and Associate Provost for Information Technology for the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, will moderate the broadcast.

<P><LI><A HREF="http://www.hitl.washington.edu/people/tfurness/">Thomas A. Furness III</A>, Director of the <A HREF="http://www.hitl.washington.edu/">Human Interface Technology Laboratory</A> and Professor of Industrial Engineering at the University of Washington.

<P><LI>Eben Gay, Virtual Reality Consultant for ERG Engineering, Inc. [replaces <A HREF="http://www.hyperreal.com/~mpesce">Mark Pesce</A>, co-creator of VRML and author of <I>VRML: Browsing and Building Cyberspace</I>].

<P><LI>Lynn Holden, Consultant, <A HREF="http://topaz.rec.ri.cmu.edu/">SIMLAB</A>, NASA Robotics Engineering Consortium, Carnegie Mellon University [replaces Carl Loeffler, Project Director in Telecommunications and Virtual Reality for Carnegie Mellon University].
</UL>

<H3><A NAME="materials">Supplemental Materials</A></H3>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="../../../guides/irg-32.html">From Reality to Virtuality: Readings and Resources in Virtual Reality</A> - Includes: Papers and Articles, Books,
WWW Resources (Guides, Overviews and Bibliographies), Journals with Virtual Reality Coverage, Projects/Institutes, Conferences, Tools/Files, Featured Speakers Bibliography. 
</UL>

