<HR>
<CENTER><H2>"Distributed Learning Environments: An Integrating Model for Distance Education"</H2>

<P><B>Original Broadcast Date:</B> March 23, 1995
<BR>[ <A HREF="#overview">Overview</A> | <A HREF="#speakers">Key Speakers</A> | <A HREF="#materials">Supplemental Materials</A> | <A HREF="#video">Video Ordering Info</A> ]
</CENTER>
<P><HR><P>

<H3><A NAME="overview">Overview</A></H3>

<P>Distance education provides a means to reach students who cannot participate in traditional on-campus courses. However, too often distance education courses themselves are only a "remote" version of the traditional lecture-based teaching model. They still create time and place constraints for the learners and can increase scheduling complexity among different institutions. Additionally, the learning experience may be compromised by trying to adapt all the requirements of the learning experience to one technology for delivery.

<P>The Distributed Learning Environments model for distance education provides a means to eliminate these constraints. It is a learner-based approach that integrates a number of different technologies to enable opportunities for activities and interaction in both asynchronous and real-time modes. This model is based on blending a choice of appropriate technologies with aspects of open learning systems and distance education. This approach gives teachers the flexibility to customize learning environments to meet the needs of the students, while providing both high quality and cost-effective learning. 

<P>In this video, we discuss both pedagogical and institutional perspectives on the need for such new environments, as well as the technologies that enable us to create them.

<H3><A NAME="speakers">Key Speakers</A></H3>
<UL>
<P><LI>Kathryn Conway - IAT Senior Analyst for Distributed Learning Environments, will moderate this broadcast. She is also Director for Research in Learning Technologies for the Office of Information Technology at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

<P><LI>Robert Dunham - Senior Vice President and Dean for the Commonwealth Education System, The Pennsylvania State University. He is responsible for academic and administrative affairs for 17 undergraduate campuses and one graduate center, and serves as a senior advisor to the president of the university.

<P><LI>Linda Harasim - Associate Professor, School of Communication, Simon Fraser University, Burnaby, BC, is principal investigator in a multi-million dollar project to develop a virtual university, sponsored by CANARIE (Canadian Network for the Advancement of Research in Industry and Education). 
</UL>

<H3><A NAME="materials">Supplemental Materials</A></H3>

