<HR>
<CENTER><H2>"Reengineering Distributed Learning Environments"</H2>
<P><B>Original Broadcast Date:</B> Thursday, September 29, 1994
<BR>[<A HREF="#overview">Overview</A> | <A HREF="#speakers">Key Speakers</A> | <A HREF="#materials">Supplemental Materials</A> | <A HREF="#video">Video Ordering Information</A>]</CENTER>
<P><HR><P>

<H3><A NAME="overview">Overview</A></H3>

<P>Technology can be an added expense to the way we already teach, or it can be a vital element in rethinking and reworking the process of teaching and learning. Technology is most effective when it is coupled with appropriate models for teaching and learning.

<P>In this video we examine ways to apply process engineering to the design of learning envrionments - integrating hardware, software, facility design and learning theory in new and more efficient ways. As a case study, we examine the development of the Comprehensive Unified Physics Learning Environment (CUPLE) and the design of new facilities to accommodate it at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute.

<H3><A NAME="speakers">Key Speakers</A></H3> 

<UL>
<LI>Kathryn Conway - IAT Senior Analyst for Distributed Learning Environments.
<LI>Diana G. Oblinger - Academic Programs Manager, IBM Higher Education.
<LI>Anne Parker - Deputy Director of the Office of Information Technology, University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.
<LI>Jack M. Wilson - Director of the CUPLE project and Professor of Physics at RPI.
</UL>

<H3><A NAME="materials">Supplemental Materials</A></H3>
<A HREF="../../../guides/irg-09.html">Reengineering Learning Environments: Bibliography</A>

<H3><A NAME="video">Video Ordering Information</A></H3>
