</TABLE>

<BR>

<BR>Bert Wolf, IAT Training Developer and Course Instructor, had this to say about Neuron&#153:
<UL>
<DL>
<STRONG>Wow! ToolBook plays on the 'net. </STRONG>

<P>The beta release of Neuron, Asymetrix' plug-in for Netscape 2.0 on Window 95 or NT puts ToolBook at the forefront of distributed development tools. The Asymetrix press release provides most of the details but doesn't capture the excitement I feel. Everything good about ToolBook, the book metaphor, the object hierarchy, OpenScript, etc. is now available outside the bounds of a specific hardware/software platform. 

<P>Suddenly, ToolBook authors are sitting on a very hot knowledge base. Take, for example, some of the simple stuff demonstrated in the sample apps we and our students have done. Try and figure out the hours in Java, Director, Shockwave, whatever and you'll be glad you know ToolBook. The functionality of the CBT version is supported too, so you can get a lot done if you're a new ToolBook user and want to develop lesson/quiz materials for distribution over the 'net.

<P>Asymetrix may have really hit the spot with this one. Their goal is to make authoring of interactive net-based materials a task for subject matter experts and graphic designers, not Java gurus.




<P>
</DL>
</UL>

<BR>
