<BR><BR><BR><BR>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>W</FONT>eb<FONT SIZE=+3>A</FONT>pp<BR> <EM>It Only Takes a Click</EM> </FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>

<P>WebApp is a World Wide Web browser helper application that dramatically simplifies
installation and execution of software distributed via the World
Wide Web.

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#intro">Overview</A> of WebApp.
<LI><A HREF="wa_rev.html">New versions</A> of WebApp added May
30, 1996.
<LI><A HREF="wa_dwn.html">Download</A> a 30-day, trial version
of the 16-bit (<STRONG>Windows 3.x</STRONG>) version of WebApp.
<LI><A HREF="win32ver.html">Download</A> a 30-day, trial version
of the 32-bit (<STRONG>Windows 95 and NT</STRONG>) version of
WebApp.
<LI><A HREF="macwebapp/index.html">Download</A> a 30-day, trial
version for the <STRONG>Macintosh</STRONG>.
<LI>How to obtain a <A HREF="#register">registered version</A>
of WebApp.
<LI><A HREF="wa_case.html">Case study</A> of a WebApp archivesite.
<LI><A HREF="wa_back.html">Background and details</A> on WebApp.
<LI><A HREF="author.html">How to prepare Windows applications</A>
for use with WebApp. 
</UL>

<H3><A NAME="intro">Overview</A></H3>

<P>
The University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill's Institute for Academic Technology has
developed WebApp, a software program that dramatically simplifies installation
and execution of software distributed by World WideWeb servers
on the Internet.
<P>
Retrieving an application referenced in a WWW page is normally only
the first step in a lengthy process that includes de-archiving files,
creating directories, running a setup program and modifying initialization
files. With WebApp installed on a machine, onlya single click
of a mouse on a WWW page is required to installand run the application.
<P>
WebApp works in conjunction with WWW browsers, and includes configuration options
to support Virus Scanning software so that the chancesof executing
a virus-infected program are reduced.
<P>
WebApp saves sophisticated Internet users time and enables more trouble-free
distribution of software to less technically sophisticated users.
&quot;The beauty of WebApp is that it makes sophisticated educational
resources available to people who do not have extensive computer
knowledge or access to technical support,&quot; saysW.O. Crain,
Jr., of Seattle Central Community College. Crain recentlyconverted
a collection of interactive mathematics workbooks on the Internet
called the <A HREF="http://isaac.engr.washington.edu/mathwright/">Mathwright Library</A>
into WebApp format.
<P>
Creating applications that can be installed by WebApp is simple and
requires <B>no programming changes</B> and <B>no royalties</B>.Online
help, tools and samples are provided to support the creationof
WebApp-ready applications. <A HREF="author.html">Additional information</A>is
available to help you create files in the WebApp format.
<P>
WebApp compliments secure Internet transaction and proprietary software
authorization technologies by handling the installation and execution
of the distributed application.
<P>
A Microsoft Windows(TM) 16-bit shareware version of WebApp is available
for <A HREF="wa_dwn.html">downloading.</A>
<P>
Then, you can experience the convenience and time savings that WebApp
gives you by visiting one of the <A HREF="wa_arch.html">software archives</A>
that use the WebApp archive format. More detailed <A HREF="wa_back.html">background information</A>
on the creation of WebApp is also available.
