<BR><BR>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><EM><FONT SIZE=+3>N</FONT>ouvelles <FONT SIZE=+3>D</FONT>imensions</EM> <FONT SIZE=+3>N</FONT>amed <FONT SIZE=+3><BR>G</FONT>rand <FONT SIZE=+3>P</FONT>rize <FONT SIZE=+3>W</FONT>inner</FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>
<BR>

<P><CODE>[To download a demo see instructions at the <A HREF="#download">bottom</A> of this page.]</CODE>

<P><B>DURHAM, NC</B>  --  <I>Nouvelles Dimensions</I>, a multimedia CD-ROM and laserdisc product for teaching French listening comprehension, has been named the Grand Prize Winner as well as Winner in the Computer Based Training/Education Category at the 1995 Video Breakthrough Awards. Interactive and technical design for the product were created at the Institute for Academic Technology, a department of the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

<P>Announcement of the awards was made on September 11 at the 1995 Asymetrix Worldwide Developers Conference in Bellevue, Washington. The winning program features an interactive learning environment that allows students to observe and understand spoken French in a variety of natural settings. The awards -- sponsored jointly by <A HREF="http://www.asymetrix.com/">Asymetrix Corporation</A>, Creative Labs, Inc., and <A HREF="http://www.mmworld.com/">Multimedia World</A> magazine -- recognize excellence and innovation in multimedia applications using video. As the Grand Prize Winner, the Institute will receive a computer for multimedia production donated by <A HREF="http://www.intel.com/">Intel Corporation</A>.

<P>"<I>Nouvelles Dimensions</I> represents a multimedia application that is both innovative and educational," said Steve Martino, Vice President of Marketing at Asymetrix. "We are very pleased to recognize the excellent work of the IAT."

<P><I>Nouvelles Dimensions</I> incorporates video, sound and text into an interactive multimedia program that can be used in the classroom to support the instructor's presentation and in language learning centers by students working alone or in pairs. Students view on the computer screen scenes from French daily life, such as greetings, ordering food, statements of personal preferences and introduction of family members. Since what is seen and heard can be controlled through the computer keyboard and mouse, viewers interact with the program, proceeding at their own pace as they practice, take tests and complete writing exercises. 

<P>According to <I>Nouvelles Dimensions</I> creator <A HREF="../../publications/noblitt/noblitt.html">James Noblitt</A>, Research Professor of Romance Languages at UNC-CH and Academic Chair at the IAT, the program was developed over a period of three years and incorporated improvements based on feedback from students and instructors. Students enjoy the authentic feel of the material and the interactive control, while instructors like having an enriched learning environment for the learning of essential skills outside of the classroom. "The computer permits analysis of gestures and facial expressions, on a frame-by-frame basis if necessary, that adds a great deal to the understanding of communicative intent," Noblitt said. "By adding visual context and reference material to language study, the program can help the learner to master techniques for aural comprehension, such as listening for key words."

<P>Programming and technical design were accomplished at the IAT, with special credit due Bert Wolf (chief ToolBook program designer) and Amin Ansari (video capture specialist). Video materials were created by Bernard Petit, professor of French at the State University of New York College at Brockport, who used a hand-held video camera to get authentic samples of French as it is spoken by the people in everyday life. Heinle & Heinle Publishers of Boston, Massachusetts, specialists in foreign language educational materials, contributed the video and funded its creation. The CD-ROM version of the product was produced by the Electronic Production Division of One Room Systems, Inc., also located in Durham, and is published and distributed by <A HREF="http://www.thomson.com/heinle/default.html">Heinle & Heinle</A>.
<P>
<HR>

