<BR><BR>
<P><FONT SIZE=+1>A Word About the <EM>Bleeding-Edge</EM>...</FONT>
<P>When folks refer to bleeding-edge technology, they're talking about the innovations riding right at the liminal cusp of technology, new tools evolving as fast as you can read the Usenet News, the glut of listserv email, and<A HREF="http://w
ww.hotwired.com/"><EM> Wired</EM></A>'s latest report and commentary.  Bleeding edge technologies are the stuff that even the <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/">Yahoo</A> guys haven't quite indexed  yet.  Trying to get your hands around VRML, to take the temperature of the technology, seems more akin to an operating room scene from <EM>M*A*S*H</EM> than a scholarly presentation and interpretation of the current attempts to bring virtual reality onto the Internet.

<P>This WEB page attempts to keep a finger to the pulse of this new technology, to keep an eye on the triage efforts and any new discoveries that might be forming as the wide-ranging resources of the Internet community latch on to <STRONG>or </STRONG>pass over another ground-breaking technology: VRML.
<BR>


