<HR>
<CENTER><H2>"Multimedia: How Does It Really Work In the Classroom?"</H2>
<P><B>Original Broadcast Date:</B> Tuesday, February 23, 1993
<BR>[<A HREF="#overview">Overview</A> | <A HREF="#speakers">Key Speakers</A> | <A HREF="#materials">Supplemental Materials</A> | <A HREF="#video">Video Ordering Information</A>]</CENTER>
<P><HR><P>

<H3><A NAME="overview">Overview</A></H3>

<P>Multimedia is an exciting technique of using the computer to combine video, text, sound, still images and graphics to make teaching and learning come alive. Every discipline can benefit from this technology. In this video, you can follow the dialogue of a panel of experts in instructional technology as they explore such topics as:

<UL>
<LI>How you can use multimedia in innovative ways to enhance teaching and learning.
<LI>What's happening in instructional technology on campuses around the country.
<LI>Where this technology is heading in the future.</UL>

<P>Plus, you'll watch demonstrations of interactive applications in foreign language, chemistry, medicine, biology and more.

<H3><A NAME="speakers">Key Speakers</A></H3> 

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="../../graves/graves.html">William H. Graves</A> - Director of the IAT and Associate Provost for Information Technology, University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.
<LI><A HREF="../../noblitt/noblitt.html">James S. Noblitt</A> - IAT Academic Chair and Research Professor of Romance Languages, University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill .
<LI>Diana G. Oblinger - Academic Programs Manager, IBM Higher Education.
</UL>

<H3><A NAME="materials">Supplemental Materials</A></H3>


<H3><A NAME="video">Video Ordering Information</A></H3>
<UL><LI><A HREF="../vidorder.html">TO ORDER</A>
<LI><A HREF="../resource.html">Information about other videos in the IAT collection</A>
</UL>

<P>

