<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="100%" CELLSPACE=1 CELLPADDING=1>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP WIDTH="60%">

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2>Noblitt Wins Award for French Language Learning Programs</FONT></CENTER>

<P>
Imagine a learning environment in which access to materials is global. A French language student clicks on a computer icon to launch a video of a conversation in Paris; she then re-plays the scene after consulting a list of vocabulary terms embedded in a CD-ROM . . . .
<P>
No need to imagine it. This scenario is already in development at the Institute for Academic Technology. 
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/technology/demos/nouvelle.html">Nouvelles Dimensions</A> is a CD-ROM for French listening comprehension taught through video and audio as well as more traditional textual methods. Its author, Jim Noblitt, is IAT academic chair and a research professor of romance languages at UNC. He was recently honored as winner in the 1996 <A HREF="http://www.educom.edu/web/medal/medalHome.html">Educom Medal</A> awards program for his promotion of computer-assisted instruction for language learning.
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.educom.edu/">Educom</A>, along with the Modern Language Association, selected Noblitt for this award based on his continuing achievements using computer technology to make learning easier and more meaningful for students. Since the IAT was founded in 1989, Noblitt has studied the role of information technology in learning and research, with particular emphasis on his specialty, Romance Languages. He led the effort to develop "Systeme-D: French Writing Assistant" and "Nouvelles Dimensions: Multimedia for French Listening Comprehension" software programs, both of which have won awards for their technical and educational merits.
<P>
These programs can be used to support the instructor in classroom presentation as well as provide students with help when they work alone. The idea is to provide students with authentic samples of the language along with the lexical and grammatical information needed for understanding. The interactive design engages learners and helps them make good use of their time between classes. Instructors then have more time to spend on the larger issues of culture and creativity in language study. 
<P>
Robert Heterick, president of Educom, noted that Noblitt's "total immersion" approach to learning a language is what makes his work so effective and unique. For Noblitt, the computer is simply a tool that can dramatize, illustrate and manipulate learning materials through multimedia devices such as CD-ROMs. "The traditional curriculum is reductionist," Noblitt said. "We build from basic to complex. But the computer is a device that allows us to be task-focused. We start with a phenomenon of interest, like a French conversation, in all its complexity. The machine lets us take off one layer and then another to study it. Nouvelles Dimensions, for example, allows students to take note of a speaker's gestures and eye movements, the intangible things that form a sub-text to any dialogue, thus placing vocabulary and pronunciation in illuminating context."
<P>
As the leading organization for the advancement of information technology in higher education, Educom conceived the Medal Awards program to honor people whose professional achievements have contributed to the improvement of the undergraduate learning experience and the promotion of information technology in higher education. According to Heterick, "Jim has long held the attention of the information technology community for his groundbreaking work in foreign languages. We at Educom are very pleased to be a participant in similar recognition from his professional colleagues in the language community."
<P>
<TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT  WIDTH="440">
<IMG SRC="../../../media/gifs/1X17pix.gif" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH="17" HEIGHT="1325">

<IMG SRC="../../../media/photos/jimn.jpg" WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=149  VSPACE=10 BORDER=0 ALIGN="RIGHT" VALIGN="TOP"></A>

