<PRE>   

</PRE>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>T</FONT>he <FONT SIZE=+3>M</FONT>onitor: October 1, 1996 </FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>


<BR>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="100%" CELLSPACE=1 CELLPADDING=1>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP WIDTH="60%">

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2>Re-Locating Literary Teaching and Learning with VRML</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1>by <A HREF="mailto:chad_kearsley@unc.edu">Chad Kearsley</A></FONT></CENTER>

<P>Book-based literary studies and teaching may be enhanced by locating aspects of that work in three dimensional spaces--spaces that allow for asynchronous and interactive learning in ways that break out of traditional pedagogical models. Clearly, literary studies are not the most ideal place for discussing three dimensional humanities computing applications. The work of literary studies is in texts, books, the printed word and image, in text-based communication. That study should not be limited, however, to the two dimensional space and page alone.

<P>Certain aspects of literary studies lend themselves to the capabilities of three dimensional, virtual reality environments. By relocating the learning to a virtual space, students and scholars are provided with new tools for understanding the impact of literature in three dimensional space. Literature is returned, in part, to the three dimensional culturally-connected space in which it was written, which can then make those cultural connections explicit to students. The broad scope of cultural studies that now widens the perspective of literary construction and asks scholars to return writers to their place within a culture might benefit from computing tools, especially those available on the Internet, that re-locate literary texts within three dimensional spaces.

<P>The emergence of Internet technologies into the academy promises to shift the way scholars go about their studies and teaching. One of these emerging technologies, the Virtual Reality Modeling Language (<A HREF="../../../technology/vrml/">VRML</A>)--and the browsers and authoring tools being developed to use this standard--brings the promise of three dimensional space to the Internet. With the advent of VRML and its cousin technologies, the metaphor of space in the term cyberspace becomes a reality, giving teachers the ability to create virtual spaces easily transportable across the Internet. VRML offers promising possibilities in humanities computing, especially in the teaching and Learning of literature and literary history.

<HR ALIGN="CENTER" SIZE="1" WIDTH="50%">

<P><FONT SIZE="+1">Using the Virtual Reality Modeling Language</FONT>

<P>The Virtual Reality Modeling Language known as VRML 1.0 (and sometimes pronounced VUHR-MUHL) is an ASCII-based language specification that allows for the description of three dimensional spaces, a language standard that can then be interpreted by rendering engines on different software platforms. VRML allows detailed description of three dimensional spaces. With this standard, objects can be described three-dimensionally or worlds can be created in three dimensional space as rich or as plain as desired, changing light sources, object textures and complexity, size and location, etc.

<P>The ASCII nature of VRML permits compact worlds to be developed which are reasonably accessible across the Internet, since the client-server relationship underlies the basic premise of VRML's portability. A complete VRML file, marked with a .wrl extension, resides on a server and is accessed and downloaded across the Internet through a client browser, giving it the strong advantage of portability across operating system platforms.

<P>In early 1996, the VRML Architecture Group (<A HREF="http://vag.vrml.org/">VAG</A>) that steers the development of the VRML standard, solicited proposals for the new <A HREF="http://vag.vrml.org/VRML2.0/FINAL/">VRML 2.0</A> standard from corporations and others. The new standard will advance currency of VRML from the static description of three dimensional space and objects by providing the means for adding interactivity, moving objects, action, animation, and other elements. A strong, collaborative community bridging the public and private sectors is coming together to develop the VRML 2.0 standard, guided by the expertise of the VAG.

<P>Some literary genres and forms seem quite natural candidates for study in a virtual space. Their creative and literary expression work within and evoke three dimensional space as part of the fabric of their textuality. Other areas of literary study are not as readily adaptable to movement into three dimensional, virtual space. Virtual reality applications might be developed in literary teaching and learning to effectively demonstrate its possibilities and limitations. Such models could then suggest directions literary studies and instruction might take as the technology moves toward a virtual reality environment distributed over the Internet.

<HR ALIGN="CENTER" SIZE="1" WIDTH="50%">

<P><FONT SIZE="+1">VRML and the Theater</FONT>

<P>The most natural place to combine three dimensional space and literary study is in the theater. By its dual nature as a performance text, drama resides in a liminal space, half-way between text and performance between imaginative, virtual space, and concrete, physical place on a stage. This duality as text and performance object allows drama to lend itself to computer applications in three dimensional space. For some time now, scenic designers have been using autocad software to aid in designing sets. Directors have used the same software to help them visualize blocking and stage focus. A few designers are beginning to turn to VRML as a means of describing the three dimensional spaces of their set designs. The same technology might as easily be brought into the teaching and studying of drama as literature.

<P>To demonstrate how VRML technology might be used in drama studies, Henrik Ibsen's <EM><A HREF="http://etext.lib.virginia.edu/cgibin/toccer?id=IbsWild&images=images/modeng&data=/lv1/Archive/eng-parsed&tag=public&part=head">The Wild Duck</A></EM> could serve as the subject of a VRML <A HREF="http://www.unc.edu/~chadk/wildduck.wrl">prototype</A>. How might the study and teaching of Ibsen's play be enhanced through VRML technology? Ibsen's experience in <A HREF="http://www.uib.no/guide/bergen-intro.html">Bergen, Norway</A>, was as a dramaturge--a technical director of sorts. He began to learn during his years working in Bergen (at <A HREF="http://odin.dep.no/html/nofovalt/depter/ud/nornytt/uda-433.html">Den Nationale Scene</A>) about the space and place of the theater, about sight lines and acoustics, about entrances and exits, and other elements of stagecraft. The technical theater Ibsen learned in Bergen plays out in his dramatic work in the explicitness of the stage cues and instructions he gives in the texts of his plays.

<P>Ibsen's texts are full of explicit and implicit clues about props, stage design, exits and entrances, lighting, movement, etc. By adding to the study of Ibsen's craft a movement into a virtual place rendered in compliance with the VRML standard, it would be possible to re-locate one aspect of the study of Ibsen' s drama and to shift perspectives on that drama in new ways.

<P>A virtual space designed to represent the set as indicated in Ibsen's text of <EM>The Wild Duck</EM> can demonstrate the capabilities of VRML to hyperlink between three dimensional worlds/spaces and HTML documents. For example, the virtual doorway into the Ekdal's attic might hyperlink the student to a text-based discussion of the attic's symbolic function in the play and give the student opportunity to write a response to that discussion.

<P>A description of this space in compliance with VRML 1.0 only allows limited interactivity. With the potential enhancements of VRML 2.0, this type of world might allow the student to move the attic space on the stage and respond to the changes that makes to the theatrical experience. Or the student might walk on that stage, interacting with objects whose behavior demonstrates the range of stage directions Ibsen himself indicated in his texts: entrances, exits, props, etc.

<P>Finally, this type of virtual theater advances earlier efforts to bring computing to drama studies. <A HREF="http://www.dsu.edu/~johnsone/">Eric Johnson</A> at Dakota State University developed software called ACTORS, "designed as a tool to process the electronic text of a play in order to tell which dramatic characters are on stage simultaneously and thus to suggest possible doubling of roles for a performance" (Johnson, 1995, p. 399). Johnson suggested at the time that "additional literary and dramatic insights might be gained if researchers noted which characters are on stage together, when, and how often" (1995, p. 399).

<P>With VRML, Johnson's work can be extended into three dimensional visualization, locating those actors on stage and giving the student or scholar (as well as the theater professional) a chance to place those actors and, in so doing, to visualize the performance text. Pushing the concept even further, a VRML theater might suggest how bringing Ibsen's play (and any other drama for that matter) into virtual space allows students and scholars to study interactively the complexities of set design and its impact on theatrical metaphor and dramatic meaning. Unlike film, virtual spaces created in VRML allow users to interact more directly with the objects on the virtual stage. With VRML, we re-locate an inherently three dimensional literary text into a virtual space and place.

<HR ALIGN="CENTER" SIZE="1" WIDTH="50%">

<P><FONT SIZE="+1">VRML and Literary History</FONT>

<P>Writers write in a place, in a location. Writers do not write in cultural vacuums but are very much products of cultural place and location. A second, natural use of VRML in literary study might develop virtual spaces that serve as a means of re-locating literary history. For example, a symbolic, three dimensional recreation of <A HREF="http://www.concordma.com/">Concord, Massachusetts</A> during the 1840s and 1850s could be used as a vehicle for teaching the relationships between the writers of the American Renaissance--<A HREF="http://miso.wwa.com/~jej/1emerson.html">Emerson</A>, <A HREF="http://engserve.tamu.edu/files/fuller/fullerhp.html">Fuller</A>, <A HREF="http://www.tiac.net/users/eldred/nh/hawthorne.html">Hawthorne</A>, <A HREF="http://www.melville.org/">Melville</A>, and <A HREF="http://miso.wwa.com/~jej/1thorea.html">Thoreau</A>--who were themselves located in the small New England town at one time or another.

<P>The virtual space, a layout of Concord at the time, would allow students to interactively and asynchronously hyperlink from places within that space: from Emerson's home to the House of the Seven Gables to Walden Pond--from critical writings about the relationship of these authors to digitized versions and excerpts of their works to multimedia presentations of the locations as they are today.

<P>With the potential functionality of VRML 2.0, entire classes might meet in the virtual space for a virtual tour and follow-up discussion of the American Renaissance.

<HR ALIGN="CENTER" SIZE="1" WIDTH="50%">

<P><FONT SIZE="+1">Conclusions</FONT>

<P>VRML and the three-dimensionality it provides empowers teachers across all disciplines in exciting ways, shifting teaching paradigms and opening interesting opportunities for distance learning in synchronous and asynchronous pedagogical situations. In literary teaching and learning, VRML offers a chance to re-locate both a naturally three-dimensional genre like drama as well as bring together valuable cultural studies resources into a virtual space.

<HR ALIGN="CENTER" SIZE="1" WIDTH="50%">

<P><FONT SIZE="+1">References</FONT>

<UL>
	<LI>Ibsen, Henrik. (1928). <I>Hundrearsutgave. Henrik Ibsens samlede verker.</I> In F. Bull (Ed.), Halvdan Koht, and Didrik Arup Seip. Vol. 1-21. Oslo: <A HREF="http://www.gyldendal.no/">Gyldendal</A>.
	<LI>Johnson, E. (1995). "ACTORS: Computing Dramatic Characters that are on Stage Simultaneously". <I><A HREF="http://ach.stg.brown.edu/">Computers and the Humanities</A></I>, 28(6), 393-400.
</UL>

