<PRE>	

</PRE>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>T</FONT>he <FONT SIZE=+3>M</FONT>onitor:  August 15, 1996 </FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>


<BR>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="100%" CELLSPACE=1 CELLPADDING=1>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP WIDTH="60%">

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2>A Gutenberg Juncture:<BR>
Changing the Model of Instruction <BR>in a New Technological Environment</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1>by <A HREF="mailto:tom_wason@unc.edu">Tom Wason</A></FONT></CENTER>

<P><B>If you look far enough into the future... you can see the past</B>. The development of new information technologies has placed the educational establishment at a juncture parallel to the fifteenth century academy shortly after Gutenberg's revolution: How can we use the technology to improve learning? The Academy again has a chance to shift the learning model away from lecture-centered instruction and significantly increase learning.

<P>The ideal of the Socratic (<A HREF="http://www.ilt.columbia.edu/academic/digitexts/socrates/bio_socrates.html">ca. 470 - 399 B.C.</A>) method used questions to move students through a learning experience. In that method, Socrates was expected to fill three roles: the master of the primary resources, the developer of effective questions leading to new insights, and the teacher who asks the questions that fit the student's learning needs. The current educational model, based on Pierre Abelard's model (1079-1142), asks the instructor to fill only one of those roles in order to satisfy the lecture-followed-by-test: the master of the materials who serves up the lecture and evaluates retention through question-based testing. Textbooks largely follow the same model--the medium is different.

<P>Today, new information technologies open to us the chance to develop a student-centered model of learning akin to the Socratic: a process of education effectively applying the specialties of a trio of content experts: the resource expert, the question developer, and the teacher. 

<P>Historically speaking, the lecture-followed-by test instructional model developed out of necessity: primary sources were simply not widely available.  In 12th century France, Pierre Abelard (<A HREF="http://www.nd.edu/Departments/Maritain/etext/abelard.htm">1079-1142</A>) developed the lecture model of instruction. With limited access to primary resources, no method of resource reproduction existed other than the scribal  hand. Experts, with knowledge of the primary resources, used the lecture hall as an effective means of efficiently gathering groups of learners together to learn about the resources. The modern university grew out of this model:  lecturers presenting information, students being tested, and learning being inferred from test-performance.

<P>Two centuries later, Gutenberg's (<A HREF="http://www.slip.net/~graphion/guten.html">ca. 1390 - 1468</A>) invention of movable type began to make primary resources more accessible and opened a window of opportunity for breaking out of the lecture model of instruction, but the window closed and the lecture method remained.

<P>Now, some five centuries later, information technology again opens a window of opportunity for the adoption of a new model of instruction. Will that opportunity be lost?

<P>What new instructional method is possible? Simply this: instead of lecture-based instruction followed by testing, students can learn by a system of carefully developed questions that guide them through the learning process rather than questions as vehicles to test the learning product. And if we're going to shift the model to a question-based process of learning, teaching has three distinct and Socratic components: 
	<UL>
	<LI>Resource access
	<LI>Questions
	<LI>Teaching
	</UL>

<P>Resource access is the first principle of this new "Socratic" method of instruction. Ironically enough, technology has given us the same problem that Abelard tried to solve--access to resources--by making too many resources available.  For instance, searching for web references to Socrates and Plato can create an <A HREF="plato.html">unwieldy list</A> of potential resources. Such a list is almost useless to a student new to the field. The sheer number of resources makes the task of reviewing them unmanageable. How well would you do with a dictionary organized randomly rather than alphabetically? How is the student to know which pieces of information are significant? Which pieces of information are valid? Which pieces are relevant to the question at hand? A  web search engine is a poor educational resource manager. 

<P><STRONG>Availability </STRONG>is not <STRONG>accessibility</STRONG>. An effective system of access combines  content-relevant navigation and landmarks. Resource access is content-specific. People deeply knowledgeable can work with program specialists to create navigation and landmark systems for accessing the knowledge base. This task alone is demanding work. 

<P>Second in this new model, we have the development of questions. Instruction is embodied in a library of questions. Questions are the underlying instructional tool,  questions of instruction rather than questions of assessment. Through proper question sequences, students discover knowledge relationships and acquire learning skills; in other words, they learn how to use effectively the primary resources. Questions can be created which meet specific criteria. Before writing a question, the designer decides on the instructional purpose of the question. This process is different from generating a question to probe a student's competence: it takes time, experience and skill to generate good instructional questions. 

<P>Thirdly, we have teaching. Teaching is the process of working with specific students. The teacher needs to be knowledgeable in the area and have a gift for teaching. Teachers select questions from the question library to meet the needs of the specific student. As the students work in self-selected groups and alone, the teaching mode becomes, in part, asynchronous. Each student can be taught on an individual basis, even in a classroom setting or in a distributed learning environment.

<P>This technology-integrated model of teaching allows specialization of skills for creating resource access, question libraries, and teaching students. The teacher marshals all of the resources to focus on the educational process of a particular student. The educational process becomes student-centered rather than enterprise-centered; the learning process take precedent over the learning product.


<P>(<A HREF="summary.html">Related Reading</A>)


<TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT  WIDTH="440">
<IMG SRC="../../../media/gifs/1X17pix.gif" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH="17" HEIGHT="1500">

<A HREF="../../../media/photos/wason200.jpg"><IMG SRC="../../../media/photos/Wason100.jpg" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=143  VSPACE=10 BORDER=0 ALIGN="RIGHT" VALIGN="TOP"></A>
<BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR>
<BR><BR>
