<PRE>   

</PRE>
<CENTER><STRONG><FONT  SIZE=+2><FONT SIZE=+3>T</FONT>he <FONT SIZE=+3>M</FONT>onitor: February 3, 1996 </FONT> </STRONG> </CENTER>


<BR>
<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH="100%" CELLSPACE=1 CELLPADDING=1>
<TR>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP WIDTH="70%">

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2>VERA:  A Pragmatic Approach <BR>to Intranet Creation </FONT><BR><FONT SIZE="+1">by <A HREF="mailto:carolyn_kotlas@unc.edu">Carolyn Kotlas</A></FONT></CENTER>
<P>VERA, the Institute for Academic Technology's intranet, was created in 1996 to manage the flow of information among the staff and to provide online connections to frequently-requested information. This paper describes how the system was set up and the benefits we derived from using an in-house information network.


<P>
<A HREF="#1">What is an intranet?</A><BR>
<A HREF="#2">Why an intranet? </A><BR>
<A HREF="#3">Who is our audience? </A><BR>
<A HREF="#4">Which tool to use? </A><BR>
<A HREF="#5">Where did the information come from? </A><BR>
<A HREF="#6">How was the information organized? </A><BR>
<A HREF="#7">After the prototyping, what next? </A><BR>
<A HREF="#8">How long did it all take? </A><BR>
<A HREF="#9">What were some unexpected benefits?</A><BR>
<A HREF="#10">What did we learn? </A><BR>
<A HREF="#11">Want to see VERA? </A><BR>
<A HREF="#12">Want to know more about intranets? </A><BR>
<A HREF="#13">Want to contact VERA's creator? </A><BR>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="1"></A><FONT SIZE="+1">What is an intranet?</FONT>
<P>
intranet.  <EM>n</EM>.  A network that provides services <B>within </B> an organization similar to those provided by the Internet <B>outside</B> it but which is not necessarily connected to the Internet.  e.g. A company sets up a web server on an internal network for distribution of information within the company.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="2"></A><FONT SIZE="+1">Why an intranet?</FONT>
<P>
The IAT Information Resources Group strives to support the teaching, research, and administrative information needs of the faculty and staff of Institute for Academic Technology at minimal cost and with a small staff of one full-time information professional and one quarter-time clerical assistant. Any new services that I provide must be easy to implement, easy to maintain, and easy to use. VERA (acronym for <STRONG>V</STRONG>irtual <STRONG>E</STRONG>lectronic <STRONG>R</STRONG>eference <STRONG>A</STRONG>ssistant) successfully meets all these requirements.
<P>
Originally, my goal in setting up our intranet was to improve user access to several files that I maintained on our network. These files included information about the IAT Library, newsletters, book and magazine catalogs, and bibliographies. 
<P>
Before I set up VERA, users had to know the file's name and where it was located on our local area network drives. This "user-unfriendly" situation meant that the casual user had to learn some of the intricacies of subdirectory and file organization. It was inconvenient for all our users: experienced computer users never access the files often enough to memorize locations and inexperienced computer users often were confused by the details of virtual drives and other file directory structures. By designing a friendlier interface using tools that all users were familiar with or could easily learn, I hoped to increase the use of the files and decrease user questions and confusion.
<P>
Once this first goal was met, I wondered if, by better understanding my user audience, VERA's content could expand to fill many more information needs within our organization.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="3"></A><FONT SIZE="+1">Who is our audience?</FONT>
<P>
Employees of the IAT include a wide range of computer users, from novice-level users, who are comfortable with a limited range of software, to highly-experienced multimedia developers and network designers. Their activities include clerical and office administration tasks; teaching, writing, and research in several academic disciplines; providing technical support for computer users; and computer programming. Our intranet was designed be used by all employees and answer the information needs of the full range of users.
<P>
Based on frequently-asked questions, I already had a general idea of the nature of unmet information needs of many employees. However, I did not want to ignore the needs of the less vocal employees -- those who hesitated to bother me with their questions.
Rather than assume that their needs could be ascertained from their job descriptions, I gathered information by individually interviewing these employees. Special attention was paid to those positions that are often overlooked, but are vital to the day-to-day operation of our organization. These positions included receptionist, personnel officer, and accountant. 
<P>
I set up appointments with several employees to talk about what general types and specific pieces of information they needed in the course of their work. Some materials were needed by all employees, regardless of position: general information explaining the IAT to outsiders, staff directories, employee policies and forms, calendars, who to contact for help. Because we are part of the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, employees wanted information from sources on campus. Because we are also state government employees, they wanted information from North Carolina state agencies that affected them. There were also specialized needs: our personnel officer needed access to our university's employee manuals and benefits information; our accountant needed access to state government purchasing catalogs and campus accounting forms.
<P>
Some of the information resources that employees used became obvious only through spending time in their offices. I have discovered that if you want to know what information people need to use frequently, check out their office bulletin boards and the notes taped around their computer screens. Often these "files" contain information that co-workers would also find useful, if only they knew of its existence. This type of hidden information was a good candidate for adding to our intranet. By making it available electronically, all employees would have access to it, and it wouldn't be lost if an employee left or if it accidentally got lost or discarded.
<P>
I discovered another advantage of spending time with employees. Often we were interrupted by telephone calls that required the employee to refer to information in files. I was able to reproduce this type of information on VERA and help minimize some of the searching that goes on when callers ask for data that is not readily available.
<P>
After I had a grasp of the information needs of my audience, the next step was to organize everything and design a prototype of the interface that the users could try out.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
 <A NAME="4"></A><FONT SIZE="+1">Which tool to use?</FONT>
<P>
For me, choice of intranet tool was simple. Since all IAT employees have access to the Netscape browser, and most were already familiar with using this tool, I decided to design VERA as a collection of hypertext documents (using HTML) and store them on our local area network. This would eliminate the expense of buying any new software. And since I already had experience in creating and maintaining collections of linked HTML documents for our external Web server, I would not have to learn a new tool. I also was confident that the documents would be easy to update and maintain.
<P>
I realized that some training in using Netscape to access VERA would be necessary. This training would serve a dual purpose. Employees who gained competency in using Netscape to browse VERA could also use these skills in browsing the World Wide Web.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="5"></A><FONT SIZE="+1">Where did the information come from?</FONT>
<P>
The content for our intranet came from several sources. First of all, there were the files that we already had on our local area network. Adding these to VERA was simply a matter of creating meaningful titles for them in the intranet and then linking to the files. Although this was the information for which I originally wanted an intranet, in the end this turned out to be the smallest part of VERA's content.
<P>
A second source of content was printed materials in our offices. These materials included staff telephone directories, holiday calendars, employee policies, visitor information, and travel authorization and reimbursement forms. Since the hardcopy items were generally only one or two pages long, these were quickly typed into HTML-format documents. 
<P>
External Web sites provided links to the bulk of the information on VERA. Some of these links were easy to set up. I already knew what was on our campus and state government Web sites. I chose to provide pointers both to their main Web pages and also to specific, selected pages that our employees used frequently. For example, for locating a campus employee's telephone number, I made a direct link (one "mouse click") to that part of the university's Web site. If users had to work their way down from the homepage to the staff directory, it would take four "mouse clicks."
<P>
In many cases, I started with an idea of a type of information that I wanted to provide, and then performed searches on the Web to locate these resources. I spent time both locating and evaluating the results so that externally-supplied information would be high quality. Acquiring this part of VERA's content was the most time-consuming part of content collecting, and it continues to require the most maintenance, since we have no control over other sites' materials. However, it is an extremely valuable service that augments employees' own collections of links (bookmark files). I have had users tell me that they use VERA's links to the Web, rather than try to maintain their own lists of links.
<P>
Employees also provided suggestions for links to sites that they had found useful. I verified the links they gave me, and, in some cases, replaced their suggestions with sites that were better sources of the same information.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="6"></A><FONT SIZE="+1">How was  the information organized?</FONT>
<P>
To design the layout of VERA's documents I borrowed ideas from Web sites that I found useful. I tried to keep the format very simple: two columns of headings with brief explanations of the headings. To minimize scrolling, I tried to keep the opening screen compact to fit as much as possible within the space on the average user's computer screen. I kept graphical elements to a minimum to accommodate the range of computer systems that we have at the IAT. 
<P>
The columns were organized to display two categories of information. One column contained the type of information typically provided by the Information Resources Group: library information, answers to a variety of general reference questions, links to library-type materials on other sites (directories, dictionaries, online newspapers),     and links to "fun" information (area leisure activities, movie and restaurant reviews) which would help promote VERA as a truly all-purpose information resource.
<P>
The other column was devoted to work-related information arranged from smallest work unit level (information specific to the IAT) to ever-broadening levels (University information and North Carolina state government information). Within these broad headings, the information was further organized into smaller and smaller units. Where necessary, I made liberal use of duplication, deciding that I would put a topic heading in as many places as a user might be likely to look for it. The organizational goal was to get the user to the information as quickly as possible in the shortest number of steps. The philosophy behind good intranet organization is that the designer, not the user, should do most of the work.
<P>
To augment the topic headings in VERA's screens, I also created an index of terms and concepts that appear in VERA's documents, along with synonyms that users might try to use to access information. The initial creation of this human-produced index was laborious, but the subsequent maintenance has not been difficult.
<P>
To generate interest in regular use of our intranet, I also included space for announcements of additions or changes on VERA.  I try to include seasonal items that will bring the casual users to VERA. These include links to information on sports tournaments, federal income tax, and presidential elections. By changing this area at least monthly, I hope to demonstrate that VERA is a dynamic, user-responsive service.
<P>
Finally, in case users could not find what they wanted on VERA, I covered that possibility by adding links to several external Web searching sites. 
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="7"></A><FONT SIZE="+1">After the prototyping, what next?</FONT>
<P>
After the initial design, I sent out an announcement that VERA was up and running and where they could find it. I offered to personally help users set up a Netscape bookmark to VERA, and a several took me up on my offer. I asked all employees to try it and give me feedback and comments. Rather than only rely on voluntary feedback, I also watched selected employees use VERA and made notes on any navigational difficulties. These difficulties pointed to places where the organizational structure should be improved. I had already planned to give employees a formal demonstration on how VERA was organized and how to move around the different screens and levels. However, I wanted the average users to be able to easily figure out on their own how to use VERA. I especially didn't want the VERA's structure and layout to be so hard to understand and follow that I would be spending a lot of time on user support. 
<P>
I also noted every time VERA failed to serve up information that an employee attempted to locate. I later located this information and added it to VERA.
<P>
After the initial shakedown period, I scheduled an employee orientation session. During the session, I explained what was in VERA, how it was organized, how to move around in VERA, and how to use the index. The employees then spent time exploring VERA while I answered questions and provided personal assistance. At this point VERA was as fully operational as any work in progress could be. VERA will never be complete because it must reflect the constantly-changing information needs of our organization.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="8"></A><FONT SIZE="+1">How long did it all take?</FONT>
<P>
VERA was an idea I toyed for a couple of weeks in December 1995. Upon returning from the holidays in January 1996, I started work on the outline of what I wanted to include in the intranet. I estimate that I spent 10-15 hours a week during the development period in January. This included both creating the HTML documents, interviewing staff, locating links to external resources, and transferring printed materials into electronic format. During the month of February 1996, I spent about 5-10 hours a week testing and tweaking VERA. By March 1996, VERA was fully functional, requiring only routine maintenance. Now that VERA has existed for one year and the bulk of resources have now been added to the collection, I find I spend less than an hour a week on maintenance. I periodically check the links in various sections and fix any that don't work and also respond to error reports from users. While users can still request new items to be added to VERA, these suggestions have dropped to about one a month.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="9"></A><FONT SIZE="+1">What were some unexpected benefits?</FONT>
<P>
While my original idea was to make existing IAT Library information more accessible, VERA vastly exceeded my modest goals. Our intranet has become a central depository of information needed everyday by all employees.
<P>
Creating VERA was a project that involved every level of our organization. It enabled all employees to be a part of a product that would benefit all employees. Such projects can have a side benefit of highlighting the value of all employees in an organization.
<P>
VERA has helped me save some of our library's money. By linking to reference tools on the Web such as directories, dictionaries, maps, etc., I was able to provide these resources at no cost. I have to evaluate the worth of these resources, but I would have to do this for printed resources as well. While I would normally purchase only one or two copies of a reference tool, by using Web-based resources, I can give everyone equal access to these materials.
<P>
VERA has become a good internal and external public relations tool. Better than any other tactics I had tried, VERA helped me show other employees what I, as an information professional, could do for them. It has increased the visibility of my position, caused more employees to ask me for assistance rather than take less successful routes to locate information, and encouraged employees to ask me for other information-providing services.
<P>
We also use VERA as an external public relations tool to show our clients what they can accomplish on their own sites at very low cost. VERA proves to them that intranets do not require arcane skills to produce. 
<P>
Another unanticipated benefit that resulted from the project is related to how people feel about seeing information on a computer screen. We often accept information in hand-written notes and poorly-reproduced photocopies for our personal use. However, when employees realized that we would all will be seeing the information on our computer screens, they became more particular about the content and appearance of the documents. When I set about converting printed resources (employee policies, internal memos, standard forms) into VERA screens, the employees who provided these resources were motivated to revise, update, and improve upon the hardcopy originals before submitting them to me. Many forms and employee handouts that had not been updated in years were reworked before being transferred to VERA. Papers from the new employee information packet were for the first time made available in one central location where even long-time employees would be able to refer to them. This has helped us all become more aware of our internal policies.
<P>
Setting up VERA also encouraged employees to think about new forms of information that we had never had before. For example, we set up areas to report on the progress of various projects and to provide reports of meetings held by internal task forces. We also set up a staff directory arranged by area of expertise. This "people resource" helps us know who to call for help in special areas.
<P>
Of course, VERA is not perfect. It requires regular maintenance and someone assigned to that task. Periodic tweaking is required as new items and headings are added and old headings are divided into more manageable parts. Because we use materials on external Web sites, sometimes links are unavailable; and when our Internet connection is down, we are limited to only our internal information. But these are small prices to pay for the overall value VERA.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="10"></A><FONT SIZE="+1">What did we learn?</FONT>
<P>
The VERA project has been a learning experience for many of us. We found that there is a lot more ignorance within an organization than there should be, and a lot more knowledge than most of us realized. Those who are ignorant are often reluctant to expose this state. VERA provides a means by which these employees can get their information anonymously and from a reliable source. Those who are keepers of our organization's knowledge either don't know others also need it or don't know how to share it easily. As the maintainer of VERA, I can take the dissemination responsibility out of their hands while not adding to their work load.
<P>
We also learned that even a simple low-tech intranet can provide a high payoff for an organization. While powerful, sophisticated tools are entering the intranet market, the real power of an intranet does not reside in the tool itself. The power lies in the information that the intranet serves up. The value is in the ease of use, accuracy and currency of the contents, and the enthusiasm with which the intended audience accepts and uses the service.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="11"></A><FONT SIZE="+1">Want to see VERA?</FONT>
<P>
A demonstration version of VERA is available at <A HREF="http://projects.iat.unc.edu/vera/">http://projects.iat.unc.edu/vera/</A>
<BR>
Because VERA is designed for internal use, some of the links may point to information only on our LAN and, therefore, do not work properly in the demo version. However, this version does contain most of the same information available in the working version.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="12"></A><FONT SIZE="+1">Want to know more about intranets?</FONT>
<P>
For a bibliography of additional readings and Web resources on intranets, see the IAT's Information Resource Guide, "Intranets: Readings and Resources" at <A HREF="http://www.iat.unc.edu/guides/irg-34.html">http://www.iat.unc.edu/guides/irg-34.html</A>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="13"></A><FONT SIZE="+1">Want to contact VERA's creator?</FONT>
<P>
VERA was created and is maintained by Carolyn Kotlas, IAT Information Resources Manager. <BR>
Reach her by email: <A HREF="mailto:carolyn_kotlas@unc.edu">carolyn_kotlas@unc.edu</A>



