<TR>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP WIDTH="50%">

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2>Using Information Technology for Music Education & Scholarship</FONT></CENTER>

<P>The IAT has just completed a one-year study on the uses of information technology for music scholarship.  The study was made possible by a planning grant from the <A HREF="http://www.mellon.org/">Andrew W. Mellon Foundation</A>, historically supportive of scholars interested in research and development in the Humanities.

<P>The principal investigators for the project--Jane Harris (musicologist), Jim Noblitt (IAT Academic Chair), and Doug Short (IAT Fellow)--were interested in ways the computer provides interactive access to time-based media.  Music researchers and educators have always worked with a multitude of media, from journal articles and facsimiles to recordings and scores.  With help from IAT technical resources, the project members explored the possibilities for making an integrated research and learning environment for scholars and students.

<P>The following tasks were completed in the course of the grant:

<UL>
<LI><STRONG><EM>A <A HREF="../../../technology/music/music.html">survey</A> of current digital library and related efforts in music.</EM></STRONG> Jane Harris reported on national and international initiatives in this area.  In the U.S., the Indiana <EM>Variations </EM>Project is the most ambitious.  They are digitizing their entire sound collection and creating links in their online catalog to the digitized recordings. (<A HREF="http://www.music.indiana.edu/variations/description_june96.html">David Fenske's D-Lib article</A>)

<LI><STRONG><EM>An interface to facilitate listening and research.</EM></STRONG>  Doug Short developed tools which enable the user to capture timing points and attach events, such as captions, to those timing points.  The approach provides a visualization of the time-based event and facilitates rapid random access to points of interest.    Jane Harris demonstrated uses of the approach for musical analysis.  Jim Noblitt demonstrated an application for music and foreign language learning.  They believe that these tools have the potential to support research in music perception (See <A HREF="http://cap-media.com/">CAP-Media</A>).

<LI><STRONG><EM>A feasibility study of music study over the Internet.</EM></STRONG>  Several <A HREF="../../../technology/music/index.html">examples</A> of a "hybrid" approach created by the IAT team are available on the WWW.  A hybrid approach requires the listener to supply a CD for the computer's CD-ROM drive, but the interactive interface is available from the Internet.  (CD audio over the Internet is currently problematic due to issues of insufficient bandwidth and copyright.)
</UL>

<P>The <A HREF="http://www.unc.edu/depts/music/">UNC-CH Department of Music</A> recently received a substantial grant to create a digital music classroom.  The department is interested in applications for general education as well as research in music perception. The IAT team plans to work with the Music Department to continue the development of an interactive approach to listening.  This partnership allows commentary from researchers and students to assist in refining the design. 

<TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT  WIDTH="440">
<IMG SRC="../../../media/gifs/1X17pix.gif" ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH="17" HEIGHT="1325">

