<HEAD>
<TITLE>Intranets: Readings and Resources</TITLE>
<!-- Created: June 6, 1996 by Carolyn Kotlas -->
<!-- Last revised: January 21, 1997 by Carolyn Kotlas -->
<!-- Filename = irg-34.html -->
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFCE7" TEXT="#00006F">
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=+2><STRONG>Intranets: Readings and Resources</FONT></STRONG>
<P>
Compiled by: Carolyn Kotlas, MSLS<BR>
Institute for Academic Technology<BR>
Last revised: January 21, 1997</CENTER>
<P>
What is an intranet? <A HREF="http://www.raleigh.ibm.com/nnn/nnn2edit.htm">Lorrie Nelson</A>, editor of <EM><A HREF="http://www.raleigh.ibm.com/nnn/nnn1int.htm">NetNews</A></EM>, defines an intranet as "Internet + access to internal information + firewall security." Behind this simple equation lies a powerful tool for institution-wide communications, collaborative projects, and the establishment of a sense of community on a manageable scale. Find out why intranets are "hot" and how they can be used in organizations to share information and ideas.
<P>
<A HREF="#articles">Articles/Papers</A><BR>
<A HREF="#books">Books</A><BR>
<A HREF="#www">WWW Resources</A><BR>
<A HREF="#seminars">Online Seminars</A><BR>
<A HREF="#journals">Magazines/Newsletters</A> <BR>
<A HREF="#conferences">Conferences </A>
<BR><BR><BR>
<A NAME="articles"><STRONG>Articles/Papers</STRONG>
<P>
</A>Ayre, Rick. "Intranet How-To: Setting Up Shop." <EM>PC Magazine</EM> 15, no. 8 (April 23, 1996): 151-158.<BR>
	<A HREF="http://www.pcmag.com/issues/1508/pcmg0054.htm">http://www.pcmag.com/issues/1508/pcmg0054.htm</A>
<P>
Babcock, Charles. "Client/server Is Dead; Long Live the Intranet." <EM>Computerworld</EM> 30, no. 11 (March 11, 1996): 126.<BR>
	<A HREF="http://www.computerworld.com/search/AT-html/9603/960311SLdead.html">http://www.computerworld.com/search/AT-html/9603/960311SLdead.html</A>
<P>
